<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday, 09/05/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Sept. 5, 1999 -- RADIOCITY, 9-5 -- A new
gold silk curtain, weighing two tons, which was hoisted up to the
sunrise rings of the proscenium arch at Radio City Music Hall last
Thursday as part of the hall's estimated $70 million renovation.
Only one month before the scheduled reopening of Radio City Music
Hall on Oct. 4, more than 500 workers -- masons, electricians,
plumbers, plasterers, steamfitters, metalworkers, carpet installers
and more -- are bent to the task of both preserving and modernizing
this architectural treasure for the HDTV generation. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Sept. 5, 1999 -- NY-CARDINAL-REACT, 9-5 --
Nuns part of the Sisters of Life order pray for the well-being of
Cardinal John O'Connor at St. Patrick's Cathedral on Sunday. For
the 47 nuns of the order, the cardinal's well-being is a deeply
personal subject. In 1991, O' Connor started their religious
community, which is dedicated to defending human life. Doctors at
Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center removed a small tumor from
O'Connor's brain, his spokesman said Saturday. The tumor was
diagnosed while the 79-year-old cardinal was hospitalized for tests
since Aug. 25. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) CHICAGO -- Sept. 5, 1999 -- UNIONS-CLERGY-2, 9-5 --
Veronica Meneses, action coordinator for the National Farm Worker
Ministry, a clergy group dedicated to helping migrant laborers,
speaking with a parishioner of the St. Pius Roman Catholic Church
on Sunday. Ms. Meneses talked about the gains unions had made for
workers. The service was part of a fast-growing nationwide effort
in which clergy members and union members teamed up with the goal
of educating congregations on labor matters and lending the
church's moral authority to labor's cause. (Steve Kagan/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) CHICAGO -- Sept. 5, 1999 -- SUB-UNIONS-CLERGY-1, 9-5 --
Oscar Varnadoe, a member of a printer's union, greets a parishioner
of the St. Pius Roman Catholic Church, after addressing the
congregation on Sunday. The service was part of a fast-growing
nationwide effort in which clergy members and union members teamed
up over the weekend at more than 600 religious services -- about
twice last year's number -- with the goal of educating
congregations on labor matters and lending the church's moral
authority to labor's cause. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LOS ANGELES -- Sept. 5, 1999 -- LOSANGELES-CHESS, 9-5 --
John Graham, left, and Thomas Harbin finish a match outside Fifth
Street Dick's coffee shop in Los Angeles. In a city where many
restaurants stop seating at 11 p.m. and the bars close at 2 a.m.,
street chess is an exception to the minimal late-night street life.
The game is as much an obsession as it is recreation, with players
continually trying to best one another, the clock and themselves.
Many of the games continue into the early morning, some until dawn
or later, and each spot has its own culture. (Jill Connelly/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) HOUSTON -- Sept. 5, 1999 -- BKL-LIBERTY-COMETS, 9-5 --
Tina Thompson of the Houston Comets, who had 13 points, celebrating
in the final moments as the Comets won their third league title in
the WNBA's third season, by defeating the New York Liberty 59-47 on
Sunday. At right is the Liberty's Sue Wicks. The Liberty has to
live with a second loss in a WNBA finals. The Liberty lost a key
player in forward Rebecca Lobo to a season-ending knee injury in
the first game and then struggled through an 18-14 regular season.
(Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) MIAMI BEACH, Fla. -- Sept. 5, 1999 --
BBO-GAY-EXPLAYER-2, 9-5 --Billy Bean, 35, a former major league
beaseball player, with his dog Paco, struggled with being a gay
athlete in the fiercely competitive and hyper-masculinized arena of
major team sports. Bean, now a restaurant owner, is the first major
league player to publicly discuss his homosexuality and the first
athlete in a major American team sport to do so since the football
player Dave Kopay, who came out in 1975. ``For nine years,'' Bean
says, ``I felt as though I had one foot in the major leagues and
one on a banana peel.'' (Gary Rothstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) MIAMI BEACH, Fla. -- Sept. 5, 1999 --
BBO-GAY-EXPLAYER-1, 9-5 --During nine seasons in the sun in the
major leagues, Billy Bean, 35, now a restaurant owner, wore the
uniforms of three teams and struggled with being a gay athlete in
the fiercely competitive and hyper-masculinized arena of major team
sports. Bean eventually would have to choose between his personal
and professional lives. ``I never dated another major leaguer and I
have no idea whether or not there are other gay ballplayers,'' says
Bean. ``One would think so, but if they were as deeply closeted as
I was, who would know?'' (Gary Rothstein/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BERWYN, Ill. -- Sept. 5, 1999 -- VETS-CLUBS-DECLINE-2,
9-5 -- Bill Lincoln, left, and George Alexander remember when their
Veterans of Foreign Wars hall in Berwyn, was in full swing. As time
conquers the heroes of World War II, and the nation loses more than
1,000 veterans a day, VFW posts around the United States are
struggling to survive. With membership falling, nearly 300 of the
nation's 10,000 VFW posts have folded in the last few years. ``The
best thing about being here is also the hardest,'' says Alexander.
``You get to have such good friends. And then you lose them.''
(Todd Buchannan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BERWYN, Ill. -- Sept. 5, 1999 -- VETS-CLUBS-DECLINE-1,
9-5 -- The Veterans of Foreign Wars Post 2378 in Berwyn, has long
served as a sort of working-class country club in this Chicago
suburb. As time conquers the heroes of World War II, and the nation
loses more than 1,000 veterans a day, VFW posts around the United
States are struggling to survive. With membership falling, nearly
300 of the nation's 10,000 VFW posts have folded in the last few
years, unable to shoulder property taxes on the halls. (Todd
Buchannan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ALEXANDRIA, Va. -- Sept. 5, 1999 --
HOMELESS-KIDNEY-DONOR-1, 9-5 -- Marian Neal, 40, an unemployed
woman who donated a kidney to a young boy, Terrance Varner, now 8,
shaking hands with Andrew Cuomo, the secretary of housing and urban
development. Ms. Neal, who was left homeless when she was evicted
from a public housing project in Alexandria, a Washington suburb,
is living in Carpenter's Shelter, a place for the homeless in
Alexandria. Ms. Neal has been offered her own place to live by
Cuomo. Cuomo says his department will lease Ms. Neal a recently
renovated one-bedroom town house in Washington. The rent will be
based on her income. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) ALEXANDRIA, Va. -- Sept. 5, 1999 --
HOMELESS-KIDNEY-DONOR-1, 9-5 -- Marian Neal, 40, an unemployed
woman who donated a kidney to a young boy, Terrance Varner, now 8.
Ms. Neal, who was left homeless when she was evicted from a public
