<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1904 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT &LR;      09-06 0768
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETER BREAKS THROUGH, AND ANGELS PAY PRICE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ As he waits his turn for his first at-bat
every game, Derek Jeter turns toward the stands and hold up two
fingers of his right hand, or one, or whatever signal happens to be
appropriate. Mike Borzello charts pitches for the Yankees from the
stands and operates a radar gun, and he responds in kind _ perhaps
two fingers, if the pitcher is throwing 92 miles an hour, or three
fingers for 93.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter uses the sign language to help him gauge opposing
pitchers, and he has had fair success this season doing so. He had
more Sunday night, hitting two singles, a double and a home run
while the Yankees embarrassed Anaheim, 8-3. Darryl Strawberry
smashed his first home run since rejoining the Yankees last week,
the 333rd homer of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Yarnall, who has journeyed from the Mets to the Florida
Marlins to the Yankees in the last 15 months in trades for Mike
Piazza and then Mike Lowell, struck out four in six innings and
earned his first victory in his first major league start. The
Yankees are 84-52 and on a pace to win 100 games.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday night's game, Jeter leaned back on two chair legs
at his locker and chatted about his offense, in a hoarse voice he
blamed on the air-conditioning in the team's hotel. Jeter said he
has felt better at the plate than last month, when he was pulling
the ball so much. Now he is again hitting the ball to the opposite
field. But Jeter added that he wanted to get back to the way he hit
earlier this season, when he was driving the ball more.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into this game, Jeter had just six extra-base hits and
eight runs batted in during his last 23 games. He had not hit a
home run since Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   The circumstances were ripe for a breakout Sunday night. Chuck
Finley, the Angels' left-hander who usually pitches well against
the Yankees, was unable to make his scheduled start because of back
trouble; in the late afternoon and early evening shadows of this
game, which started at 5 p.m., Finley would have been even tougher
than usual.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fyhrie, a journeyman right-hander who gets by on lots of
savvy and little stuff, started in place of Finley, and Jeter
singled through the middle in the first inning. Then, in the third
inning, Jeter drove a pitch high over the wall in left field _ his
first home run after 100 homerless at-bats and his 22nd of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees hammered Fyhrie for six hits (including four
extra-base hits) in the first three innings, and the Anaheim
relievers could not contain Jeter, either. He slammed a double in
the fifth inning, driving home a run, and he led off the eighth
inning with another single for his first four-hit game of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter's numbers continue to mount at an extraordinary rate. He
has 188 hits, the most in the American League. At his current rate,
he will accumulate 224 hits _ which would give him 800 for his
first four full seasons, and the most for any Yankee since Don
Mattingly had 238 in 1986. Jeter has 109 runs scored and 89 RBI,
and is batting .353, a point behind Boston's Nomar Garciaparra, who
leads the American League.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry provided the exclamation point in the Yankees'
victory Sunday night. They scored three runs in the fifth inning
and assumed a 7-3 lead, and with two outs in the sixth, Strawberry
batted against Al Levine, the Angels' third pitcher of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry blasted a high drive down the right-field line; fans
stood, their voices escalating as the ball neared the stands, and
the Yankees rushed forward in their dugout to see if Strawberry's
drive would stay fair.
</P>
<P>
   It did not. Strawberry, who had taken a few steps down the
first-base line, returned to the batter's box and crushed Levine's
next pitch beyond right field, where Anaheim's Garret Anderson took
one step and then stopped to admire the flight of the ball.
Estimated distance: 415 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee fans here cheered loudly as Strawberry ambled around
the bases with his first major league home run since Aug. 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry has reached base in 10 of his 14 plate appearances,
with four hits in eight at-bats and six walks. Joe Torre, the
Yankees' manager, intends to use Strawberry when he rests Chili
Davis, the designated hitter. But as one member of the organization
said recently, if Strawberry hits and Davis does not, Strawberry
will play in the postseason _ just as Davis played last year in the
playoffs, after Tim Raines and Strawberry were beset by physical
problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
