<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' KENNY ROGERS SEARCHES FOR HIS COMFORT ZONE 
CANSECO SOUNDING UPBEAT ABOUT FUTURE WITH RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They still remember Kenny Rogers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   He was gone almost two years but he said they still recognize
him when he steps outside his Upper East Side apartment in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you they know who you are,'' Rogers said. ``I can
drive for three hours out to the middle of nowhere and they still
recognize me. You know how it is in New York. You do well there,
they're going to love you. You do bad, you're going to hear about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers found out about New York during his two years with the
Yankees. He heard about it, too. Given a four-year, $19.7 million
contract before the 1996 season, Rogers won only 12 games in each
of his two years and pitched poorly in the playoffs before being
traded to the Oakland Athletics for third baseman Scott Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   The trade looked like a giveaway because the Yankees felt
Rogers, a country boy from central Florida, was totally unsuited to
pitch in New York. Brosius, now an All-Star, had hit .203 the year
before and the Yankees agreed to pay a substantial portion of
Rogers salary to convince the Athletics to do the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rogers is back in New York, only this time with the Mets.
Undeterred by what happened across town, the Mets acquired Rogers
from the Athletics on July 23 for two minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   He is there to reinforce a mediocre starting rotation and get
the Mets in the playoffs. After that, he's a free agent. The
question then will be if he wants to remain in New York or go
someplace where he's most comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Like Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a possibility,'' Rogers said with a smile. ``Any place
you're comfortable and is good for your family, you'd like to play
there. But it can change in a hurry. A place you have your heart
set on, they may not need a left-hander.''
</P>
<P>
   But knowing the Rangers have an all-right-handed rotation in a
ballpark that favors left-handers, Rogers smiled and said, ``Being
left-handed doesn't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers refuses to admit he blundered by not accepting a
four-year, $17 million offer from the Rangers after the 1995
season. The World Series ring from playing for the Yankees in 1996
shows he might be right even though he pitched terrible in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   But his experience in New York was one reason he got on the
phone in the off-season and told his best friend, Rafael Palmeiro,
he needed to take control of his contract situation himself.
Palmeiro did and ended up re-signing with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He owes me,'' Rogers said, again with a smile. ``He owes me
big-time. He could be an MVP this year. That's what happens when
you're playing somewhere where you feel comfortable. Comfort is the
key. If you're comfortable, you can relax and go out and play the
game. If you're not comfortable, it makes everything a little
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Palmeiro, ``I'm trying to get him over here but he and his
agent, Scott Boras, are probably going to play the free-agent game
again. But he'll be sought after. He's a good pitcher. It's going
to be up to him where he wants to play. He put his family through a
lot the past three years.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers was not comfortable with the Yankees and the Mets knew
that. Assistant general manager Omar Minaya admitted some people
within the organization were against trading for him because of
what happened across town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any qualms,'' Minaya said. ``It was just a bad
situation, especially his second year. I think New York brings out
the best in a veteran player. You put a veteran in a pennant race
in New York, it creates an intensity you can't find anywhere in any
city in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers insisted his time with the Yankees would have been
different if he had been healthy. But he had shoulder problems and
was slow in recovering from arthroscopic surgery after the 1996
season.
</P>
<P>
   But Yankees manager Joe Torre saw it differently. He saw it as a
lack of confidence. After the 1996 season, he said, ``I still
believe in Kenny Rogers. The problem is he doesn't believe in
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers, who won 16 games for Oakland last year, responded by
saying, ``If I didn't feel confident in myself, I wouldn't have
made it this far. If I was capable of pitching well, it would have
worked out. But you've got to feel comfortable and I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said he will take a more active role this off-season than
in 1995 when he let Boras shop him to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my future, not anybody else's,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't rule out returning to the Mets. He is 3-0 with a 3.97
earned-run average in seven starts since the trade and said there's
a much different atmosphere at Shea Stadium than with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The most important factor is he is much closer to his family _
wife Becky and their two children _ than when he was in Oakland.
Rogers makes his permanent home in Tampa, Fla., and his family can
join him in New York when the Mets are in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife was really happy when she heard about the trade,''
Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   His family had a hard time getting out to the West Coast; that's
why Rogers made it clear he wasn't going to stay in Oakland beyond
this year. His position alienated many of his teammates and was a
factor in why the Athletics, despite being contenders in the
wild-card race, traded him to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they made up their own reasons,'' Rogers said.
``Whatever they want to make up is fine. I'm not going to feel bad
because I wanted to be closer to my family. If anybody doesn't like
that, too bad.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
