<HEADLINE>
BOOK TOUR OPENS DEBATE ON MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KRIS MAYES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - On Tuesday, Arizona Sen. John McCain will make some
New York book-tour appearances that strongly resemble campaign
opportunities to boost him in the race for the GOP presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   It's not an uncommon event. But to some observers, it also
raises questions about whether the mix of book publicizing and
political preening has gone too far, whether publishers are
improperly, even illegally, helping underwrite campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, for instance, will take part in a whirlwind of
interviews by such media personalities as Kathie Lee Gifford, Regis
Philbin and Don Imus. Later he will be feted at a book signing
party by Michael Bloomberg and Georgette Mosbacher.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate will be asked about his campaign and will be given
a broad forum to air his political views _ a media dream come true
for someone running for president.
</P>
<P>
   Later, McCain will travel to Rockefeller Center, where he hopes
that throngs of New Yorkers will line up to get his signature on
their copies of his new book, ``Faith of My Fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is not the only candidate who has piggybacked a book on
his campaign. Pat Buchanan, Dan Quayle and Steve Forbes also have
come out with books this year, and Alan Keyes and George W. Bush
are finishing ones.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle also hit the book-tour circuit, and he had to be careful
not to commingle the campaigning with the marketing too much.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission advises campaigns that if
publishers pay for a book tour closely tied to a campaign, it could
be considered a corporate contribution to the campaign. Corporate
contributions to presidential campaigns are illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Huff, a spokeswoman for the FEC, said the agency hasn't
formally spoken on the issue of presidential book tours. But she
said FEC lawyers believe that candidates should keep the two
separate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would really depend if it was strictly book-related, as
opposed to maybe throwing in a few campaign-related activities -
(then it) would be maybe considered a corporate contribution,''
Huff said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain aides said they have been careful to pay for many of the
activities associated with the book tour and to keep it separate
from his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``My impression is that we are paying for a lot of it just
because the guidelines are clear,'' said Wes Gullett, McCain's
deputy campaign director.
</P>
<P>
   But the top aide to presidential hopeful Steve Forbes, who
recently released a campaign book entitled ``A New Birth of
Freedom,'' said that he believes any book tour associated with a
campaign should be paid for entirely by the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Dal Col, Forbes' campaign manager, said the Forbes campaign
will pay for expenses on all book tours the candidate decides to
take.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that is remotely concerning the book will be paid for
by the campaign so there is no ambiguity or doubt,'' Dal Col said.
``Anyone not doing that is taking a risk of accepting a corporate
contribution or at least creating the perception of accepting a
corporate contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Gullett's statement, the McCain campaign seems to have
made little effort to divorce itself from the book tour.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign announces each of the book tour's dates and cities
on its Web site, and aides told ``The Arizona Republic'' they are
doing fund-raisers in most of the cities on the tour. A
fund-raising letter McCain sent out Aug. 27 includes a promotional
leaflet for the book, indicating that the book has become an
integral part of the campaign's fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gullett acknowledges that the book is a plus for McCain's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets John's personal story out there and it gives him an
opportunity to be interviewed by a lot of the national media,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the gains, such book tours can also have downsides.
</P>
<P>
   They take candidates through many states, but not always ones
key to the campaign. For instance, this month, McCain will go to
Rockford, Ill., Kansas City, Mo., and Boston, none of them in
states vital to his presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of it helping with overall things, it gives him an
opportunity to be in a lot of places, but it also takes us out of
(key states like) New Hampshire and South Carolina,'' Gullett said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some of those book-stop states will be big.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the McCain tour will cut a wide swath through
California, a state McCain must win to garner the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, now California is an early (primary) state,''
Gullett said.
</P>
<P>
   Also tapping into the book-tour potential has been former Vice
President Dan Quayle. Last month, he got maximum mileage out of his
tour for his book ``Worth Fighting For'' by hosting a book signing
right after a speech he made at the Nixon Library in Yorba Linda,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign promoted the speech as a major foreign policy
address and issued press releases on campaign stationery about the
event.
</P>
<P>
   Following the address, Quayle signed copies of his book for an
hour and then did radio interviews about the campaign and the book.
He was later whisked away in a chauffeured car arranged by the
publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the candidate's trip was paid for by the campaign,
with the exception of the limousine that ferried Quayle to and from
the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is is a gray area, and we've really tried to be careful
about it,'' Quayle's campaign chairman Kyle McSlarrow said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Quayle's publisher said the corporation has
also made every effort to not mix book-promotion dollars with
campaign dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to be extremely mindful of keeping those two
separate,'' said Jana Munsinger of Word Publishing, which issued
Quayle's book. ``We want to make sure that the publisher isn't
helping pay for the campaign. I've spent hours on the phone with
(Quayle's lawyer).''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush is also expected to release a book
this fall, but a spokeswoman for Bush's publisher said the
candidate is not expected to go on tour for the book.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to GOP candidate Alan Keyes, a talk-show host who is
putting the finishing touches on a book he started before the race,
say the dicey legal complications are troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Godzich, an aide to Keyes, said the question is just one
more thing to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Keyes' schedule is ``wacky,'' he has to make a living while he's
running for office, and then questions arise about whether the two
activities are improperly mixed, the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes hard to say what's what,'' Godzich said, sighing. &QL; 
 &QL; 
quote: &QL; 
(The book tour) gets John's personal story out there and it gives
him an opportunity to be interviewed by a lot of the national
media. In terms of it helping with overall things, it gives him an
opportunity to be in a lot of places, but it also takes us out of
(key states like) New Hampshire and South Carolina. &QC; 
by Wes Gullett &QC; 
 &QL; 
qcredit: JOHN McCAIN CAMPAIGN &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
