<HEADLINE>
`EDVENTURE' WILL BRING SA FARI INTO VALLEY SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA BIGGS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - From the primitive wilds of Africa, via satellite
phone and laptop, an Arizona State University professor hopes to
inspire the world's children to learn, to think, to dream.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Wilson will use the Internet to bring students along on
his ``African Edventure'' _ with videos of scuba diving in Lake
Malawi, hiking the 19,340 foot summit of Kilimanjaro and bungee
jumping 709 feet from a bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson departs Sept. 13 for South Africa, where he will meet up
with videographer Aaron Frick of New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The target date to begin their six-month, 18,000 mile expedition
is Oct. 15. They will travel by Land Rover and sleep in a rooftop
tent to be better protected from malaria-carrying mosquitoes and
baboon ``raiding parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Items on his itinerary that sound like fun are actually his
strongest teaching tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've used that (bungee jump) as a way to demonstrate gravity,
acceleration and energy,'' Wilson said. ``So those sort of boring
things, it's a way to get kids not to switch off.''
</P>
<P>
   Scuba diving will be used to demonstrate density and pressure.
To teach conservation biology, Wilson will visit a cheetah preserve
in Namibia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not, `Oh, let's go look at the cute cheetahs,' '' he
said. ``It's the science of conservation biology. It's everything
from the high-tech DNA science to capturing animals that are
causing problems on neighboring farms.''
</P>
<P>
   To rev up interest in the trip, they've sent videos to schools
from Thailand to Australia, as well as the United States. Some
Valley teachers have already made plans to tag along - virtually.
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Udall, an eighth-grade teacher at McKemy Middle School in
Tempe, is incorporating Wilson's trip into her lesson plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids will be following him,'' Udall said. ``We're going to
be studying Africa at the time he is over there. We'll be
corresponding through e-mail and fax.''
</P>
<P>
   The expedition's Web site, www.Africa-Edventure.org, will be a
base camp of sorts, where schoolchildren can visit to follow
Wilson's progress. People are encouraged to e-mail questions, ideas
and comments.
</P>
<P>
   During the seven-day hike up Kilimanjaro, Wilson will pitch camp
each day and set up the satellite phone. He's hoping to receive
phone calls while on the summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll only be there for a short time,'' Wilson said. ``It's
kind of difficult to know when we'll be able to get the sat phone
up and running.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's goal in posting diary entries on the Web site is not
just to teach, but to inspire children to think about controversial
issues, such as the survival balance between people and animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, I wanted to hit the science because I'm a
scientist, but there are so many issues,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   He cites the ``bushmeat trade'' as an example. Animals are
butchered for food, ornaments or other uses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely horrific,'' Wilson said. But he also
understands that the survival of locals might depend on hunting
animals for money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to put provocative questions like, `If you were in
that situation where you had to make a decision of eating that
gorilla or starving your family, what would you do?' '' Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   The trip is not without danger. Some areas, such as northeast
Kenya, cannot be safely traveled in a lone vehicle, so Wilson and
Frick will join up with a convoy.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Edventure'' vehicle was built from 1973-era parts of
ex-military vehicles. It's equipped with riot grids inside the
windows, fuel capacity to travel 1,200 miles, and solar panels to
run a refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not actually for food,'' Wilson said, ``it's to keep the
film cold. I bought 600 feet of film.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the journey, they will visit places where scientists have
discovered evidence of early human ancestors - what Wilson calls
the ``Dawn of Humans'' project.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and Frick have financed most of the trip themselves, but
they have formed loose alliances with the Phoenix Zoo and ASU's
information technology staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in particular excited and interested in the educational
aspect of it, letting children get a first-hand look at the animals
and his adventure,'' said Alice Sluga, public relations manager for
the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   ASU Professor Sam DiGangi said students and staff have been
working with Wilson for several months. Though a trek across Africa
is hardly a new idea, DiGangi said the ``Edventure'' takes it to a
new level.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of a resource for teachers . . . this is a very
innovative approach that he's taking,'' DiGangi said.
</P>
<P>
   DiGangi called the project a valuable experience for his group.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably involved 15-20 staff and students, ranging
everywhere from the graphic artist to the network programmers,
people who are doing the technical aspects of making the site work.
Also our video production people _ we digitized and encoded the
video so it could be streamed across the Internet,'' DiGangi said.
</P>
<P>
   As the realization of Wilson's dream approaches, last-minute
problems such as how to disassemble a winch and ship it do little
to dampen his excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wanted to do this. Always,'' he said. ``There's
some charm or charisma in getting out there in remote Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Even _ or especially _ with much of the world watching. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Patricia Biggs can be reached at (602) 444-2473 or at
patricia.biggs(at)pni.com. &QL; 
quote: &QL; 
My kids will be following him. We're going to be studying Africa at
the time he is over there. We'll be corresponding through e-mail
and fax. &QC; 
by Mindy Udall &QC; 
credit: EIGHTH-GRADE TEACHER, MCKEMY MIDDLE SCHOOL, TEMPE &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
