<HEADLINE>
DISNEY'S TRY AT OWNERSHIP A GOOFY ERROR THAT SHOULD END
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Disney has made billions of dollars drawing pictures of lions,
fairy godmothers and a talking mouse, putting them on an animation
board and parading them in front of a movie camera.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to baseball, the fabled family entertainment
giant has been a colossal flop, taking a reasonably average
franchise and turning it into a running joke. The Anaheim Angels
have become to baseball what ``Pocahontas'' and ``Hercules'' were
to cinematic art. Now everybody is either jumping ship or being
tossed overboard.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins, a good baseball man who deserved better,
went first on Friday, resigning his position one step ahead of the
lynch mob. There was little doubt Collins was in deep trouble since
his players, including that renown warrior Mo Vaughn, quit on him
long ago.
</P>
<P>
   The sad irony is Collins wants to manage but can't, while Jim
Leyland can manage the Colorado Rockies as long as he wants but is
ready to quit at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Leyland, smart enough to realize the Rockies will never have
enough pitching to win, is ``burned out'' and insists he'll never
manage again. But some say he really wants the Detroit job.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Rockies should hire Collins, who has never been a guy
to run away from a challenge. It's just that he had no choice in
Anaheim, and it's a good bet Don Baylor will replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Disney does have a choice, and the company is ready to get out
of the sports business. They've put both the Angels and their
hockey team, the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim, up for sale, and
apparently they've found a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Henry T. Nicholas III, 39 years old and worth billions, is ready
to plunk down some $400 million for the two franchises. Nicholas
made his fortune running Broadcom, a manufacturer of high-speed
communication chips, but needs a sports franchise so the whole
world will know he's a financial and technological genius. After
all, what good is it to be a billionaire when nobody has ever heard
of you?
</P>
<P>
   That might end up being the bigger trend in baseball ownership.
Everybody trembled at the coming of entertainment giants such as
Disney and Fox, but all they've done is foul things up. The next
wave of owners could be a bunch of self-made multimillionaires from
Microsoft, Silicon Valley and Telecom Corridor who are dying to
shed themselves of their anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Call it baseball's version of ``Revenge of the Nerds.'' Pretty
soon athletes will be working for the same geeks whose lunch money
they were stealing in junior high.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn will no doubt love that.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is just the first of many problems for whoever owns the
Angels. He's into only the first year of a six-year, $80 million
contract and what an inaugural campaign it was. Not only did he
lead the mutiny against his manager, but he also alienated pitcher
Troy Percival last week in Cleveland when he remained in the
clubhouse while the rest of the team was engaged in a brawl on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn has had to play hurt, and injuries have been a big part
of the Angels' disaster. Vaughn, Gary DiSarcina, Tim Salmon and Jim
Edmonds have all missed substantial playing time because of
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest problem for the Angels is that every big-name
pitcher brought in the past few years _ Tim Belcher, Jim Abbott,
Ken Hill, Jack McDowell _ has been a bust.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney people can market. They can entertain. They can draw
a picture of a mouse and they can sell souvenirs by the truckload.
But when your pitching stinks, your players have quit and your best
player is one giant, overweight headache, it's time to get out of
baseball and back into Fantasyland. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
