<SLUG> BC-BEACON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDER AIRPLANE BEACONS LEAD TO MANY FALSE ALARMS, FRUSTRATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDD SLIVKA  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The garbage can wasn't lost at sea. It just sounded that way.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard and Washington state's aviation division heard
the signal _ a high-pitched warble _ that meant a plane or ship was
in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Newell Lee heard it, too, and it drove him nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is the man responsible for tracking down emergency beacons
that help authorities locate planes that go down over land.
</P>
<P>
   After four hours of direction finding and flyovers, Lee figured
it out. A fisherman at Poulsbo Marina had thrown his old disaster
beacon in a garbage can. That's when it got wet and started
broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   No one was lost at sea.
</P>
<P>
   No planes had crashed in fiery heaps in the folds of the
Cascades.
</P>
<P>
   It was just another distress call on the commonly used and often
unreliable 121.5-megahertz radio frequency.
</P>
<P>
   More than 170,000 121.5-MHz emergency beacons are used
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Once a beacon is activated, it sends a signal to a satellite,
which relays the beacon's approximate position to a ground station.
It helps leads rescuers to boats and planes.
</P>
<P>
   But the 121.5-MHz frequency isn't just for boats and planes;
it's also the same frequency used by, say, a garage-door opener or
a miskeyed microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Designating the emergency frequency was a good idea in the late
1960s, when it was uncrowded. Technology has passed it by, and many
machines use it.
</P>
<P>
   Newer beacons use the 406-MHz frequency, dedicated solely for
search-and-rescue purposes. Because of the high cost of those
beacons _ $2,500, compared with $150 _ the old frequency remains
far more popular. Until 406-MHz beacons come down in price, the
older frequency will remain the standard _ and a major headache.
</P>
<P>
   Each time something goes out on 121.5, authorities have to
investigate. Those false alarms cost taxpayers money, though
neither the Coast Guard nor the state Department of
Transportation's Aviation Division has figures available.
</P>
<P>
   But this much is known: Nationwide, there were 3,468 distress
calls on the 121.5 frequency recorded by the Coast Guard between
July 1998 and July 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Of those, 56 were real distress calls.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, the 13th Coast Guard District _ which covers
waters from the California-Oregon state line to Canada _ reported
88 alerts on the frequency between April and July.
</P>
<P>
   None of them was real distress calls, and to this day, 80
percent remain a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The beacons sent a signal to a satellite, then stopped
transmitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes a guy will be washing his boat and hit the thing by
accident,'' says Coast Guard Lt. Adam Wasserman, a duty officer at
the district's command center in Seattle. ``Or it's someone's
garage door opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've caught the Navy a couple times. Someone's keyed a mike
on one of their aircraft and leaves it open and that can send a
signal.''
</P>
<P>
   Every incident must be investigated, which takes time,
especially because the troublesome beacons use anonymous signals.
Coded signals, such as those used on the 406-MHz band, can tell
searchers who the boat or plane belongs to, along with addresses
and phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Some newer planes and boats are equipped with the new beacons;
others aren't.
</P>
<P>
   It's not known how many boats and planes in Washington use the
121.5-MHz frequency, but the Coast Guard and the state Department
of Transportation would like to see boaters and pilots use the
406-MHz band, but haven't forced a change because of the high cost
of the new beacons.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they call it a safety issue.
</P>
<P>
   Because beacons on the 121.5-MHz frequency are so unreliable,
rescue workers are reluctant to dedicate planes and boats to
searches until they can prove there is a real emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``High false alarm rate makes first-alert launch infeasible,''
the Coast Guard's search-and-rescue manual reads. ``Absent
independent distress corroboration (command centers) must wait for
additional alert information. 121.5-MHz beacon launch decisions
take six hours longer than for 406-MHz beacons on average. Almost
half of aviation accident survivors perish in the first six hours
after the incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, an aeronautics program specialist with the state
Transportation Department, is disgusted with the frequency.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of out every 80 is probably real here,'' he says. ``I used
to figure the 121s had a 92 percent failure rate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard is less forgiving in its estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fewer than one in 100 alerts are actual distresses,''
according to a passage in the search-and-rescue manual.
</P>
<P>
   The 121.5-MHz beacon is uncoded, just a warbling tone for planes
to track.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to ascertain the situation is to dispatch
resources to investigate _ a costly disadvantage,'' the Coast Guard
manual reads.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has his own problems with the broadcasts, which fall into
two categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get one or two a month where it's something beside (an
emergency beacon) that's broken down or gone haywire,'' he said.
``We go and check it out and it turns out to be the machine at the
cellophane factory has gone crazy and is putting out that
frequency.''
</P>
<P>
   The other half?
</P>
<P>
   ``The first course of action is to call the local airport and
see if anyone has heard it,'' Lee says. ``Of course, no one has. So
we send a pilot up to look, and the pilot is just getting off the
ground and the signal goes away.''
</P>
<P>
   When the first report of an emergency beacon comes in by
satellite, it includes a preliminary set of coordinates, usually
accurate to within 10 to 20 kilometers, which is a lot of ground to
cover.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with the unreliability, search authorities have become
reluctant to put their own people at risk based only on the
testimony of a 121.5-MHz beacon.
</P>
<P>
   And when they do search, the results are often anti-climactic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horror stories?'' Lee asks. ``What kind of horror stories do
you want? About three weeks ago, we had in a garbage can at the
Fisherman's Terminal. About eight years ago, I had two Civil Air
Patrol squadrons digging through Olympia's garbage dump.''
</P>
<P>
   Most calls that come from the 121.5-MHz frequency take between
2{ and four hours to clear, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   And that fact sets rescue personnel to worrying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about the 121.5s is they stick in the back of your
mind,'' says Coast Guard Lt. j.g. Rich Howes, a duty officer at the
district command center. ``The 406s you can usually figure out with
a phone call. But the 121s just take forever, and you get one and
you're always kind of wondering `What was that?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
