<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1920 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-BOY'S-DEATH-SPI &LR;      09-06 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOY'S-DEATH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEW FINDS STATE WORKERS WERE TRYING TO INTERVENE WHEN BOY DIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT GAVIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLYMPIA, Wash. _ Laura Mjelde had a history of drug use and a
social welfare file filled with complaints of child neglect and
abuse, nearly all determined to be unsubstantiated. For months a
Washington state social worker had tried to get her into drug
testing and treatment, but she always found excuses to avoid them.
</P>
<P>
   By last September, the frustrated social worker became so
concerned about Mjelde's two children that he told his supervisor
he was prepared to take the case to court _ the first step in
taking the children from the mother. But Child Protective Services
officials decided they didn't have enough evidence for court
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month later, Mjelde's 14-month-old son, Christopher
Hutton, drowned in a bathtub in Renton, Wash., while under the care
of Mjelde's boyfriend, Stanley Red. Mjelde, Red, and Red's sister,
Cynthia, then cremated the baby, drinking brandy while the tiny
body burned in an aluminum trash can in a park. Prosecutors called
it a case that ``shocked the conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   The short life of Christopher Hutton today seems particularly
tragic, not because social workers turned their backs on him and
his older brother, but rather because they tried repeatedly to
protect them, according to a review by the Department of Social and
Health Services recently obtained by the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   The DSHS report, obtained under the state Public Records Act,
shows social workers closely monitoring the family and responding
quickly to complaints; threatening, pleading and encouraging Mjelde
to get help. It also reveals the frustrations and difficult
decisions facing social workers who, despite concerns for children,
must operate within a system that strives to keep children with
their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Katharine Cahn, director of the Northwest Institute for Children
and Families, said the Hutton case is typical of chronic neglect
cases that are perhaps the hardest for social workers to gauge.
These cases are rarely clear-cut, Cahn said; they present no solid
evidence of abuse or imminent danger to children that would make it
an easy decision to take the children away.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the tightrope they walk,'' Cahn said. ``It's such a
momentous decision, the court requires review every step of the
way, and all of a sudden what looks simple becomes very, very
complex. People don't remove a child lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Katz, an instructor at the University of Washington's
School of Social Work, adds that caseworkers also must weigh the
potential of additional damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can absolutely do harm,'' she said. ``A 1-year-old baby
taken (from parents) would cry without ending. You can't say to the
kid, `Everything will be all right.' The child is devastated. They
lose weight. They don't sleep well. It's a terrible thing to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Mjelde's oldest son was placed in foster care after her arrest
in March. A child born to her in May while she was jailed was
reportedly placed with a family member.
</P>
<P>
   Mjelde, 22, who pleaded guilty to rendering criminal assistance
in connection with Christopher's death, is free on bail pending a
Sept. 24 sentencing, according to the King County Prosecutor's
Office. Prosecutors on that day will ask for a one-year jail term
and also will recommend 16 years for Stanley Red, who pleaded
guilty to first-degree manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   They also will seek a sentence of 30 days of community service
for Cynthia Red, who also has pled guilty to rendering criminal
assistance for her limited role in the cremation.
</P>
<P>
   The just-released DSHS internal review is the first in a
two-step process followed when a child dies while under agency
supervision. An independent panel, overseen by the state Department
of Health, is also conducting a review.
</P>
<P>
   While the internal review shows social workers tried to stay on
top of the case, Vicki Wallen, the state's Family and Children's
ombudsman, warned of an inherent conflict-of-interest in the DSHS
review process.
</P>
<P>
   She declined comment on specific cases, including that of
Christopher Hutton, but said her independent watchdog agency plans
its own study of how DSHS investigates itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you ensure an independent review when the information is
being provided by DSHS?'' Wallen asked.
</P>
<P>
   Mjelde first entered the child protection system nearly two
years before Christopher Hutton was born, according to the internal
review. In December 1995, King County sheriff's deputies responded
to an abuse complaint in south King County and found her oldest son
with scratches, marks on his face and legs, and blood and mucus
coming from his nose.
</P>
<P>
   Mjelde and a male friend claimed the boy had fallen, and a
doctor could not determine conclusively how the boy was injured. No
action was taken, but social workers tried to follow up, losing
track of Mjelde in March 1996, when she moved.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1997, Tukwila Police responded to another abuse
complaint involving her oldest son. Christopher was born a few
weeks later, on Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Social workers, investigating after Christopher's birth, found
no injuries, and a nutritionist who was working with the family
said the children seemed attached to their mother, and well-cared
for.
</P>
<P>
   Social workers determined the risk to the children was low, but
remained concerned about Mjelde's use of marijuana and other drugs.
</P>
<P>
   They warned her to stop and recommended parenting classes and
drug counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Another neglect complaint came in October 1997. This time,
social workers found a tidy apartment, the children well-cared for
and no evidence of drug use. Once again, they determined the risk
to the children was low.
</P>
<P>
   In less than a year, Mjelde was back in the system. Jailed on
outstanding warrants, she left Christopher, then 11 months old,
with a friend, who then passed him to another woman. Unable to care
for him, the woman called police. The report doesn't say where the
older child was at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher was dirty, but otherwise all right, according to the
review. Social workers placed him in foster care. When Mjelde was
released, they reunited the family on condition that she get safe
housing and treatment for drug and alcohol abuse. They also tried
to connect her with other services.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next two months, social workers followed up several
times, at least once threatening to take her to court. Even after
Christopher's death in October _ which Mjelde kept hidden by
telling social workers he was with his father _ state workers
continued to check on Mjelde and insist she pursue drug treatment.
</P>
<P>
   At least twice before learning of Christopher's death, they
considered seeking court intervention, but determined they lacked
enough evidence. In December, an outside panel of experts, called
the Child Protection Team, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   In January, DSHS officials finally thought they were ready to
seek custody of Mjelde's children.
</P>
<P>
   But then Renton Police called to say they believed Christopher,
who had been reported missing, was in fact dead.
</P>
<P>
   Mjelde confessed a few days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems as they are doing the job within reasonable
expectations,'' Cahn, of the Northwest Institute for Children and
Families said, of the social worker's actions. ``You go home, and
you never know. You hope you made the right decision. It's a
devilish choice _ damned if you, damned if you don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
