r s BC-FBC-TEXASTECH-TEX     09-06 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THUMBS UP FOR TEXAS TECH QUARTERBACK
</HEADLINE>
 TECH-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The memory, they say, is the first thing to go when the gray
hairs force unconditional surrender from the dark-colored ones atop
your head. But in this case, the longest-tenured football coach in
the Big 12 pleads extenuating circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Spike Dykes, 61, normally has recall abilities that would be the
envy of most circus elephants. So it produced a mild surprise when
the Texas Tech coach came home after a recent practice and gushed
about his starting quarterback. His wife, Sharon, said she'd heard
it all before. At the same time, last year.
</P>
<P>
   That's when it dawned on Dykes: Rob Peters, after an
injury-marred 1998 season, is ready to stun opponents the way he
did his coach during summer two-a-days. And not a moment too soon.
Tech opens its season Monday night against Arizona State at 7 p.m.
in Tempe, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I'd forgotten how good a healthy Rob Peters
is,'' Dykes said. ``We never got to see that in games last year.
Everything was out of sync a little bit. At times, he was
struggling ... to throw the routes you take for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you watch him in practice now, and he can throw the deep
pass much better. He's better on the (sideline) routes and the
short ones, too. He's made remarkable improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters gets a thumbs-up review from his coach because a broken
thumb no longer impairs his throwing mechanics. Peters suffered a
chipped bone in his right thumb on the first play of the 1998
opener against UT-El Paso. After two weeks of inactivity, he spent
the rest of the season trying to compensate for the injury.
</P>
<P>
   He adjusted his grip to minimize the pain, which created
inconsistency with Peters' release. Some weeks, he looked like
Johnny Unitas. Witness his 322 passing yards in a 42-35 upset of
Texas. Other times, Peters resembled Johnny Come-Lately. Check out
his fourth-quarter benching after completing 10-of-23 passes, with
a couple of ill-timed turnovers, in a 20-17 loss to Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I really had to zip it, I wasn't sure where it would go.
The ball never came out the same way twice, especially on deep
throws,'' said Peters, who still completed 52.5 percent of his
attempts for 1,269 yards, with more touchdowns (9) than
interceptions (4). ``It feels great to throw with a normal grip
again. I can put the ball where I want it, when I want it there. My
confidence level is back where it needs to be.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, are his passes, thanks to off-season thumb surgery that
kept Peters out of spring practice. But the biggest questions
heading into Monday night's game are these: Who, besides flanker
Derek Dorris, will handle the brunt of those receptions? The other
four players in Tech's receiver rotation have combined for fewer
career catches (21) than Dorris had last season (28 receptions, 395
yards, 3 TDs).
</P>
<P>
   That begs the question: With the departure of leading receiver
Donnie Hart, a finalist for the 1998 Biletnikoff Award, can the Red
Raiders generate enough of an aerial threat to prevent defenses
from stacking the line to stop standout tailback Ricky Williams?
</P>
<P>
   Dykes said they can, pointing to Tim Baker, Justin Reed, Dee
Jackson and Darrell Jones as targets capable of eliminating
opponents' temptation to double-team Dorris. Although that foursome
combined for just 14 catches last season (10 of those by Baker),
Dykes predicted better days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even after losing Donnie Hart, I think we will be improved
over last year at receiver. That position, as a group, will be more
productive,'' Dykes said, citing greater accuracy from Peters as a
primary factor that should lead to better stats.
</P>
<P>
   Peters, a fifth-year senior, said he's ready to accept the
challenge. A graduate student on pace to receive his master's
degree in the spring, Peters (6-foot-3, 229 pounds) understands the
need to increase his completion percentage and decrease his
penchant for turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   During narrow losses to Oklahoma (20-17), Missouri (28-26) and
Colorado (19-17) last season, four Peters fumbles and an
interception resulted in 31 points by opponents. As a team, Tech
suffered 26 turnovers last season, up from 14 in 1997. Peters said
his thumb surgery should help in that department as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have enough strength in my thumb to squeeze the ball
and hold it as well as I had in the past,'' Peters said. ``If I got
my hand slapped, I couldn't hold the ball. That shouldn't be a
problem anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor should starting his car, tying his shoes or throwing the
deep route _ three activities that caused shooting pain in 1998.
Peters said he understands if Dykes considers him a different
player than the one he witnessed last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone here has seen what I can do in a game
yet,'' Peters said. ``I'm just excited to finally get to play at
100 percent.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
