<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TCU-ARIZONA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU DROPS HEARTBREAKER TO NO. 15 ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Patrick Batteaux's fourth-down pass bounced
twice and then dribbled a couple of inches farther.
</P>
<P>
   Only 50 seconds remained, so TCU's upset bid of No. 15 Arizona
dribbled away, too.
</P>
<P>
   Wildcats coach Dick Tomey and his crew had escaped from a
rain-soaked Amon Carter Stadium with a 35-31 victory Sunday night,
a victory that for so long looked to belong to coach Dennis
Franchione and his Frogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts, it really hurts,'' TCU safety Curtis Fuller said.
``I believe in my heart they are a real good football team, and we
were right there with them for four quarters. We blew some
coverages; they capitalized on our mistakes. We shut down the run,
passing was their only option.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it didn't matter that the Frogs led until late in
the third quarter and then again until only 2:10 remained. It was
then that the Wildcats grabbed the lead for good.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it didn't matter that the Frogs' defense had two
safeties, three fumbles recovered, including one returned for a
touchdown and an interception. The Frogs' offense never quite was
able to capitalize.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it didn't matter that the Frogs had held the
Wildcats to 14 yards rushing on 37 attempts. The Wildcats simply
passed and passed and passed. Wildcats receiver Dennis Northcutt
finished with 10 catches for 257 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They found a lot of different ways to get him the football,''
Franchione said of Northcutt. ``He was very hard to defend. ... We
didn't get enough pressure on their quarterbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   They finished with 337 yards passing, including four touchdown
passes touchdowns in the second half. The game-winning one came
with 2:10 remaining, a 30-yard pass from Keith Smith to Northcutt.
</P>
<P>
   TCU had faced a fourth-and-inches with 4:18 remaining, but
Franchione decided to punt, setting up Arizona's game-winning
drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a sound football play to punt the ball away,''
Franchione said. ``I changed my mind about 12 times in 30
seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs had one last chance and 2:01 to make something of it.
</P>
<P>
   They got as close as Arizona's 43-yard line, but Batteaux's
fourth-down pass was well short of Mike Scarborough's reach. TCU
finished with 204 yards rushing, including 170 by tailback
LaDainian Tomlinson, but only 77 yards passing.
</P>
<P>
   The Horned Frogs frenzied comeback attempt was necessitated by
the Wildcats comeback.
</P>
<P>
   TCU had a 25-7 lead early in the third quarter. But unlike their
41-7 season-opening loss to Penn State, where Arizona got down and
stayed down, the Wildcats thawed after halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona scored three touchdowns in the third quarter, all on
pass plays. There was a 38-yarder from Ortege Jenkins to Northcutt
followed by the 22-yarder from Jenkins to Brandon Manumaleuna and
capped by a another Jenkins-to-Northcutt score, a 59-yarder this
time.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Arizona had a 28-25 lead.
</P>
<P>
   TCU responded with two Chris Kaylakie field goals, a 43-yarder
to end third-quarter scoring and a 44-yarder to open fourth-quarter
scoring and give TCU a 31-28 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs defense looked like they might be able to make it
stand up until Northcutt struck one more time. TCU's defense,
especially the front four, did what they had been doing ever since
the opening seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Leo Mills fumbled TCU's opening kickoff, forcing the
Wildcats to start at the 1-yard line. A couple of seconds later,
Frogs linebacker Shannon Brazzell tackled Trung Canidate for a
safety. Thirteen seconds had elapsed and TCU had a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   And so went most of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats couldn't get any type of running game going, and
the Frogs couldn't take advantage of the good field position. So
the Wildcats stopped trying to run the ball, and the Frogs managed
to turn some of the turnovers into scores.
</P>
<P>
   There was a 18-yard touchdown run by Tomlinson and a 51-yard
Kendrick Patterson fumble recovery and 8-yard pass from Batteaux to
Scarborough to send the Frogs into halftime thinking of an upset.
</P>
<P>
   There was Scarborough again, seemingly a lifetime later,
watching the ball bounce in front of him and the upset become the
one that got away. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
