<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIN SHOWERS REPLACED BY TEARS AFTER FROGS FALTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ First came the rain.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a forecast that TCU fans know all too well:
</P>
<P>
   Heartbreak. With an inevitable shower of tears.
</P>
<P>
   So fair and foul a night it was for TCU, a team that appeared to
have a thunderous upset within its grasp.
</P>
<P>
   After seizing opportunity after opportunity, while dazzling the
home crowd, the Horned Frogs squandered an 18-point lead and then
went quietly into the damp night. You could argue that they weren't
supposed to upset the 15th-ranked Arizona Wildcats, and they
didn't, losing 35-31.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that the Frogs sustained the ruse for nearly four
quarters made the night hard to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   At the intermission, TCU was outgaining the visiting 'Cats on
the ground, 163 yards to 3, and appeared to have a solid grip on
its 23-7 lead.
</P>
<P>
   With Patrick Batteaux and LaDainian Tomlinson sparking the
option, the Frogs were able to control both the clock and the
scoreboard. Tomlinson had 144 yards on the ground by halftime.
</P>
<P>
   An intriguing upset was on the verge of taking place.
</P>
<P>
   Press box archaeologists began scurrying for traces of the last
so-momentous TCU upset in a season opener _ the last time that the
Frogs had upset someone so truly good. We were back to 1943 and
Dutch Meyer _ 13-0 over Arkansas _ when we realized it wasn't going
to matter.
</P>
<P>
   For coach Dennis Franchione's young team, it could have been a
stunning affirmation, a golden reminder that their Sun Bowl triumph
over Southern Cal was no fluke. I would argue that playing the No.
15 team in the country off its feet for nearly four quarters is
affirmation enough.
</P>
<P>
   But for some Frog fans, this is going to be deja vu, TCU-style,
all over again.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Tomlinson finished with 170 yards rushing. The
defense held alleged Heisman candidate Trung Canidate to only 56
yards. It prompted Arizona coach Dick Tomey to go to his bench and
replace quarterback Keith Smith with the slipperier Ortege Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in the simplest of terms, the Frogs lost because they could
not cover the Wildcats' dazzling receiver Dennis Northcutt.
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, Northcutt found a seam, a canyon, or a cavernous
opening in the TCU secondary. The Frogs gave Northcutt the respect
_ and the 10-yard cushion most of the night _ he richly deserved.
</P>
<P>
   But they never could really stop him. Northcutt finished with
257 yards in receptions and scored three touchdowns, including the
game-winner with 2:10 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Great teams are led by great players. Maybe, in time, Arizona
will prove to be the national power that it was forecast to be. In
Northcutt, the Penn State debacle aside, it has a solid start.
</P>
<P>
   How the Frogs view the toasting by Northcutt remains to be seen.
The Frogs remain young and precocious. And there was little shown
Sunday night to suggest that they should not be a favorite in the
Western Athletic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   If one trait buttressed Franchione's team in last year's bowl
season, it was its resiliency, its ability to bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   With this team, we will see. This is a defeat that will be hard
to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   So fair and foul a night ... Batteaux mostly ran the option like
an experienced veteran. But his passing was inconsistent. When the
Frogs needed to play from behind, Batteaux failed to move the team.
</P>
<P>
   The first half, as it turned out, was a tease. Arizona rebounded
after the intermission and, for the most part, dominated the final
30 minutes, mostly because Jenkins and Smith kept finding
Northcutt.
</P>
<P>
   For TCU fans, what could have been a memorable night ended up
reeking of the familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Heartbreak, mixed with a shower of tears. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
