<DOCNO> NYT19990906.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1929 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     09-06 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REV UP THE ZAMBONI, IT'S TIME TO HIT ICE AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ Repeat after me: There's not one thing bad about
winning the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually we're repeating after Mike Keane, the veteran
Dallas Stars winger who patiently attempted to explain that mantra
to a skeptical outsider Sunday after the team's first training camp
workout.
</P>
<P>
   The skeptic would be me, because I'm struggling to understand
how a team so fresh from a Stanley Cup championship that the beer
in the silver goblet's still cold can possibly be ready to rekindle
the same hunger that drove them through the most grueling trek in
team sports less than three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, my body hasn't recovered from Buffalo yet. How can the
Stars possibly be ready to play again? Granted, it's a poor analogy
since I'm generally wheezing after back-to-back computer baseball
games, but you get my drift.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing bad comes from winning the Cup,'' Keane insisted again
as he straddled his mountain bike and prepared to peddle away from
little Dobson Arena, the Stars' late summer home away from home.
``Nothing. I see no other reason but to play for the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess some players play for the money, or the fame, but if
you win the Cup, the money and the fame and all those things come
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-eight days after the Stars sent Buffalo into a whining
pout with a Game 6 triple-overtime victory to win the Stanley Cup,
they were back on the ice here Sunday morning, beginning the
arduous journey all over again.
</P>
<P>
   This must be somebody's idea of a cruel joke. Since it has
brought us all together at this playground for the rich and famous
for a few days, however, I'm all for it.
</P>
<P>
   I just haven't quite figured out how they're going to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't it just Sunday that we were watching Brett Hull, skating
on one leg, score the final game-winning goal over a sprawled out
Dominik Hasek? Didn't we just reach for our hankies as Mike Modano
wept openly in the Stars' emotion-choked locker room?
</P>
<P>
   ``We counted the number of days we had (until camp) as soon as
that day was over,'' Modano admitted after a lively and vocal
practice session. ``It was something like 70, but suddenly it's
single digits and then you're here again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully as the season goes on we'll get more of a hunger
going. Complacency is a word (coach Ken Hitchcock) is probably
going to be using a lot. Teams will be grading themselves against
us every night. Hopefully that will give us a little push. You get
that winning feeling, you want to keep it, you want to have it.
Always.''
</P>
<P>
   That won't be easy. Dynasty is fast becoming a lost word in
sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Detroit had the best chance to have a dynasty like
Edmonton did in the '80s,'' Keane said. ``They won two in a row.
But the game has changed with free agency. Key players get hurt.
This year they couldn't get past Colorado.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate is now on for the Stars. Sure, they've discovered the
formula for winning the Cup. But will they be as hungry the second
time around? Will they be as willing to make the sacrifices that
have to be made knowing how difficult it is, especially now that
they will always be able to say they played for a Stanley Cup
champion?
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you have the key, the lock and the door, and you
don't want to give that up,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``You feel
like you have all those aspects and you're not interested in giving
that up to anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I thought I knew about winning, there's another
level out there that I didn't recognize. We're not prepared to let
that feeling go.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, an avid Civil War historian, often finds motivational
techniques there that he can apply to coaching the Stars. But even
the Union didn't have to win back-to-back Lincoln Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Hitch's Juniors teams, however, won six championships in seven
years. He knows a little bit about repeating.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I learned is that it's not people chasing you, it's not
people going after you, it's you focusing only on yourself,''
Hitchcock said. ``When you get where we're at, the focus changes to
nothing but yourself. You have no focus on anything to the outside.
Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't worry about what other teams are doing. You don't
worry about what other teams are saying. You're not focused on what
trade another team has made or what elevation they're going to,
you're focused on only yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The process gets easier now, said Keane, who should know, since
he has three Stanley Cups (Montreal, Colorado, Dallas) on his
resume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you've won a Cup, you know what it takes to win,'' he
said. ``People look at you, they see a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   I look at this team and I still see Buffalo. I still see the
sweat, the blood, the tears from 23 playoff games, eight of which
went into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   I still hear the whining.
</P>
<P>
   And you're telling me it starts all over again in less than a
month?
</P>
<P>
   I don't think I'm ready for this but don't worry boss, I'm
willing to train right here in Vail for as long as it takes. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
