r s BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX     09-06 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETERMINED WINGER AIMS FOR SPOT ON STARS ROSTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ Jamie Wright has added seven pounds of muscle to
his six-foot frame. But maybe even more important for the Stars'
hopeful winger-to-be, he added a good dose of determination.
</P>
<P>
   Wright on Sunday was one of the standouts of the Stars' first
training camp workouts, scoring two goals in the intrasquad
scrimmage. It was a welcome opening act for a player who said he
might be running out of chances to impress the critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, I see this as a do-or-die season for me,'' said
the 24-year-old winger who has had mixed results in two tries at
earning a permanent spot on the Stars. ``I understand my situation,
and now is the time for me to make a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Two seasons ago, Wright was good enough to play in 21
regular-season games and five playoff games with the Stars. Last
season, he wasn't even invited to hang around as a spare part in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot more time than anyone else to think about things
this summer. I had a good 31/2 months to work out,'' he said of his
improved conditioning. ``I was obviously excited that they were
able to win the Stanley Cup, but there's also a bad taste that I
wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said he sees the change in Wright's
determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you seen him?'' Hitchcock responded. ``Just looking at
him, he's a different player. He's matured.'' SEVERYN SAVED
</P>
<P>
   The NHL has reversed its decision and will include Brent
Severyn's name on the Stanley Cup, Stars general manager Bob Gainey
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Severyn, who did not meet the NHL's criteria of playing in 41
regular-season games or one game of the Stanley Cup Finals, played
all of last season with the Stars and was included after an appeal
was lodged by the Stars _ an appeal that was pushed through by
Stars winger Mike Keane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the whole organization really, all the players and
everything,'' Keane said of the push to include his former
teammate. ``Sevy was a part of that team from the start. He
deserved to be on the Cup, so we just let them know that.'' NEW
SLOGAN
</P>
<P>
   Coach Ken Hitchcock has used a slogan for his previous three
training camps and has a new one this season _ ``Enjoy the
Challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to face every team's best efforts every time we go
out and we might as well be ready for it,'' center Guy Carbonneau
said. ``In the end, it could make us a better team.'' NO ADVANTAGE
</P>
<P>
   While the Stars might find it difficult to breathe in the high
altitude of the Rocky Mountains, they'll get no conditioning
advantage from six days in Vail, Colo., said J.J. McQueen, the
Stars' strength and conditioning coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to be up here 4-6 weeks to feel any difference and
I'm not sure it would make that much of a difference,'' McQueen
said.
</P>
<P>
   What the Stars are taking advantage of is a cool climate and a
great atmosphere for training and camaraderie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think just walking out the door, it makes things easier to
get back to work up here,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   McQueen said his plan is to work the players just enough to make
them feel it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to complement the on-ice workouts and practices,''
McQueen said. ``We don't want to wear them out and let them have
nothing left for the scrimmages. We just want to push their
conditioning.'' HEALTH REPORT
</P>
<P>
   Winger Grant Marshall said he'll likely only play in two
preseason games due to a severe tear of his left groin muscle he
sustained in the playoffs. Marshall can participate in light
skating, but will not go through any on-ice drills at training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   The other Stars' injuries, however, are responding well. Brett
Hull is working out and said he feels ``a lot better than I thought
I would'' after suffering a tear of the medial collateral ligament
in his right knee and two pulled groins in the playoffs. Mike
Modano's fractured thumb has healed and now he said he experiences
only a little pain from strained ligaments in his thumb.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
