<HEADLINE>
STARS OPEN CAMP FILLED WITH GUSTO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   VAIL, Colo. _ Mike Modano skated up and down the ice, making
plays and almost glowing with a new inner leadership. Joe
Nieuwendyk glided through practice as if he was still playing in
the Stanley Cup playoffs. And Brett Hull declined an invitation to
sit out a full-contact scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day back to the NHL grind _ the official start of
training camp _ the defending Stanley Cup champion Stars on Sunday
surprised their coach. And maybe even themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in here a little cautious and concerned. But the
moment they skated out onto the ice, all the apprehension
disappeared,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``The veterans went
out and had a lot of fun and really enjoyed themselves. To tell you
the truth, I think everyone is excited to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Greeted by a sunny day with temperatures in the 70s, two groups
of the Stars' 53 players chugged through an on-ice practice, an
off-ice workout and an intrasquad scrimmage that created a buzz of
fans and media around the Dobson Ice Arena. And while many expected
there to be a severe hangover after a short summer left little time
to rehabilitate, the Stars showed they're ready to defend their
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if excited is the word, but it is good to be
back,'' said Nieuwendyk, just two months removed from winning the
Conn Smythe Trophy as playoff's most valuable player. ``There were
a lot of turnovers and you could see some rust, but there were also
some pretty good plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The scrimmage highlighted the day's activities as Hitchcock
chose to break up his old combinations and move some of his star
players onto lines with newcomers fighting for jobs. The results,
for at least one day, were sensational.
</P>
<P>
   Modano played on a line with wingers Jamie Wright and Jon Sim _
both fighting for a roster spot. Wright scored two goals.
</P>
<P>
   Hull played with Mike Keane and 27-year-old center Pavel Patera,
an import from the Czech Republic who will be a roster regular for
the Stars this season. The trio were exciting every time they were
on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk played beside Jere Lehtinen and Warren Luhning,
helping Luhning score a goal in his first workout with the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Blake Sloan played beside Guy Carbonneau, Jamie Pushor took
shifts with Darryl Sydor and Shawn Chambers often played beside
Brad Lukowich _ continuing the apprentice program.
</P>
<P>
   In each situation, Hitchcock found a solid balance between
veterans and newcomers. The veterans helped the newcomers learn and
the newcomers helped the veterans pick up the pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sometimes nice to go back and be with the young guns,''
Modano said. ``It's kind of refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the balance was so important, he plans to follow
through during the team's nine preseason games, which begin
Saturday at Reunion Arena against the Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't give a player who has the potential to make the team
a real opportunity unless you put him with legitimate players,''
Hitchcock said. ``I don't think you get a true look at them until
that's there. So that's what we're going to do for the next 31/2
weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the speed of the young players and the push to
incorporate more passing through the neutral zone created more
scoring chances on the first day of workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's evident we can get around the ice a lot quicker and make
plays a lot quicker,'' Hitchcock said. ``And we saw against teams
like Buffalo that, when you have footspeed, you can give people a
lot of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   And on a day when there was concern that the challenges would be
presented mostly to the Stars, that was a welcome realization. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
