<HEADLINE>
STOUTMIRE WAIVED AS COWBOYS TRIM TO 53
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The release of former starting safety Omar
Stoutmire was one 17 roster moves made by the Dallas Cowboys on
Sunday to comply with the NFL's 53-man limit.
</P>
<P>
   But it's clear that the Cowboys aren't through maneuvering their
final roster heading into Sunday's season opener against the
Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones, who was unavailable to comment,
huddled with coach Chan Gailey and members of the scouting
department late into the evening at the team's Valley Ranch
headquarters analyzing possible additions from the league waiver
wire.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are likely looking for help at cornerback, running
back and tight end.
</P>
<P>
   The release of Beau Morgan and Denvis Manns leaves the Cowboys
without a backup to running backs Emmitt Smith and Chris Warren.
Former Cowboys running back Sherman Williams is being considered.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys need to bolster their depth at cornerback because of
the uncertainty surrounding the availability of injured veterans
Deion Sanders (toe) and Kevin Smith (back). Both could miss the
first two games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Mathis and Charlie Williams are slated to start against
the Redskins, but they are backed up by rookie free-agent Duane
Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
   The problem at tight end stems from an injury as well. With
rookie seventh-round pick Mike Lucky out four to six weeks with a
stress fracture in his left foot, the Cowboys are without a true
run-blocking tight end to backup starter David LaFleur and work in
their two-tight-end offense.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether the Cowboys can find a good financial
fit on the waiver wire to fill in until Lucky comes back. Other
stop-gap answers include using defensive end Ebenezer Ekuban or an
extra offensive lineman to play tight end on short-yardage
situations.
</P>
<P>
   Stoutmire's departure likely paved the way for the salary-cap
strapped Cowboys to field a practice squad, which can consist of no
more than five players. Morgan and rookie receiver MarTay Jenkins
top the list of possible practice candidates. The decisions will be
made this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights of Sunday's moves include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Linebacker Robert Thomas beating out Ryan Neufeld and David
McCann to back up Daryl Johnston at fullback.
</P>
<P>
   _ Former TCU receiver Jason Tucker making the squad as the sixth
receiver.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cowboys keeping six defensive tackles _ Michael Myers,
Alonzo Spellman, Darren Benson, Nathan Davis, Brandon Noble and
Chad Hennings. When the Cowboys need a roster spot to add another
player they will look to this position, as only Spellman, Hennings
and Davis are sure bets to be with the team for the season opener.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
