<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATCHING UP AT THE U.S. OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
MEN'S RECAP
<TEXT>
<P>
   Recapping the first week: Three of the top six seeds exited
before the end of the first day when No. 1 Pete Sampras pulled out
before playing a point because of a back injury, No. 4 Patrick
Rafter withdrew in the fifth set of his first-round match against
Cedric Pioline because of shoulder tendinitis, and No. 6 Tim Henman
lost in straight sets to Guillermo Canas. That robbed the bracket
of two of its marquee players and another who seemingly had an
outside chance to win it all. By the end of the week, third-seed
Yevgeny Kafelnikov was guaranteeing that only he, Andre Agassi or
Richard Krajicek could win the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite: Andre Agassi. Agassi was having a great year anyway,
losing only four matches since winning the French Open. Three of
those were to Sampras, so Agassi became the heavy favorite when the
top seed pulled out. Agassi showed the role was deserved by
dropping just one set in winning his first three matches.
</P>
<P>
   Challengers: Yevgeny Kafelnikov, Richard Krajicek, Todd Martin,
Greg Rusedski. All have games well suited to the hard courts of the
National Tennis Center, and with the exception of Martin's tough
five-set victory in the first round against Stephane Huet, had
little problems advancing to the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   Possible breakthroughs: Marcelo Rios, Gustavo Kuerten. Rios, the
No. 10 seed, is into the fourth round at the Open for the first
time. However, a quarterfinal date with Agassi looms. Kuerten,
perceived as a clay-court specialist, has a clear path to the
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead: Martin and Rusedski, are the best two hard-court
players in the top half of the bracket, but they meet in the fourth
round tomorrow. Kafelnikov and Krajicek are on a collision course
to meet in the quarterfinals, with the winner likely to face
Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN'S RECAP
</P>
<P>
   Recapping the first week: The women's bracket was more notable
for what happened off the court than on it, with a mild war of
words between the Williams family and top-seeded Martina Hingis.
Richard Williams predicted his daughters, Venus and Serena, would
meet in the final, prompting Hingis to comment on the mouth size of
the father and his offspring. Hingis later extended an olive branch
to papa Williams in the form of an autographed T-shirt. The best
stories on the court were Jennifer Capriati, who continued her
comeback with an upset of No. 11 Nathalie Tauziat, and Anke Huber,
who beat No. 8 Jana Novotna and No. 15 Amelie Mauresmo.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite: Hingis. The Smiling Assassin is refocused after losing
in the first round and as deadly as ever, dropping just 21 games in
winning her first four matches.
</P>
<P>
   Challengers: Lindsay Davenport, Venus Williams, Monica Seles,
Serena Williams. While Hingis and the two Williamses got all the
attention, Davenport cruised into the fourth round. The defending
champion lost a mere seven games in winning her first three
matches. The Williams sisters both struggled, Serena dropping a set
in the third round and Venus in the fourth, but toughened up when
it counted.
</P>
<P>
   Possible breakthrough: Barbara Schett. The 12th seed dropped
just two games in winning her third- and fourth-round matches. Next
up, though, is Venus Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead: Only Huber and Schett stand in the way of a dream
semifinal between Hingis and Venus Williams. Inconsistent Mary
Pierce is the only real obstacle between Davenport and the
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   COMEBACK KIDS
</P>
<P>
   Monica Seles and Jennifer Capriati were teen-agers when they
staged a match for the ages in the 1991 semifinals. Seles prevailed
in a third-set tie-breaker and went on to beat Martina Navratilova
in the final.
</P>
<P>
   They meet again today in the fourth round in different
circumstances. Seles, whose stellar career was sidetracked when she
was stabbed on the court in 1993, is seeded fourth. Capriati, who
missed two years after being arrested for marijuana possession and
shoplifting, is unseeded.
THE OTHER GERMAN
</P>
<P>
   Steffi Graf has retired, but there's still a German in the Open
quarterfinals. Anke Huber, ranked No. 27 in the world, advanced
with a 6-4, 6-4 victory against 15th-seeded Amelie Mauresmo, one
round after knocking off eighth-seeded Jana Novotna.
SHOT OF THE DAY
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Haas hit a between-the-legs shot for a clean winner in his
match against Hicham Arazi.
SINGIN' IN THE RAIN
</P>
<P>
   Inclement weather wreaked havoc with the schedule. Martina
Hingis and Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario were scheduled to play in the
morning session, but ended up toiling under the lights. Two of the
men's fourth-round matches still were in the early stages when
another rain delay hit at 10:30 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast calls for lots more thunderstorms today, and a
chance for rain the next four days.
QUOTE OF THE DAY
</P>
<P>
   Andrei Medvedev said he would consider marrying girlfriend Huber
if he wins the Open. Responded Huber: ``If I win it, I'll consider
it, too.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
