<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN A SCAPEGOAT FOR ANGELS' TROUBLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Mo Vaughn is getting a few boos at Edison Field these
days, probably because some fans expect more for $80 million, which
Vaughn will get over the life of his six-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Fans also might put some blame on him for some of the discord in
the clubhouse, because he came with expectations of being a
clubhouse leader.
</P>
<P>
   But general manager Bill Bavasi, who orchestrated the free-agent
deal to bring in Vaughn, doesn't think it's fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problems aren't because of what happened with Mo,'' Bavasi
said.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn went 0 for 3 with two walks Sunday and is now hitting
.262 with 23 homers and a team-leading 83 RBI. His home run and RBI
totals project to 27 and 99, despite missing 22 games and being
hampered all season with a severely sprained left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Hurting: Maybe Chuck Finley and Tim Salmon have been hanging
around each other a little too much lately.
</P>
<P>
   Both arrived at the ballpark Sunday complaining of bad backs,
and both were sent out for precautionary MRI exams.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who was scheduled to start Sunday against the Yankees,
has been bothered by a sore back since his last start in Cleveland
last Tuesday. He is expected to make his next start, probably
Friday in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon, who initially was diagnosed with a strained lower back,
pinch-hit in the sixth inning Sunday and walked.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the call: The Angels will promote three players from the
minors Tuesday _ catchers Bret Hemphill and Steve Decker and
outfielder Jeff DaVanon.
</P>
<P>
   DaVanon was one of the three minor-leaguers acquired in the
trade that sent Randy Velarde and Omar Olivares to the A's last
month. DaVanon was playing at Double-A in the A's organization
before the trade but has played well at Triple-A Edmonton for the
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   In 32 games with the Trappers, DaVanon is hitting .325 with six
homers and 19 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Percival waits: Troy Percival's three-game suspension for
hitting the Indians' David Justice with a pitch last Tuesday is
being appealed, but Percival doesn't know when his case will be
heard.
</P>
<P>
   The league has asked him to have his appeal conducted on the
phone because the Angels won't be in New York, where the league
offices are located, again this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
