<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESPN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I CONFESS; I PAID NO ATTENTION TO ESPN DURING ITS START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The story drifted through the sports department about some cable
outfit back East that was going to do a 24-hour sports network,
even though it had almost no major sports contracts, or even local
sports to fill time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' I said to someone in the office, ``is an idea that's
so dead a cat wouldn't eat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, go ahead and laugh at me now. But remember, I said the
same thing about Microsoft and Amazon.com. So there.
</P>
<P>
   I paid no attention to ESPN during its start _ hey, in '79 I was
trying to get over the death of Sid Vicious of the Sex Pistols by
converting to the Bee Gees. Maybe you can appreciate the
distraction.
</P>
<P>
   But by the spring of 1980, the NCAA men's basketball tournament
was about to fire up again, the year after the epic championship
match between Michigan State's Magic Johnson and Indiana State's
Larry Bird gave college hoops such an adrenaline spike.
</P>
<P>
   That spring was also when the Seattle SuperSonics were defending
their NBA championship and Bird and Johnson had been through
Seattle for the first time as pro rookies. Basketball hereabouts
was large.
</P>
<P>
   It would be fun to reveal that during a time of high hoops
interest ESPN showed me some great NBA national coverage that would
be useful in comparing with the champion Sonics. But ESPN didn't
televise the NBA. Nor did ESPN televise the Final Four, which
remains to this day the province of the broadcast networks.
</P>
<P>
   It would be fun to say I enjoyed ESPN's telecast of the early
rounds of the tournament, which I had never seen before. While
there was some entertainment there, I couldn't get over this one
monumentally annoying color analyst, who shouted every sentence and
closed them all with ``bay-bee!''
</P>
<P>
   Well, I thought, it's a rookie network that has to let everyone
try out. That clown won't make the first cut.
</P>
<P>
   What I did find helpful and amusing that spring was an ESPN
telecast, or maybe it was a long highlight, that few others might
remember _ the finals of the National Invitation Tournament, which
back then had a little fizz because the NCAA hadn't yet expanded
its field all the way to the Van Allen radiation belt.
</P>
<P>
   In this game was a skinny 7-foot-4 freshman who brought the ball
up the floor, shot from outside and ran with the grace of someone a
foot shorter. He had 15 points and 15 rebounds, leading Virginia to
a 58-55 win over Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, I had never heard of Ralph Sampson. After that TV
flash, I figured I had seen athletic genius in its obscure genesis.
For a young sportswriter, this was cool, because I knew something
most of my colleagues and rivals didn't. Those things were coins of
my new professional realm.
</P>
<P>
   Bad break, however, for feline diets everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   What I didn't know was the wise guys had already discovered
ESPN. What I came to learn over the past 20 years is that there are
no more Sampson-like coins, because ESPN has made sure nothing is
obscure.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone under 30, it's probably hard to believe that someone
of Sampson's extraordinary talents was once a regional secret.
Today, of course, all of America would know about a gifted 7-foot-4
freshman down to his junior prom date.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this is good or bad is a matter for social
anthropologists. But it's hard to deny that a well-done, 24-hour
sports channel has transformed the sporting landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes alter their games to create a highlight worthy of
national telecast. Teams change schedules and routines to
accommodate ESPN attention. Media types track its coverage to shape
their own work. New sports plot how their games will show on ESPN.
And ESPN can invent its own events, the X Games, and not be shamed
into surrendering the silliness.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that ESPN's 20th anniversary today is a sufficient
cultural touchstone to draw A-1 of this newspaper is testimony to
its reach and influence _ not to mention a slow news day.
</P>
<P>
   Without ESPN bringing sports to the sports nation, would:
</P>
<P>
   _Anyone have heard of the Big East Conference?
</P>
<P>
   _Shawn Kemp have grabbed his crotch after a dunk?
</P>
<P>
   _Dick Vitale be anything but a vacuum-cleaner salesman with a
limp, having had his foot crushed in doorways endless times?
</P>
<P>
   _Bert Blyleven be known more for the Chris Berman-bestowed
middle name ``Be Home By'' instead of a stalwart pitching career?
</P>
<P>
   _Drunken college kids spend a fair chunk of the semester
gyrating behind ESPN's live remote talking-head set on game days so
they could show mom and dad back home what a rotten investment that
tuition money was?
</P>
<P>
   _Stuart Scott have taken smug hipness to frontiers unknown even
to Pat O'Brien?
</P>
<P>
   _Big-time sailing still be interesting only to wealthy elites
after a camera in 1987 was fixed on the mast of an America's Cup
yacht while it was being blasted by the Indian Ocean?
</P>
<P>
   _Lame rock songs by Gary Glitter become annoying national sports
anthems?
</P>
<P>
   _The scoring signal of the weird-hatted official in Aussie-rules
football be considered the funniest gesture in worldwide sports?
</P>
<P>
   _Postgame interviews in clubhouses and locker rooms be
interrupted by athletes craning to see themselves on
``SportsCenter''?
</P>
<P>
   _Baseball have suffered one of its greatest indignities when its
September stretch-drive coverage was bumped to ESPN2 in order to
telecast NFL games, which draw three and four times the Sunday
audience?
</P>
<P>
   _Sports anchors everywhere feel compelled to twist metaphors
beyond recognition, a task normally reserved for columnists who do
that sort of overreaching for a living?
</P>
<P>
   _Anyone watch Berman grow over the 20 years and recognize that
his chins are as rings to trees?
</P>
<P>
   The answers are all no. Maybe this ESPN thing will catch fire,
after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
