<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1943 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     09-06 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
TERESA Weatherspoon did it again Sunday, scoring the final three
points of the game on a bomb launched from somewhere in the next
county. This time, however, nobody noticed or cared.
</P>
<P>
   No, this time the confetti kept spewing, in perfect rhythm with
the unbridled hysteria on display in the jammed Compaq Center,
Laptop of champions. There would be no more outrageous reversals of
fortune, no more daggers in Van Chancellor's overstressed heart.
</P>
<P>
   Cruel fate wouldn't dare jack with the Comets any further.
Enough was by-gosh enough.
</P>
<P>
   Destiny's-turned-dynasty's darlings had long since stuck a fork
in T-Spoon and her fellow mugging victims from New York. Knives,
too, and probably every other kitchen utensil you can imagine.
Houston's lady killers shackled the Liberty with what Chancellor
called ``the best defense I've ever seen in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   New York scored six points in the first 15:52 of the second
half. That's how you explain the Comets landing their Game 3
knockout punch despite hitting an atrocious 28.8 percent from the
field.
</P>
<P>
   OK, the possibility exists that a bit of lousy offense also had
a hand in Houston's 59-47 three-peat clinching performance, but
there's no reason to rain on the Comets' parade at such an
exuberant and relief-filled moment, after a season that would have
turned Job himself into a blubbering fool.
</P>
<P>
   When you lose your starting point guard to cancer, then she
passes away a week before the playoffs start, you are dealing with
adversity of such magnitude as to render virtually all other
purported examples of same superficial.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets' winning No. 3 for No. 10 _ Perrot's number _ becomes
an instant contender then, on emotional grounds alone, for
story-of-the-millennium honors in these parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't think the spirit of Kim Perrot is alive in the
Comets' world right now,'' Chancellor said, ``you're dead wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody thinks that, of course. Perrot, who went from being a
no-hoper in Houston's inaugural tryout camp to becoming the floor
general and inspirational leader for the first two championship
teams, will always be accorded a special niche in the city's
sporting lore.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kim's closest friend, Cynthia Cooper, the woman
singularly most responsible for making Sam Houston's town the
epicenter of women's pro hoops, she now qualifies as a certified
Texas legend, up there with ol' General Sam himself. Coop was born
in Chicago and grew up in Los Angeles, but we're claiming her,
period. End of discussion.
</P>
<P>
   And she seems to appreciate us as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like the fans have lived every moment with us,''
Cooper said. ``All the hurt and the pain we've felt, they felt it
also. They are definitely the sixth man or the X-factor or whatever
you want to call them. I'm just thankful they're ours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, when (Weatherspoon) hit that big shot, the fans
went to the box office, and every ticket sold out within a couple
hours. That shows you how great the fans of Houston are.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, the greatest player in the WNBA all three of its
seasons, had sunk just a single field goal in 10 tries during the
68-67 sucker-punch defeat Saturday. On Sunday, however, she nailed
her first bucket in the opening moments to inform everyone _
especially the Liberty _ that she would be making her presence more
felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right from the beginning,'' she said, ``I wanted to establish
that I was going to the basket today, that I was going to be a
force to be reckoned with. I was going to go down fighting for my
team to win a third championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Coop's 24 points, 13 of which came on free throws, were 11 more
than anyone else scored. The Liberty would be led, nominally
anyway, by Sue Wicks' 11. Of all the participants on both teams,
New York's Vickie Johnson (4-for-7) was the only one to shoot
better than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were beating the out of each other,'' Wicks said
indelicately.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the Liberty got the worst of the carnage by far,
never mind its minute advantage (.309-.288) in shooting percentage.
New York also suffered 16 turnovers, and its bruises wouldn't
translate into many gimmie points. The Comets attempted 32 free
throws to New York's nine and made 19 more, providing the winning
margin with plenty to spare.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Richie Adubato, the Liberty coach, accepted the
blame instead of predictably laying it on home-court-biased
officiating. He said he needs to do a better job of teaching his
players to attack the basket _ a la Coop.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, fairly late in life, the 36-year-old Cooper has made
herself an icon of her sport and given Houston a new reason to
celebrate Labor Day weekend. Three tries, three titles. Anybody for
a four-peat? Coop wouldn't guarantee same, but she promised to try
her best to deliver it.
</P>
<P>
   And her best has always been good enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
