u s BC-ESPN-MAYNE-SPI &LR;      09-06 1881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESPN-MAYNE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUCCESS FOR KENNY MAYNE COMES AFTER MANY OBSTACLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It used to be that everything in Kenny Mayne's life was like his
hair _ going everywhere but the intended direction.
</P>
<P>
   Now he sits in a chair on the SportsCenter set, amusing America
with his one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   Not that long ago, one of the nation's most recognized faces in
sports journalism was known only as Kenny, the part-timer hired by
Sea-Tac Disposal near Seattle to assemble garbage cans.
</P>
<P>
   Or the reserve quarterback at Nevada-Las Vegas. Or the second
stringer at KSTW, Seattle's UPN affiliate. Or the mop-up guy
peddling MCI. Or the loser at Longacres horse racing track.
</P>
<P>
   If Mayne was on a ladder to success, the rungs kept snapping.
For a while, sea level was a tough climb, even in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In the broadcasting business, for all of the breakups, there is
an occasional breakthrough. Mayne finally had one, ESPN rewarding
his persistence with a job at the highest-rated sports cable
channel in the country.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, this 40-year-old man who should have been enjoying his
popularity and riches, could not. He would have traded the
professional pinnacle for a child to be named later.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mayne household, where Kenny lives with his wife Laura,
it was never known as the birthing process. It was the birthing
ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Using his on-air vernacular, the Maynes, after so many
disappointments, finally experienced a ``Yahtzee'' on Aug. 16 when
their little girl, Riley Hope, was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't understate the thickness of emotion,'' Mayne said.
``It's pretty humbling. We were so used to the tragedies that
occurred in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, when the pediatrician came by to check on Riley
Hope, the Maynes were understandably anxious until receiving the
doctor's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lady actually said the word `perfect,''' Mayne said.
``It's what most people get to hear, and we never had.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Laura Mayne gave birth to premature twins. One,
Creighton, was stillborn. The other, Connor, weighed 1 pound, 7
ounces.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, after surviving countless operations and
growing to 7 pounds, Connor's battle ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody fought to live more than this guy,'' Mayne said.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1997, Laura became pregnant again with a little girl
they planned to call Riley. Mayne found out about it on the same
day he got his new assignment with Dan Patrick. It seemed like all
the karma was finally connecting. Until September, when Laura
miscarried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything came crushing down on us again,'' Mayne said. ``I
didn't know how Laura was ever going to pull through. It was the
next-closest thing to suicidal. I took some time off.''
</P>
<P>
   And then _ as if to reaffirm that life isn't fair, it's a foul
ball in the seats _ Laura lost another baby, a Billy-to-be, last
October.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, when Laura was in her sixth month of
pregnancy, the Maynes were encouraged because they had been told
that every previous problem was unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctors,'' Mayne said, ``couldn't come up with anything
but bad luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what his career was filled with early on.
</P>
<P>
   For the longest time, this could have been a
local-boy-tries-but-never-makes-good story.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1994, when the Federal Way, Wash., product began to appear
on ESPN2, Mayne was like one of the claimers he used to bet on at
Longacres _ a 50-to-1 shot.
</P>
<P>
   Business was down, really down, on Mayne street. In 1986, the
guy you think is so funny now was a weekend sports anchor at KSTW,
doing offbeat bits, eventually clashing with management and
quitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one night (on the air) when he said he felt like he
had a runny nose,'' said Shawn Doran, one of Mayne's lifelong
friends. ``He continued to read the story even though he had blood
all over his hand and blood running down his face. Then he comes
back from a commercial with a wad of toilet paper hanging out his
nose.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving KSTW, Mayne was either trying to find himself, a
job or both. That was when he began talking trash. To pay the bills
for a while, Mayne assembled garbage cans, the big green toters
that you wheel to the curb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was using tools that I had never heard of, like an air-rivet
gun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After there were no more cans to assemble, Mayne needed another
job. So he looked in the classifieds and was hired by a
telemarketing firm. New position: Pre-paid legal insurance
salesman. Pay: minimal. Prestige: none.
</P>
<P>
   Mayne sat in an office. An automated computer system dialed the
numbers for him. One day, Bristol, Conn., popped onto the screen,
ESPN's hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``That moment was the real low point,'' Mayne said.
</P>
<P>
   The place he aspired to be, flashing in his face. He was
free-lancing for ESPN, badgering ESPN, interviewing with ESPN. In
1994, the relentless pursuit of a job at the cable king resulted in
an anchor's position for an update show on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   That led to a gig as host of RPM2night, his checkered career
giving way to the checkered flag three years later on SportsCenter.
</P>
<P>
   ``All along, there was something there,'' said Al Jaffe, ESPN's
vice president for production and talent recruitment who saw
Mayne's first audition tape. ``When it's right, you know it. He had
that certain something the camera loved. He's wry, clever,
different. He is someone you want to watch and invite
</P>
<P>
   into your home.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mayne was growing up, you could say the kid had Star Lake
potential. That's where he lived, on the shores of the little lake
east of Interstate 5 on the outskirts of Federal Way.
</P>
<P>
   His journalism teacher at Thomas Jefferson High School said
Mayne was a wonderful athlete, good student and mischievous
teenager.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had that sparkle,'' said Joe Gotchy, who still teaches
social studies at Jefferson. ``You knew that this person had
promise and potential.''
</P>
<P>
   As a prospective broadcaster perhaps, not a negotiator or
handicapper.
</P>
<P>
   In eighth grade, Doran was flipping coins in a game of even-odd
with a much-bigger ninth grader. When Doran won, the freshman
refused to pay him a dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kiss my ass,'' the ninth grader told Doran.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark the spot,'' Mayne piped in, ``you're all butt.''
</P>
<P>
   The ninth-grader responded with two punches, putting Mayne on
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't cure his wise-guy tendencies. On a high-school road
trip to Kelso for a basketball game, Mayne and his buddies pulled
off to the side of the road to relieve themselves, attracting the
local police. He was a minor in possession of everything but his
senses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in jail and the cop wanted to do a strip search,''
Doran said. ``Kenny looked at him and said: `But I hardly know
you.'''
</P>
<P>
   In those formative and occasionally degenerative years, Mayne
received a fine education at Star Lake Elementary, Totem Junior
High, Jefferson High and Longacres, where lessons are costly.
</P>
<P>
   Doran and Mayne would hitchhike to the Renton horse-racing
track, attempting to bet before they were of legal age. By the time
they were 20, they were playing all-night poker games with
Longacres security men at the nearby Doubletree Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the worst gambler of all time,'' Doran said. ``I've
been to the track with him a million times and he just doesn't
win.''
</P>
<P>
   There was one notable exception when everyone profited from
Mayne's mistake. He had been sent to the window with $30 to box
three horses in the exacta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny used the wrong numbers, but it came in and we won
$3,000,'' Doran said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, Mayne is cashing another ticket. He never
made it as a walk-on quarterback at the University of Washington in
Seattle with Warren Moon and Tom Flick already on campus. He shined
at Wenatchee, becoming a community college All-American. But in
another Strip search, Mayne failed to find stardom in Las Vegas,
injuries contributing to his role as a backup quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   He was given a tryout with the Seahawks in 1982 but failed the
team physical because of a previously fractured ankle.
</P>
<P>
   If Kenny Mayne was ever going to call plays again, they would
have to be on television.
</P>
<P>
   Mayne doesn't get back to Seattle with any regularity but was
here last Jan. 16 to celebrate his father's 75th birthday. His mom
died in 1986, and his dad had a rough year and a half, experiencing
a minor heart attack and a stroke. Mayne also has three older
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   He misses his friends and family and the scenery. In a way,
Kenny Mayne is still here, in our living rooms, appearing as more
than a talking head to those at Jefferson High School. In the race
for most famous alum, Mayne still trails but is closing in on Josie
Bissett.
</P>
<P>
   The man who sparked the passion in journalism is now inspired by
Mayne. Gotchy watches his former student every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes me laugh,'' Gotchy said. ``He reminds me that every
student I work with has that promise and potential. You just don't
know where they're going to end up. His story is almost legend
among the older faculty members here. It says that from a very good
public high school, nothing is impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   When he returned last week from vacation, Mayne felt as if he
had been demoted. His SportsCenter times and days and partners had
changed. For two years, he tag-teamed with Dan Patrick as the
deadpan straight man, helping form the No. 1 tandem on the cable
giant.
</P>
<P>
   Now, because Patrick has a radio show, Mayne has been paired
with Trey Wingo. Mayne also does not appear on the Sunday night
SportsCenter show anymore, which bothers him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest show of the week,'' he said. ``It's pretty
exhilarating.''
</P>
<P>
   As careers go, Mayne is still soaring, if not off the charts
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   More accustomed to obscurity, Mayne is somewhat uncomfortable
with celebrity. He is the same person who assembled garbage cans
before discovering the recycling bin. He goes to a movie with his
wife and wears a baseball cap but still sees people staring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like Leonardo DiCaprio, but it's weird,'' Mayne said.
``It's sort of odd how we get calls from old friends. They're
thinking the whole thing is SportsCenter and the ads. With Laura,
all we talk about is family.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time in their eyes, they had one, referring to the lost
twins in the present tense. On what would have been Connor's second
birthday in May 1998, the Maynes went to Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to experience it as if he was still here, like,
here's what we might have been doing,'' Mayne said. ``We took a
couple of his (stuffed) bears with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Reality in Riley finally joined the Maynes last month. If you
ask Laura Mayne, it was an overdue date. As well as a miracle of
sorts. Mayne said that his wife did not think she ovulated during
the month of conception.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be attributed to a religious experience for
non-churchgoers like the Maynes? Perhaps. When Mayne went to
Minnesota to interview Vikings quarterback Randall Cunningham for a
story in ESPN Magazine, the man who let him through the locked door
was the team pastor. He said a prayer for the Maynes.
</P>
<P>
   And the ultrasound bites were flawless _ in the hospital, on the
set. Kenny Mayne had finally gone quadrangular.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
