<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON STATE TIES TO ESPN ARE STRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Linda Cohn, a New Yorker, used to work in Seattle. Bob Stevens,
who grew up in Walla Walla, always wanted to. Today, each has one
of sportscasting's dream jobs: anchor on ESPN's ``SportsCenter.''
And though ESPN's hometown of Bristol, Conn., doesn't match Seattle
for postcard possibilities, neither of them is complaining.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, John Clayton, who still works in Seattle, is a
colleague to both as one of ESPN's resident experts on pro
football.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn, who worked as a sports reporter/anchor at KIRO/7,
Seattle's CBS affiliate, from 1989-92, says her seven years at ESPN
have been ``a great run.'' Lauded by management for her
versatility, Cohn often co-anchors the 11 p.m. (Eastern) edition of
``SportsCenter'' because she's good at working on the fly with
little advance preparation.
</P>
<P>
   The second of four children, Cohn says she was always into
sports, much more so than her only brother. Passions were
basketball and hockey. As a high school senior on Long Island, she
played goalie on the boys' hockey team. She did the same on a
women's club-level squad at the State University of New York at
Oswego.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating in 1981, she began her career in radio, and she
still enjoys doing the occasional piece for ESPN Radio broadcasts.
She joined a Long Island TV station in 1985 but went back to ABC
radio in 1987, becoming the first full-time female sports anchor on
a national radio network.
</P>
<P>
   When KIRO offered her a job in '89, Cohn jumped, and then
wondered if she'd made a mistake when ESPN came calling six months
later. She honored her commitment to KIRO and told ESPN ``no
thanks.'' But when they called again in '92, she accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn says she doesn't remember much about Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always working,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens considers himself ESPN's ``oldest rookie.'' The
44-year-old anchor joined the network in 1996 for the launch of
ESPNEWS, its 24-hour sports news network. Didn't take long before
he moved up to ``SportsCenter'' duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was here three months and saw my name show up on the
schedule,'' he said. ``I've played pinch-hitter and utility man
since then.'' In fact, by his count, Stevens had more
``SportsCenter'' appearances last year than any other anchor.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens grew up on a wheat farm in Walla Walla. When his parents
divorced he moved with his mother to California, where he finished
high school. He graduated from the University of Tulsa in 1977 and
spent three more years in Tulsa as sports director of KOTV-TV. He
moved on to WEWS-TV in Cleveland in 1990, where he met his wife,
who hosted a local show on the same station.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who broadcast Little League baseball games when he was
in high school, interviewed for the sports director's job at KOMO,
Seattle's ABC affiliae, a few years ago and thought he had it, but
KOMO went with Eric Johnson instead. His disappointment dissipated
when ESPN called. Happy to be in Bristol, he's also keenly aware of
the impact ESPN has had on sports.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton came to the Puget Sound area from his native Pittsburgh
in 1986 as the Seattle Seahawks/NFL beat writer for the News
Tribune in Tacoma. An alumnus of Duquesne, where he got bitten by
the broadcasting bug, he soon picked up a side gig doing Seahawks
reports on KJR radio. A companion career was born.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, still covering the Hawks for the Tribune, he signed his
first contract with ESPN Radio and was given additional
responsibilities as news gatherer for ESPN's Prime Time Monday show
and a consultant to its Sunday Countdown program.
</P>
<P>
   He left newspapering 1{ years ago to sign on with ESPN The
Magazine and as an on-camera reporter for the Inside the Huddle
segment of Tuesday SportsCenter telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton, who lives in Renton, Wash, with his wife, Patricia,
does his network feeds by satellite on his travels to NFL cities
and training camps throughout the country. In addition to Inside
the Huddle, he appears on NFL Tonight on ESPN2 and, occasionally,
ESPNEWS. Last season, he was host of an NFL talk show on ESPN
Radio.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, as for the John Clayton who's co-host of KJR-AM's Sports
Saturday? That John Clayton?
</P>
<P>
   Same guy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
