<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 01:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1946 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-ESPN-ANNIVERSARY-SPI &LR;      09-06 2251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESPN-ANNIVERSARY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN 20 YEARS, ESPN HAS CHANGED THE FACE OF SPORTS BROADCASTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Conn. _ Ten weeks ago, when Tony Hawk turned the first
``900'' in a skateboarding competition, it was not only fitting
that ESPN be there to record the event, it was pretty much
required, dude.
</P>
<P>
   Hawk was competing, after all, in the X (for extreme) Games, an
invention of ESPN, which 20 years ago launched itself into the
cable consciousness with these words from sportscaster Lee Leonard:
``If you're a fan, if you're a fan, what you'll see in the next
minutes, hours and days to follow may convince you you've gone to
sports heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who only remember skateboarding as a playground
activity of the '60s, a ``900'' is boarder-talk for 2{ revolutions
in the air _ a full 900 degrees. To all you throwbacks, as well as
all the sports widows/widowers out there, Leonard's words may seem
a tad overinflated. But to a new generation of athletes, as well as
millions of people who are happy to watch sports programming
twenty-four/seven, Leonard was a prophet. Over the ensuing two
decades, ESPN has done what every entrepreneur dreams: It found a
need and filled it. Along the way, it also changed the way sports
fans get their information.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some will argue that ESPN created the need, that 20
years ago most Americans really had no wish to see the professional
slo-pitch softball world series (ESPN's first live event), or an
installment of pro beach hockey hosted by a bikini babe (one of its
more recent inventions; the game, that is, not the babe).
</P>
<P>
   ESPN anchor Chris Berman disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not have been the sports you wanted to see,
necessarily,'' he said recently, ``... but there's an audience for
all of those, and we believed there were people out there just like
us that wanted to see sports 24 hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman, one of the first broadcasters to make humor a regular
part of sports reportage, should know. Tomorrow at 4 p.m. he'll
host a three-hour special on ESPN's 20th anniversary. He's been
there for all but three weeks of those 20 years, and vividly
recalls the early days, such as the time he did play-by-play for a
darts tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever do a replay on darts?'' he asked. ```Ooh, nice wrist
action. Really good!'''
</P>
<P>
   Berman, who remembers when ESPN amounted to three satellite
dishes and 70 employees, is unapologetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper,'' he admitted, ``we looked like a wing and a prayer.
But I will say this: We never put junk on.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong words from a guy who works for a company that now has 25
dishes and 2,100 employees who have to find enough sports-related
stuff _ we didn't say junk _ to fill 24 hours on not one, but five,
cable channels: ESPN, ESPN2, ESPN Classic, ESPNEWS and ESPN
International.
</P>
<P>
   That's only the foreword of the book on ESPN. If there were a
dictionary illustration for ``branding,'' it might well be the ESPN
logo.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there aren't many serious sports nuts who can get through
a day without tuning in ESPN cable or listening to ESPN Radio or
logging on to ESPN.com or leafing through ESPN The Magazine. Heck,
in Baltimore, Chicago and, soon, New York City, they can do it all
and have dinner, too, at ESPN Zone, the latest in themed restaurant
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   This explosion of ESPN's presence has happened mostly in the
'90s, especially after Walt Disney Co.'s 1996 acquisition of
Capital Cities/ABC Inc., which had owned 80 percent of ESPN since
1984. With Disney's deep pockets and marketing savvy, ESPN is the
Microsoft of sports information: No. 1, and a couple of light years
ahead of the competition. But where Microsoft is perceived by many
as arrogant, ESPN is like your best buddy.
</P>
<P>
   It all started with Bill Rasmussen in 1978. Rasmussen, public
relations director of the New England Whalers of the old World
Hockey Association, wanted to build a sports network in
Connecticut. He figured one of the linchpins would be Whalers
telecasts, a sure way to build interest in the team, which had
moved from Boston to Hartford in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The dream eventually expanded to accommodate a national vision
and, bankrolled by the Getty Oil Co., Rasmussen launched the
Entertainment and Sports Programming Network on Sept. 7, 1979, with
the first edition of ``SportsCenter.''
</P>
<P>
   Building credibility is crucial to any television start-up.
ESPN's got a boost when veteran NBC sportscaster Jim Simpson signed
on a week after liftoff. But the real turning point came in March
1980, when ESPN aired the obscure early-round games of the NCAA
basketball tournament, featuring a motormouth analyst named Dick
Vitale.
</P>
<P>
   Fans loved it, and after Simpson taught Vitale the value of
coming up for air _ he had Vitale's microphone cut during one
telecast _ Vitale became the love-him-or-hate-him mainstay of
basketball on ESPN. He was loud, obnoxious, funny and the
antithesis of the traditionally colorless ``color commentator.''
His presence and his patois _ ``it's awesome, bay-bee!'' _ made the
broadcast an event that was sometimes bigger than the game.
</P>
<P>
   Today there are Web sites devoted to getting Vitale off the air,
but others cherish the humorous, self-deprecating,
you-know-as-much-as-we-do style that is the hallmark of ESPN. Some
Web sites offer dictionaries to help decipher Vitale's own patter;
some pay tribute to Berman and the hundreds of nicknames he has
bestowed on athletes, such as Bert ``Be Home'' Blyleven and Roberto
``Remember The'' Alomar; others focus on the inventive ways
``SportsCenter'' anchors describe home runs, such as Dan Patrick's
``it's deep and I don't think it's playable'' and Stuart Scott's
``boo-yah!''
</P>
<P>
   In Vitale-speak, ESPN has made ``prime-time players'' of several
anchors. Berman, Patrick, Scott and Kenny Mayne are among fan
favorites still drawing a paycheck in Bristol, which is a hundred
miles from New York, a hundred miles from Boston, and across the
street from the world's skinniest skyscraper, which Otis Elevator
Co. uses to crash-test its products.
</P>
<P>
   Others have left the semirural charms of central Connecticut for
bigger bucks and higher profiles, notably Craig Kilborn, who jumped
to Comedy Central and is now hosting his own late-night talk show
on CBS, and the celebrated Keith Olbermann, who left ESPN to join
MSNBC, then left MSNBC to join Fox Sports Net, Rupert Murdoch's
ESPN wannabe.
</P>
<P>
   Al Jaffe, vice president of talent negotiation and production
recruitment at ESPN, says there's no requirement that a
``SportsCenter'' anchor be a comedian. The majority, in fact, are
pretty straight shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the heart of everything,'' Jaffe said, ``is sports
knowledge. There isn't one anchor here who doesn't know sports
really well.''
</P>
<P>
   But they also have more than a passing interest in literature,
history, pop culture, whatever, and can salt their sports reports
with esoterica pulled right out of left field. They do go overboard
at times. Movie buff Rich Eisen recently performed a spoof of ``The
Blair Witch Project'' to spotlight the Chicago Bears' quarterback
woes (``The Which Bear Project''). And Scott, one of ESPN's most
creative anchors, sometimes seems to forget he's doing a sports
show, not a comedy routine.
</P>
<P>
   Jaffe says management neither encourages nor discourages the
shticky stuff. Rather, it stresses the avoidance of ``cookie
cutter'' journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I don't want is the 40-regular, off-the-rack style,''
Jaffe said. ``When we're hiring, the question John Walsh always
asks is, `Are they smart?'''
</P>
<P>
   John Walsh is senior vice president and executive editor of
ESPN. A relative newcomer _ he came aboard in 1990 _ Walsh spent
much of his career in print journalism, including tours at Rolling
Stone, the Washington Post, U.S. News &AMP; World Report and Inside
Sports.
</P>
<P>
   He has overseen ESPN's expansion this decade, always aware that
good television starts with good writing. ESPN anchors write their
own material, and anchor applicants have to write a mock show so
Walsh can see if they're good writers or simply good readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can judge it by grammar,'' Walsh said, ``by the way they
choose their sentences.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh chooses his sentences carefully when describing ESPN's
impact on sports journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's presumptuous of me to talk about it,'' he said. But he
does remember going to a meeting of New England sports editors once
and being amazed at how many said they used ``SportsCenter'' as a
guide for the next day's sports pages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never dreamed it,'' Walsh said. ``It was unfathomable. I was
the last guy to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh is probably being modest, because he tends to agree with
Jaffe's contention that ``we are still the sports network of
record. Sports fans are afraid not to watch us.''
</P>
<P>
   That goes double for local sportscasters. ESPN has so changed
the sports landscape that the late sports reports on local TV
rarely provide complete, league-wide scores. They focus on the home
teams, figuring that viewers have already gotten their national
information from ESPN or a competitor like CNN/SI or Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Johnson, an associate professor in the Edward R. Murrow
School of Communications at Washington State University, considers
ESPN the sports equivalent of CNN. Just as we've become accustomed
to turning to CNN when national or international news breaks, he
said, we expect ESPN to be on top of the big sports story.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything is going to happen in sports,'' Johnson said,
``you pretty well know ESPN is going to have it.'' The corollary,
he said, is that ``local stations know they'd better cover local
stories because that's how they can distinguish themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ESPN programming is so pervasive that athletes can't help but
notice. ``SportsCenter,'' ESPN's flagship program of daily
highlights, is sometimes on the air as often as 12 hours a day _
three hours live and the rest on tape. Along with ``Jerry
Springer,'' it is a favorite in locker rooms around the country
because it's human nature to see if you've made the highlight reel.
</P>
<P>
   This has led critics to suggest that ESPN is changing the way
team sports are played, and some ESPN reporters are sensitive to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It concerns me,'' anchor Dan Patrick admitted. ``It concerns
me that we value dunks, that if you can dunk you're a great player.
That's not the way it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, Patrick decreed that one edition of
``SportsCenter'' be dunk-free. He said production assistants
grumbled, but they managed to comply until the final highlight,
when a dunk sneaked in because it's just one of those automatic
things that people don't even think about when putting together
highlight clips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were apologizing to the viewers because we showed a dunk,''
Patrick recalled with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   But the awareness has stayed with him, even if Dick Glover,
ESPN's executive vice president of programming, doesn't entirely
agree that ESPN might be showing youngsters an unseemly sort of
behavior by focusing, say, on Shawn Kemp's histrionics after a
dramatic dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Glover says ESPN would be roundly criticized if it didn't show
the complete truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``In point of fact,'' he said of this chicken-and-egg issue,
``we wish we had the power that people sometimes think we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most visible sign of ESPN's influence is the ABC
television series ``Sports Night,'' which Aaron Sorkin created
because he got hooked on ``SportsCenter'' while holed up in a hotel
writing the film ``The American President.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorkin wanted to create something that spoke to him the way the
accessible, intelligent people on ``SportsCenter'' did. He speaks
for sports fanatics across America, skateboarders and non, when he
says, ``I felt like this is a place I'd like to work. This is a
place where I could meet my best friend.''
</P>
<P>
   The ESPN empire
</P>
<P>
   Begun in 1979 by Bill Rasmussen, ESPN was controlled by the
Getty Oil Co. for the first five years. When Getty merged with
Texaco in 1984, it sold its 85 percent interest to Capital
Cities/ABC Inc., which had bought 15 percent of ESPN earlier that
year. ABC, now a unit of Walt Disney Co., sold a 20 percent
interest in the company to Nabisco, which sold its share to Hearst
Corp. in 1990. The 80/20 split between Disney/ABC and Hearst
continues today.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPN. Twenty-year-old flagship sports-television network
reaching 76 million homes.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPN2. Launched in 1993, the ``second'' ESPN now reaches 65
million homes.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPNEWS. All-day sports news network launched in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPN Classic. Created in 1997 when ESPN acquired Classic
Sports Network, a 24-hour channel featuring footage of historic
sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPN Radio. Launched in 1992, it's the largest sports network
on radio, with more than 600 affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPN International. Based in London, where an international
version of ``SportsCenter'' is beamed to 138 countries.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPN.com. The most popular sports site on the Web, it's the
successor to ESPN SportsZone, launched in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPN The Magazine. ESPN says circulation of the 18-month-old
publication has climbed from 350,000 at launch to 850,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ ESPN Enterprises. Created in 1992, it develops all new
products using the ESPN brand, including the ESPN Zone themed
restaurants, ESPN merchandise available in Sears stores, videos,
CDs and CD-Roms and books.
</P>
<P>
   Source: ESPN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
