<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAVARES: ANGELS LIKE `A DAY-CARE CENTER'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Angels president Tony Tavares is sticking to his
recent statement that everyone, from general manager Bill Bavasi on
down, will be evaluated at the end of the season and moves will be
made accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake about it, it's the players that will undergo
the most scrutiny. Tavares is like the tough school principal who
will try to expel any student he deems a misfit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a day-care center down there, not a ballclub. And
you can quote me on that,'' Tavares said Sunday night as he watched
the Angels fall 8-3 to the New York Yankees at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   If the message wasn't clear already, it certainly is now.
Potential and expectations don't mean much anymore to Tavares. The
lack of performance this season is inexcusable, Tavares said,
regardless of the rash of injuries the team dealt with from the
start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good teams find a way to overcome adversity,'' Tavares said.
``Bad teams make excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had another ``excuse'' Sunday, learning that
scheduled starting pitcher Chuck Finley had a sore back and was
unable to start. He went to the hospital for an MRI instead of
facing the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Finley has any reason to fear the Yankees _ he's
16-9 against them in his career. In Finley's place, Mike Fyhrie,
who has spent most of the season in the minors, made his first
career appearance against New York a short one.
</P>
<P>
   Fyhrie, who was given the start over Ken Hill, was given a 2-0
lead in the first inning but was gone by the end of the third with
the Yankees leading 4-2. Knuckleballer Steve Sparks allowed three
more runs, and Al Levine followed Sparks and garnered the
distinction of giving up the first home run to Darryl Strawberry
since his arrest April 14 on drug and solicitation charges.
</P>
<P>
   All the offense delighted the pro-Yankees crowd of 35,481,
prompting a sarcastic comment from Angels center fielder Jim
Edmonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always tough to play in Yankee Stadium,'' said Edmonds,
who made a diving catch but went 0 for 4 and was limping noticeably
after the game because of a strained right groin. ``It's always bad
when the Yankees are here, but it seems worse than normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, who is platooning with Chili Davis at DH but is not
eligible for postseason play, reached base four times Sunday with
the homer, a double and two walks. Derek Jeter, who began the day
tied with Boston's Nomar Garciaparra as the leading hitter in the
AL, had four hits to raise his batting average to .353.
Garciaparra, however, also had four hits and is hitting .354.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Fyhrie) started out nicely, but you can't make pitches in bad
spots to this lineup,'' Angels interim manager Joe Maddon said.
``When you make a mistake to those hitters, you know you made a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Angels to 52-84, the worst record in the
majors, one-half game behind the Kansas City Royals (53-84). The
Angels remain on pace for a franchise-record 100 losses. They can
avoid the century mark by winning 11 of their final 26 games. But
in their past 26 games, the Angels have won only six times.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels managed only three runs (two earned) off Yankees
starter Ed Yarnall (1-0), who was starting in place of a resting
David Cone. It was the major-league debut for Yarnall, whose name
was mentioned in the Finley trade rumors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
