<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS CAN'T CLOSE OUT RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The roof opened. The roof closed. The roof caved.
</P>
<P>
   Symptomatic of a season with little top side to it, the Mariners
kept the rain out but couldn't keep Jason Varitek in. The result
was another late-inning bullpen blowup and a 9-7 defeat to the
Boston Red Sox Sunday before 44,019 fans at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   Five hundred million dollars has brought comfort from the
elements, but inadequate protection with the game on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek, the Mariners' No. 1 draft pick in 1994 and
pennant-drive trade bait two years ago, launched two home runs for
the Red Sox, the latter a three-run jolt off reliever Jose Paniagua
that erased a 6-4 deficit and fueled a five-run eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Falling to 68-68 and 8{ games behind Boston in the wild card
race, the Mariners close out their four-game set against the Red
Sox today with a holiday matchup at 1:30.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the home club was treated to a Safeco first _ roof
closure midway through a ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   Under cloudy skies and the threat of rain, the retractable
ceiling covered the field during batting practice, was opened for
the first pitch and shut a second time once a rain squall was
unleashed during the top of the third inning. Sunshine couldn't
nudge it open a second time. Still, the huge steel contraption went
back and forth so much it could have passed for a waterfront street
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little different,'' said Mariners first baseman Ryan
Jackson. ``I never had experienced that before. That's the
convenience of having it. The weird thing is when it was closed, it
was nice outside. They couldn't seem to get it together there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor could his baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners let home runs by Ken Griffey Jr., Alex Rodriguez
and Edgar Martinez go to waste, and a potential 15th victory for
rookie pitcher Freddy Garcia slip away. All because they couldn't
register the final five outs in timely fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pretty tough loss, especially because we came from
behind to take a nice lead and we took it out of our own hands,''
Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   After an easy 1-2-3 seventh inning for Paniagua, the
right-hander bottomed out in the eighth. American League batting
leader Nomar Garciaparra led off with a single to right, one of his
four hits. A fly-out later, Jon Nunnally laced another single to
right, putting runners on first and third. Varitek then drove an
0-1 fastball over the left-field fence for his 15th homer and
second multi-homer game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Safeco Field, this was nothing new. The blown save was
the 16th for the Mariners, and eighth for Paniagua (6-11) in 11
chances.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the Red Sox save was credited to reliever Derek
Lowe, who accompanied Varitek from Seattle to the Red Sox in the
ill-fated 1997 trade for reliever Heathcliff Slocumb. As Boston
inches closer to the playoffs, the two former Mariners have played
vital roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things are happening right, that's all,'' said Varitek,
whose second-inning solo homer off Garcia was his first in 118
at-bats. ``I was thinking about trying to get the ball to the
outfield to get us one run closer. (Paniagua) got the ball over the
plate and I was able to get it out of the yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Varitek also prevented a Mariners run in the fifth when he
effectively blocked the plate from David Bell, who was trying to
score on a fly ball. Leaping over the catcher, Bell apparently
missed the plate as well and was tagged out as he walked to the
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, the Mariners couldn't argue the final outcome.
There were no ready excuses for the bullpen meltdown, a regular
occurrence in the past few seasons. However, manager Lou Piniella
did take a moment in the fifth to question the mound work of
Boston's John Wasdin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like every time Wasdin went to his belt buckle, the
ball sank pretty well,'' the manager said sarcastically, raising
the possibility Wasdin might have been scuffing the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Summoned for a conference, the umpires took no action. Case
closed. Roof closed. And, as far as any Mariner progress, road
closed.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
