<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ ENTERS RACE FOR BATTING TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The American League batting race has been like a
lonesome highway this season. For long stretches, the leaders have
gone miles without encountering anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   They might want to peek in the rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   That blur on the horizon is Edgar Martinez, his foot pushing
hard on the accelerator. Over the past month, the Mariners
designated hitter has come out of nowhere to challenge for his
third batting crown.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 2, Martinez was hitting .309, trailing then-leader Derek
Jeter of the Yankees by 51 points, well out of the AL's top 10.
Entering Sunday's game, he was fourth in the league at .339, just
10 points behind Boston's Nomar Garciaparra _ the closest he's been
this year to the top spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a month to go,'' Martinez said. ``I know I'm getting
closer. There's a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Martinez went 1-for-3 while Garciaparra was 4-for-5,
with both players homering. The splurge upped Garciaparra's average
to .354, 15 points higher than his Mariners counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra shrugged when asked about the batting title, which
would be his first, insisting it doesn't concern him. But he paid
homage to Martinez, saying, ``He's always been an unbelievable
hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Aug. 2, Martinez has hit .422 (47-for-112), collecting
five three-hit games and going hitless in just five games.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, he has zipped past a handful of guys, leaving just
Garciaparra, Jeter and the Yankees' Bernie Williams ahead of him.
And he's done it without leaning on the horn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of the way Edgar is: He works hard, he produces
every day and he does it quietly,'' catcher Dan Wilson said. ``You
do those things and pretty soon you're creeping up on a batting
title. I wouldn't doubt he would do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammates remember when Martinez was hitting around the .280
level earlier in the season, thinking that wouldn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   ``You knew he was going to go something like 40-for-45,'' Tom
Lampkin said. ``That's what's so amazing about him. He's going to
get (his hits). If not early, then later. He's going to bunch hits
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was the AL batting champ in 1992, hitting .343, and in
'95, finishing at .356. One more crown and he becomes the 10th
player to lead the AL three or more times. Those in this select
group: Ty Cobb, 12 (1907-'19); Rod Carew, 7 (1969, '72-'75,
'77-'78); Ted Williams, 6 (1941-'42, '47-'48, '57-'58); Wade Boggs,
5 (1983, '85-'88); Harry Heilmann, 4 (1921, '23, '25, '27); George
Brett, 3 (1976, 1980, 1990); Nap Lajoie, 3 (1901, '03-'04); Tony
Oliva, 3 (1964-'65, '71); and Carl Yastrzemski, 3 (1963, '67-'68).
</P>
<P>
   Martinez says he doesn't consciously keep track of the batting
race, but often sees listings posted on the Safeco Field scoreboard
and peruses them with passing interest.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates are cognizant of the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't help him any by not getting Nomar out,'' pitcher Paul
Abbott cracked, referring to a home run he gave up to Garciaparra
on Saturday. Abbott was not alone. The Red Sox shortstop homered
off Freddy Garcia Sunday, giving him three homers in three games
against the Mariners over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez has hit .322 or better in his previous four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``All batting titles are special,'' he said. ``I can tell you
'95 was a lot of fun. We didn't have a chance to think about it. We
were so into the pennant race, personal stats became secondary.
When you're way out of it, that's when you think about them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, if I'm close, it will be exciting the last
week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
