<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1959 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSYCOLUMN     09-06 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARITEK NEXT GENERATION OF CATCHER 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Jason Varitek is every manager's answered prayer: a
tough, switch-hitting catcher who wants to play every day. Of all
the deals that Red Sox general manager Dan Duquette has made,
perhaps his best is the swindle of Seattle that yielded Varitek and
Derek Lowe for Gas-can Heathcliffe Slocumb.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Varitek and Lowe for Slocumb. In Boston lore,
it's moving up there alongside Dennis Johnson for Rick Robey, and
Cam Neely for Barry Pederson.
</P>
<P>
   Varitek Sunday caught his 120th game, only one fewer than Most
Valuable Player candidate Pudge Rodriguez of Texas. In a
come-from-behind 9-7 victory over the Mariners, Boston's lumberjack
backstop hit a pair of homers and saved a run when he blocked the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Home runs are obvious. Varitek hit a solo shot to right-center
on a 3-2 pitch to cut Seattle's lead to 5-3 in the fourth inning.
The bigger blow came in the eighth when Boston's new star cranked a
three-run shot (No. 15 for the year) to give the Sox a 7-6 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Blocking the plate is something more subtle, and Varitek does it
well. On a Friday night at Fenway in May against the Angels, he
saved a run when he made Matt Walbeck miss the dish. Sunday,
Varitek denied Seattle's David Bell.
</P>
<P>
   With the Sox trailing, 5-4, in the fifth, Alex Rodriguez hit
what looked like a certain sacrifice fly to left. Troy O'Leary made
the catch, but Bell tagged at third and was significantly ahead of
O'Leary's throw. Varitek stuck out his left foot and Bell _
eschewing any kind of slide _ stepped on the catcher's foot instead
of the plate. Bell kept running all the way to the Seattle on-deck
circle and Varitek chased him and tagged him near the box seats.
Too bad we were spared the sight of a rundown between the on-deck
circle and home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been tough if he ran like Jacque Jones,'' said
Varitek with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the most focused players I've seen in a long
time,'' said Boston manager Jimy Williams. ``He certainly had a
great day today, not only with the home runs but blocking the
plate. There is no stat for that.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some stats that indicate Varitek, a 27-year-old
second-year player, is moving into the elite class of American
League catchers. He may not be Carlton Fisk, but he's moving up on
Rich Gedman. Varitek leads all AL backstops in total chances and
doubles (33). Rodriguez is the only AL catcher with more homers.
</P>
<P>
   So what about it, Dan? When you suckered Seattle with
Heathcliffe, did you know what you were getting in Varitek?
</P>
<P>
   ``He was drafted three times,'' deadpanned the Duke. ``He was
well-scouted as an amateur player. At the time of the trade (July
31, 1997), Jason still hadn't really established himself in
professional ball. He went to the Winter Instructional League in
'97, then, to his credit, made our club out of spring training.''
</P>
<P>
   Varitek shared the catching duties with Scott Hatteberg in 1998.
He hit .253 with seven homers in 86 games. They were still sharing
the job before Hatteberg hurt his elbow this spring. Now Varitek is
very much No. 1, and it shows in the trainer's room. After Sunday's
win, he wore ice packs on his back, right shoulder, and right knee.
He doesn't want to come out of a game, or a series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tough,'' said teammate Mike Stanley, a former catcher.
``That's the No. 1 thing you've got to be. Guys try to run you over
and you get hit with foul tips. There's so many different things,
mentally and physically. He's strong-willed.''
</P>
<P>
   And strong-bodied.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got barrel kegs for legs,'' noted Stanley. ``No one's
gonna run him over.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All you got to do is check those thighs out,'' added the
manager. ``He's got great trunks.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra, who has homered in all three games at Safeco,
teamed with Varitek at Georgia Tech and at the 1992 Olympic Games
in Barcelona. ``Jason's done a tremendous job for us this year,''
said Nomie. ``Catching all those games? That's unbelievable. He's
really been a big part of our game. He's definitely an intelligent
ballplayer and he's worked extremely hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Bret Saberagen, who has seen a catcher or two in his day,
compares Varitek to a young Todd Hundley. ``Like Todd, when Jason
first came up, he was so focused on his catching that his batting
average suffered. Jason's a great receiver, and as he learns more,
his batting average is going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   What else is there to know? Varitek was born in Michigan, made
it to the Little League World Series, and played high school ball
in Florida. He doesn't like to bring much attention to himself.
When veteran Rod Beck joined the Red Sox, Varitek gave away No. 47
because that's the number Beck always had worn. So now Varitek is
No. 33 in your program. Every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, every day,'' he said. ``We're in this thing to win, now.
Just that gets you through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
