<HEADER>
A1969 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOURQUE-BO     09-06 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOURQUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS' BOURQUE A CLASS ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Mass. _ If you didn't look at his face and only
watched him skate around on the first day of the Bruins' training
camp Sunday, it'd be easy to conclude 38-year-old Ray Bourque was a
28-year-old veteran instead. The experience is there, the
efficiency of motion, the block of granite of a body. He continues
to defy time and age.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque always has been happy to lead by example. However, when
it comes to the young players who have matured into seasoned
competitors, Bourque has taken an active role as a mentor.
</P>
<P>
   He was side by side with Gord Kluzak when the No. 1 overall pick
in 1982 broke into the league before injuries ended Kluzak's career
prematurely. He helped Don Sweeney gain the recognition he
deserved. He ushered 18-year-old Kyle McLaren into the league his
first year. The last couple of seasons, his pupil has been Hal
Gill, who is out of camp at the moment in a contract dispute.
</P>
<P>
   As stellar as Bourque's career has been, he said he takes just
as much pride in acting as a teacher to some very willing pupils.
It looks as if two prime candidates this year will be 19-year-old
defensemen Jonathan Girard and 20-year-old Nick Boynton, with whom
Bourque was paired Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy doing that, and I'm enjoying their progress,'' said
Bourque. ``I played a little bit with Boynton, and he seems to have
some pretty good composure. He had a great year in junior; they won
the Memorial Cup and he was the MVP, so he has to be doing
something right.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque knows Girard even better. Girard spent the summer
working with the same trainer Bourque uses _ Ben Leduc _ and
coupled with the fact that Girard spent a little bit of time with
Boston early last season before being sent back to his junior team
in the Quebec League, Bourque believes he'll come into this year
much better prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did Ben's program all summer, and he was tested three times
and he's in great shape,'' said Bourque, who added that team scout
Daniel Dore comes from the same area in Quebec as Leduc and put
Girard together with him. ``He's a great athlete, very strong. He's
very serious how he goes about his business. He's very dedicated.
Ben had a lot of fun working with him. He's got all the tools. One
thing he's got to do is stay with it. He has a tendency at times to
get a little relaxed. He's intense, but he needs to keep that
intensity constant, and if he does that, he's going to stay here.
He's got it all.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngsters who come to camp have grown up watching Bourque.
Many, like Girard, weren't even born when Bourque first started
playing, so Bourque said he tries to put them at ease. Some are
more apt to seek his counsel than others, and there are varying
degrees of intimidation when dealing with a player of Bourque's
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he gets a lot of queries from the young players,
Bourque smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on the person,'' he said. ``A guy might take a
little while to get comfortable around me, especially the first
year, but I try to go up to them early and try to point out a few
things to look for. As we go on, I keep doing that, and they'll
come to me and ask me about certain things. We're lucky, too, to
have a guy like (assistant coach Jacques Laperriere) who's so good
with the defensemen. He covers so much about the position that all
you have to do is kind of feed off him, and a lot of times you're
repeating what Lappy has been telling them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said he's enjoyed every playing partner he's had, and
they've all been important for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a blast with Gordie Kluzak,'' he said. ``We have a
pretty special relationship. Donny has gone on to be super solid
and overachieving. Because of his size and his heart, he's played
great. Kyle came in as an 18-year-old, and making the team and my
playing with him for the first year and him being a big part of the
club was great. Same thing with Hal. He was a big guy and they
loved his reach and all that, but they didn't know if he was going
to be able to play at this level. Then you've got Jaromir Jagr and
all those guys talking about him being the toughest guy to play
against. That's quite a feat after only a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Bourque's career will come to an end. He is signed
through this season and reiterated Sunday he won't make a decision
on whether to extend it beyond that until after he plays it out.
</P>
<P>
   With the retirement of players such as Wayne Gretzky, Dale
Hunter, Dino Ciccarelli, and Craig Ludwig in Bourque's age group,
it hits home how remarkable Bourque's career run has been,
especially since at the age of 38, he was a finalist for the Norris
Trophy last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt that way for quite a while now,'' said Bourque. ``I
know that I'm very fortunate and lucky to still be playing. I still
feel I'm at a good level. I'm not the player I was 10 years ago,
but I'm still able to be real productive and to be a part of this
team. I know I'm very fortunate to still enjoy what I do for a
living. When you see those guys retire, you just know your turn and
your number is coming up. I'm not looking past this year. I'll play
this year and see how it goes and how I feel, but I know there's
not all that much time left.''
</P>
<P>
   Time ticks on, and so does Bourque with Season No. 21 on deck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
