u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARINERS-B     09-06 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARITEK HOMERS KEEP RED SOX AFLOAT 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-MARINERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Yes, it's true, Jimy Williams admitted Sunday
afternoon. Even as his Red Sox were rallying behind Jason Varitek's
three-run home run during a five-run eighth inning that carried
them over the Seattle Mariners, 9-7, his mind was elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a nice win for us, a really nice win to come back,''
Williams said, ``but yeah, I was watching (the scoreboard) out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   That was more than his left fielder, Troy O'Leary, could say on
an inside-out afternoon at Safeco Field, which began with the roof
opening for the first pitch and closing when rain came in the
bottom of the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't look today, but yeah, everybody looks,'' said
O'Leary, who made two tumbling catches and threw out a runner at
home plate. ``Who won today?''
</P>
<P>
   Among the three teams contending for the wild-card spot in the
American League, only the Red Sox. While the A's fell to the Tigers
in Oakland and the Blue Jays were losing in Kansas City, the Sox
slew Seattle on the strength of Varitek's two home runs, four hits
by Nomar Garciaparra, including his third home run in three games,
and 6 2/3 innings of solid relief work by the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   With 25 games left, the Sox lead the A's by two games, the Blue
Jays by four and they also assured themselves of no worse than a
split of this four-game series with the Mariners, who had home runs
from twin terrors Ken Griffey (his 42d, tying him with Texas's
Rafael Palmeiro for the AL lead) and Alex Rodriguez (No. 35) but
could not hold the 5-2 lead they took against ineffective starter
Mark Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   While O'Leary did his part, he saw no reason for an assembly
around his locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about me,'' he said. ``This is about 'tek. He won
the game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Varitek, the catcher who once belonged to the Mariners but was
bounced to the other coast along with Derek Lowe for Heathcliff
Slocumb, the Human Angioplasty, ended a string of 118 at-bats
without a home run with his pair Sunday. He also blocked the plate
in the fifth inning to keep David Bell from scoring after he tagged
and raced homeward on Rodriguez's sinking liner nabbed by O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, who came up throwing, said he didn't think he had a
chance at doubling up Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I slid for a long time,'' O'Leary said. ``I don't
know what happened at home plate. I still don't know what happened.
All I know is I was running off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever John Wasdin, who was backing up the plate, saw exactly
what took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tripped over Jason's foot,'' Wasdin said. ``I kept saying,
`He didn't touch the plate, he didn't touch the plate,' because the
umpire (Dale Scott) never made a call. He just looked at Jason, who
might already have known it.''
</P>
<P>
   Varitek sped after Bell and tagged him out steps away from the
Mariners' dugout, which ended 2 2/3 innings of scoreless work by
Wasdin, who came under scrutiny from Seattle manager Lou Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept saying something about my belt, my belt,'' Wasdin
said. ``He was probably thinking, `That guy doesn't have anything
that moves like that,' after I threw a pitch that moved a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella went to Scott, who consulted with crew chief Al Clark
but never subjected Wasdin to a search.
</P>
<P>
   Wasdin was amused by the whole business. ``If they want to think
I was cheating, let them think that,'' he said, ``but that was kind
of weird. Maybe he liked my belt buckle. I bought it at Nordstrom's
on sale.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox scored two runs in the first but found Seattle starter
Freddy Garcia, a 14-game winner, to be no bargain thereafter. But
Varitek led off the fourth with a home run that made it 5-3,
Garciaparra homered (No. 21) to make it 5-4 in the fifth, and
though Seattle answered with Edgar Martinez's home run off Rich
Garces in the sixth to make it 6-4, Varitek would weigh in once
more in the eighth, this time against reliever Jose Paniagua.
</P>
<P>
   Singles by Garciaparra and designated hitter Jon Nunnally,
making his first start since his callup from Pawtucket, preceded
Varitek's blast into the right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``His first home run was a line drive that if it had been a foot
lower would have been caught by the second baseman but was gone
when it came off his bat,'' Wasdin said. ``The second one, they
tried to pitch him up and in, but Jason got on top of the ball. Jay
(Buhner, the right fielder) didn't move. He killed that ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox added two more runs on Wilton Veras's single, Damon
Buford's double and a base hit by Jose Offerman. Derek Lowe, loser
of the 2-1 heartbreaker that opened this series, gave up a run in
the ninth on Griffey's opposite-field double, but thrust his fist
after striking out Rodriguez for his 11th save, preserving Garces's
fourth win.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe, of course, came with Varitek in the trade for Slocumb,
when both were still in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot, it's not like either one of us were mainstays here,''
Lowe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trades are trades. We could have both fizzled out and been
done, and it would have been a good trade for them. But he's the
starting catcher, I'm the part-time closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trades are crazy. You never know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 0148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990906.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1981 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS     09-06 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS CAN BEAT TUNA WITHOUT THE HYPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ This week will be a fitness fanatic's dream
and a fisherman's delight.
</P>
<P>
   It's Tuna Week.
</P>
<P>
   Six days from now, New England's football team journeys to a
swamp known as the Meadowlands to meet the New York Jets in Tuna
Bowl V, the semiannual confrontation between the Ghost of Christmas
Past and the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   It is a football game whose size knows no bounds. If it were a
park it would be Yellowstone, not Fenway. If it were a building it
would be the Sears Tower, not the Prudential Center. If it were a
western it would be ``The Big Valley,'' not ``Bonanza.''
</P>
<P>
   It is BIG beyond big, a game like no other until the next time
they meet, in Tuna Bowl VI come Nov. 15 on ``Monday Night
Football,'' although in this case it will be MONDAY! NIGHT!
FOOTBALL!
</P>
<P>
   They are already gearing up their cliches for this event in both
places, preparing to talk about how it's just another game and it's
only one of 16 and, win or lose, it won't mean a thing if you don't
win the next Sunday, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity to get off on a great note,'' Patriots
coach Pete Carroll said Sunday of Tuna Bowl V. ``It's a chance to
take a full stride right from the get-go.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure it is. That's why Tennessee opened its season against
Wyoming instead of Florida State. It's why Florida played Western
Michigan instead of Michigan. It's why Arizona thought it had an
opportunity to get off on the right foot when it opened against
Penn State until it played the game.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, it's never a great opportunity for anything but
trouble to open your season against a great team, but this being
the NFL, that's the approach you're supposed to take faced with
such a situation. Ignore the obvious. Take a tip from our Commander
in Chief: ``Deny, deny, deny!''
</P>
<P>
   They will do that in Foxborough and down on Long Island all week
even though it's so far from the truth it's no longer even funny.
That will be especially true here in New England, where the
Patriots are 1-3 against Bill Parcells since the Tuna swam
downstream to become the Big Kahuna as well as the Tuna on Long
Island.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, truth be told, the Patriots are really 1-3 with
an asterisk because had John Hall not had a 29-yard field goal
attempt blocked in Tuna Bowl I by Mike Jones with 16 seconds to
play in regulation, New England would be 0-4 since Tuna was taken
off the menu.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, each loss has been bigger than the previous one, from a
24-19 defeat in Tuna Bowl II two years ago to last year's 24-14 and
then 31-10 defeats. That makes for an aggregate score of 103-70 and
increasing margins of defeat that began at 5, then doubled to 10,
then more than doubled again to 21. If this continues, the Patriots
not only will lose Tuna Bowl V, they'll lose it by 42 points.
</P>
<P>
   One has to assume the latter will not be the case Sunday when
these evenly matched teams square off, but nothing that was done in
the past few days _ either by addition or subtraction _ will change
what is to come.
</P>
<P>
   No departed players such as Sedrick Shaw or Damon Denson (who
were half of the Tuna Ransom the Jets paid in draft picks to Bob
Kraft to allow Parcells to skip town) will make a difference. Nor
will incoming ones such as nose tackle Bob Kuberski, a career
backup at Green Bay and Atlanta whose arrival Sunday was heralded
by some as if he were Curly Culp, even though it was closer to
importing Curley Howard.
</P>
<P>
   No, when they kick it off in Tuna Bowl V, all that will really
count is whether or not Pete Carroll can convince his players that
this game isn't about the Tuna at all.
</P>
<P>
   Several departed Patriots acknowledged after leaving town that
the team had in the past gotten too bound up in devouring the Tuna
and not focused enough on simply doing what it does _ which,
frankly, is playing pretty well on the days when it concentrates on
football and nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   On those days, the team Carroll picked Sunday can beat the
Dolphins as well as the Tunas, so the problem he will face all week
is not so much how to beat the Jets or even how to beat Parcells.
The problem will be how to make sure his team doesn't beat itself
by wanting too badly to prove that the Tuna is not the shark he
seems to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put things in perspective, everybody's going to talk about
this game off the charts and all,'' Carroll conceded Sunday. ``We
gotta go get it and it's a critical opportunity for us to cash in
on, but next week (the Colts) is just as important. Hopefully we'll
keep it in a good perspective and keep a good head about it and
play our best football.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think there's any question that's out there (that
his team in the past has gotten too keyed up for the Jets game).
You can go beyond where you need to go. You can get caught up in
the hype. So it's important that we're mature about it, handle it
well, and know that it's an immediate thing and just have fun with
it and the fans have fun with it and we go about our business doing
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything we do in our line of business is personal. We take
it all personal in all areas. But you can take it too far. Football
needs to remain No. 1 and winning No. 1, and anything personal has
got to be (left) in your back pocket for this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it does, because in Tuna Bowls I-IV it hasn't been left
there and the result was that the Tuna put them in his back pocket.
</P>
<P>
   There is but one way they can reverse that Sunday. The way to do
it is not to talk about how this is not Tuna Bowl V and not to talk
about how it isn't any different from any other game, but rather to
know it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   It is a football game. A big football game, to be sure. One of
the biggest of the year, because the psychological impact of
allowing ever-doubling losing margins to continue could be fatal to
the hopes of this new team in this new year. Yet it is just a game.
Still just one of 16.
</P>
<P>
   Just a game the Patriots can win if they look at it that way but
probably cannot win if they do what the rest of us will do this
week and turn it into another Tuna Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
