<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS ADD EXCITEMENT WHILE SUBTRACTING 15 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ With a team that too often finds itself in
emotional valleys so deep it can't fight its way out for entire
games, the Patriots coaching staff has been looking for a few
energetic souls to add some peaks to the equation.
</P>
<P>
   And so it wasn't shocking to see both seventh-round draft picks,
the magic act of Michael Bishop and Sean Morey, on the team's
53-man roster (plus supplemental draft pick J'Juan Cherry), which
Sunday was finalized, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop's presence on the roster was never in question as the
third quarterback, but Morey's was as the sixth receiver. The
Patriots have gone with five receivers in the past, but the team is
now gun-shy after losing most of its receiving corps to injuries
last year. So six were kept, and Morey will be used on cover teams
to add sparks and energy.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots resisted trading one of their veteran receivers
Sunday, just as they turned deaf ears on offers for Terry Glenn on
draft day. The team tried to make a deal for a linebacker, but all
the ones who were available were too expensive, including
Philadelphia's William Thomas, who will earn $2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   There was no real suspense, though the Patriots did part with
third-year offensive guard Damon Denson, heading the list of the 15
given their walking papers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Denson, who was one of the Bill Parcells compensation
picks and who started four games at left guard last year, the
Patriots also let go of sixth-round pick Marcus Washington, though
it appears that if the safety isn't claimed on waivers he'll wind
up on New England's practice squad.
</P>
<P>
   Another cut who could wind up on the squad is Garrett Johnson,
the rookie free agent defensive tackle from Illinois whose fate was
sealed when the Patriots acquired veteran Bob Kuberski. Johnson was
impressive throughout camp, but the team elected to go with eight
defensive linemen, with veteran Sterling Palmer the surprise among
the eight kept.
</P>
<P>
   The team also went heavy on linebackers, keeping eight,
including Ted Johnson. He was not placed on the injured reserve
list, meaning the team believes he can return from his ruptured
biceps tendon. The Patriots cut Billerica's Dana Cottrell and kept
backups Ron Merkerson, Bernard Russ, Vernon Crawford, and Marty
Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Also cut were linebacker Aaron Adams, tight ends Jamie Bowers
and Henry Lusk, cornerback Jayson Bray, defensive end Willie Cohens
(two sacks in the exhibition season), safety Kadar Hamilton (a big
32-yard interception return in the Carolina game), cornerback Corey
Ivy, wide receiver Anthony Ladd, defensive end Tim Martin,
defensive tackle Jon McCall, and defensive tackle Leonta Rheams, a
fourth-round pick two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The roster:
</P>
<P>
   QUARTERBACK (3): Drew Bledsoe, John Friesz, and Michael Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   This is the way it was going to be from the start. Bishop may be
the guy who plays if Bledsoe gets hurt for a long period of time,
but Friesz will go in if Bledsoe needs to shake off a minor injury.
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING BACKS (6): Kevin Faulk, Terry Allen, Chris Floyd, Tony
Carter, Harold Shaw, and Lamont Warren.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said Faulk and Allen will share the load, while Shaw
made it as a special teams player and possible change-of-pace
runner. Warren is the third-down back.
</P>
<P>
   WIDE RECEIVERS (6): Terry Glenn, Shawn Jefferson, Troy Brown,
Tony Simmons, Vincent Brisby, and Sean Morey.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem like too many, but the Patriots realize there's some
fragility in this group and they don't want to be calling on
40-year-old Henry Ellard to bail them out at midseason. Morey has a
chance to be a Wayne Chrebet type, and his brilliant 47-yard
reception in the fourth quarter of the Carolina game sealed his
spot.
</P>
<P>
   TIGHT ENDS (3): Ben Coates, Rod Rutledge, and Mike Bartrum.
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect world, Lusk or Bowers would have been kept as a
third tight end, but the Patriots went heavy on linebackers, so
Bartrum becomes a receiver as well as the long-snapper. Lusk's
dismissal also enabled the Patriots to pay Kuberski the veteran
minimum of $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   OFFENSIVE LINE (9): Bruce Armstrong, Max Lane, Damien Woody,
Todd Rucci, Zefross Moss, Heath Irwin, Jason Andersen, Derrick
Fletcher, and Ed Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Denson just didn't do anything to push the starting guards,
while Irwin did. Ellis won a reprieve, but if the Patriots need a
roster spot, he seems to be on the cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE LINE (8): Willie McGinest, Chad Eaton, Henry Thomas,
Brandon Mitchell, Chris Sullivan, Bob Kuberski, Sterling Palmer,
and Greg Spires.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots kept Palmer hoping he can be their Ferric Collons:
Stop the run and maybe be a decent pass rusher if his health holds
up. Spires is a good situational pass rusher and can reduce
McGinest's reps.
</P>
<P>
   LINEBACKERS (8): Tedy Bruschi, Andy Katzenmoyer, Chris Slade,
Ted Johnson, Vernon Crawford, Bernard Russ, Ron Merkerson, and
Marty Moore.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of quality, the Patriots went with quantity. If
Katzenmoyer and Moore are hurt for the Jets game, it may fall to
Russ and Merkerson in the middle. So many were kept because so many
are getting hurt.
</P>
<P>
   DEFENSIVE BACKS (9): Ty Law, Steve Israel, Lawyer Milloy, Chris
Carter, Tebucky Jones, Kato Serwanga, Larry Whigham, Tony George,
and J'Juan Cherry.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots don't have to count Cherry, a supplemental draft
pick out of Arizona State, for two weeks after the final roster is
set. There's still some concern about the nickel package, an area
the Patriots will continue to tinker with.
</P>
<P>
   KICKERS (2): Adam Vinatieri and Lee Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials were not available for comment on the final cuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
