<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAKEUP IN STORE FOR REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The campaign has started in earnest. Six
games remain in the Revolution's fourth Major League Soccer season,
and what occurs in the next few weeks likely will determine the
direction of the team for next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution will remain in the playoff race through games
against Kansas City Tuesday and at Miami Saturday. And if they can
rally as they did in the final six games of last year, they have a
legitimate chance of remaining in contention to the end, and also
of keeping the status quo for next season.
</P>
<P>
   During last September and October, many current members of the
team solidified their positions with effective and purposeful
performances. This is what they will need to do again to convince
management not to make major changes.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Revolution continue to falter as they did in a 5-1
loss to Tampa Bay Saturday, there surely will be an overhaul of the
team. The Revolution, and most of the players, will need a fresh
start.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is difficult to imagine the Revolution succeeding in the
next month. Not only do they carry the burden of having failed to
win in regulation time since July 4, they also simply do not have
enough substance in their game on which to fall back in difficult
times.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will they ever become a consistent, organized team without a
strong central defense. Imad Baba (groin) could make his season
debut Tuesday, and Leonel Alvarez (right quadriceps) could return
Saturday, but until the Revolution solve their problems in the
back, they will not win.
</P>
<P>
   Player-coach Walter Zenga had the right idea when he was placed
in charge last year. The foundation of the team needed to be
rebuilt, and Zenga started with the back line.
</P>
<P>
   If the Revolution could hold the fort in the back and the rest
of the team could be committed to defending en masse, they could
establish an identity. This pragmatic approach should have kept the
Revolution from the devastating blowouts that destroyed their
confidence last season.
</P>
<P>
   But Zenga overestimated the abilities and the resourcefulness of
his players. Zenga also might have overestimated his own coaching
prowess and his ability to inspire loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Once Dan Calichman began struggling with injuries in June, the
Revolution's difficulties accelerated. Soccer teams simply cannot
succeed without a strong central defense. The foundation of the
best MLS teams is experienced, quality central defenders. This does
not mean they need to be bruising, tough guys, because the position
also requires finesse and speed, and duties can be executed with
elegance. And though these defenders are usually the ones who
administer punishment, they are also vulnerable _ so it is a good
idea to stock up on them.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga had hoped to bring Giuseppe Bergomi to the Revolution to
bolster the defense. But if Zenga does not return next season,
there is little chance of Bergomi arriving. And unless the
Revolution can recruit a player with some of Bergomi's qualities,
they certainly will be in trouble again next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
