<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALMOST FINISHED AFTER THESE STARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ So much for fresh starts. For Lou Holtz, Tommy Bowden,
and Gary Barnett, the excitement of new jobs and new challenges
gave way to the harsh reality of game time over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   All three high-profile coaches, who took on new challenges at
different schools, opened their season Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   All three saw their teams lose.
</P>
<P>
   Not much was expected of Bowden, coming off an unbeaten season
at Tulane and having to reconstruct the program at Clemson, or
Holtz, who is at the University of South Carolina after a two-year
post-Notre Dame hiatus with CBS.
</P>
<P>
   And not much happened. South Carolina was washed out by its own
mistakes, the remnants of Hurricane Dennis, and a North Carolina
State team that is a surprising 2-0 after its 10-0 win over the
Gamecocks.
</P>
<P>
   Some Clemson fans feared the worst when they saw the Tigers were
hosting a tougher-than-many-people-realize Marshall team in their
home opener. They got it, as Marshall pulled out a 13-10 win.
</P>
<P>
   But the worst debut by far was Barnett's return to Colorado,
where he had cut his coaching teeth a decade ago as an assistant on
Bill McCartney's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Much was expected of Barnett, who coined the phrase ``Return to
Dominance'' in the preseason, hoping to spur the Buffaloes back to
the days when they were a national power.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Colorado proved it is not even the best team in its
own state as Colorado State pounded the Buffs, 41-14. The game was
marred at the end by an incident between unruly fans and police who
determined they needed to be quelled with tear gas and pepper
spray.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to blame me and you've got to blame my players,''
said Barnett. ``I know it's probably commonplace for us to stand
here and say we'll move on to the next game, but it won't be that
easy. We have to find out why this happened. This is going to
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   How bad was it? Colorado, which entered the game ranked 14th in
the Associated Press poll, trailed, 28-0, at halftime and never
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still hoping that I wake up and it's Saturday morning and
we're still in the hotel,'' lamented Colorado safety Robbie
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz's debut at South Carolina was not much better. Try this:
South Carolina was inside the North Carolina State 35 eight times
and came up with nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Holtz, looking every bit his 62 years after the game, talked
about a lot of things, including the torrential rains that pelted
the 51,500 fans who chose to spend Saturday night at Carter-Finley
Stadium in Raleigh. ``We just haven't had a lot of practice playing
in the rain,'' said Holtz. ``We haven't had much rain this summer.
And the few times it did, we had lightning, so we had to go inside.
We're not fast enough to dodge lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   Or North Carolina State.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Clemson, 85,000 fans came to Death Valley expecting a
revival of the program led by Bowden, son of Florida State's Bobby
Bowden, and coming off a 12-0 season at Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, my friend. Marshall took care of business early.
Clemson missed three field goals, including a potentially tying
34-yarder with 10 seconds left, and Marshall, a Division 1-AA
program only a few years ago, handed Clemson its first home-opener
loss since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Two other returning coaches did make successful debuts. Former
Southern Cal coach John Robinson won his opener at Nevada-Las
Vegas, beating North Texas Thursday night, while former University
of Miami coach Dennis Erickson won his opener at Oregon State,
topping Nevada Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was good news, bad news for siblings of Patriots. Patriots
quarterback Drew Bledsoe's younger brother Adam was one of the
victims of the Colorado State pounding. He and starting Colorado QB
Mike Moschetti were sacked nine times and combined for four
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   That was the bad news. The good news?
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Terrence Edwards caught 10 passes for 196 yards and two
touchdowns in Georgia's 38-7 rout of Utah State in its opener.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards is the younger brother of Patriots running back Robert
Edwards, whose career with New England may be over after he
sustained a career-threatening knee injury in a flag football game
during last season's Pro Bowl festivities in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Edwards, who recently bought a house in Athens, near
where he is doing his rehabilitation on the Georgia campus, was on
hand to watch his brother's college debut.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's a warning for Top 25 teams. Beware of Sonny Lubick's
Colorado State squad. Although the Rams have seldom been in the Top
25 during Lubick's tenure, his Colorado State teams are 9-8 against
Top 25 competition . . . Nice to see Texas bounce back from last
week's embarrassing upset loss at home to North Carolina State. The
Longhorns took their frustrations out on Stanford in a 69-17
victory. Naturally, someone had a criticism of the Longhorns
attack, which featured a superb performance by sophomore
quarterback Major Applewhite (17 of 27, 353 yards, 3 TDs),
suggesting that Texas's running game needed some work. Said
second-year Texas coach Mack Brown, ``If we score 69 points, I
won't worry about the run. We'll worry about that later.'' Since
Texas plays Rutgers next week, Brown shouldn't have too much to
worry about. The other Longhorn highlight of the evening was
hotshot freshman QB Chris Simms, who threw his first collegiate
touchdown pass. Simms's father, Phil, the former New York Giants
signal-caller, was in the stands cheering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stupid Prediction of the Week: Hawaii Gov. Ben Cayetano
predicting that the Rainbows, 27-point underdogs to Southern
California, and a team that hasn't won a game since 1997, would
upset the Trojans. Final score: USC 62, Hawaii 7 . . . Virginia
Tech, which had been temporarily shunted aside in the Big East
picture because of all of the publicity generated by Miami's win
over Ohio State last week, made its debut Saturday night against
James Madison. As expected, the Hokies rolled to a 47-0 triumph.
And, as predicted by many, redshirt freshman quarterback Michael
Vick had a spectacular debut, running for three touchdowns before
being knocked out of the game in a dive into the end zone. Vick
gave Hokies coach Frank Beamer and the fans in Blacksburg a scare
when trainers worked on him for several minutes after he flipped
over a tackler and landed on his ankle. X-rays were negative,
however, and Vick says he will be ready to play against
Alabama-Birmingham next Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Penn State coach Joe Paterno continued his two-quarterback
system in a 70-24 win over Akron, using starter Kevin Thompson and
junior Rashard Casey. Paterno never has been a two-QB guy, but he
is willing to go along with the plan for now. ``Both looked pretty
good and they have no problems with it,'' said Paterno. ``I'm not
trying to create a problem for myself, but I think both are
handling it well.'' Paterno probably can afford to experiment
another week since the Lions face Pittsburgh, but then comes a game
at Miami, which will be anything but easy . . . Part of Boston
College's opening success in its 30-29 win over Baylor can be
attributed to conditioning. For the last two years, most of the
Eagles have remained on campus during the summer, engaging in a
strenuous conditioning program. Eagles coach Tom O'Brien believes
conditioning was a factor in the win. ``Being able to stay on
campus the past two summers has helped, no question,'' he said
Sunday as he savored the victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 0158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
