<SLUG> BC-TEN-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS WILLIAMS CATCHES A BREAK 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She lasted through a hotter than hot start by Mary
Joe Fernandez. She lasted through _ and caught a break from _ three
rain delays. She took full advantage of a slip that felled
Fernandez and left her opponent with a strained right quadriceps.
</P>
<P>
   And not long after they turned on the lights in Arthur Ashe
Stadium at the request of several loud fans, No. 3 seed Venus
Williams rolled into the US Open quarterfinals after turning around
Sunday's match against Fernandez, 2-6, 6-1, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is on a collision course with No. 1 seed Martina
Hingis, who beat No. 10 Arantxa Sanchez Vicario, 6-4, 7-5. Just two
obstacles stand in the way of that Williams-Hingis semifinal:
Williams must get past Barbara Schett and Hingis past Anke Huber.
No. 12 seed Schett crushed Elena Likhovtseva, 6-0, 6-1, and Huber
upset No. 15 seed Amelie Mauresmo, 6-4, 6-4, to reach her first
quarterfinal in a major.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis made it an even dozen straight wins over Sanchez Vicario.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis, the 1997 champ, and Sanchez Vicario, the winner in 1994,
were headed for a second-set tiebreaker. But Hingis put away a
short ball and then watched a Sanchez Vicario shot go wide, making
it 15-40 and match point. Hingis nailed a forehand winner, and it
was over.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis beat Sanchez Vicario, 6-1, 6-1, in Canada last month and
knew she would be in for a tougher match on a bigger stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't underestimate anybody, especially right now,''
Hingis said. ``Not here.''
</P>
<P>
   No. 7 seed Todd Martin got his own breaks against Magnus
Larsson, winning the third-round match when Larsson retired with a
bad knee after Martin won the first set, 6-3. Martin knew Larsson
was hurting, but he still was caught off guard when his opponent
came over and shook his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, when he came up to shake my hand I was a little
surprised, because, you know, when someone is really ailing, it's
usually a bit more one-sided than one squeaky break,'' said Martin.
</P>
<P>
   In another third-rounder, No. 9 seed Greg Rusedski, the
runner-up at the US Pro at Longwood, knocked out Chris Woodruff of
Knoxville, Tenn., 7-5, 3-6, 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The day's play was delayed by rain (more is expected Monday),
which raised havoc with the schedule. Hingis's meeting with Sanchez
Vicario became a night match, as did several men's matches.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez had Williams moving all over the court in the early
part of their match. Fernandez broke Williams the first three times
she served and grabbed the opening set.
</P>
<P>
   Then the match turned. In the first game of the second set,
Williams was in a 15-40 hole,giving Fernandez three break points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went for a lob on one,'' Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 6 feet 1 inch, went up and drilled a winner on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask me why I would have lobbed her,'' Fernandez said.
``That was definitely a big game, because then I would have gone to
the other side with the wind. A couple games like that, and you
start thinking, `Gee, if I don't start playing better or winning
these games, I'm going to be in a big hole.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, she was.
</P>
<P>
   Williams broke Fernandez, and it was 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   At deuce in the next game, a light rain began to fall.
Fernandez, chasing a shot on the baseline, slipped and landed on
the court and sat there for a couple of minutes, hurting, and
taking stock of her situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how many body parts I hurt,'' Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   The players took what turned into a 90-minute rain break, and
when they came back, Fernandez was tightly taped. Williams quickly
took control of the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just started to move me a lot more, obviously,'' Fernandez
said. ``I think my balls were landing a little bit shorter, so it
gave her the opportunity to dictate play a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I started playing more consistently, stopped missing a lot,''
Williams said. ``Once you start doing that, you aren't giving so
many points away.''
</P>
<P>
   Huber survived her own rain delay _ and a case of nerves _ on
the way to beating Mauresmo.
</P>
<P>
   She had Mauresmo down, love-40, for the match when the No. 15
seed escaped the first match point. Then a round of showers led to
a quick break. When they came back out, Mauresmo held on for that
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very tight,'' Huber said. ``I was getting really
nervous. I said to myself when it was raining, `Come on, keep
quiet, concentrate, take it easy.' Somehow I couldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   She then held serve for the match.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 0200EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990906.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1987 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-MARTIN-BOS     09-06 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN VOLUNTEERS HIS OPINION 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-MARTIN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While such starving, destitute golf players as Tiger
Woods and David Duval hope somehow to subsist during their
miserably underpaid Ryder Cup weekend in Boston toiling for the
USA, a well-compensated tennis player named Todd Martin believes
everybody's got it all wrong. Including his Davis Cup employer, the
US Tennis Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody should be paid to play for his
country,'' Martin is saying after a semi-free ride into the US Open
fourth round Sunday. ``That means me and my teammates, too. The
honor . . . the privilege . . . that's enough. I'd really like to
see guys be proud to represent their country, and leave it at
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who'd labored nine sets in winning his first two matches
and expected to be severely tested by the lofty Swede, Magnus
Larsson, needed only 36 minutes. Loftier by two inches at 6 feet 6
inches, Martin came in shorter head-to-head (2-4). But Larsson
surrendered on losing a 6-3 set, unable to continue on a wobbly
knee, and the subtitled St. Elsewhere Open limped on, also claiming
Mary Joe Fernandez for an illustrious list of wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Rock-hard courts and a loonily overlong season are an unkind
combination for those depending on their bodies to make a living.
</P>
<P>
   In this golden age of greed, Martin may seem loony himself in
setting forth his radically unfashionable feelings about sporting
volunteerism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm an idealist, and that most of the guys disagree
with me,'' he says, sitting on a table in the trainers' room. ``But
I think the $25,000 additional the USTA contributes to a charity of
our choice is sufficient. That's fine. And some expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   He sounds like somebody out of the ``ask not what your country
can do for you, ask what you can do for your country'' 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   For quite a while, the USTA has paid its Davis Cuppers and its
female Fed Cuppers handsomely, although for some seemingly
embarrassed reason, the USTA tries to keep it secret, as though
amateurism were still in effect. The tennis players do a lot better
financially than the disgruntled US Ryder Cuppers, who may arrive
at The Country Club by bus or hitch-hiking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no problem paying our teams, and paying them well,''
says Rick Fermon, the USTA's executive director. But then he
refuses to say how much. I can imagine thousands of USTA members
and financial donors would be interested to know the amounts
lavished on millionaires to wear the red-white-blue. They are pros.
They get paid, and the figures should be public. Probably the USTA
can afford it, since the current Open will net $80 million.
</P>
<P>
   It is known that the US team, defeated, 4-1, by Australia at
Longwood Cricket Club in Brookline in July, got at least $50,000
for each player for the weekend, and also that the USTA was
prepared to pay Pete Sampras a million bucks for the season not
long ago. Sampras turned it down.
</P>
<P>
   The German Tennis Federation hired Boris Becker and Michael
Stich for a million apiece a few years ago, but that didn't buy the
Cup.
</P>
<P>
   In a postmortem on that lost weekend at Longwood, Martin agrees
that the US didn't put its best sneakered feet forward. ``The
singles lineup should have had Pete. Pete and I or Pete and Jim
(Courier). But Pete wasn't comfortable with it. He wouldn't play
anything but doubles, and the rest of the guys sort of agreed with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   He declines to knock the failed leadership, captain Tom
Gullikson, whose job is understandably shaky. Leading candidates
appear to be the telecaster Brothers McEnroe, John and Patrick, and
Harold Solomon, presently coaching Jennifer Capriati.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll play for anybody, and I have complete faith in
Gullikson,'' Martin says.
</P>
<P>
   I guess I'm as outdated as Martin in believing, as he does, that
athletes should receive no more than room, board, carfare, and the
charitable contributions for the priceless opportunity to flaunt
the stars and stripes. However, I must confess having accepted cash
for the same myself, $90 monthly as a US Army corporal, and I
concede it was a bad deal for the country.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Todd, how naive can we be?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I know we all hope Les Miserables of the Links can
get what they consider a square deal. Or will Tiger and the gang
have to pack their own lunches before going to work at The Country
Club? Don't worry. I know a couple of club members who've promised
to provide peanut butter sandwiches and chocolate chip cookies for
our side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 0201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
