<SLUG> BC-LA-LABOR-TOWN-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A.'S UNION STRENGTH AT 40-YEAR HIGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV AND BETH BARRETT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles has never been known as a labor city
like New York, Chicago or San Francisco. In fact, its history is
marked with anti-labor sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, as the nation commemorates Labor Day on Monday, nowhere
else will the celebration be louder than in Los Angeles, where
recent gains have made it one of the most union-active cities in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a banner year for us,'' said Miguel Contreras,
executive secretary-treasurer of the Los Angeles County Federation
of Labor, AFL-CIO, an umbrella organization of 324 unions with some
800,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had so many victories this year that it shows Los
Angeles and the rest of the world that the labor movement is
committed to Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past year alone, unions have added some 85,000 new
members _ 74,000 of them Los Angeles County home workers. New
members also include 1,600 teaching assistants at University of
California, Los Angeles, 500 Los Angeles County hospital doctors,
500 Metropolitan Transportation Authority workers and 6,000 Los
Angeles school district teachers.
</P>
<P>
   And other organizing drives are under way. Unions recently won
agreements from major firms at Los Angeles International Airport
and elsewhere to have a ``card neutrality'' program where employers
will not pressure workers against the union.
</P>
<P>
   So important is Los Angeles to the labor movement that for the
first time in 30 years, the AFL-CIO is holding its national
convention in the city in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``They chose us intentionally,'' Contreras said. ``When they had
it in Pittsburgh two years ago, they wanted to show an
organizational drive, and they couldn't find any. Here, in Los
Angeles, we were doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   So influential are the unions that the Democratic National
Committee, which only goes to cities with strong labor movements,
will hold its national convention in Los Angeles next year _ even
with a Republican chief executive, Mayor Richard Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the labor movement in Los Angeles and California
seemed near death.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say we were dinosaurs on the verge of extinction,''
Contreras said. ``We no longer mattered as part of the U.S.
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1990s, the portion of American workers belonging to
unions had dropped to 13 percent, down from 35 percent in the
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Pete Wilson decided to challenge the labor movement with
Proposition 226 _ which would have prohibited unions from making
political donations without getting member approval _ coupled with
his support of initiatives such as Propositions 187 and 209.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those put us in contact with Latino organizations and others
and we worked together,'' Contreras said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Mulholland, political director of the California Democratic
Party, said it did more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They painted over the rust,'' Mulholland said. ``Pete Wilson
brought them up to speed. They organized and went on to defeat
Proposition 226 and bring in an initiative increasing the minimum
wage to $5.75 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It raised the labor movement in California to one of the most
effective in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   And the unions were early supporters of Gov. Gray Davis in last
year's election, backing him against better-financed candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has paid off for them handsomely,'' Mulholland said. ``They
have key appointments in the administration and on various
commissions.''
</P>
<P>
   It also has resulted winning back requirements that employers
pay overtime after eight hours of work. In negotiations to create a
special transit zone for L.A.'s San Fernando Valley, one of the key
points has been making sure union workers do not lose any benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pete Wilson helped in galvanizing unions,'' said Fabian Nunez,
political director of the county Federation. ``He became the
bogeyman because he was trying to take away so many things such as
OSHA regulation, trying to end prevailing wage.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a long road from the farms of the San Joaquin Valley to
L.A.'s political power circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I would always be in a field with a bottle of
water,'' said Contreras, 47.
</P>
<P>
   He learned organizing in those hostile fields as a teen-ager and
during one particularly difficult strike in 1973, he was arrested
18 times for violating injunctions against picketing.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the farm workers union, he came to Los Angeles to
work with the Hotel and Restaurant Workers Union, where he met the
woman who would become his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Elena Durazo now heads that union. Together, they form a
potent team.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their union jobs, Contreras sits as a Riordan
appointee on the Los Angeles Airport Commission, and the mayor
appointed Durazo to the Recreation and Parks Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Contreras described his relationship with the pro-business,
multimillionaire mayor as one of pragmatism.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor knows we're here and that he has to work with us,''
Contreras said. ``Together, we can accomplish a great deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to say there haven't been disputes, such as over the recent
battle for a new City Charter.
</P>
<P>
   Contreras proudly shows off a picture in which he and Riordan _
with mock grimaces _ choke each other.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Kelly Martin said Riordan supports many union
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by political savvy and favorable court decisions,
unions have steadily entrenched themselves in government at all
levels in California, reaping salary rewards and some of the
nation's richest benefit packages as a result.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians depend on unions as one of their deepest election
pockets and are reluctant to buck them. So friendly is the
relationship, politicians have led the charge for living wage and
other labor-friendly changes.
</P>
<P>
   Unions have proved again and again to be decisive as perhaps the
most organized of election forces in the city. In the Los Angeles
City Charter Reform Commission election, for instance, they proved
decisive in electing the 15-member panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have won 12 of the last 13 elections in the city and
Legislature,'' Nunez said. The one loss was in the 14th Council
District, where Nick Pacheco, supported by Riordan, won after the
union came late to the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest boons to labor power has been something they
originally opposed _ term limits.
</P>
<P>
   Unions originally opposed the concept because they were able to
count on a cadre of political friends they had helped over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   Today, they put their money on new politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can marshal a block of voters for one election,'' said
Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Economic Development Corp. of
Los Angeles. ``In a lot of these races, there are so many
candidates, it's hard to tell the players without a scorecard. So
the unions are able to help decide on a candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Kyser warned, union gains could have an unintended effect
on the local job market and employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the longer term, you have to look at what will happen to
the businesses generating these jobs,'' Kyser said. ``Will they
move if the costs to operate become too high?''
</P>
<P>
   Kyser also attributed much of the recent union gains to the
state of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it starts to drop, how will that affect unions?'' Kyser
asked. ``No one really knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Kyser also pointed to the change in union membership from years
past.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, unions were primarily filled with white males
coming from the aerospace and auto industries. Today, aerospace is
dwindling and the auto industry _ which once had plants in the
region _ has all but disappeared from California.
</P>
<P>
   The new union members are younger and represent a more diverse
ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
   It is the growing influence of government unions that has
changed the way the labor movement operates, said Joel Kotkin of
Pepperdine University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an Achilles' heel for labor,'' Kotkin said. ``They become
so dominated by public employees that they will have losses where
they have had a traditional link with the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, they are becoming the advocates of an increased
bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Contreras sees no end to the growth of unions in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think conditions are right in Los Angeles,'' Contreras said.
``Two things are happening that resonate with workers. One is the
increasing wage gap between the high- and low-wage earners. And,
second, there is higher job insecurity, particularly in the middle
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``What unions do is help to create a better middle class.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
