<HEADER>
A1201 &Cx1f; var-z
u v BC-R-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      09-06 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Sept. 5, moved Saturday and are repeated Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   SMART-GENES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Now that researchers have shown
that mice can be made smarter, a whole world of opportunities opens
up. But there are serious ethical dilemmas involved. In mice,
monkeys and probably humans, nature has engineered a deliberate
fading of memory with age. Scientists have many caveats about
whether tweaking the genetic memory receptor would be helpful in
the more complicated human brain. After all, with too retentive a
memory you might clutter up your mind with all kinds of things
you'd be better off forgetting. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   WORK-HOURS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The much-acclaimed economic
expansion, now entering a record ninth year, may be attributable to
too much work. With the economy booming amid a labor shortage in
much of the country, there's so much work that needs to be done _
finishing that Web page, getting out that legal brief, putting the
final touches on those architectural plans _ that many Americans
are clocking 60-hour weeks. For many Americans, the 40-hour week
has become a fond, and unattainable, memory. A look at the pros and
cons. By Steven Greenhouse. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES-COMFORT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Just about anyone who has
flown in a coach section in recent years thinks that space is
getting more cramped and that airlines have installed narrower
seats and added more rows so they can wring a few more dollars of
profit out of each flight. But while the experience of flying may
indeed be worse than ever, airplane interiors have actually gotten
slightly larger in recent years. Boeing has done extensive
research, interviewing 10,000 people about what they hate most
about flying, and found that passengers tend to blame leg room and
seat width when they are really angry about other things. By
Laurence Zuckerman. (Eds: Will also move in `t' category)
</P>
<P>
   INVESTIGATIONS-REVIEW (Washington) _ Barely weeks after the
independent counsel law died and was bid good riddance, Washington
is astir with calls for a new round of independent investigations
led by special counsels _ on Waco, Democratic fund-raising, Russian
money laundering, etc. But wait a minute: Aggressive outside
investigations were supposed to be out of favor after the nation's
experience with Kenneth Starr's prolonged inquiry. What gives? The
answer is that things are back to normal in Washington now, even if
the legal mechanics have changed. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   TRADEMARKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Boom times have a trademarked
feel. Literally. It is harder and harder to get through the day
without tripping over the ubiquitous little `TM' symbol. Trademarks
flourish in a strong economy, and the boom of the late 1990s has
seen an increase in the trademarking of words, images and sounds by
at least 10 percent annually in three of the last four years. By
Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   BAD-WRITING-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ 19th century author Sir
Edward Bulwer-Lytton Edward has achieved eponymous infamy as the
patron saint of the Bulwer-Lytton Fiction Contest, an annual
competition held by the English department of San Jose State
University. The challenge is simple: ``to compose the opening
sentence to the worst of all possible novels.'' A look at some
examples.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GIULIANI-JUROR-REVIEW (New York) _ One angry man: what's the
verdict when the mayor is also jury foreman? Rudolph Giuliani's
upcoming jury duty raises the question of whether or not it is
desirable to have lawyers, politicians and celebrities serving on
juries. A look at the pros and cons. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   DC-URBAN-FOSSILS (Undated) _ Washington's hot asphalt streets
are just the right stuff for turning small objects that drop on
them into instant fossils. By Sarah Boxer. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-REVIEW (Jakarta) _ Indonesia, the world's fourth
most-populous nation, is deep in a crisis of economics, politics
and national identity. Its leaders and institutions have lost much
of their popular standing and even their legitimacy. The forces
that most overtly held Indonesia together _ the unquestioned grip
of a dictator and the harshness of his military _ have retreated
since the forced resignation 15 months ago of President Suharto. A
country so unsure of its unity that it has made oneness an
obsession is being forced to rediscover the logic of its
nationhood. By Seth Mydans. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   ARMS-CONTROL-REVIEW (Washington) _ By many measures,
international arms control seems to be on the verge of unraveling,
if developments in the U.S. Russia, Iraq, Iran and North Korea,
India and Pakistan are any indication. Why, then, are many arms
control advocates echoing the bullish declaration of former CIA
Director Stansfield Turner, `This is the most opportune moment in
past 40 years for nuclear arms control'? By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   LANDMINES-REVIEW (Washington) _ It has been two years since the
death of Princess Diana gave a last, emotional boost to an
international treaty to ban anti-personnel landmines, then being
feverishly negotiated in Oslo. Some say her efforts to draw
attention to mines may be one of her greatest legacies. But what
kind of legacy is it? Despite a treaty signed by 135 countries to
ban their use, production and stockpiling, antipersonnel landmines
appear to be as popular as ever in fighting wars these days. By
Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Tim Hilchey (e-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
</P>
