A2089 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBAC     09-06 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Sept. 12)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE EVOLUTION OF JANE &LR;  By Cathleen Schine. Plume, $12.95. This
clever novel uses the principles of natural selection to illuminate
the life of its heroine, a young American woman visiting the
Galapagos Islands. ``The book is a beautifully descriptive
travelogue ... loaded with mini-lectures on natural history,
evolutionary theory and Darwiniana, wrapped around a rollicking
family saga,'' Barbara Kingsolver wrote last year in The New York
Times Book Review.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WE WISH TO INFORM YOU THAT TOMORROW WE WILL BE KILLED WITH OUR
FAMILIES: Stories From Rwanda &LR;  By Philip Gourevitch. Picador USA,
$15. A New Yorker writer chronicles the massacre of as many as
800,000 Tutsis by the Hutu majority in Rwanda in 1994, examining
both the roots and the consequences of a genocidal crime carried
out not by soldiers but by neighbors, co-workers and relatives. His
ghastly account, selected as one of the best books of 1998 by the
editors of The New York Times Book Review, is filled with the
testimony of survivors, participants and witnesses. ``A grim book
this, and a burden on world conscience,'' Wole Soyinka wrote. ``It
closes the habitual avenue of escape _ anonymity _ for collective
atrocities.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AFRICA: A BIOGRAPHY OF THE CONTINENT &LR; , by John Reader (Vintage,
$17), digs deep into prehistory to track the emergence of Homo
sapiens and Africa's extraordinary diversity of life and terrain,
as well as the modern woes of the sub-Saharan region. Last year the
reviewer Thomas Pakenham called this ``a masterly synthesis of the
geological, climatological and paleontological discoveries of the
last decades.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GOLDEN CHILD &LR;  By Penelope Fitzgerald. Mariner/Houghton
Mifflin, $12. In the author's first novel, a stodgy London museum
is thrown into disarray when a wildly popular exhibit of an ancient
African king is found to be possibly fraudulent. The result is ``a
classically plotted British mystery ... leavened with a wicked
sense of rapierlike humor,'' Newgate Callendar wrote in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has reissued another of Fitzgerald's novels,
 &UR; AT FREDDIE'S &LR;  ($12), which takes place at a famous school for
child actors run by a formidable old woman renowned in the London
theatrical world. In 1985 the reviewer Roxana Robinson was
generally unimpressed but called this a ``well-mannered,
well-written'' novel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BASQUIAT: A Quick Killing in Art &LR;  By Phoebe Hoban. Penguin,
$15.95. A magazine journalist traces the hype-saturated rise and
fall of the charismatic painter who went from graffiti artist to
Warhol collaborator and art-world phenom before burning out on
drugs at the age of 27. Last year Patricia Bosworth called this a
``compulsively readable'' biography.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AT THE OWL WOMAN SALOON: Stories &LR;  By Tess Gallagher. Scribner,
$12. The poet's second prose collection is grounded in blue-collar
realism, often involving characters struggling to make do in the
logging camps and faded beauty parlors of the Pacific Northwest. In
1997 the reviewer Sarah Ferguson called these tales ``a bittersweet
mixture of deflated New Age wisdom and tired wonder.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HONOR'S VOICE: The Transformation of Abraham Lincoln &LR;  By
Douglas L. Wilson. Vintage, $15. This understated portrait starts
not with Lincoln's greatness as president but with the sources of
that greatness when he was between the ages of 22 and 33, searching
for identity and finding his way into law and politics. The book
``establishes Wilson as the leading historian of the young and
private Lincoln,'' Gabor Boritt wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ONE HAND CLAPPING &LR;  By Anthony Burgess. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $11.95.
Janet Shirley is a mild-mannered British housewife who is vaulted
into a world of luxury, courtesy of a loving husband with a
photographic memory who parlays his winnings on a television quiz
show into a fortune. Needless to say, it's a mixed blessing. ``Read
this witty and shrewdly joyful novel,'' Richard P. Brickner wrote
in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A WORLD TRANSFORMED &LR;  By George Bush and Brent Scowcroft.
Vintage, $16. The former president and his national security
adviser recount the Bush administration's major foreign-policy
challenges, including the collapse of the Soviet Union and the
Persian Gulf war. Their ``remarkably frank, intelligent'' account
is ``the most important book yet written about the end of the Cold
War,'' Fareed Zakaria wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE RIVER WARREN &LR;  By Kent Meyers. Harvest/Harcourt Brace, $13.
This first novel borrows from ``Our Town'' and ``Rashomon'' in
exploring how the fatal crash of a trucker and his wife shatters
the tranquillity of a Midwestern farming town. The author ``moves
cleanly from the event itself to an insightful inspection of local
life and its discontents,'' James Polk wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEST OF MYLES &LR;  By Flann O'Brien (Myles na Gopaleen). Dalkey
Archive, $13.95. This selection of newspaper columns published in
The Irish Times from 1939 until the author's death in 1966 pokes
fun at everything from Gaelic revivalists to plumbers, and displays
a finely tuned ear for common Dublin speech. In 1968 the reviewer
Benedict Kiely praised the ``humorous, satirical, learned,
grave-faced, crazy writing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
