<HEADLINE>
BEST SELLERS: PAPERBACK BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For release on Sunday, Sept. 12)  
(Eds: This file is the abbreviated best-seller list for paperback
books. See BESTSELLERS-PAPER-L-NYT for the full version that
includes how many weeks each book has been on the list.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rankings reflect sales figures for the week ending Aug. 28, at
almost 4,000 bookstores plus wholesalers serving 60,000 other
retailers, statistically weighted to represent sales in all such
outlets nationwide. The number of titles within the two
subdivisions of nonfiction can change from week to week, reflecting
changes in book buying.
</P>
<P>
   An (x) following a book's ranking indicates that a book's sales
are barely distinguishable from those of the book above. A (b)
indicates that some bookstores report receiving bulk orders for a
book.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. RAINBOW SIX, by Tom Clancy. (Berkley, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   John Clark, heading a task force, probes terrorist
</P>
<P>
   incidents.
</P>
<P>
   2. UNSPEAKABLE, by Sandra Brown. (Warner, $7.99.) A
</P>
<P>
   psychotic killer, returning to his Texas hometown
</P>
<P>
   to wreak vengeance, uses a troubled widow as his pawn.
</P>
<P>
   3. STILL WATERS, by Tami Hoag. (Bantam, $7.50.) A woman
</P>
<P>
   who is a newcomer to a small Minnesota town faces
</P>
<P>
   suspicion that she has committed murder.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE KLONE AND I, by Danielle Steel. (Dell, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A woman believes she has found Mr. Right, a high-tech
</P>
<P>
   expert, and then is amazed to meet his clone.
</P>
<P>
   5. POINT OF ORIGIN, by Patricia Cornwell. (Berkley,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Kay Scarpetta battles an old enemy, a serial
</P>
<P>
   killer resuming her crimes.
</P>
<P>
   6. THE WILDFLOWERS: Misty and Star, by V.C. Andrews. (Pocket,
</P>
<P>
   $3.99 each.) The first two novels in a series about teen-age
</P>
<P>
   girls from broken homes.
</P>
<P>
   7. TELL ME YOUR DREAMS, by Sidney Sheldon. (Warner Vision,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) Three women suspected of murder undergo a bizarre
</P>
<P>
   trial.
</P>
<P>
   8. SUMMER SISTERS, by Judy Blume. (Dell, $7.50.) Two
</P>
<P>
   young women from very different backgrounds come of
</P>
<P>
   age on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   9. FINDERS KEEPERS, by Fern Michaels. (Zebra, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   To escape her family's possessiveness, a Charleston belle
</P>
<P>
   flees to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   10. THE PILOT'S WIFE, by Anita Shreve. (Back Bay/Little, Brown,
</P>
<P>
   $13.95.) After learning that a plane flown by her husband
</P>
<P>
   has exploded, a woman tries to unravel the secret life
</P>
<P>
   he led.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE MERCY RULE, by John Lescroart. (Island/Dell,
</P>
<P>
   $7.99.) An ``assisted suicide'' causes battles in and
</P>
<P>
   out of San Francisco's courts.
</P>
<P>
   12. MEMOIRS OF A GEISHA, by Arthur Golden. (Vintage, $14.)
</P>
<P>
   The life of a young woman growing up in Kyoto who has
</P>
<P>
   to reinvent herself after World War II begins.
</P>
<P>
   13. RED, WHITE AND BLUE, by Susan Isaacs. (Harper
</P>
<P>
   Paperbacks, $6.99.) An FBI agent and a journalist
</P>
<P>
   track a paramilitary group in Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   14. MURDER AT THE WATERGATE, by Margaret Truman.
</P>
<P>
   (Fawcett, $6.99.) A law professor and his wife
</P>
<P>
   probe crimes that involve the White House.
</P>
<P>
   15. BAG OF BONES, by Stephen King. (Pocket, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A series of terrifying events besets a best-
</P>
<P>
   selling novelist four years after his wife's death.
</P>
<P>
   16.(x) THE DISAPPEARANCE, by J.F. Freedman. (Signet,
</P>
<P>
   $6.99.) Luke Garrison pursues the truth behind the
</P>
<P>
   murder of a media tycoon's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONFICTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. ANGELA'S ASHES, by Frank McCourt. (Touchstone/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $14.) An Irish-American writer recalls his childhood
</P>
<P>
   amid the miseries of Limerick.
</P>
<P>
   2. MIDNIGHT IN THE GARDEN OF GOOD AND EVIL, by John
</P>
<P>
   Berendt. (Vintage, $12.) The mysterious death of a young
</P>
<P>
   man in Savannah, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   3. A RAGE TO KILL, by Ann Rule. (Pocket Star, $7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Accounts of 10 cases in which men and women felt
</P>
<P>
   impelled by rage to murder innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE SEAT OF THE SOUL, by Gary Zukav. (Fireside/S&AMP;S,
</P>
<P>
   $12.) How daily activities can be enhanced by feelings
</P>
<P>
   of meaning and purpose. (b)
</P>
<P>
   5. THE PERFECT STORM, by Sebastian Junger.
</P>
<P>
   (Harper Paperbacks, $6.99.) The story of the
</P>
<P>
   nor'easter of 1991, focusing on a single crew.
</P>
<P>
   6.(x) A WALK IN THE WOODS, by Bill Bryson. (Broadway, $13.)
</P>
<P>
   A journalist finds beauty and humor while hiking the
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   7. UNDER THE TUSCAN SUN, by Frances Mayes.
</P>
<P>
   (Broadway, $13.) Life in the Italian countryside.
</P>
<P>
   8. GUNS, GERMS, AND STEEL, by Jared Diamond. (Norton,
</P>
<P>
   $14.95.) A physiologist attributes Western dominance to
</P>
<P>
   geographical advantages. (b)
</P>
<P>
   9. JOHN F. KENNEDY, JR.: A Life in the Spotlight, by
</P>
<P>
   Michael Druitt. (Ariel/Andrews McMeel, $14.95.)
</P>
<P>
   An updated version of an illustrated biography.
</P>
<P>
   10.(x) INTO THIN AIR, by Jon Krakauer. (Anchor/Doubleday,
$7.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ascending Mount Everest in 1996, the deadliest season in
</P>
<P>
   history.
</P>
<P>
   11. THE MILLIONAIRE NEXT DOOR, by Thomas J. Stanley
</P>
<P>
   and William D. Danko. (Pocket, $14.) An analysis
</P>
<P>
   of the lives of wealthy Americans. (b)
</P>
<P>
   12.(x) PRINCE CHARMING, by Wendy Leigh. (Signet, $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   A biography of John F. Kennedy Jr.
</P>
<P>
   13. THE GIFTS OF THE JEWS, by Thomas Cahill. (Talese/
</P>
<P>
   Anchor/Doubleday, $14.) What Western civilization owes
</P>
<P>
   an ancient nomadic tribe.
</P>
<P>
   14. OPHELIA SPEAKS, by Sara Shandler. (Harper Perennial,
</P>
<P>
   $12.95.) Dozens of girls, ranging in age from 12 to 18,
</P>
<P>
   discuss their feelings about themselves and about life.
</P>
<P>
   15. THE TEN COMMANDMENTS, by Laura Schlessinger and Stewart
</P>
<P>
   Vogel. (Cliff Street/Harper Perennial $14.) The significance
</P>
<P>
   of the Ten Commandments today.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ADVICE, HOW-TO AND MISCELLANEOUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1. DR. ATKINS' NEW DIET REVOLUTION,
</P>
<P>
   by Robert C. Atkins. (Avon, $14 and $6.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Ways to lose weight and achieve a healthy body. (b)
</P>
<P>
   2. CHICKEN SOUP FOR THE COLLEGE SOUL, compiled by
</P>
<P>
   Jack Canfield, Mark Victor Hansen, Kimberly Kirberger
</P>
<P>
   and Dan Clark. (Health Communications, $12.95.) Inspiration. (b)
</P>
<P>
   3. SUZANNE SOMERS' EAT GREAT, LOSE WEIGHT, by Suzanne Somers.
</P>
<P>
   (Three Rivers, $15.) The television personality offers a plan
</P>
<P>
   for losing weight. (b)
</P>
<P>
   4. HEALING BACK PAIN, by John E. Sarno. (Warner, $13.99.)
</P>
<P>
   Advice from a physician on how to deal with back problems. (b)
</P>
