<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 09:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2095 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-NY-GIULIANI-JUROR-R     09-06 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NY-GIULIANI-JUROR-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE ANGRY MAN: WHAT'S THE VERDICT WHEN THE MAYOR IS ALSO JURY
FOREMAN? 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Mayor Rudolph Giuliani swore to serve as jury
foreman in a Manhattan personal injury case last week, he set off
down a path many citizens but few famous folk have trod.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a settlement, Giuliani will spend Tuesday listening to a
final day of tedious, at times tortuous testimony in an intensely
personal personal injury case _ a man's claim that water in a
shower scalded his genitals so badly he has been unable to have sex
with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The six-person jury will then, under the guidance of their
hard-charging foreman, decide whether Oliver Johnson's request for
$7 million in punitive damages from his landlord is justified. If
the jurors rule that it is, they must put a dollar figure on the
pain (and deprivation) Johnson and his wife, Larene, have suffered.
</P>
<P>
   That Giuliani was called is far from noteworthy. Since loopholes
allowing doctors, lawyers and a dozen other professions to avoid
jury duty were eliminated in New York in 1996, an increasing number
of politicians, judges and celebrities have been called. The trend
is occurring elsewhere in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, Harvey Keitel, Robert DeNiro, Marisa
Tomei and Bernadette Peters, among others, were all called. Gov.
George Pataki was also called, and the state's chief judge, Judith
Kaye, has been called twice.
</P>
<P>
   But of that group, only Keitel and Giuliani were actually
chosen. (The mayor is not alone; other lawyers are empaneled with
him.) Though no definitive studies have been done, legal experts
say the mayor's pioneering service will provide anecdotal evidence
to a continuing debate about the wisdom of choosing politicians,
celebrities and particularly lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Trial lawyers have long shied away from choosing celebrities,
politicians, judges or lawyers as jurors lest they unduly influence
the others. A study conducted for the state court system last year
found that 61 percent of lawyers believed their colleagues would
have an undue influence. But in other studies non-lawyers said they
give lawyers no more credence during deliberations than other
jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Sonya Hamlin, a Manhattan jury consultant, predicted that
Giuliani will have tremendous authority as foreman. ``They could
turn to the mayor,'' she said, ``and ask, `What would be the impact
on the city?'''
</P>
<P>
   But others downplayed the mayor's impact. Vincent Homenick,
chief clerk of the Manhattan Jury Division, said anecdotally that
the judges and lawyers who served have not have enormous sway over
their peers. ``They're New Yorkers,'' he said, referring to other
jurors. ``It takes a lot for them to be overwhelmed by anything.''
</P>
<P>
   One lawyer, though, did go too far. A Manhattan judge ruled in
June 1998 that Ralph Gant, a lawyer serving as a juror in a civil
trial regarding control of a rent-controlled apartment, gave his
fellow jurors an incorrect legal definition during deliberations.
State Supreme Court Justice Shirley Werner Kornreich threw out the
verdict and ordered a new trial. A special committee has since
recommended that judges instruct jurors not to ask for or accept
legal definitions from lawyers serving on the jury.
</P>
<P>
   Some worry, too, that Giuliani, a likely U.S. Senate candidate,
who relishes the opportunity to express his views on civic duty and
the law among other topics, might use the case to make a political
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hamlin believes politics played a role in both sides'
decision to pick the mayor as foreman. ``The plaintiff's lawyers
imagine that he feels he needs to make friends in Harlem,'' said
Ms. Hamlin. ``The people who work for the landlord think he is a
conservative and he would want to prevent lots of suits like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Ms. Hamlin is right and whether Giuliani adds to or
detracts from the process _ all will be revealed this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 0911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
