<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 09:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2096 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-AIRLINES-COMFORT-RE     09-06 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-AIRLINES-COMFORT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAMPED? YOU'RE A BIT FLIGHTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just about anyone who has flown in the coach section of a
commercial airplane in recent years comes away convinced that space
is getting more cramped. No one appears to doubt that airlines have
installed narrower seats and added more rows so they can wring a
few more dollars of profit out of each flight.
</P>
<P>
   But while the experience of flying, especially in economy class,
may indeed be worse than ever, the industry insists it is not
because the plane is smaller. The fact is, airplane interiors have
actually gotten slightly larger in recent years, seats in coach in
most cases are a little wider, and there may even be more leg room
than there was 10 or 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Impossible? Yet true, say the airlines, seat makers and airplane
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, what constitutes a bad flight is of intense
interest to airlines and airplane makers. Boeing Co., which
produces most of the world's passengers jets, has done extensive
research, interviewing 10,000 people about what they hate most
about flying. What Boeing found is that passengers tend to blame
leg room and seat width when they are really angry about other
things.
</P>
<P>
   According to Boeing's research, two factors above all others
determine whether a flight is enjoyable, especially when traveling
relatively short distances: One is whether the plane arrives on
time, and the other is whether or not there is a person in the
adjacent seat. If your flight is late and there's somebody in the
seat next to you impinging on your sense of personal space, you're
more likely to also complain about other things, real or imagined.
(On long-range flights, more than 5,000 miles, comfort becomes a
much greater priority.)
</P>
<P>
   ``When a short-range flight is late, people said the coffee was
cold, the meal was cold, the seats were lumpy,'' said Klaus Brauer,
the Boeing executive leading the research about passenger comfort.
``Every phenomenon you can think of gets influenced by the halo
effect of the reliability of the flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Which may help explain why there have been so many complaints of
late about the airlines. This year through August, delays were up
nearly 20 percent compared with the same period in 1998, according
to the Federal Aviation Administration. During the summer, when
thunderstorms and the introduction of new radar screens at some
air-traffic control centers caused further slowdowns, they rose 36
percent compared with last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Airline executives have been complaining that the long-outmoded
and mismanaged air traffic control system is seizing up under the
strain of greater traffic. Improvements are still years away.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, thanks to a strong economy and powerful
computers that allow airlines to precisely gauge ticket demand,
more seats than ever are being filled on any given flight. In 1988,
the average jet took off with 62.5 percent of its seats occupied.
By the end of last year, the average had jumped to 71 percent,
according to the Air Transport Association in Washington. In
practice, that means most flights during peak hours are more than
90 percent full.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the traffic on the way to the airport, the long walk
to the gate, the fight to board the plane, the dearth of palatable
food during the flight, and you get some pretty unhappy
associations with flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airplane used to be the respite from a lot of these
things,'' said David Stempler, president of the Air Travelers
Association, an advocacy group. ``There were plenty of flights
where you could find extra room to spread out. Now, that extra room
isn't there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, improvements in technology have increased the range
of smaller planes. The Boeing 737 used to be able to fly only as
far as Denver from New York. But the newly redesigned models can
now make it from New York to Seattle, a six-hour trip during which
comfort, rather than on-time performance, becomes a greater
priority as the minutes tick by.
</P>
<P>
   But the dimensions of the seats themselves have not shrunk. The
width of a coach seat on Boeing's single-aisle 737 and 757, which
have the same fuselage, was about 17 inches until about 10 years
ago, when it was expanded to 17.2 inches, Boeing said.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus Industrie of Europe, now Boeing's only rival, likes to
brag that the fuselage of its single-aisle A-320 jets is 7 inches
wider than the 737. But most airlines still use seats of the same
dimensions, using the extra space for a wider aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Because comfort is more important on long flights, economy seats
on wide-body airplanes are slightly larger: 18 inches on a 767 and
18.5 inches on a 777. And of course, the more you pay for a seat
the more space you get. Business-class seats are now usually 20 or
21 inches wide; first-class seats in large planes are 22 or 23
inches across.
</P>
<P>
   And while it is true that in the last 15 years many airlines
have reduced the so-called seat pitch, or the distance between your
seat and the seat in front of you, the actual amount of leg room
has not diminished, said Brauer, the creature comfort expert at
Boeing. He said the older seat backs were about 4.5 half inches
thicker than today's, so even though seat pitch has declined by
about 3 inches, there's a little more leg room.
</P>
<P>
   But even if it is true that the airplanes have not shrunk, are
not passengers getting larger? Most studies do show that Americans
in all age categories have gotten heavier. But Brauer said the
scientific literature suggests that people have not grown as much
as the media suggest. In any case, he added, the expansion in the
width of seats on narrow-body planes by 0.2 of an inch and by 1.5
inches on the newest wide-bodies ``is far in excess of the
percentage growth of the species over the period.''
</P>
<P>
   Brauer also said people tend to judge the size of an interior
space at eye level. As a result, about 12 years ago, Boeing widened
the 737 cabin by 1 inch on each side. On its newer planes it molds
ceiling panels and positions lights to make it appear that the
cabin is larger than it really is.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines are also doing their part to try to make their
airplanes more comfortable. Together the nation's two largest
carriers _ United Airlines and American Airlines _ plan to spend
$900 million to outfit their fleets with new interiors over the
next few years. Many of the new coach seats will be equipped with
the amenities now found in business class, like foot rests,
adjustable lumbar supports and adjustable head rests.
</P>
<P>
   But they won't be any wider. Brauer, who likes to carry around a
tape measure, pointed out that even though most office chairs and
train and theater seats are no wider than 17 inches, they do not
seem to inspire the same amount of collective resentment as
airplane seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Seattle Opera House has 17.2-inch seats,'' he said, ``and
we sit there for years and years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 0912EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990906.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 09:12 </DATE_TIME>
