 NEWS AND FEATURE SUMMARY - No. 2571 - September 6, 1999 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are offering the following articles for sale. Please contact
us for availability your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
</P>
<P>
   1. WHAT DO YOU DO ABOUT MAO? On October 1, China will mark 50
years since Mao proclaimed the People's Republic before cheering
throngs in Tiananmen Square. In the best Communist fashion,
betraying a mix of pride and insecurity, China is giving Beijing a
virtual makeover in preparation. The big day will feature a
minutely orchestrated parade of 140,000 -- everything from Young
Pioneers in red bandannas to China's latest ballistic missiles. The
marchers will pass under the giant painting of Mao that perennially
hangs over Tiananmen, facing toward the mausoleum where the Great
Helmsman's embalmed body is displayed. But an unflinching look at
the half century of Communist Party rule is the last thing today's
leaders want. By Erik Eckholm. From The New York Times Magazine.
1,800 words.
_________________________________________________________________
2. THE SINGER SOLUTION TO WORLD POVERTY Do you like foie gras? Own
a Bugatti? Plan to buy a new TV set even though your old one still
works? Then, according to this controversial Australian ethicist,
you are helping to starve the world's children. By Peter Singer.
From The New York Times Magazine. 2,500 words.
_________________________________________________________________
3. BEWITCHED, BOTHERED AND BEWILDERED The U.N. Security Council has
suffered a disastrous year : ignored by NATO, defied by Iraq, and
hamstrung by great power vetoes. Here's how to fix it. By Richard
Butler. From Foreign Affairs magazine. 1,500 words.
_________________________________________________________________
4. FROM MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE :
</P>
<P>
   (a) CHALLENGING WOMEN TO WALK FOR HEALTHIER HEARTS Women do not
need to jog, much less run marathons, to reduce their chances of
heart disease. A new survey of more than 72,000 women shows that
those who either walked briskly for a minimum of three hours a
week, or who exercised vigorously at least 90 minutes a week, had a
30 to 40 per cent reduction in their risk of heart disease. By
Alisha Berger. 525 words.
</P>
<P>
   (b) IN PURSUIT OF AUTOIMMUNE WORM CURE There is a downside to
modern hygiene : children in relatively wormfree industrialized
countries have a much greater tendency to grow up into adults with
autoimmune disorders like rheumatoid arthritis, multiple sclerosis,
lupus and inflammatory bowel disease than their Third World
counterparts, whose immune systems are constantly exposed to
potential pathogens. By Andy Newman. 1,100 words.
_________________________________________________________________
5. GENETICALLY ALTERED FOOD WON'T CONQUER HUNGER Peter Rosset,
director of the Institute for Food and Development Policy and
co-author of ``World Hunger : Twelve Myths,'' argues that
genetically altered foods are not essential, despite our efforts to
feed the world. New York Times Op-Ed. 800 words.
_________________________________________________________________
6. FROM PROSPECT MAGAZINE (N/A U.K.)
</P>
<P>
   (a) INFERTILITY AND THE NEW BABIES New reproductive technology
is offering childless couples an alternative to adoption. But what
are the consequences for children who are not genetically related
to both their parents? By Katharine Quarmby. 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   (b) THE BRAND IS IT John Kay looks at why modern advertisements
contain no information. 800 words.
_________________________________________________________________
7. FROM NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE (N/A Australia, Brazil, New Zealand)
</P>
<P>
   (a) ALL IN THE MIND Is it ethical for surgeons to cut patients
open and sew them up without doing anything? By Philip Cohen. 1,000
words. (b) FLIGHT INTO DANGER So you think a jet plane is the
safest way to get where you want to go? That isn't necessarily
true. The fact that air travel is growing while the accident rate
is stable means that a decade from now, twice as many people could
be killed in air crashes. By Andrew Weir. 1,000 words. (c) SEASON
TO TASTE Campaigners hope that compulsory labelling will curb
Europe's unhealthy lust for salt. By Debora MacKenzie. 1,000 words.
(d) SOLITARY KILLERS Up to five metres high, they can strike when
the water is perfectly calm. Freak waves are threatening Europe's
coastline and our demand for high-speed ferries could be to blame.
By Mick Hamer. 1,500 words. (e) WINGING IT What if birds evolved
feathery forearms not for soaring through the air but for pouncing
on prey from a great height? A new theory flies in the face of
convention. By Graham Taylor. 1,500 words.
