</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   And the Hippo Begat the Whale
</P>
<P>
   How did nature ever get the idea of making a whale? Biologists
have found the answer by analyzing the DNA of whales and their
nearest terrestrial relatives, the artiodactyls, or even-toed
ungulates.
</P>
<P>
   Once there was an ancestral artiodactyl, this Just So story
goes, but its descendants did not get along with the bad-tempered
camel, which split off from the rest to become a separate species.
</P>
<P>
   The pig and peccary family was the next to depart, according to
the evidence of their genes, followed by giraffes and the deer
family.
</P>
<P>
   That left the hippo, a creature so aquatic that it gives birth
underwater. Sooner or later some hippos ventured down their river
estuary to the open sea, shed their hind limbs and shaped their
forelimbs into flippers.
</P>
<P>
   That, my children, is how nature fashioned the whale, and if you
don't believe it, you may consult the learned article by Dr.
Norihiko Okada and colleagues in this month's Proceedings of the
National Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NICHOLAS WADE
</P>
<P>
   Cars for the Credit-Challenged
</P>
<P>
   Detroit car dealer Mel Farr doesn't mind leasing used cars to
people with bad credit, as long as they don't mind driving around
with a gizmo on the dashboard that keeps their cars from starting
if they miss a payment.
</P>
<P>
   Those who lease from Farr must pay up weekly in order to get a
code to punch into the device on the dashboard. Anyone who is late
paying can still drive around, but once they turn the car off,
they'll find it won't start again.
</P>
<P>
   With lobbying help from the Rev. Jesse Jackson and financial
help from Wall Street, Farr, a former Detroit Lions football
player, said he was helping those who otherwise couldn't afford a
car. Critics, including Ralph Nader, worry that the devices could
prove unsafe, and said the interest rates of up to 25 percent take
advantage of the desperate. Farr counters that the high prices
reflect his risk.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBYN MEREDITH
</P>
<P>
   Israelis and Palestinians Agree to Agree
</P>
<P>
   After shuttling between both sides, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright announced that Israel and the Palestinians had concluded
an agreement to implement the land-for-peace accord they reached
nearly a year ago at the Wye River resort in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, which provides for more Israeli redeployments
from the West Bank, set a deadline of early next year for the
parties to create a framework for final negotiations and of next
September for a final settlement. Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
has expressed hope that negotiations will also resume with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Among the final sticking points was the question of how many
Palestinian prisoners would be released from Israeli jails. Also,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat had wanted the right to declare a
Palestinian state, but the Israelis were opposed to any
``unilateral action.''
</P>
<P>
   Deaths on a Roller Coaster
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey state investigators removed four cars from a roller
coaster in Ocean City to determine why a woman and her daughter
died on the ride. The woman, Kimberly Baily, 39, of Pomona, N.Y.,
and her daughter Jessica, 8, were at Gillian's Wonderland Pier when
the car they were riding slipped backward down a steep incline,
made a 90-degree turn and ejected them. There have been six deaths
on rides at American amusement parks so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   A Beef Over Burger King
</P>
<P>
   It is hard not to relish the idea of the humble Whopper
innocently entangled in the Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But this is no laughing matter to the parties involved, and
least of all to Burger King International, which somehow did not
realize that, through an Israeli franchise holder, it had opened a
restaurant in a Jewish settlement in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Burger King officials said the Israeli franchise holder misled
them into thinking the settlement, Maale Adumim, was located in
Israel, and company officials apparently never consulted a map.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after Arab-American protests, the company ordered the
Burger King name removed. The franchise holder refused. And now the
Burger King of Maale Adumim has become another contested fact on
the ground in the disputed territories.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DEBORAH SONTAG
</P>
<P>
   A Teachers' Strike in Detroit
</P>
<P>
   Teachers in Detroit's public schools went on strike, refusing to
work without a contract. That left 178,000 students on an extended
summer vacation, and many of their parents scrambling to find child
care.
</P>
<P>
   A settlement may prove slow in coming. Rank-and-file teachers
took a harder line than their Detroit Federation of Teachers,
rejecting the union leadership's recommendation to go back to work
with a 10-day bargaining extension.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers are concerned that a new school board is not taking
their views into account as it struggles to improve student
performance in a district where half the students don't graduate
from high school.
</P>
<P>
   They also object to being paid less than their suburban
counterparts. So far, many parents in this union town are
supporting the teachers.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ROBYN MEREDITH
</P>
<P>
   Fewer Applications For Medical School
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is sure why, but the number of people applying to medical
schools in the United States is slipping. A study published in the
Journal of the American Medical Association reported a 12 percent
drop since 1996 in applications to the 125 schools accredited by
the American Medical Association. But there is still no shortage of
candidates. The 41,004 applicants last year vied for 16,000 spots.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
