<SLUG> BC-R-INVESTIGATIONS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER WACO: DEJA VU _ AN OUTSIDE COUNSEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (The Week in Review)  
 (bl)  
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Barely weeks after the independent counsel law died
and was bid good riddance by everyone from President Clinton to
Kenneth Starr, Washington is astir with calls for a new round of
independent investigations.
</P>
<P>
   On controversial matters like the 1993 government raid on the
compound of the Branch Davidian sect in Waco, Democratic
fund-raising, and the possible diversion and laundering of
international relief money by the Russians, the administration's
critics have renewed demands for special counsels.
</P>
<P>
   But wait a minute: Aggressive outside investigations were
supposed to be out of favor after the nation's experience with
Starr's prolonged Whitewater inquiry, which encompassed the
president's sex life and led to his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   What gives?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that things are back to normal in Washington now,
even if the legal mechanics have changed.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law was supposed to take politics out of
investigations of the government, but didn't. It gave power to a
three-judge panel to appoint and oversee independent counsels,
taking from the Executive Branch the power of investigating itself.
</P>
<P>
   But after the Whitewater inquiry and other investigations of the
Clinton administration, the law became a popular target of
criticism. Democrats claimed it was being used for partisan ends,
while Republicans said the White House and its allies had resorted
to political attacks to taint legitimate inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   So the law was scrapped, and now the American tradition of
outside inquiries continues, with the risk of political taint at
least as strong as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure over disclosures that the FBI had withheld
evidence of the use of incendiary grenades in the Waco siege,
Attorney General Janet Reno on Friday announced her intention to
appoint an independent lawyer to re-examine the government's
handling of the Branch Davidians. The inquiry would not directly
involve the same kind of independent counsel that has been used to
investigate Clinton and members of his Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of the type of investigation, calls for
independent inquiries even after the expiration of the law were
entirely predictable, say former prosecutors and officials. The
Justice Department's credibility is at a new low after the Waco
disclosures, on the heels of its failure to get to the bottom of
the campaign finance questions. ``There is a lack of confidence
over the ability of the Justice Department to do its job,'' said
Paul Curran, a special counsel during the Carter administration.
</P>
<P>
   While Reno made greater use of the independent counsel law than
any other attorney general since its enactment after the Watergate
scandal, she was besieged by critics urging its wider use, and
seemed relieved by its lapse this year. In its place, she issued
new rules giving her broad discretion over the appointment of
outside counsels.
</P>
<P>
   The rules do nothing to resolve the problem of an outside
counsel's autonomy. To be credible, an outside prosecutor should
generally not be accountable to another member of the Executive
Branch, like the president or one of his appointees. But in being
unaccountable, a prosecutor may abuse his power and become
partisan, as Democrats have charged lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is always going to be there,'' said Terry
Eastland, who was a Justice Department official in the Reagan
administration and who has long been critical of the law. ``It
always has been there from the beginning and it is embedded in the
Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   President Ulysses S. Grant had the dubious distinction of
appointing and then dismissing the nation's first outside
prosecutor. The lawyer, John B. Henderson, was named to examine the
relationship between the administration and what became known as
the St. Louis Whiskey Ring, a group of Midwestern liquor distillers
and federal revenue agents who cheated the government out of
millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let no guilty man escape!'' Grant exclaimed as he opened the
investigation in 1875. But Henderson was dismissed after his
inquiry focused on Orville E. Babcock, the president's private
secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents Theodore Roosevelt and Harry Truman were among those
who later appointed outside counsels. And one of Truman's attorneys
general also fired an outside prosecutor, after that prosecutor
decided to investigate the Justice Department. Truman, shaken by
that decision, promptly replaced his attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   But the most infamous incident was the Saturday Night Massacre
in 1973, when President Richard M. Nixon dismissed the special
Watergate prosecutor, Archibald Cox, named by his Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   That action ultimately led to the adoption of the independent
counsel law. But, as is obvious today, it did little to quell the
political controversies surrounding sensitive government
investigations.
</P>
