<SLUG> BC-MARTIN-LAWRENCE-IN-BLUE-STREAK-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTIN LAWRENCE: COMEDIAN UNDER PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Martin Lawrence in a scene from the
upcoming film ``Blue Streak.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Martin Lawrence can't catch a break.
 &HT;    A major star with a long-running television show and several hit
films under his belt, Lawrence has been plagued by legal problems
that threatened to derail his career and health scares that nearly
claimed his life.
 &HT;    Los Angeles police arrested him in 1996 for carrying a loaded
gun, shouting obscenities and biting an officer.
 &HT;    Months later, he was back in cuffs for attempting to board an
airplane with a nine-millimeter pistol.
 &HT;    In late 1997, Tisha Campbell, Lawrence's co-star on the
television sitcom ``Martin,'' sued the funnyman for battery and
sexual harassment.
 &HT;    More recently, the tabloids have focused on Lawrence's battles
with his ex-wife over custody of their three-year-old daughter.
 &HT;    Finally, in mid-August, Lawrence collapsed from heat stroke
while working himself into shape for an upcoming film.
 &HT;    The 34-year-old comic remains in ``serious, but guarded''
condition at the Los Robles Regional Medical Center in Thousand
Oaks, Cal.
 &HT;    Just a couple of weeks before the latest incident, a noticeably
nervous but game Lawrence faced the press to promote his new movie
``Blue Streak.''
 &HT;    The action-comedy, which opens nationwide on Sept. 17, casts
Martin as Miles Logan, a thief who attempts to recover a
$20-million dollar diamond he'd hidden years earlier in an
unfinished building.
 &HT;    Now, the building has been finished, and serves as headquarters
for the officers of Precinct 37 in Los Angeles.
 &HT;    To find the diamond, Logan poses as a cop.
 &HT;    He fits right in.
 &HT;    Martin, interestingly, did little research.
 &HT;    ``I just had to keep my mind focused on being a thief, so I
really didn't have to research being a cop,'' he says. ``I just had
to be a good thief.''
 &HT;    And...
 &HT;    ``I was never a thief,'' Martin says, smiling. ``I stole one
Chunky when I was a little kid. And I took it back. It had a bite
out of it, but I took it back. I took a bite out of crime.''
 &HT;    Why?
 &HT;    ``It was just my conscience,'' he says.
 &HT;    Although he's been arrested a couple of times, Lawrence has also
talked his way out of situations. A bemused grin crosses his face
as he recounts one instance:
 &HT;    ``The police let me go a little early one time when they
arrested me,'' he says. ``I had some tears in my eyes. I had two
tears right here.''
 &HT;    He points to his over-sized eyes.
 &HT;    ``I wasn't acting,'' Martin says. ``I was serious. I said, `Hey
man, I'm not supposed to be here,' and they let me go. That was
cool.''
 &HT;    At the time of this conversation, Martin insisted that
everything in his life was cool.
 &HT;    He had completed ``Blue Streak,'' he enjoyed the support of his
family and friends, and he was gearing up for his next project, a
comedy called ``Big Mama's House.''
 &HT;    ``I'm having fun,'' he says. ``I'm just enjoying learning how to
not take certain things in life so seriously. I'm just trying to
have fun and enjoy (life) and respect myself as well as others.''
 &HT;    The pressures of stardom clearly got to Lawrence in the past,
however. He doesn't deny it.
 &HT;    ``I think you always have pressures,'' he says somberly. ``This
is just such a big industry. It's been going on since the
(beginning) of time.
 &HT;    ``So, it puts pressure on people. That's part of growing,
learning how to deal with those pressures and having the right
outlets.''
 &HT;    Lawrence grew up in Maryland, surrounded by his mother,
grandmother, three sisters and an older brother. He discovered
early on that he could make people laugh, and after eliciting
laughs during an open mike night at a local comedy club, headed to
New York City to give the city's club scene a shot.
 &HT;    An appearance on ``Star Search'' in 1987 led to a recurring role
on ``What's Happening Now!' an update of ``What's Happening?''
 &HT;    Lawrence then relocated to Los Angeles, and soon after performed
in an HBO comedy special which led to roles in films including ``Do
the Right Thing'' (1989), ``House Party I'' (1990), `House Party
II'' (1991) and ``Boomerang'' (1992) with Eddie Murphy.
 &HT;    Then came ``Martin,'' a controversial sitcom that cast Lawrence
not only as the lovelorn host of a Detroit radio talk show, but
also as the host's mother, Sheneneh. The series began in 1992 on
Fox and lasted five seasons.
 &HT;    ``We stuck to a regimen of what was real to us, and I think
people felt the energy and saw that we were having fun as well,''
Lawrence says. ``It showed.''
 &HT;    ``It was grueling, but it's worth it when you can get five years
out of it and you know that you've got an audience that's there for
you.''
 &HT;    As Lawrence's star rose, however, his problems increased. And he
found that fame can sometimes be a prison.
 &HT;    ``It can be a pain,'' he says. ``It cuts your privacy,
sometimes. You can't always just get out there like a normal
person. People want autographs. You're always questioned about your
weight or whatever. There's just a certain focus that you have to
have.''
 &HT;    Lawrence lost that focus several times, but his fans stayed
loyal.
 &HT;    ``They just say, `Martin, we can't wait to see you back out,'''
he says. ```We love what you do and damn them articles that dog
you!'''
 &HT;    Just before his latest crisis, Lawrence appeared to be on the
mend, dealing with his demons, shunning drugs and concentrating on
his career.
 &HT;    And during an interview, he spoke lovingly of his young
daughter.
 &HT;    ``I look at (her) as truly a blessing,'' he says. ``That's what
allows me to work as hard as I do, to take these dual characters
and things like that.
 &HT;    ``They're all to make a better way for her. I thank God for
helping me be in the position to do that.''
 &HT;    Lawrence once dreamed of achieving star status equal to that of
Eddie Murphy, Arnold Schwarzenegger and Bruce Willis.
 &HT;    But his continuing, high-profile problems could become an
obstacle to his grand ambitions.
 &HT;    As Lawrence himself admitted prior to the latest headlines:
``You can get the money that you want if you work hard enough ...
but there's a lot that goes with it. There's more to it than you
may think.''
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Blue Streak'' consult the
Columbia Pictures Website at www.spe.sony.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
