<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 11:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2133 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-KEVIN-COSTNER-IN-FOR-     09-06 1375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEVIN-COSTNER-IN-FOR-LOVE-OF-THE-GAME-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of actor Kevin Costner in the film ``For
Love of the Game.'') 
 &HT;     By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Kevin Costner is weeping.
 &HT;    Sitting on a hotel bed with his head in his hands, his body
shaken by sobs, he hunches over and shakes with grief.
 &HT;    Sandy blonde hair an unkept mess, handsome face beet red _ it's
not the kind of pose most ``A-list'' movie stars strike very often.
 &HT;    Not on-screen, and rarely in a $70 million movie.
 &HT;    For the love of a game called acting, Costner insists that
director Sam Raimi let him fall apart in his new baseball movie
``For Love of the Game.''
 &HT;    The crying jag happens after Costner pitches a perfect game. It
should be the most joyous moment in the character's life, but
Costner plays a loner sequestered in his hotel room, and it's a
hollow victory.
 &HT;    ``It wasn't easy for me to cry on screen,'' Costner says over
breakfast at the Regency Hotel in New York City. He looks
strikingly handsome in a beige Armani suit, and his blue eyes stare
like laser beams when he discusses his craft.
 &HT;    ``It wasn't even written that I would cry in the scene. I just
said to Sam, `I have this idea: let the cameras roll and don't stop
me.' Then I sat down on the hotel bed and cried. Everyone was a
little shocked and taken back.''
 &HT;    Costner is no stranger to a moment like this one. In many ways,
he is like his character, a man who appears to have it all. A
superstar millionaire with all the trappings of success, he has
mansions and cars and a slew of Oscars on his mantle.
 &HT;    ``There are still many days when I feel very alone. And I
shouldn't be alone,'' says Costner, a father of three who has been
divorced for six years from his longtime wife and high-school
sweetheart Cindy Costner.
 &HT;    ``I think we forget that actors are just people,'' Costner says.
``You know, I didn't suddenly just exist on this planet as a star.
I started out as a poor kid who grew up in Compton, California,
where getting a new pair of shoes was a big deal because we
couldn't afford it. Later on, I was a gawky teenager. I was just
another face without a name.''
 &HT;    He shrugs.
 &HT;    ``My life still isn't perfect. I still have problems. I get up
in the morning like any other father thinking, `How will my kids do
in school today?' I struggle with mundane issues: ``Do I let my
daughter go to this party? Who's driving the f---ing car? I want to
see this boy. I don't want you in the car with him.'
 &HT;    ``I have to deal with everyday concerns,'' Costner adds, ``and I
think that puts me on a level playing field with everyone else.''
 &HT;    He is back on the baseball field in his new movie ``For Love of
the Game'' opening Sept. 17. In the film, Costner plays an aging
superstar baseball pitcher who, during the course of one final
game, mulls over his life, his love and his losses.
 &HT;    The movie is a final chapter in what the actor dubs ``my sports
trilogy'' after ``Field of Dreams'' (1989) and ``Bull Durham''
(1988).
 &HT;    ``I've been asked if I'm afraid to go back to such familiar
territory as baseball. My answer is simple,'' Costner says. ``I
don't really have fears about what people are going to think about
any movie. If I try to anticipate how any movie will be received or
categorized, I think I'd just be paralyzed.''
 &HT;    Costner's return to the baseball diamond gave him a chance to
brush up on his throwing skills: at the height of his game, Costner
could pitch a speedball at 85 miles per hour.
 &HT;    ``I've heard that I could play for a minor league team,''
Costner says, smiling. ``The truth is I can't pitch 85 miles an
hour consistently. There were many days where I'd do 15 pitches and
then go have arm iced down from the pain.''
 &HT;    Also painful were stories Costner read about battles with his
director over control of the film.
 &HT;    ``We discussed this movie. But that happens on every film,''
Costner counters. ``I know the way I feel about movies, which is
really pure. I don't allow anybody tinkering with them for
commercial reasons. I don't like it. It could be a really good
friend and I just won't allow it. Maybe that's the trouble with
me.''
 &HT;    Costner has had other troubles with the media. He felt hostility
from the press when Premiere magazine listed his perks on ``For
Love of the Game,'' including what they claimed was a $4,500 a week
personal trainer.
 &HT;    Always up front, Costner doesn't skip a beat:
 &HT;    ``I don't think anyone would argue that I needed a good trainer
to do a sports movie,'' he says, evenly. ``I could barely get
through the f------ day when my arm hurt. But the flipside is that
I don't have a trainer on my next movie `13 Days' which is about
the Cuban missile crisis.
 &HT;    ``Listen,'' he implores. ``There is a lot of money tossed around
on movie sets. I'm not going to get into the details of it. But I'd
like to say that if I want a private plane to take me somewhere, I
take my own G3 plane. I pay for it. I don't live a lifestyle that's
out of line.''
 &HT;    Costner has worked hard for his G3.
 &HT;    He worked in marketing for about ten minutes, and decided to try
his hand at an acting career.
 &HT;    It didn't happen overnight:
 &HT;    He had one speaking line in ``Frances'' (1982), and his role as
a corpse in the opening credits of ``The Big Chill'' (1983) landed
on the editing-room floor.
 &HT;    He fared better in ``Silverado'' (1985), ``The Untouchables
(1987), ``No Way Out'' (1987), ``Field of Dreams'' (1989) and ``The
Bodyguard'' (1992).
 &HT;    By the end of the 1980s, Costner was one of the best-liked and
highest-paid leading men in Hollywood.
 &HT;    His ``Dances With Wolves'' (1990), which he starred in and
directed, earned seven Academy Awards, including best director and
best picture.
 &HT;    Then, Costner hit choppy waters with the much-lambasted
``Waterworld,'' which he acted in and also produced in 1995.
Critics were also unsympathetic toward his work as actor and
director on the futuristic parable ``The Postman'' (1997).
 &HT;    ``I don't look back and have regrets,'' he insists. ``I wanted
to make these movies. I'm proud of these movies. I hope they find
their audience someday.''
 &HT;    Costner says it will all shake out in the mix.
 &HT;    ``Look at Gary Cooper and Steve McQueen, who weren't really
appreciated as actors: Gary was thought of as being wooden and kind
of goofy. The press wrote mean things about Steve.
 &HT;    ``But now we think of them as legends. It's funny. I identify
with them because both have said they didn't really enjoy fame when
they were going through it.''
 &HT;    Above all, Costner says he will follow his own path.
 &HT;    ``I don't kowtow to conventional wisdom,'' he adds. ``I try to
be straight with people, including the media. On a movie set, if
you get a no, you get it from me and not an agent or a manager.
 &HT;    ``A lot of people don't have their fingerprints on the things
they do. They have other people do it ... That's not my way.''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``For Love of the Game,''
consult the official Website at www.universalpictures.com. And
don't forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
