<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2139 &Cx1f; tab-z
w a BC-POKEMON-STARBEAT-ART-     09-06 1445
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POKEMON-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE POCKET MONSTERS TAKE OVER AMERICA'S YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of animated Pokemon characters) 
 By LAUREL GRAEBER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although the Japanese have exported many inventions to beguile
American children, it's only since last fall that they've offered a
product equally intriguing to parents: something that sends 3- to
11-year-olds bounding out of bed at the crack of dawn, bright-eyed,
energetic and eager to start the day.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a high-tech alarm clock.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``Pokemon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon'' (pronounced POH-kay-mahn), which is short for
``pocket monster,'' finished the 1998-99 season as the No. 1
children's show in the United States, both in syndication and on
the networks.
</P>
<P>
   (Its Saturday broadcast had earned an impressive 22 share among
viewers ages 6 to 11.)
</P>
<P>
   The animated series concerns the quest to capture all 150
species (that's 150, and counting) of pocket monsters, which range
from fuzzy and cute to things that look like escaped mutants from
``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   And Kids' WB, part of the network, which now owns the exclusive
rights to show ``Pokemon'' in this country, is doing everything
possible to make sure these odd critters remain tops in children's
minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're focusing on what kids like the best: the creatures,
their evolution, the depth of the whole world,'' said Donna L.
Friedman, senior vice president of Kids' WB.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman vows to stay on top of the game, in the face of the
recent arrival on the Fox network of what looks like a blatant
imitation: ``Digimon,'' a Japanese animated series about, yes,
evolving digital monsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the No. 1 franchise with `Pokemon,' and the formula
for creating such a phenomenon is so far unknown to man or
producer,'' Friedman said serenely.
</P>
<P>
   ``So although many people will try to copy 'Pokemon's' success,
it will not be easy to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon'' has achieved its hit status in appropriately
Zen-like fashion: without displays of bloodshed or weaponry, or
even sophisticated animation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been an assumption that you can't grab kids unless
you're ultraviolent or ultra edgy,'' said Alfred Kahn, chairman and
chief executive officer of 4 Kids Entertainment, the New York
company whose various divisions produce, distribute and license
``Pokemon'' outside of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't. It's clever, and it's got a terrifically in-depth
story line.''
</P>
<P>
   The story revolves around Ash Ketchum, a 10-year-old training as
a Pokemon master.
</P>
<P>
   His education doesn't involve martial arts but a kind of mixture
of the Boy Scouts and safari hunting: aspiring pokemon masters tame
wild pokemon and collect badges that indicate their level of skill.
</P>
<P>
   (Ash's pokemon sidekick, Pikachu, who resembles a cross between
a koala bear and a chipmunk, is definitely at the cuddly end of the
pocket-monster spectrum.)
</P>
<P>
   The goal of pokemon trainers is expressed by the series's tag
line: ``Gotta catch 'em all!''
</P>
<P>
   A trainer usually captures a pokemon by sending one of his own
pocket monsters (they're not, by the way, pocket-size) into a
match.
</P>
<P>
   Although these battles involve the pokemon's special powers,
which range from electric to psychic, there's no gore.
</P>
<P>
   As for the trainers, they're likely to shake hands and offer one
another fighting tips at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon'' started as a video game for the hand-held Nintendo
Game Boy. But even though the series mirrors the game, that's not
the only key to its success.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the cartoon series ``Super Mario Brothers'' also came
from Nintendo and was far from a runaway hit.
</P>
<P>
   ```Pokemon' is like a soap opera for kids; the story never
ends,'' said Norman Grossfeld, president of 4 Kids Productions, the
corporate division that produces the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different from other shows, where the bad guy gets
battled and then it's over. Here, if you miss a show, you feel
you've missed something.''
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, where the series is about to enter its third season,
50 percent of children watch it, Grossfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon'' is also a hit in Canada, Australia and New Zealand.
It entered the British, Mexican and Latin American markets this
spring and will hit most of the rest of Europe next month.
</P>
<P>
   Amy B. Jordan, a senior research investigator at the
Philadelphia offices of the Annenberg Public Policy Center, which
studies children's television, attributes the success of
``Pokemon'' to its savvy incorporation of many aspects of other hot
children's properties.
</P>
<P>
   It offers the morphing qualities of ``Power Rangers,'' the
concept of animal nurturing that has fostered children's hits since
``Lassie'' and ``Rin Tin Tin'' and the collectability of Beanie
Babies (with ``Pokemon'' toys and trading cards, children can
``catch 'em all'' along with Ash and his friends Brock and Misty).
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of series-related merchandise has been
especially helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have lots of products, and particularly products in
other media, you set up this kind of symbiotic relationship,''
Jordan said.
</P>
<P>
   But although the ``Pokemon'' merchandise has fast become a
billion-dollar industry, the television program is only now
approaching profitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spend probably close to six figures a show,'' Mr. Kahn
said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the expense goes into Westernizing ``Pokemon.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the characters, as in most animi (the popular term for
Japanese animation), look generically Caucasian, the dialogue and
setting are steeped in Japanese culture.
</P>
<P>
   The American producers go through each episode frame by frame,
adapting the tone and remaking some of the characters'
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   James, one of the two human villains, is more flamboyant and
foppish than his slightly malevolent Japanese counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   He and Jessie, his female partner, have a catlike pokemon,
Meowth, who's a bit of a philosopher in Japan; here it speaks
Brooklynese, calling to mind Danny DeVito in one of his more
buffoonish bad-guy roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goals and physical humor of each episode are the same, but
word for word we change it,'' Grossfeld says.
</P>
<P>
   With all this time and money going into ``Pokemon,'' is it
high-quality entertainment?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not say that `Pokemon' is particularly enriching for
children,'' Jordan says. ``But on the other hand, I don't worry
about it as much as, say, `Beast Wars,' `Batman' or `X-Men,''' all
animated series that she said emphasized violence.
</P>
<P>
   And while Jordan does see some favorable aspects to ``Pokemon''
_ the games and cards encourage reading and problem solving _ she's
not sure it has staying power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be peaking now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not if the producers can help it.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-September, Kids' WB is going to push the permanent
broadcast schedule to 12 times a week, seeking viewers before
school, after school and on weekends with a mix of old and new
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   A CD of ``Pokemon'' songs was recently released, and new Pokemon
Nintendo games are on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this a feature film (``Mewtwo Strikes Back,'' in
November), and you have a full-scale Pokemon attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a huge audience that is just getting into
it,'' Friedman says. ``A lot of kids who haven't seen it yet will
be able to have their own Pokemon training now, right from the
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Gotta catch 'em all.
 &UR; c. The New York Times 1999 &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Laurel Graeber is a New York-based writer.) &LR; 
