<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2146 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-SALONS-SPREAD-VIRUSES     09-06 1186
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALONS-SPREAD-VIRUSES-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAIR AND NAIL SALONS MAY SPREAD DEADLY VIRUSES
</HEADLINE>
  By CHARLES DOWNEY 
 c.1999 magazine 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, when a woman sits down to have her fingernails manicured,
probably the last thing on her mind is catching a potentially
deadly disease.
</P>
<P>
   But back in 1965, a medical researcher looking for the source of
hepatitis B for a group of patients traced them all back to a
barber who unintentionally transmitted the virus by shaving them
with the same razor. The barber had used a disinfectant, but the
substance wasn't strong enough to kill all the germs.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers are now asking if poorly trained cosmetologists and
barbers using dirty instruments could be unwittingly spreading
diseases such as AIDs, hepatitis B and C and viral infections.
</P>
<P>
   A Texas dermatologist, Shelly A. Sekula, M.D., has closely
looked into the sanitary practices of the cosmetology and barber
industry and found conditions lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Sanitation in nail and hair salons and barber shops is important
because medical researchers say 4 million Americans now have
hepatitis B. But 10 percent of those cases have no known cause.
Many hepatitis B patients later develop cirrhosis, liver failure
and even liver cancer and tragically pass the virus on to others,
including newborns.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers investigating hepatitis C cases say 30 percent of
patients have not shared needles with another illicit drug user _
the chief means of transmission.
</P>
<P>
   So where could the unexplained cases be coming from?
</P>
<P>
   ''Nail and hair salons may be a source of blood-borne as well as
other infectious diseases,'' says Dr. Sekula who practices in
Houston, Texas, and chairs the Legislation Committee for the Texas
Dermatological Society. ''There is good evidence that razors, nail
files, barber's scissors, tattoo needles, and body piercing
instruments are risk factors for transmitting hepatitis B and C.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sekula's interest began when she saw a patient with a
contagious fungal infection on her toes and feet. The patient
remarked that a pedicurist had only given her ''one little cut.''
</P>
<P>
   ''And the red warning flags went up,'' Dr. Sekula says. ''If I
were going into a nail salon, I would look for a photo license of
th operator. I would also ask about sterilization procedures and
would not permit an electric drill to be used on my nails. Nail
drills whir so fast they can easily penetrate the nail and cut
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Phoebe Rich, M.D., president of the Council for Nail
Disorders in Schaumburg, Ill.: ''There is a potential for the
spread of infection if the salon instruments are not properly cared
for.''
</P>
<P>
   The best sterilization methods are steam, ethylene oxide gas,
dry heat and chemical germicides.
</P>
<P>
   Anything that can draw blood _ nail nippers, cuticle scissors,
callus paring blades, reusable and straight razors _ should be
soaked in a chemical germicide.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, most states only require cosmetologists and barbers
to use a low-level hospital grade disinfectant _ which may or may
not kill all the microorganisms,'' Dr. Sekula says. ''To really be
safe, I suggest bringing your own instruments.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there's another huge safety edge _ wearing latex
gloves _ although cosmetologist rarely use them.
</P>
<P>
   Why? If you sat down in a salon for a manicure or a pedicure and
the technician put on a pair of rubber gloves, you probably might
think she has some contagious condition.
</P>
<P>
   But actually, she would be protecting you from any ailments
suffered by the previous client. Many professionals _ health and
dental workers, emergency teams, firefighters, cops, correctional
officers and others _ routinely wear latex gloves because they are
using a technique known as ''universal precaution.'' That means
limiting the spread of blood diseases by assuming everybody's
blood, bodily fluids and tissues are at all times infectious.
</P>
<P>
   ''The federal Occupational Safety and Health Administration
(OSHA) requires any worker at risk of contracting an infection to
wear gloves,'' Dr. Sekula says. ''But, curiously, OSHA regulations
leave it to employers and the various states to decide if workers
in the cosmetology and barber industries should wear gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a previous client in a salon may have an injury to
the cuticles, a cut in the nail folds or could have bled when
calluses were removed too deeply. A hair cutter could have
accidentally nicked the client. Customers could have had open areas
or cracks in their scalps. Crusts, scale and lice can attach to
combs and brushes and easily transmit infection or infestation to
the next unwitting patron.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, a warning that barber scissors and razors contaminated
with blood can pass along the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV)
was sounded. A medical researcher found hepatitis C could be
transmitted on the straight razors commonly used in barbershops to
trim sideburns and necks. The researcher dunked razors from five
different barber shops into five commonly used sterilizing
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Results? None of the five solutions destroyed hepatitis C, even
thought some were soaked for six hours, 24 hours and seven days.
</P>
<P>
   ''Other research shows hepatitis B can survive outside the body
for seven days or more on chairs, headrests, workbenches,
instruments and tools,'' Dr. Sekula says. ''Hepatitis B is 100
times more contagious than the HIV virus.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Centers for Disease Control (CDC) in Atlanta,
Ga., hepatitis B is now the United States' leading cause of liver
transplantation and the second leading cause of cirrhosis, after
alcohol. About 10,000 Americans will contract hepatitis B this year
with that number expected to triple over the next two decades.
Currently, the CDC says hepatitis B costs the United States $700
million yearly in lost work and health care costs.
</P>
<P>
   Cuts, nicks and scrapes at the beauty salon or barber shop can
led to other less deadly conditions for both clients and shop
operators. Risks also include warts, bacterial and fungus
infections and reactions to various products and fumes.
</P>
<P>
   But, says Dr. Sekula, ''The risks would be virtually eliminated
if operators used disposable instruments, wore rubber gloves,
employed proper hand washing and used appropriate sterilization
techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   She would also like to see physicians appointed to the governing
boards in every state so the beauty industry could have the latest
health information.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Charles Downey is a California-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
