<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hog's lard and chicken droppings: The stuff homemade cures are
made of
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ According to a crumbling paperback I found in
a box of stuff a neighbor was throwing out (The Standard
Cyclopaedia of Useful Knowledge, F.M. Lupton, New York, November,
1896), baldness is curable. I thought you'd want to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``In two ounces of spirits of wine,'' the practicioner advises,
``steep two drachms of cantharides (pulverized) for a fortnight or
three weeks shaking it repeatedly during that time. Then filter it,
and rub up one-tenth of the tincture so procured, with nine-tenths
of cold hog's lard. Scent it with a few drops of any kind of
perfume, and rub it well into the head every morning and evening.''
</P>
<P>
   The only obstacles I can see to this cure might be finding a
drachm measure, figuring out what cantharides is so you can
pulverize some, and finding friends who don't mind hanging out with
a guy who smears lard on his head twice a day.
</P>
<P>
   But, there are alternatives. They come in my morning mail.
</P>
<P>
   Generous readers often take the time to share with me a few
hints of their own. I'll pass them on, but I make no guarantees
because it's a little tough to know when someone's pulling my leg
through the mail. You be the judge.
</P>
<P>
   An Illinois reader who apologizes for his broken English because
he's just visiting here from his home on the Baltic, swears his
cure for baldness has worked for half the male population of his
village. (Note: He does not name his hometown or give any clue to
exactly (SET ITAL)where(END ITAL) on the Baltic it might be. For
good reason, I'm sure, because after reading his remedy for hair
loss, I suspect he'd have his passport pulled and be stripped of
membership at the local Baltic equivalent of the Elks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men do not need to lose hair if they take precaution before
it's too late since this cure is not retroactive.'' All they need
do, he suggests, is put on clean socks each morning and fill their
shoes with fresh chicken droppings. He says it works far better if
the person under treatment is active all day like a floorwalker in
a department store rather than a streetcar conductor who just sits
on a stool and clangs his bell. He does suggest avoiding
restaurants and elevators until the cure is complete.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months ago, readers were clamoring for a cure for
the common cold so I thumbed the dog-eared little reference book
and found a few simple remedies based on pine pitch, borax, and
camphor spirits, which I happily shared.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the moment, a reader in Iowa wrote to offer his own:
``When I feel a cold coming on, I have my wife slather Vicks on the
bottoms of my feet. Then she puts some heavy socks on and brings me
the juice of three onions generously laced with peach schnappes in
my favorite cup.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear just who's wearing the heavy socks but the
writer swears that by morning he is sniffle-free.
</P>
<P>
   An Ohio reader thanks me for adding a little ``spice'' to her
life. ``I am 71 years old,'' she writes, ``and do not remember some
of the really old remedies. Every spring my father would talk of my
taking Epsom salts (inwardly). I believe this might have helped
acne, but my memory is not clear. I still use Epsom salts but only
as a soak for minor bites. I am not sure either if I ever really
took it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we used was `sheep dip' for minor cuts, etc. I was
expected to climb only one small tree, and not to take any chances.
There was no time for anyone to take me to the hospital. I never
had a broken bone. I was hurt on the school playground, but there
were never any x-rays considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that after I had scarlet fever all the items I
looked at were burned, including one of my favorite books. The
doctor made house calls then.''
</P>
<P>
   I too remember those days ... and those doctors _ mine brought
Juicy Fruit chewing gum.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, thanks for writing folks, and as a bonus, I have another
tip for you straight from the Cyclopaedia: ``People who chew plenty
of good beef and eschew pork are sensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming next week: A Lesson in Decorating: ``Choose a plain,
smooth red-clay flowerpot. If it is rather stupid-looking, all the
better. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
