<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dog walkers sniff out the seasons
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Sometimes it takes a dog to sniff out
what's changing around you.
</P>
<P>
   The one I used helped me determine that summer might end. These
results are still inconclusive, but I suspect I'm onto something.
</P>
<P>
   Others use handier tools that smell better and don't chew the
carpet: calendars, planners or their awesome electronic
equivalents. Organized people who are attuned to their surroundings
manage to flip calendar pages over on the very first of the month.
They notice right away when lunch boxes are being stacked at the
supermarket entrance. A lot of us, though, are oblivious to our
surroundings and get our news in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   I get busy and the year slips out from under me. I am guilty of
riding the days the way the dog travels in the car: mouth open,
head out the window, thrilled at the ride but not noticing the
traffic pattern.
</P>
<P>
   This lifestyle is particularly tempting in Florida where the
seasons have been efficiently pared to two: air-conditioning
weather and sleeping weather.
</P>
<P>
   Air-conditioning weather explains itself. Sleeping weather is
so-called because there's something about getting out blankets that
makes folks rest cozier. It's a known fact. Sleeping weather
arrives when the night temperature dips a few notches below 70 for
the first time. Its arrival makes everyone happier. The morning
after, everyone I see looks a little more alert.
</P>
<P>
   We have not entered the sleeping-weather season. Nevertheless,
society seems determined to put an end to summer. We even have a
national holiday devoted to finishing off all thought of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Labor Day has long ago ceased to celebrate anything about
working people except to mark the time of year when they should get
back to work.
</P>
<P>
   I am, by nature, deaf to all calls to go back to work. I never
take Labor Day's hint. This is not without its risks. You risk
missing autumn altogether if you don't look out for it. That's
where the dog comes in.
</P>
<P>
   The dog is an unplanned dog. I am still adjusting to the drill
of walking him in the morning and walking him in the evening. These
short strolls around the block have changed my life.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as a dog walker, I have discovered the rhythms of the
neighborhood. Things I previously sensed only vaguely. I know which
houses are up for sale. I know that little kids are getting older.
I am warned by example just what mole crickets can do to a lawn. I
find all the garage sales and bought two fine and large beer mugs
for 50 cents. I am a census taker of loose dogs, barky fenced-in
dogs and dogs with owners who have schedules like mine.
</P>
<P>
   I watch the progress of the night sky's constellations, but only
the big, bright easy ones like Orion and the dipper part of Ursa
Major. On trash day, I know who is remodeling and the identities of
conscientious recyclers. I know which kids hold parties when their
parents are gone.
</P>
<P>
   Dog walkers see all. Dog walkers know all.
</P>
<P>
   If I were not a dog walker, I would ignore Labor Day. I would
still wear my summer jacket with white buttons. I would cruise
through September with a surf-dude's endless-summer grin. Instead,
I walked the dog out into the early morning and felt an unfamiliar
sensation. I was outdoors and I was not hot. It wasn't cool
exactly. But clearly I had stumbled upon a landmark day in the
Florida year _ the first non-hot day.
</P>
<P>
   The first non-hot day doesn't grab you the way a first snowfall
does, but it signals seasonal change with the same finality. The
first non-hot day is falling leaves, the first sprinkle of
instantly melted snow and the smell of the heater kicking on for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   When I feel it, I rush at summer things. I have heard the last
call before closing time and don't need another warning. Because I
am a dog walker, I'm privileged to get this information early,
while there's time to get to the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Dog walkers are masters of the seasons. And we are there before
you when the good stuff is still lying around the garage sale.
Don't worry, though, I always leave the popcorn poppers for anyone
who might really need one.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is associate editor at The Daytona Beach News-Journal.
E-mail: marklane(at)n-jcenter.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
