<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grape jelly bait lures away raccoons, puts smile on planter's
face
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIGER, Ga. _ My friend Coyl Justice, who grows some of the best
rhododendron and native azalea in North Georgia, couldn't wait to
tell me the news. No, it wasn't about plants; it was about catching
coons with grape jelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look here,'' he said, pointing to his grape arbor, ``my grapes
aren't 50 feet away, but those coons go straight for the jelly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``'Course I don't blame 'em,'' he added with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Justice and his wife Mildred love plants and critters, so
there's no worry about how the raccoons and possums will be treated
after they venture into the wire cage for a toast and jelly snack.
Justice gives them water out of a milk jug and takes them down the
road a few miles from his home. He sets them free in the woods,
careful not to send them off in the direction of his neighbors'
blueberries or grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Justice couldn't wait to share his jelly secret with John and me
because he knows we had our share of ``varmits'' sampling the
grapes last fall at our farm in Tiger. We even had a bear or two. I
told Justice about the ``bear scare'' contraption our electrician
friend Vaughn Ramey rigged up _ a combination of motion lights and
a radio set to blare forth simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   The grape jelly trick, Justice wanted to confess, wasn't his
idea _ and he wasn't advising it for bears. ``Russell Turpin down
at the feed store in Clayton is the one who told me,'' he said.
``'Course everybody already knows about catching groundhogs with
apples, but jelly's something else.''
</P>
<P>
   The groundhogs have attacked the zinnias this year. ``Some of my
neighbors are hoppin' mad about it,'' Justice said. He thinks grape
jelly will lure groundhogs, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Justices, who've lived in the area 40 years, manage Betty's
Creek Tree Farm, a nursery that attracts old timers and newcomers
alike. But their pride and joy is the native azalea and
rhododendron they grow in the greenhouses beside their home. They
sell them at their own smaller Big Creek Nursery, but the joy's in
nurturing them.
</P>
<P>
   Looking over hundreds of seedlings in tiny pots, Justice can't
wait for spring. ``What's exciting is when people come see the
blooms,'' he said. ``To me, it's an accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Mildred remembers when Coyl started growing the native plants
from seed. He'd put them in clear plastic shoe boxes with some peat
moss. Then he'd slide the boxes up on top of the drape cornices in
her dining room. That would get them the right amount of heat and
air to germinate.
</P>
<P>
   The plants are all in greenhouses now, but the Justices still
lift each fragile seedling into its individual pot, using a
toothpick or a nail.
</P>
<P>
   Justice marvels at how everybody seems to want so many plants in
their yard today. ``If you turn around twice,'' he said, ``seems
like you're near covered up with plants.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembers when grass was ``a no-no.'' His mama took pride in
sweeping the dirt yard he played in as a kid. She pulled out every
blade of green. But from her he learned to love flowers. She
planted beds of them _ which her husband inevitably cut down. ``All
he cared about was his dogs and chickens, it seemed like,'' Coyl
recalled. ``I watched my mama fret, and I guess it impressed me
what all she went through just to have a few flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justices, whose grandchildren help them run the tree farm,
wouldn't want to do anything else or live anywhere else. Coyl
savors the view of his favorite mountain, ``Pickens Nose.'' The
couple's best friends are those who go to the small Baptist church
nearby, which Coyle says is ``the most lovable place you can
find.'' He's taught a young adult class there ``forever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mildred says the young adults never want to leave Justice's
class. ``We've got 'em 17 to 40 now,'' she said with a laugh.
Whatever age, Coyl said, ``It's hard to beat the people up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Ezzard writes for the Atlanta Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
