<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Koresh's deeds are there to read in the DNA
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Like a flame not controlled, events at Mount
Carmel were a local story that became a national story that became
an international story.
</P>
<P>
   They were events out in the sticks, near Elk, that singed the
city of Waco, and then the city of Washington, and caused people
around the world to have to turn from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   But it all started with a local story.
</P>
<P>
   That story was suspected child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there were more questions about the Branch Davidians _
about weapons, about suspected scam marriages _ but what was
happening to children at Mount Carmel is what caused some former
Davidians to go from audience to audience, including local and
federal law enforcement, and finally this newspaper, to get someone
to take the matter seriously.
</P>
<P>
   And it wasn't just vague suspicion. It was testimony in a child
custody hearing.
</P>
<P>
   With all the questions about the events at Mount Carmel: Who
fired when? Who fired what? Who started the fire? There is
absolutely no question now about the central issue that drew the
attention of Waco Tribune-Herald reporters Mark England and Darlene
McCormick to the case: child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   David Koresh, claiming that all the world's women were his, was
marking them off by bedding and in several cases impregnating
under-age girls.
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, maddeningly, commentaries by some of the
best in our business, as with the half-cocked crowd with Internet
connections, contain the assertion that law enforcement had no
evidence of child abuse in February 1993. Maybe it depends on their
definition of abuse, or of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   If it's anecdotal evidence that proves sufficient, Kiri Jewell
provided it.
</P>
<P>
   A Michigan child custody case concerning her was the first time
questions about child abuse by Koresh were raised on the record.
The court removed her from the Branch Davidian community where her
mother remained. Kiri later testified to Congress, as she did on
``Donahue'' and in the press. She said that at age 10 she'd been
molested by Koresh. Not only that, he had shown her and others how
to stick a gun in their mouths if events called for suicide.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the investigation by local state social workers
into suspected child abuse, the state had only that story to rely
on.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, maddeningly, the state's investigation into child abuse
had made no progress when federal authorities got involved at the
request of the McLennan County sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   The feds used illegal weapons as the pretext for a raid that
couldn't have been botched worse. Later they cooked up a pretext of
illegal drugs. It had no apparent merit, but brought military
forces into the equation as the subsequent standoff dragged on.
</P>
<P>
   The ATF blew it. The FBI blew it. But first of all this was a
local story _ an inability or unwillingness by local authorities to
address a clear and present danger: that David Koresh was making
babies with children far too young to give legal consent, much less
understand the term.
</P>
<P>
   Read the DNA and weep. Tests on the fire victims showed that
Koresh had sired between 13 and 15 children, some with under-age
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   An offense worthy of the death penalty? Of course not. Everyone
should have walked out of Mount Carmel alive. Everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Koresh should have, could have, been arrested away from Mount
Carmel on any of the pretexts law enforcement had for its raid in
the first place. Of all the whoppers told, one of the biggest was
the ATF's assertion that Koresh wasn't away from Mount Carmel for
weeks preceding the raid. Absolutely false. A monster lie, quickly
exposed by this newspaper's reporters.
</P>
<P>
   But you know what? Another monster lie is being perpetrated
about the events that should have interested everyone in David
Koresh. The truth is in the DNA.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
