<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Preparation, a slow hand needed to handle PC's innards
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sooner or later, with trembling fingers, you'll open
up your PC to work on its innards.
</P>
<P>
   I had a friend _ a physician _ who could deal with
life-and-death situations without a quiver. But the very idea of
taking the top off her PC was so frightening that simply thinking
of such of a thing gave her anxiety dreams.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know when your day will come. Perhaps you'll want to add
memory or swap hard disks or even do something as simple as change
an internal modem. But I promise it will come.
</P>
<P>
   Just as hospitals sometimes guide a patient through the steps
that will take place before an operation, today we'll take a little
tour _ think of it as an insider's view to a computer. Along the
way, you'll learn a few things that will make the process easier
and less frightening.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't a single standard way to open the case of your
computer. On those tall skinny tower cases, there's usually an
access plate on the side. On regular desktop cases, the top usually
slides back and off. Check your computer manual to find out how
your PC's case opens.
</P>
<P>
   My first hint sounds painfully simple, but someday you may thank
me for it. When you remove the screws to open the case, put them in
a small container well away from the working area. I don't know how
many computers I've owned, but I can't think of a single one that
survived with a full complement of screws. Sure, I eventually found
them. I knew I had because I could hear the vacuum cleaner rattle
as it sucked them out of the carpet.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing to remember when working inside a computer is
that static electricity _ even in amounts too small to notice _ can
kill memory chips and microprocessor chips. Since many of us keep a
computer in a room with a carpeted floor, it's easy to build up a
static charge. Before you touch anything _ those new memory chips
or the innards of your PC _ touch the chassis to ground yourself.
If you really worry about static electricity (and that isn't a
crazy thing), go to any electronics supply house and ask for a
grounding strap. You wear it on your wrist, and it prevents static
electricity buildup.
</P>
<P>
   Shock of a different kind also is a component killer. That's the
shock that comes when something hits the floor. Dropping a chip or
a card that contains chips won't necessarily ruin it. But it could.
So handle with care.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have the cover off and are ready to install your new
component, you'll notice a strange compulsion almost universal
among those who are new to working on computers. You'll feel an
overwhelming compulsion to rush. To grab the danged thing, shove it
into its proper place and then get the top on ... as if you got
extra points for speed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, once the case is open, review the instructions for
putting in the part. Then _ without touching anything _ take a
close look at where the part will go. If something doesn't make
sense, after seeing where the chip or the card will go, stop right
there. While being inventive and spontaneous may work just fine in
your personal life, it's not such a great idea while working on
gadgets. If you're confused and try to force something, the odds
are that it will break. So, if you're confused before you start,
call tech support for the company that makes the chip or gadget and
get advice now.
</P>
<P>
   For most small upgrades, the task is fairly straightforward. But
there are times _ when replacing a CD-ROM drive, or adding a hard
disk, and certainly when replacing a motherboard _ when you can
forget which connection goes where, or which side of the connector
is up. Sometimes it is a good idea to make a sketch, showing where
the connectors go, before you remove them from the old gadget. Even
if you never refer to the sketch again, just the process of
creating it will help you remember.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, remember that PCs are complicated beasts but _ as far
as the kind of upgrades the home user might do _ really simple to
work on. Everything snaps together like Lego blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
