<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bypassing the mall an individual cosmetic decision
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Buying makeup would seem to be the one thing you just
cannot do on the Internet. Lipstick with names like Russian Red,
Viva Glam or Sheer Plum may sound enticing, but until you slap a
stripe across your wrist, there's no way of telling if it will make
you look sensual or silly.
</P>
<P>
   Makeup looks different on different people. Once, a very peeved
saleswoman at the Chanel counter at Saks Fifth Avenue practically
reached across the counter to smack my friend Janet because the red
tones absolutely refused to stay red and turned a bizarre shade of
orange when Janet tried them on.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is my friend Linda, who is allergic to certain kinds
of perfume. She can't breathe and her eyes start to water when she
smells certain scents.
</P>
<P>
   These women are not weird. Makeup has an individual look and
feel on everyone who wears it. Cosmetic companies know this and are
trying with some success to develop Web sites that evoke a brand,
an image and a color selection women might actually want to go out
and buy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most sites warn customers what you see isn't always what
you'll get. The colors on the monitor may not be the same colors
you'll find in the mall. Online ordering is available from
companies, but the process is clunky and prices are often higher
than you'd find in many stores. Lipsticks recently for sale online
at one site cost $14 plus tax and shipping but were only $12 plus
tax at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   The main focus for most cosmetic sites is not shopping but
increasing brand awareness and image and teaching consumers about
their products.
</P>
<P>
   A growing trend for makeup sites is to give users an interactive
consultation. The notion of letting customers play with colors
keyed to their skin tone was pioneered by Cover Girl several years
ago. Cover Girl (www.covergirl.com) originally asked users to try
out eye shadows and lipsticks on the virtual faces of supermodels
such as Tyra Banks.
</P>
<P>
   But most women quickly found out that while most anything looks
good on Tyra, the average Web-surfing woman isn't so lucky. To its
credit, Cover Girl's site now lets women choose makeup, not only
according to their coloring, but other factors as well, including
lifestyle and personality.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, the British-based Body Shop (www.bodyshop.com)
devoted most of its Web site to a brand-awareness campaign that
stressed its political activism, detailed the company's
no-animal-testing policy and documented how Body Shop products help
people in Third World countries. It was a great branding strategy
but offered almost no information about its products, let alone
where to buy them.
</P>
<P>
   But the Body Shop site has grown up. While it still touts the
company's environmental and political activities, it now offers the
interactive features Cover Girl uses.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, the Urban Decay site (www.urbandecay.com) was
all about weird poetry, lists of places to kiss and
not-too-realistic representations of its offbeat but very wearable
lipstick, eye shadow and nail polish.
</P>
<P>
   The list of places to kiss is still there, but so are several
key improvements, including detailed text descriptions of what
colors like ``manic depressive,'' ``roach'' and ``AC/DC'' are
supposed to look like. Online ordering is available but stops you
before you enter your credit card number to tease you into buying
something else. While this may work at the makeup counter, it's
just time-consuming and crass on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   With all its drawbacks, shopping online may be the only
alternative for fashion mavens who must have the latest colors no
matter what, but it's the rare woman who wears only one company's
products.
</P>
<P>
   Sites like Eve.com offer a good selection of cult brands like
BeneFit and Philosophy that turn up in all the magazines but are
often hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   With a variety of products, tips and hints, Eve is a good bet if
you know what you want and what you like and just want to stock up
on your favorites.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that makeup aggregators like Eve.com will be the real
Web winners in this difficult online category.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
