<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MEDIA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New niche magazine Sony Style covers what's chic in the world of
high tech
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You know technology has become chic when it gets its
own style magazine. That's what happened with the launch of Sony
Style. The premiere issue features stories about how celebrities
incorporate digital gizmos into their lives. Fashion designer Diane
Von Furstenberg, for example, explains how she designed a ``life
vest'' for the wired woman. The vest includes pockets for a cell
phone, MiniDisc player and camcorder, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo Internet Life dedicates its September issue to how people
use the Internet. You'll find articles about the Net's impact on
ordinary people and a discussion of whether blacks and Latinos are
being left behind by the rapid growth of the Web. There are also
snapshots of Web use across the globe.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Imagine if you could hold every issue of Mad magazine ever
published in the palm of your hand. Well, this is no longer
fantasy. Broderbund has published a collection of the magazines on
seven computer CDs. The set, called ``Totally Mad,'' features 50
years of back issues. The collection is available only for PCs with
Windows 95 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   The Web is a great place to research your family tree. One of
the better sites for geneaological searches is Ancestry.com. The
site includes a massive index of some 240 million names. There are
also more than 1,600 searchable archives from a host of public
archives. This depth of resources comes at a price: $59.95 a year,
to be precise. But the site also makes a limited amount of its
database free. You'll find the site at www
</P>
<P>
   .ancestry.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
