<P>
   High-tech Holidays
</P>
<P>
   During the next two weeks, Jews across the world will celebrate
their High Holidays. Rosh Hashana is a two-day holiday for the
Jewish New Year beginning Friday. The following week, on Sept. 19,
beginning at sundown Jews will fast on Yom Kippur, the Day of
Atonement. On this day, Jews ask forgiveness for wrongdoings and
think about ways to improve. Click around the Jewish Children's
Learning Resource Web site at www.akhlah.com to learn about the
traditions and blessings for these holidays. You'll also find facts
on Israel, Hebrew words and coloring pages. _ Anne Y. Meyers
</P>
<P>
   Yuck it up!
</P>
<P>
   What's a teacher's favorite candy? Chalk-olate! What's the best
state to get school supplies? Pencil-vania. These are two of a
couple hundred chuckles in ``Jokes You Shouldn't Tell Your
Teacher'' by Eric Arnold (Aladdin/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $2.99).
Actually, maybe you shouldn't tell your teacher any jokes. Get
serious! Save these ridiculous riddles to get friends giggling on
the bus ride home. _ Julie Bookman
</P>
<P>
   Try out for `Nutcracker'
</P>
<P>
   or
</P>
<P>
   Dance, dance, boogie-woogie-woogie
</P>
<P>
   Want to play toy soldiers, nesting dolls or fairies in next
year's Atlanta Ballet production of ``The Nutcracker''? Tryouts are
scheduled for Sept. 12 and 19 from 2 to 7 p.m. at 1400 W. Peachtree
St. Dancers must be at least 10 and have several years of dance
training. For information on dress code and other requirements as
well as audition times, call 404-873-5811, Ext. 409. _ Judith Green
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
