<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time running out on Beanies
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Breathe deeply, and don't panic. We have some bad
news.
</P>
<P>
   The company that makes Beanie Babies announced last week it's
retiring the entire line of stuffed toys on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   But there is some good news. Toy industry experts don't believe
Ty Inc. will stop producing the profitable toys completely. ``The
backlash from Beanie collectors, people who really invested a lot
to build their collections, would be huge,'' said Chris Byrne, a
consultant and editor of the Toy Report.
</P>
<P>
   Some have suggested that the message posted on the company's
Internet site is a marketing gimmick to raise prices of the older
Beanies and prepare buyers for a new line.
</P>
<P>
   Photographers cleared in Princess Diana's death
</P>
<P>
   A French judge dismissed charges against photographers and a
press motorcyclist in the death of Princess Diana two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Princess Diana was killed in a car crash in a Paris
traffic tunnel Aug. 31, 1997. Her boyfriend, Dodi Fayed, and the
driver, Henri Paul, also were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the accident was blamed on photographers who were
chasing Diana's car at high speeds hoping to get pictures of her
with her new boyfriend. The shots could be sold for a very high
price to publications. The photographers acknowledge tailing Diana,
but said they did not cause the crash.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ruled the accident was due to the driver of the car
being under the influence of alcohol and drugs, which prevented him
from controlling the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Internet, pop culture drive new dictionary
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find the word ``bogart'' (``to hog something'') in
your dictionary at school, tell your teacher you want the Encarta
World English Dictionary (St. Martins Press, $50 hardback, $19.95
CD-ROM). It's the first new English-language dictionary to be
published in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   More than 320 scholars in 20 nations toiled for the last three
years to produce it. The Encarta is unusual because it's not an
updated version of an earlier edition.
</P>
<P>
   Encarta was written to address the effect the Internet has had
on the English language.
</P>
<P>
   As the Internet has expanded, so has English. It's the language
of 85 percent of the sites on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Because people from different countries have different English
words for things, talking via the Internet can get confusing. For
example, in South African English the word for stoplight is
``robot.'' The Encarta dictionary can help people understand the
different meanings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
