<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: I parked on the University of Texas campus in
a reserved lot the other night. I received a $50 ticket! Do I have
to pay this? What can they do? _ C.E.
</P>
<P>
   A: Not much if you are not a student, faculty member or relative
of either. If you have a connection, they will track you down. You
can appeal the ticket within 12 calendar days. Call 471-PARK for
details. Your unpaid ticket and accrued late charges remain in the
UT computer. Ticketed again? You could be towed. Yikes! Parking on
campus is a competitive sport. Odds of finding a place with a C
(commuter student) permit are slim, since 7,000 permits are sold
for 3,525 parking spaces. Staff members do not have it much easier.
For the 3,000 A (staff ) permits sold there are 1,550 spaces. Too
bad you are not a faculty member because 1,900 F (faculty) permits
are sold for 1,560 spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My oldest daughter was born in Houston on Aug. 2, 1943. A
real big hurricane blew in there on July 27. I cannot find the name
for it. _ A.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: You cannot remember the name of this hurricane because in
1943 hurricanes had numbers, not names. The National Hurricane
Center began naming hurricanes in 1950 with the international
phonetic alphabet (Abel, Baker, Charlie, etc). In 1953 the United
States broke away from that convention and used women's names.
After an attack of gender consciousness, the United States began
using men's and women's names in 1979. The July 27, 1943, hurricane
was simply known as ``hurricane No. 1.'' Q: In the movie, ``Stolen
Women, Captured Hearts,'' a young Indian man played the part of
Chata. Can you tell me who he is, his age, what tribe he's from,
what other movies he's been in? Was he the one in ``Cry of the
White Wolf?'' _ Ruth Quinn
</P>
<P>
   A: You have seen Rodney A. Grant in both movies. Born in 1959,
Grant is of the Omaha Tribe and has been in movies since 1989.
Perhaps you spotted him as one of People magazine's 50 most
beautiful people in the world (1991). Grant also appeared in
``Dances with Wolves'' (1990), and this year's ``Wild Wild West.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have been explaining to my daughter the easiest way to tell
what is a fruit and what is a vegetable is fruits have seeds and
vegetables do not. However, my wife says that is not true. A bet is
riding on this. _ Mark Moravits
</P>
<P>
   A: You win. Botanist Jerry Brand at the University of Texas says
a fruit is a matured plant ovary _ seeds surrounded by parent plant
tissue. ``Vegetative'' plant parts include only leaves, stems and
roots, so in a botanical world a vegetable embodies only food
derived from one of those plant components. Under these definitions
an eggplant is a fruit, as are tomatoes and pumpkins. Surprised?
Your grocer may disagree, but botanically the fruit/vegetable line
is not based on how a food is eaten, but from what part of a plant
it is derived and how it is constructed. Q: I heard from an elderly
Irish cousin who included two questions in his letter: ``How are
things in `Glocca Morra'? Is the weeping willow still there?'' I
have no idea what this meant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Rosalind Brinkley
</P>
<P>
   A: This ``Finian's Rainbow'' song is about a fictional location,
the figment of Finian McLonergan's imagination in the musical. The
song lyrics are by E.Y. Harburg; music, Burton Lane. McLonergan
pines for his homeland. Order the sheet music from Alpha Music on
29th Street. ``How are things in Glocca Morra? Is that willow tree
still weeping there? Does that laddie with the twinklin' eye/Come
whistlin' by and does he walk away, Sad and dreamy there not to see
me there?''
</P>
<P>
   Q: One of the television commercials for Draeger Ford shows a
little ``creature'' running down the road yelling. What is that
little animal? _ A.E.
</P>
<P>
   A: The creature is an Australian frilled lizard; the other
