<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2227 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-NFK-FEATURE-LILLEAGUE     09-06 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-FEATURE-LILLEAGUE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Little League heroes having Major League fun
 &HT;    By Russell Frank
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Imagine you've been playing Little League baseball in
front of a few moms and dads _ and then suddenly you're stepping up
to the plate before a crowd of 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine reporters, photographers and autograph hounds gathering
around as if you were a Major Leaguer like Chipper Jones or Derek
Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   That's what eight teams of 11- and 12-year-olds did two weeks
ago when they competed in the Little League World Series in
Williamsport, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The players, who came from around the world, faced intense
competition, both at the series and in the playoffs leading up to
it. These eight teams were the best of the 7,000 teams that make up
the Little League system.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the pressure, there was still fun to be had. And lots of
kids to meet.
</P>
<P>
   All eight teams stayed in a dorm-like hotel, where they could
challenge each other to table tennis and video games or play in the
pool.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Gaynor, a pitcher from the Toms River, N.J., team, said he
joked around in the dorm room with his friends and watched a
teammate impersonate the Taco Bell Chihuahua until 3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Phenix City, Ala., team lived on the floor below the Osaka,
Japan, team for the week. Phenix City lost to Osaka 5-0 in the
championship game, but they learned a lot from their new friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw them in the dorms, I didn't think they were
ever going to talk to us,'' said Phenix City first baseman Brandon
Monk. ``Now I know the Japanese words for `hi,' `good evening' and
`stupid.''' (All very useful when you're a kid!)
</P>
<P>
   The two teams also went head to head for the table tennis
championship. Phenix City won that round.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there was lots of action on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Six Phenix City kids hit home runs in the playoffs. Outfielders
Kyle Tidwell hit a grand slam to beat the Midwestern champion team
5-4, and William Gaston III celebrated his 13th birthday with the
first two home runs of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Osaka's second baseman, Shinichiro Oki, lit up when he speared a
line drive. And all the teams were impressed when the Japanese
players tipped their helmets to the umpires when they came up to
bat.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rican pitcher Jose Casanova, the winner in his team's
first game against Osaka, learned the thrill of being asked for his
autograph, as did many of the other boys.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the final game, the friendly rivals from Alabama and
Japan took time to wish each other luck. With some coaxing from the
Little League's chipmunk-like mascot, Dugout, a few players from
each team came on the field to dance behind home plate. When the
music ended, the shaking and dancing turned into an exhibition of
hugging and high-fiving, with the two managers even getting into
the act.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always preached that fun is in the winning,'' said Phenix
City coach Tony Rasmus. ``But this has changed my outlook a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff and news services contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
