<DOCNO> NYT19990906.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2228 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN07-COX     09-06 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposed bill gives new hope to grandparents
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Imagine losing your son in a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine all you have left of him are his 1-year-old twins, a boy
and a girl.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that you have babysat for the twins since birth, and you
feel as close to them as your own children.
</P>
<P>
   Then imagine that your daughter-in-law remarries and won't let
you see the kids. Imagine being told that, under Ohio law, you have
no right to see your grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine all that, and you have some idea how it feels to be
53-year-old Linda Flory of Clearcreek Twp., Ohio. ``I just want to
see my grandkids,'' Flory says of her fight for visitation rights
with the grandchildren she hasn't seen in 19 months. ``At least,
the kids will know some day I cared enough to fight and that I
wanted to be part of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   A grandmother herself, Ohio State Rep. Barbara Pringle
(D-Cleveland) says she ``can't even imagine that happening to me.''
She has introduced House Bill 236, which would give grandparents
visitation rights except when it's not in the best interests of the
child.
</P>
<P>
   The bill stipulates that a step-parent's adoption of a child
doesn't terminate a grandparent's or close relative's right to
visit the child. The bill covers not only cases like Flory's, in
which the parent has died, but also cases of separation and
divorce. (Exceptions would be when the relationship between the
natural parent and the child is terminated before the adoption.)
</P>
<P>
   A quilt bearing the inscription, ``Grandchildren complete life's
circle of love,'' hangs in the living room of Flory's rural Warren
County home. Crocheted onto the quilt are the names of her 11
grandchildren, including the twins. Their photos are all over the
house, along with those of their late father, Darin Long. But Flory
has not seen her grandchildren since Feb. 22, 1998. (She remembers
the date without a second's hesitation.)
</P>
<P>
   Flory's nightmare began nearly two years earlier, the night of
March 12, 1996. It was 12: 37 a.m. Darin and Bryan Long were less
than a mile from their mother's home when Darin's Ford Escort went
off the road and hit a tree at 10323 Paragon Road in Washington
Twp.
</P>
<P>
   Darin died at the scene; Bryan, who was Careflighted to Miami
Valley Hospital, recovered from his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The twins provided Flory's only consolation, the living link
with the son who had a ``smile that was from ear to ear.'' Hundreds
turned out for the funeral of the 25-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Darin's twins continued to be an important part of Flory's life
until her former daughter-in-law remarried in December 1997, and
her new husband adopted the twins. The visits dwindled and then
stopped altogether. The Montgomery County Juvenile Court granted
Flory visitation rights, but an appeals court overturned that
decision in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grandparents and grandchildren need to be together,'' Flory
says. ``I was such a major portion of their lives. I loved and took
care of them like they were my own.''
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter, Tammy Garland, 35, has supported her mother in her
battle to see the twins. ``This is my family, too,'' she says.
``This is all we have left of my brother. He loved his kids, and
he'd want us to be a part of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Wagner, the attorney for the twins' mother, said his
client hasn't alleged any misconduct on the part of Flory or her
family. He defended his client's right to establish a new life.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of House Bill 236 use similar arguments. Adoption by a
step-parent creates a new family unit, they say, and parents alone
should have the right to determine who spends time with their
children.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a letter from Garland, State Rep. Cheryl Winkler,
R-Cincinnati, said she opposed the bill. When children are adopted
by a step-parent, she wrote,''...mandating the maintenance with a
relationship with relatives from the first marriage would be
disruptive to the building of the new family structure.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not disruptive for children to be torn away from
relatives they have known and loved? It's not disruptive when the
kid turns 16 and starts asking questions?
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Pringle doesn't get it. ``I can't understand how this
would be in the best interest of the child,'' she says. ``It's not
bad enough you lost your mother or your father; then you're torn
away from the family you have left. They loved that person and
suddenly (they're) not allowed to see them again. It's just not
right.''
</P>
<P>
   She talks about the grandparents in northern Ohio who raised
their grandchild for several years after their daughter died in
childbirth from a cerebral hemorrhage. The father remarried and
reclaimed the child _ and refused to allow the grandparents to
visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe a child has the right to know his heritage and his
grandparents,'' Pringle says. ``He has a right to know about his
mom, the kind of person she was, and things she liked. Otherwise, a
part of his life, part of his history, part of his culture is
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Flory case, Pringle says, ``These children have lost not
only lost their father but any connection to their father. No
matter how good a father the new one is, the child still has the
right to know about his father. The only way to know that is to
know his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the family's hopes are pinned on House Bill 236. On the hope
that Ohio lawmakers will realize it's not in a child's best
interest to erase half of his history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law is telling me I can't be a grandma,'' Flory says.
</P>
<P>
   No lawyer in the world can make her believe that.
</P>
<P>
   Mary McCarty writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
