u i BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-BOS &LR;      09-06 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGNING OF MIDEAST TREATY REKINDLES HOPE FOR PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The signing ceremony in Egypt on Sunday of a pivotal
new agreement laid out a clear path forward for the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process, even if a much-tougher road
remains ahead to a final settlement that will include Lebanon and
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's prime minister, Ehud Barak, and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat signed the document in the Red Sea resort town of
Sharm el Sheikh as Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, King Abdullah
of Jordan, and US Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright looked
on, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday we embark on a new road,'' Barak said. ``For the sake
of our mothers and fathers, children and grandchildren, we must
turn the vision of a comprehensive peace into a lasting reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat said, ``We assert, as we always promised, that we respect
and implement our commitments.'' President Clinton hailed the
agreement as ``truly a new beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   It came after three days of intense diplomacy in the region by
Albright, who said the agreement ``provides a long-awaited boost
both to the substance and spirit of the search for Middle East
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A great task has been completed,'' she said. ``And an even
larger one remains.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright had met earlier Saturday with the leaders of Lebanon
and Syria in an attempt to restart direct talks between those two
countries and Israel after talks broke down between them more than
three years ago. More mediation will be required for Albright to
achieve that, but observers say Albright is optimistic that the new
momentum in the Israeli-Palestinian track will help reinvigorate
the Syrian and Lebanese diplomatic tracks.
</P>
<P>
   South Lebanon is the last active Arab-Israeli warfront.
Hezbollah guerrillas are fighting there to oust Israel from the
9-mile wide swath of land it occupies along the border. Syria
supports the guerrillas, in part to pressure Israel to return the
Golan Heights, which Israel captured from Syria in the 1967 Six Day
War.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, the newly signed agreement is merely a modified
version of the Wye River ``land for security'' deal signed more
than one year ago. It is an agreement to implement a long-overdue
set of requirements that call for further Israeli troop withdrawals
from a further 13 percent of the West Bank and the release of about
350 Palestinian security prisoners from Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
   But in its essence, it is more than a revision of the existing
agreement. The ``Wye II'' agreement marks a crucial turning point,
the end of the interim peace process and the beginning of the
endgame that will determine the final shape of peace.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the agreements set the terms for three Israeli
withdrawals from the West Bank between September and January. It
offers the Palestinians more prisoner releases, clearance to open a
seaport in Gaza, and a ``safe passage'' for Palestinians to travel
between Gaza and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   It also calls for Israel and the Palestinians to complete by
Feb. 15 a ``framework agreement'' on the ``final status'' issues,
which remain the most thorny and emotional pieces of the process.
They include the debate over the status of Jerusalem, the fate of
millions of Palestinian refugees, water rights, and the future of
Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
   After the signing ceremony, King Abdullah evoked the memory of
his late father, King Hussein, who worked tirelessly to push both
sides to sign the Wye River agreement last fall while he battled
the cancer that claimed his life in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement reminds us all of his spirit, his vision, his
courage, and his commitment to peace, and I hope and pray that we
do not let him down,'' King Abdullah said.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak said that during the previous three years, ``there were
moments of loss of hope and despair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us all vow to turn a new page in the history of this
troubled region. God willing, we shall prevail,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
