<DOCNO> NYT19990906.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2254 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-NEWSSTAND07-COX     09-06 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    On The Newsstands: Artist or not, Normal Rockwell's hot
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With an exhibition of his paintings opening at Atlanta's High
Museum in November and traveling to half a dozen major art
galleries, Norman Rockwell, the sometimes corny chronicler of
Americana, is finally getting some respect.
</P>
<P>
   Or is he?
</P>
<P>
   The September issue of ARTnews ($6) explores the controversy
surrounding the artist whose work appeared on 322 Saturday Evening
Post covers. Although he was immensely popular, some critics
contend that he was just an illustrator, not an artist. For New
Criterion editor Hilton Kramer, Rockwell's scheduled exhibition at
New York's Guggenheim Museum is simply evidence of a further
decline in standards.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Rockwell is an artist or not is immaterial, says High
Museum Director Ned Rifkin. ``He is a force.''
</P>
<P>
   Collectors apparently agree. One of Rockwell's paintings, ``The
Watchmaker,'' sold at Sotheby's three years ago for $937,500.
</P>
<P>
   Babes in the woods
</P>
<P>
   Just because you have kids, that's no reason to curtail outdoor
activities such as camping and hiking. Women Outside ($3.95)
interviews four couples about how they incorporate children into
active lifestyles. Because of all the new high-tech gear available,
taking the entire family into the wild has become as easy as, well,
a walk in the woods. There's good news for single women, too.
Several experienced travelers offer tips for safe solo journeys to
Antarctica, Australia, Japan, Chile, British Columbia, Luxembourg
and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Troubled men
</P>
<P>
   In a Newsweek ($3.50) excerpt from her new book, ``Stiffed,''
former Atlanta journalist Susan Faludi explores the woes of the
American male and the pressure to be masculine in a culture that no
longer respects the old codes of manhood. As research for the book,
Faludi spent six years reporting on the Navy's Tailhook scandal,
The Citadel's coed controversy, the sports world, corporate
downsizing and the pornography industry. What she found was a
generation of men who feel betrayed by their fathers and society.
While Tom Brokaw and others praise ``The Greatest Generation'' for
saving the world, the sons of those World War II veterans complain
that their fathers abandoned them emotionally. `` `My father never
taught me how to be a man' was the refrain I heard over and over
again,'' Faludi says.
</P>
<P>
   Woodstock revisited
</P>
<P>
   Still haven't read enough about Woodstock '99? Spin ($2.99)
presents an hour-by-hour account of what really happened at the
three-day festival. By Sunday, the peace-and-love event had
degenerated into ``an anarchic stew of fires, riots, vandalism and
mounds and mounds of trash.'' Also in this issue, Woodstock star
Kid Rock talks about his decade-long journey from crack peddler to
millionaire musician. With his latest record, ``Devil Without a
Cause,'' gone platinum, the king of hick-hop says he still has the
same simple tastes: ``I'm into trailer parks, Pabst Blue Ribbon and
top-shelf mixed drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   A different Rock
</P>
<P>
   Who's the funniest man in America? Time ($3.50) says it's
comedian Chris Rock, and ``Saturday Night Live'' producer Lorne
Michaels agrees. ``There's no one as good,'' he says. Even Woody
Allen says he's exploring the possibility of appearing opposite
Rock in a comedy about sportscasters.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
