A2259 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-UPSCALE-AZR &LR;      09-06 2392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPSCALE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN UPSCALE AMERICA, NO LUXURY IS TOO MUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAIMEE ROSE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Wal-Mart is installing cappuccino bars. Oprah is
hawking haute literature. TV is fine, but Bose home theater is very
much the dream screen.
</P>
<P>
   The sport utility vehicle has trumped the station wagon.
Wolfgang Puck has his own TV dinners at Fry's. Phoenix Art Museum
ads are nestled between Britney Spears and Cher on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   There are dog-biscuit bakeries, Ralph Lauren restaurants and
concierges at apartment complexes. Even cigar bars, chic home decor
at Target and brand-name water.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the pretty little picture? Right under our upturned
noses, America is going decidedly upscale.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in American economic history, there is what
cultural analyst David Frum has dubbed a ``mass upper class,'' and
popular taste is leaning toward the ritzy, glitzy and generally
costly _ or imitations of same.
</P>
<P>
   It is the offspring of the indulgence that comes with a record
economy, record media saturation and record available credit.
</P>
<P>
   It's also just a simple '90s way of thinking, a cultural melange
that we're going to pin on Martha Stewart. &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
The fashion bomb
</P>
<P>
   (at)j  &QL; 
Long the bastion of the East Coast elite, Martha was the darling of
proper domestic tranquillity. Her name was a lifestyle, her ideas
sublime. She was inaccessible and nearly impossible to mimic.
(Turns out, few people are still sewing their own linen sheets
these days.)
</P>
<P>
   But Martha was a force. Slowly, there were specialty books _ on
weddings, on dinner parties, on the holidays. There was a pretty
magazine, ``Martha Stewart Living,'' followed by a television
program filmed at her oh-so-perfect Connecticut estate. But
Martha's world still seemed reserved for the elite and the fussy
until April 1997, when she dropped a bomb, fashioned out of yards
and yards of pretty pastel sheets and towels, onto mainstream
American retail. All of a sudden, Martha was at K-Mart, and average
America was hip. East Coast elite was accessible. Better yet, it
was cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Her empire caught fire. She bought her magazine from Time
Warner, launched an upscale, expensive mail-order catalog, started
a Web site and a line of paints and, this fall, will introduce a
series of fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, Target (affectionately called Tar-ZHAY by
tongue-in-cheek bargain hunters) gave downscaling the upscale a
try. The retail monster rolled out a home-decor line by famed
architect Michael Graves, the genius behind things as wildly
different and aesthetically amazing as the Walt Disney Swan Hotel
in Orlando and an addition to the Whitney Museum &UR; in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to appeal to a more design-savvy customer,'' says
Target Vice President Ron Johnson, the man behind Michael.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the Michael Graves toaster _ a sleek, curvy, hip little
number _ began flying off the shelves. Turns out, Americans really
liked the idea that more could be had for less, and the mass upper
class expanded.
</P>
<P>
   Target, by the way, now advertises in ``Martha Stewart Living.''
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart, not to be left out in the glitz category, began
testing upscale coffee bars in select Midwestern locations.
According to Melissa Brown, a company spokeswoman, that idea has
been successful and might just fly nationwide. (Wal-Mocha,
anyone?) &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
We'll even pay for oxygen
</P>
<P>
   (at)j  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And this is only on the discount-chain level. Upscale wants to
fill your coffee cup and hold it in its cupholder, especially if
you are driving to Barnes &AMP; Noble. It wants to own your remote
control and your home appliances. It has its eye on entire cities.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai, the vehicle line re nowned for its cheapness, recently
revamped its image into something attractive and desirable. Places
such as oxygen bars have been seeping into the culture, suggesting
that Americans are ready to pay for nearly anything au courant, no
matter if the expense is frivolous and otherwise free. Even the 25
cent cup of coffee is resigned to the $2.25 double-tall latte from
Starbucks, an example that Rommie Davis, a trend-spotting shopping
professional from Los Angeles, finds quite telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starbucks gives you style and cachet, and it's accessible to
anyone,'' she says. ``Americans are allowing themselves these
little luxuries and taking pleasure in doing so.''
</P>
<P>
   Those little luxuries are also transferring to a cerebral level.
As America is increasingly steeped in highbrow culture, some of the
previously elite-only tastes are starting to work their way into
the average American mind, (and onto the tongue, as in the case of
Puck's new mainstream frozen TV dinners.)
</P>
<P>
   Think of Oprah's Book Club: Literary fiction, a genre once
ignored by mass culture, has been canonized by a TV personality.
Even the bookstore, once a small fixture in a mall, has turned into
multiple large businesses built on the megaplex concept. (They have
pricey coffee there, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Our cultural icons have also taken a turn for prosperity. No
longer are we content to watch the cast of ``Cheers'' struggle in a
dingy bar. Now, we prefer to tune in to ``Frasier'' and his antics
at his luxury digs. (And when the scripts force Frasier out of
work, ratings plummet. A successful society wants successful
counterparts.)
</P>
<P>
   Upscaling is even happening in whole cities. Las Vegas, long the
land of the $1.99 family buffet, has morphed into a fine-dining
destination with world-class restaurant art collections and the
world's second Eiffel Tower.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle, a place of grunge and rain, is being cited as a city
that has finally ``arrived'' due to the addition of a new symphony
hall and a baseball stadium to its skyline.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Chandler is experiencing record prosperity. Previously
thought of as a sleepy, smallish suburb, Chandler is now home to
day spas and, soon enough, Arizona's second Nordstrom. Never mind
that just a year ago we were convinced that with just one Nordstrom
shoe department, the entire Valley would live happily ever after. &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
An eclectic America
</P>
<P>
   (at)j  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to Michael Kammen, a Pulitzer Prize-winning author and
renowned Cornell University historian, this downscale-goes-upscale
and vice-versa phenomenon is a product of our melting-pot culture
melting even more and is simply a way of thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've become far more eclectic,'' he says, and no longer feel
defined by social class, taste levels and economic means.
</P>
<P>
   Just look to our leadership, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Clinton's (presidential) inauguration, the music was by
Fleetwood Mac,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   An arena conventionally marked by power and prestige was brought
down to a mass level; the anointing of the leader of the free world
became a rock concert, on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   This upscaling is very much a recent thing. With a dutiful nod
to the '80s, the decade of excess, those years were marked by a
vast disparity. Yes, that was when we birthed the Lexus and when
jeans without designer labels became unworthy of the ranch. That
decade paved the way for the way we live today: Starbucks would
have starved if America hadn't bonded with brands. However, it was
also when the mass middle class was anything but upscale. People
were either drenched in money or they were late on the rent.
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, the word ``upscale'' was not introduced to a
dictionary until 1966. Similarly, ``lifestyle'' was not added until
1961.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were synonyms, and it's not as though no one thought
about it, but the fact that people were presenting themselves to
communities in a particular way, were concerned about having
watched a certain program, et cetera, was very new,'' Kammen says.
</P>
<P>
   He cites a chart published in ``Life'' magazine on April 11,
1949, as the turning point, the day that ``The Grapes of Wrath''
and ``The Great Gatsby'' began to edge together and American taste
levels began to blur.
</P>
<P>
   Titled ``Which Are You?'' the piece was a graph sectioned off by
labels: ``highbrow,'' ``upper-middle brow,'' ``lowbrow,'' etc. Next
to each level of brow-being was a list of icons that defined that
socioeconomic status. For example, a highbrow person would listen
to Lizst and a lowbrow person would be a fan of folk. The
categories ranged from libations to reading, food to furniture.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The article) set off a huge rage,'' said Kammen, who reprints
it in his recent book, ``American Culture, American Tastes.'' ``It
became a favorite parlor game. People would sit around and say,
`Which are you?'
</P>
<P>
   ``The huge irony is that when that chart appeared, that was the
peak of explicit public recognition, that was exactly the moment in
time when taste levels began to blur,'' says Kammen, citing the
paperback revolution as one of the catalysts.
</P>
<P>
   That era was the first time classics were mass-marketed and
available in more affordable, lower-quality forms. &QL; 
(at)j  &QL; 
`I want' vs. `I need'
</P>
<P>
   (at)j  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today, the blur has really taken off partly because of the
abundance of money (``it's the economy, stupid''), partly because
of record media saturation and partly due to the ease by which
credit is obtained.
</P>
<P>
   Juliet B. Schor, author of ``The Overspent American,'' says that
watching TV for an extra five hours a week, or two sitcoms per
night, raises one's yearly expenditures by about $1,000. Kammen
says that makes only too much sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This society is being literally bludgeoned to death to be more
consumer-oriented,'' he says. ``At a time when many Americans have
felt more prosperous, advertisers have been very astute in trying
to make available a huge variety of products that people find
attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   This spending spree has its dangers, however.
</P>
<P>
   For one, Davis, the shopping expert, seriously doubts that we
are always getting more for our money. Starbucks, in her opinion,
doesn't have that much on Folgers.
</P>
<P>
   Second, ``There is this illusion of more disposable income, but
we still have people paying 17 percent interest on credit cards
because they can't afford what they bought,'' Kammen says.
``Advertisers are creating the `I wants' and Americans are thinking
`I need.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's that whole keeping-up-with the-Joneses mentality.
</P>
<P>
   This nation of big spenders is leaving a smaller cash-poor
demographic in a cloud of grocery receipts, bills and unfulfilled
want lists. As pinpointed in 1997 by the Census Bureau, a great
socioeconomic divide is emerging through this economy; the rich are
getting richer, and the poor are getting poorer. Affluent America
and anguished America have turned against each other and are
quickly marching in very different directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who cannot afford or even
contemplate upscaling their tastes,'' Kammen says. ``For them,
shopping at Wal-Mart is a necessity. Just figuring out which of
this month's bills must go unpaid is a part of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet they are not ignorant of the prosperity that surrounds and
nearly plagues them. They see it on TV in ``Frasier's'' apartment
and ``Ally'' ``McBea''l's hip new digs, hear it on the radio, and
watch it walking down the aisles at Wal-Mart, where they are no
longer the most targeted demographic. It's almost as if corporate
America is simply turning its head.
</P>
<P>
   So, Kammen says, they justify.
</P>
<P>
   ``When asked if they envy the lifestyle of the people on TV,
they say no,'' he says. ``Because what they see on TV or movies in
relation to prosperous living is dysfunctional families, not to
suggest there are no dysfunctional families among them, but they
tend to be churchgoing, less materialistic, and they know what they
can't afford.
</P>
<P>
   ``They work out a rationale for why they don't want or need it,
and say, `We are a close family, we have each other.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Kammen says, through all of this prosperity, all of
this blur, the reality is that the upscaling of America will
continue to assert itself on poor people and push them out of the
little worlds they've created for themselves. The direction they
will go is simply further back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amidst all of this affluence, at least 20 to 25 percent of the
country is just making it, and the middle class is going deeply
into debt,'' he says. ``A run of prosperity for a decade is an
unprecedented phenomenon, and there is bound to be a correction
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's going to hurt the underclass very severly, especially
minorities and women: They're less likely to be hired, and single
moms have tough trade-off choices to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, his hypothesis is becoming increasingly apparent. As
always, the smaller ethnic demographics are getting a smaller piece
of the prosperity pie. There are very few upscale magazines
targeted to minorities. This fall, there will not be any minority
characters in lead roles on network TV. There are not upscale
Mexican restaurants; rather, they're billed as places to eat great
for less. Martha Stewart's pastels aren't made to appeal to bright
Hispanic neighborhoods. Soul food is not represented in Vegas' new
Bellagio hotel.
</P>
<P>
   In the Latino community, that small piece of the pie is Cristina
Saralegui, a talk-show hostess on the Spanish-language TV network
Univision.
</P>
<P>
   She talks about upscale issues, dresses flawlessly and never has
a hair out of place. She has been called a Hispanic Oprah, as
though the label is needed to explain her. It's almost as if she's
made to look like she's marketed to the masses, but only a very
small portion of Hispanics can actually identify with her success.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of cross-cultural comparison also happens in the Black
community. One star for the Black upper-class, TV goddess Barbara
Smith, has been labeled a ``Black Martha Stewart.''
</P>
<P>
   This fall, B. Smith, as she is known, will have her own
magazine, ``B.'' ``Smith Style,'' but, according to the ``New York
Times,'' the publication's success is hinged on Smith's crossover
appeal: 75 percent of the viewers of her television show, ``B.
Smith, With Style,'' are White.
</P>
<P>
   However, for the most part, and most of the country, these years
will go down as an era of good fortune, good coffee and great TV
dinners.
</P>
<P>
   And let's not forget Martha, the real Lady Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Give her your tired and your poor. She will provide them with
great, cheap sheets. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jaimee Rose can be reached at Jaimee.Rose(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
