   SCI-TSIEN-MOUSE (Undated) _ A Scientist-at-Work profile: The
world has been frenetically beating on the door of Joe Z. Tsien,
the biologist who announced last week he had created a smarter
strain of mouse. Within this enveloping chaos, Tsien has spun
around himself a small bubble of protective serenity. He calmly
describes the remarkable journey that led him from Wu Shi, a small
town near Shanghai, to the position of having made a significant,
maybe decisive, contribution to understanding the nature of memory.
By Nicholas Wade. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo (NYT3).
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ELECTRON-BONDS (Undated) _ Of the roughly 20 million
chemical substances scientists have catalogued, nearly all are
assemblages of atoms linked together by electronic bonds. The quest
to understand these tiny bonds _ the very glue of material
existence _ is the heart of chemical science. A step in this quest
was reported last week with the publication of the sharpest direct
images ever made of electronic bonds, known as orbitals. The shapes
revealed by these images _ doughnut-like rings, dumbbell-shaped
lobes and arrays suggestive of butterfly wings _ confirmed
theoretical predictions of what these bonds should look like in the
particular molecule under study. By Malcolm W. Browne. (1050 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIABETES (Undated) _ With rates of diabetes soaring, experts
are studying patterns of prevention in people genetically
predisposed to the disease, and looking a ways to control
cardiovascular problems in people who already have diabetes. By
Denise Grady. (1800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo (NYT4).
