u i BC-Israel-interrogation-     09-06 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-interrogation-0907-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERROGATIONS OF PALESTINIANS USE HOODS, SHAKINGS, SLEEP
DEPRIVATION
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM The worst is the shaking.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates are handcuffed and shackled, then shaken violently. It
goes on repeatedly, each bout lasting about five seconds. Inmates
say they lose sensation in their heads, pass out or throw up.
Later, some complain of damaged vertebrae.
</P>
<P>
   Ten inmates have died in interrogation since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The shaking is one of the abuses of Palestinian prisoners
specifically banned Monday by the Israeli supreme court. In an
unprecedented ruling, the court ordered that Israel's secret
service stop using the widespread tactics of physical abuse.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear if the security officials might find ways to
circumvent the ruling. They say they must be rough in order to find
out about imminent bomb threats. But, human rights activists say
it's more often used to force confessions or conduct fishing
expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   In a Jerusalem office Monday, Nawwaf Al-Qaysi, a 24-year-old
Palestinian from Bethlehem, was shown a clean hood silimar to those
that inmates are kept in for hours. He smiled and said it was not
like the one that he was forced to wear, which reeked of vomit.
</P>
<P>
   He underwent interrogations in 1997 in the Russian Compound
prison, a cluster of non-descript low buildings surrounded by rolls
of barbed wire in downtown Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he was released without charges, but for three
months interrogators tried to get him to sign confessions that he
was a member of a terror group and trained terrorists in using
weapons. He wouldn't confess.
</P>
<P>
   He said they kept him arched over a chair for hours while he
cried and screamed for help. When he asked for relief, his
interrogators asked if that meant he was ready to sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always told my interrogator,
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to tell the judge about the methods you are using
against me,''' says Al-Qaysi. ``He would say,
</P>
<P>
   The judge is your enemy, who are you going to complain to?'''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Israeli human rights group B'Tselem, hundreds
of prisoners face this every year under the captivity of a giant
Israeli interrogation bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   While the official name for it is ``moderate physical
pressure,'' human rights groups call it ``torture.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other names involved. There is the ``frog,'' in which
inmates are forced to crouch for hours with their hands tied behind
them.
</P>
<P>
   There is the ``table press,'' in which inmates are made to squat
on the floor while their hands are pulled up behind their backs and
cuffed at head level to a table top. Interrogators will sit on the
table jam their feet down on the inmates' shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Interrogators also cuff inmates into, or arched backward over,
tiny chairs. Inmates are handcuffed to pipes high on the wall,
requiring them to stand on their toes for hours.
</P>
<P>
   A B'Tselem report displays logs kept by interrogators of just
how long inmates were made to squat or were deprived of sleep.
Doctors occasionally check their health.
</P>
<P>
   B'Tselem also showed that often the interrogations would stop
over the weekends, when interrogators took days off. According to
the group this belies the assertion that the interrogations are
needed to thwart imminent terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
