   &UR; TRADING _  &LR; Institutional investors have enjoyed after-hours
trading for many years, trading by computer through a dozen or so
self-contained, fully automated electronic communications networks.
The networks serve as surrogate markets when the principal markets
_ such as the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq _ are closed. Now
brokers have realized that it is in their best interest to let
their retail customers trade outside the normal stock-exchange
hours. By ARTHUR LOUIS
