<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-TRAVELBIZ07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    City homers on sports travelers
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta and the South are high scorers when it comes
to drawing sports travelers to the area.
</P>
<P>
   The city tied with Chicago for getting the biggest chunk _ 4
percent _ of the nation's 75.3 million adults who attended
organized sports events in the last five years, according to a
study by the Washington, D.C.-based Travel Industry Association of
America.
</P>
<P>
   For most of those travelers, attending the sporting event was
the primary reason for the trip, the TIA survey found.
</P>
<P>
   Others attended games while in town for conventions, business
meetings or personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Only those visitors who traveled at least 50 miles from home
were included in the survey, which looked at both sports spectators
and participants.
</P>
<P>
   The results brought high-fives from officials at the Atlanta
Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ACVB officials recently invited dozens of journalists to tour
Atlanta, which they billed as ``the sports capital of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were close, and we have a heck of a story to tell,''
said Bill Howard, ACVB vice president of communications and
tourism. ``This simply validates our claim. The story is that
Atlanta has cornered the market in sports business.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite.
</P>
<P>
   While Atlanta ties Chicago in garnering the biggest share of
overall sports travelers, it ranks somewhat lower when it comes to
the percentage of overall visitors who take in a sporting event
while they are here.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that one out of every 10 visitors to Atlanta
takes in one sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   At least nine cities had higher percentages, including Charlotte
with 19 percent; Indianapolis, 17 percent; and Milwaukee, 13
percent. Those metropolitan areas also have smaller number of
visitors than Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can read this as you're doing well, but maybe you can get
the percentage up a little higher,'' said Dexter Koehl, a TIA
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The region also did well. Thirty-nine percent of people across
the nation who traveled for sports events did so to attend an event
in the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, it has to do a little bit with climate. You have a
much longer season when it's warm and people can participate in
outdoor sports,'' said Koehl. The number of professional teams and
the number of universities in the area also help.
</P>
<P>
   While this is the first year the TIA has released the study, few
doubt the economic benefits of sports in the Atlanta area. When a
big sporting event is held in the area, the big scorer is not
necessarily on the field. Restaurants, hotels and retailers all
stand to benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Shelia M. Poole writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
