<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2317 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-TEENS07-COX     09-06 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TEENS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prime time gets even younger as youth take center stages in new
series
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Here they come, barreling down their high school
hallway, three high school girls, each better-looking and more
stuck-up than the next, cutting through the losers clogging the
hallway, snapping out: ``Move. Move. Move.''
</P>
<P>
   That one scene, in Fox's upcoming be-cruel-to-your-school series
``Manchester Prep,'' nicely sums up the coming onslaught of new
fall TV shows: Get out of the way, geezers. The kids are here.
</P>
<P>
   Never before has there been such a one-time flood of new shows
set in high schools, or about teenagers and their families, as in
the coming fall television season. Six new series focus almost
exclusively on adolescents, three others deal with teenagers
prominently as parts of families, and they join seven returning
shows, from ``Sabrina the Teenage Witch'' and ``Moesha'' to
``Dawson's Creek'' (arguably the show that started this teen
tsunami). That's at least 16 series to make you realize that
television is no longer the ``vast wasteland'' that Newton Minow
famously described in 1961, but a teenage wasteland.
</P>
<P>
   Hearts will be broken, bullies will be fought, cheerleaders will
be envied, angst will be analyzed, parents will be eye-rolled and
``whatevered'' into oblivion, and sex _ talking about it, if not
always doing it _ will be more widespread than Oxy 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``High school is our one universal experience,'' says Thomas
Hine, author of the new book ``The Rise and Fall of the American
Teenager.'' ``Everything else is becoming more diverse, but very
little has changed about high school. More people can identify with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's a school of thought that nobody ever gets over high
school. ``So much of what you experience during that time of life
stays with you,'' says Gina Matthews, co-creator of the new WB
series ``Popular.'' ``It never, ever ends.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this season, anyway, as prime-time TV keeps getting younger
and younger. A decade ago, one of the most talked-about shows on
television was the Emmy-winning ``thirtysomething.'' Five years ago
this month, ``Friends'' debuted, launching a spate of copycat shows
about single people in their 20s. Now television's aim is squarely
at teens, an audience that was barely served a few years ago with
only a handful of shows such as ``Blossom'' and ``Clarissa Explains
It All.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The networks are increasingly chronologically challenged,''
says John Rash, senior vice president of the ad-buying firm
Campbell Mithun Espy. ``They're trying to program younger so
they're sampled by an entire generation that's been reared on
cable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time since the baby boom generation that the
mainstream media have really been catering to teens,'' says Hine.
Chalk it up to a couple of factors: Changing demographics and the
emergence of the WB.
</P>
<P>
   There are now about 31 million teenagers (ages 12-19) in the
United States, the largest number there has been since the baby
boom. According to the marketing firm Teen Research Unlimited, they
spend more than $120 billion a year of their own and their
families' money.
</P>
<P>
   The WB was the first network to exploit this phenomenon with
true zeal. Its lineup of shows, including ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer,'' ``7th Heaven,'' ``Felicity'' and, of course, ``Dawson,''
doesn't get a fraction of the audience of heavyweights such as ``60
Minutes'' or ``Frasier.'' But they generate tremendous buzz, and
advertisers love them: The WB's ad sales for the coming season were
up 50 percent this summer, far more than any other network.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WB used to be a joke, but now it's taken oh-so-seriously.
We all get it,'' says Leeza Gibbons, who anchored a report about
``Hollywood's Youth Obsession'' on the cable network E! last month.
</P>
<P>
   The recent, parallel explosion of teen-themed feature movies has
fed, and fed off of, television's growing teen-mania. By the end of
this year, the four cast members of ``Dawson'' will have appeared
in 13 movies since the show debuted in early 1998. This spring's
movie ``Cruel Intentions'' starred Sarah Michelle Gellar of
``Buffy,'' Joshua Jackson of ``Dawson'' and Selma Blair of ``Zoe,
Duncan, Jack and Jane,'' all on the WB; then ``Cruel Intentions''
was turned into the upcoming Fox series ``Manchester Prep.''
Jennifer Love Hewitt is both a young movie and TV star; her Fox
spinoff, ``Times of Your Life,'' will get a strong teen turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not everything is going the WB's way. ``If you're
selling Viagra, you're not going to do it at the WB,'' jokes CBS
President Leslie Moonves.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason teen shows are successful, and expanding, is
that teenagers are ``early adapters,'' picking up on new things
first. The idea is to then get younger children and adults on the
bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the WB's audience is in the 18-49 age group that
advertisers want most. And Paul Feig, creator of NBC's ``Freaks and
Geeks,'' says his show is aimed at adults with small children who
stay home on Saturday nights and don't have anything to watch. The
show's somewhat rueful nostalgia, harking back to 1980, is
reminiscent of ``The Wonder Years,'' a show that drew more adults
than children.
</P>
<P>
   (Rash, of ad agency Campbell Mithun Espy, says ``Freaks and
Geeks'' is the best of the new teen-themed shows, ``but it's going
to face Nielsen detention unless it gets expelled from its Saturday
night time period.'')
</P>
<P>
   As for preteens who might watch, concerned parents should know
that most of these shows deal pretty frankly in sexuality, although
it's interesting where different shows draw the line on different
topics. Fox's ``Manchester Prep'' has a teenage girl ogling her
nude stepbrother in the shower and later trying to seduce him. But
on ``Freaks and Geeks,'' when the young rebels go outside to a
``smoking patio,'' no one is shown smoking. ``We didn't want to
promote it,'' says Feig. ``You can't help but glamorize it.''
</P>
<P>
   But one area that nearly all of the teen shows will work
relentlessly is the idea of cliques in high schools, of ins and
outs, a subject that can be dealt with lightheartedly or with
seriousness, particularly in the wake of the Columbine High School
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone know what it's like at some point not to fit in,''
says Sarah Michelle Gellar of ``Buffy.'' ``Everyone thinks that
it's only their pain, and that only they feel it. But everyone
feels it on different levels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we're studying is this problem of teenage
alienation, the sense of not being part of the high school
experience, and being excluded,'' says WB Chief Executive Officer
Jamie Kellner. Both ``7th Heaven'' and the new series ``Safe
Harbor'' are planning several episodes about teen alienation; the
idea of being an outsider is central to ``Roswell''; and the
conflicts among various high school cliques are at the core of
``Freaks and Geeks'' and ``Popular.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hine warns that the TV industry may have overdone it.
Teenagers are notoriously difficult to capture for regular viewing.
``This is an audience that's restless, that has a lot of other
things competing for its time,'' he notes. ``Television may be
going off a cliff with this.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds against most new prime-time series are brutal anyway,
even without the oversaturation of a particular trend that Hine
warns against. Many of these new shows are destined to be canceled,
in which case the networks can at least live by the motto that
teenagers like to quote sometimes, if not actually embrace: Live
fast, die young, and leave a good-looking corpse.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
