<P>
   ISRAEL-TORTURE _ JERUSALEM _ In a landmark decision, the Israeli
supreme court Monday outlawed the systematic use of sleep
depravation, shakings and other physical abuse of Palestinian
prisoners in interrogation. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-INTERROGATION _ JERUSALEM _ They chain them contorted and
arched over tiny chairs. They deprive them of sleep for days, keep
them under hoods reeking of vomit and sweat. Worst of all, they
handcuff them and shake them furiously, leaving them dazed and, in
a few cases, dead. These are the methods the Israeli secret service
calls ``moderate physical pressure'' in interrogations of
Palestinian prisoners. When the Israeli supreme court ruled Monday
the practice must stop, it did little to please Nawwaf al-Queisi,
who underwent the treatment for three months. WITH PHOTOS. (Kaplow,
Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   WIRED-CLASSROOM _ ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech has developed Classroom
2000, a completely wired classroom that allows everything the
professor writes and says to be audio and video taped directly into
a webpage for immediate access for students. For example, a student
can click on a word or name the the professor said in class and get
that portion of the class, in text, video and/or audio. This
relieves the students from the burden of taking detailed notes and
allows them to pay more attention in class. (Suggs, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Imagine losing your son in a car
accident. Imagine all you have left of him are his 1-year-old
twins, a boy and a girl. Imagine that you have babysat for the
twins since birth, and you feel as close to them as your own
children. Then imagine that your daughter-in-law remarries and
won't let you see the kids. Imagine being told that, under Ohio
law, you have no right to see your grandchildren. Imagine all that,
and you have some idea how it feels to be 53-year-old Linda Flory
of Clearcreek Twp., Ohio. (McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURGH, Ohio _ Generous readers often take
the time to share with me a few hints of their own. I'll pass them
on, but I make no guarantees because it's a little tough to know
when someone's pulling my leg through the mail. You be the judge.
(Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANE-COLUMN _ DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Dog walkers see all. Dog
walkers know all. If I were not a dog walker, I would ignore Labor
Day. I would still wear my summer jacket with white buttons. I
would cruise through September with a surf-dude's endless-summer
grin. Instead, I walked the dog out into the early morning and felt
an unfamiliar sensation. I was outdoors and I was not hot. It
wasn't cool exactly. But clearly I had stumbled upon a landmark day
in the Florida year _ the first non-hot day. (Lane, Daytona Beach
News-Journal) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EZZARD-COLUMN _ TIGER, Ga. _ My friend Coyl Justice, who grows
some of the best rhododendron and native azalea in North Georgia,
couldn't wait to tell me the news. No, it wasn't about plants; it
was about catching coons with grape jelly. (Ezzard, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ The ATF blew it. The FBI blew it.
But first of all this was a local story _ an inability or
unwillingness by local authorities to address a clear and present
danger: that David Koresh was making babies with children far too
young to give legal consent, much less understand the term. (Young,
Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-TRAVELBIZ _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta and the South are high
scorers when it comes to drawing sports travelers. The city tied
with Chicago for getting the biggest chunk _ 4 percent _ of the
nation's 75.3 million adults who attended organized sports events
in the last five years, according to a study by the Washington,
D.C.-based Travel Industry Association of America. (Poole, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
