v b BC-BUDGET-SPI &LR;      09-06 0075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Tuesday Sept. 7 and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Mary Downes on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   NAILS-ART (Undated) _ Bye bye long, colorful nails. The look is
natural. Buffed, healthy, short nails.
</P>
<P>
   By Susan Phinney. (Story will move in the ``l'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 1805EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990906.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2336 &Cx1f; tth-z
u l BC-NAILS-ART-SPI &LR;      09-06 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAILS-ART-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRENDS POINT TO REAL, SHORT AND SUBTLE NAILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SUSAN PHINNEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long, brightly colored nails are dust. Real or fake, they have
been filed away, grown out, shed like an old snakeskin.
</P>
<P>
   Leaf through a fashion magazine. Every model and celebrity
featured is sporting natural nails _ nails that since the 1980s
have been found only on professional pianists, or possibly those in
medical professions.
</P>
<P>
   Today's status nails are short. If polished at all, they're
pale. Artificial nails still on hand are so short and subtle it
takes a detective to find them.
</P>
<P>
   Nail purists, who spent years hiding their unadorned nails while
long red talons flashed their way through fashionland, are having
the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Even the ``Fashion Police'' _ a k a columnist Jeannine Stein _
have declared that natural looking nails are in. And when nails are
the professionally applied acrylic variety, they shouldn't extend
more than a quarter of an inch, Stein declares.
</P>
<P>
   The spa that Nordstrom opened in its downtown Seattle store
doesn't offer artificial nails, or even polished nails in
manicures. Spa training director Lise Corriveau says Spa Nordstrom
is dedicated to promoting the health of the natural nail.
</P>
<P>
   Nails are oiled, conditioned and buffed three ways in a $35
manicure that doesn't end with coats of polish. Corriveau says
polish wouldn't adhere properly to nails that have been treated
with oils and a parafin dip.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica Vartoughian, a nail guru who's been preaching and
practicing natural nail care in her Hollywood salon since 1969,
says she's seen the natural trend coming for the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   She believes acrylic nails made women more aware of their nails
and nail care. Consumers have become more demanding. It's no longer
about long nails; they want beautifully groomed hands, Vartoughian
says.
</P>
<P>
   Vartoughian's clients keep 32 manicurists booked. Customers are
expected to come in every 10 to 14 days for treatment, and their
nails had better look almost as good as they did when they left the
salon after the last visit. Daily home-maintenance isn't just
expected _ it's demanded.
</P>
<P>
   If a client breaks or tears off a nail, it's to be brought to
the salon where it's repaired without glues. Vartoughian even keeps
a nail bank of real nails for ``transplants.''
</P>
<P>
   Natural may be key, but Vartoughian's a believer in polish to
protect the nails _ two basecoats, two coats of polish, a top coat
then a ``brilliance'' layer to dry and finish the manicure. At
Seattle-area Gene Juarez salons, the natural nail trend has been
growing for about five years. Linda Green, director of nail
services, says artificial nails used to be about two-thirds of
their business. Today 85 percent of their customers are into
natural nails.
</P>
<P>
   Green defines ``natural'' nails as those without enhancements _
no acrylic, fiberglass or silk applied to nails. But polish is a
must. ``A nail should never be without protection,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Reardon, owner of Frenchy's in Madison Park, says
artificial nails were about 70 percent of business three years ago.
Today it's about 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Reardon sees several reasons for the trend. ``We're going back
to a simpler, more practical way of looking at beauty. It's also
the Northwest style,'' she says. There's also a shortage of nail
technicians. A manicurist can do two ``natural'' manicures in the
time it takes to do maintenance on one set of fake nails.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding heavy maintenance is another reason nails are going
natural. Nina Ummel, owner of Ummelina Spa in downtown Seattle,
says women just don't have time to handle chipped polish, broken
nails and damage to natural nails.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that damage is simply annoying, some is serious. The
dermatology department at Seattle's Virginia Mason Clinic has seen
cases of fungal infections and contact dermatitis rise with the
popularity of acrylic nails. Even heavy coats of polish put nails
at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't understand until it happens to them,'' says
Sharon Wells, a dermatology nurse. A typical treatment is 12 weeks
on an oral, anti-fungal medication _ an expensive prescription
that's not covered by all insurance companies, Wells says.
</P>
<P>
   And after all that, you have to wait for your nails to grow out
again.
</P>
<P>
   Not all manicures are created equal.
</P>
<P>
   There are plain manicures to remove polish, file, buff,
condition cuticles and re-polish. Prices usually start at about
$15. At some salons, polish is extra. At others, the more
experienced nail technicians cost more.
</P>
<P>
   Spa manicures are another category. Prices for these start at
$20 and go to $35 in the Seattle area. These usually include warm
soaks, heated mitts, oil treatments, possibly a parafin dip for the
hands. At some salons, clients rest on a bed in a treatment room
during the manicure.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes polish is included, and at least one spa doesn't offer
it at all, so it's best to find out what's available when making an
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   And appointments are necessary. Demand still outweighs supply.
So call ahead and specify what kind of services you need.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
