UPSCALE (Phoenix) - Wal-Mart is installing cappuccino bars. Oprah
is hawking haute literature. TV is fine, but Bose home theater is
very much the dream screen. The sport utility vehicle has trumped
the station wagon. Wolfgang Puck has his own TV dinners at Fry's.
Phoenix Art Museum ads are nestled between Britney Spears and Cher
on the radio. There are dog-biscuit bakeries, Ralph Lauren
restaurants and concierges at apartment complexes. Even cigar bars,
chic home decor at Target and brand-name water. Getting the pretty
little picture? Right under our upturned noses, America is going
decidedly upscale. By JAMIEE ROSE. Story moved in the ``K'' and
``L'' catgories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TV-GOODY (Undated) _ Last March, ``60 Minutes II'' broadcast a
heartbreaking story chronicling England's postwar shipment of
10,000 children to Australia, where they were subjected to hunger,
abuse and other horrors in orphanages. In Phoenix, Mike Amphlett
tuned in. Briefly. ``I couldn't watch,'' Amphlett said. ``I just
went over to the kitchen and started gagging. That was it.''
Amphlett, you see, was one of the 10,000, one of those shipped to
Australia to relieve overcrowding in British orphanages. By BILL
GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
