<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Sept. 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   The remnants of Hurricane Dennis will continue to bring showers
and thunderstorms to portions of the Middle Atlantic States and New
England on Tuesday. In the Appalachians, the interaction of the
moisture from Dennis and an approaching cool front will lead to an
area of heavier rain in upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   Another region of scattered showers and thunderstorms will push
through New England, with some locations receiving as much as 2
inches of rain in tropical downpours. In addition, most of the
Northeast will remain very humid because of the tropical air mass
associated with the remains of Dennis.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, a weak jet-stream disturbance will pass over the
Gulf Coast, causing scattered showers and thunderstorms to erupt.
In south Texas, the remnants of a tropical depression that made
landfall in Mexico will bring numerous showers and thunderstorms
with heavy rainfall to the region.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will develop ahead of a potent cyclone
crossing the northern Plains. A cold front extending south from
this low-pressure center marks the leading edge of cooler and drier
air moving to the south from Canada. Farther west, moisture
wrapping around this cyclone will promote abundant clouds and low
conditions in northern sections of Montana.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest will continue to remain sunny and hot with just a
few thunderstorms likely in the higher elevations of New Mexico.
Meanwhile, the Northwest will turn milder as offshore winds descend
the Cascades and become warmer, raising readings across western
Oregon and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Radar Rain Gauge
</P>
<P>
   While official rain gauges are located many miles apart, radar
can act as a giant rain gauge blanketing a large area. When
microwaves emitted by radar encounter raindrops, the amount of
energy returned to the radar site provides an estimate of the
rainfall rate. The relationship between the reflected energy and
the rainfall is a complex one that depends in part upon the size
and density of droplets in the clouds. On Monday some sites in the
east switched their radars in the tropical mode to provide better
estimates of rainfall from clouds comprising the remnants of
Hurricane Dennis.
</P>
</TEXT>
