<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2356 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-VITALSIGNS-NYT &LR;      09-06 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-VITAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
 SIGNS-NYT   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUTRITION: When Refrigerator Raiders Lose Control
</P>
<P>
   Everyone gets the late-night munchies now and then, whether for
rocky road ice cream or a Dagwood sandwich of salami, pickles and
deli Swiss on rye.
</P>
<P>
   For some, however, nighttime kitchen raids are frequent,
uncontrollable and distressing.
</P>
<P>
   Night eating syndrome was first identified in 1955, but now it
is being studied in greater depth. In an article in The Journal of
the American Medical Association last month, researchers at the
University of Pennsylvania reported on the results of a study of 10
obese people who exhibited typical signs of night eating syndrome:
lack of morning appetite, evening overeating and insomnia. They
were compared with 10 people who were matched for age, sex and
weight, but did not have problems with nighttime eating.
</P>
<P>
   For the estimated 3.8 million Americans afflicted with the
disorder, the drive to eat at night tends to undermine even the
most earnest daytime weight-loss efforts. And no wonder: on
average, the study found, night eaters consumed fully 56 percent of
their entire intake of calories during these nighttime episodes.
They also tended to eat more often during the day than people in a
control group and to wake up nearly 10 times as often each night.
Finally, more than half of all waking episodes were associated with
some form of food intake.
</P>
<P>
   Just how these episodes might be controlled is still a mystery,
but the lead researcher, Dr. Grethe Stoa Birketvedt, said a
possible treatment might be suggested by the fact that sufferers
typically consume carbohydrate-rich foods at night.
</P>
<P>
   High carbohydrate intake increases serotonin production, which
in turn facilitates sleep. This suggests a vicious cycle in which
sufferers effectively wake up to eat so they can sleep. Controlling
serotonin levels might provide one solution.
</P>
<P>
   Tinkering with night eaters' day menus to prevent carbohydrate
cravings at night may be another. ``It is tempting to speculate if
this is a result of the composition of the diet that these night
eaters have,'' Dr. Birketvedt said, ``but this requires further
studies.''
</P>
<P>
   _TOM ZELLER
</P>
<P>
   IN THE LAB: Promising Progress in Lupus Research
</P>
<P>
   No one is talking about a cure, or even any improvement in the
very near future, but researchers are reporting some promising
progress in the field of lupus, a serious autoimmune disease
affecting about 1.5 million people in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the University of Texas say they have identified
four genes that can halt the now incurable, potentially fatal
disease. They published their findings in the current issue of
Immunity.
</P>
<P>
   In people with lupus, the body loses its ability to tell the
difference between its own cells and those of invaders like
viruses. As a result, antibodies begin attacking healthy cells and
organs, causing damage in the joints, lungs, kidneys and nerves.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Dr. Edward K. Wakeland, the lead author of the
study, reported finding the genes that cause lupus through three
biological ``pathways.'' Wakeland and his colleagues at the
Southwestern Medical Center at Dallas Center for Immunology found
that at least two of the genes had to be present for lupus to
occur.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest study, which used mice bred to have the disease,
Wakeland found four ``suppressor'' genes that, when present in the
mice, seemed to stop lupus.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were mice that didn't even get sick,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More work is being done to identify the suppressor genes and how
they work. If that is successful, scientists will try to develop a
drug that mimics the mechanism at the genetic level. But it will
take time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being very optimistic,'' Wakeland said, ``I imagine it would
be five years before there would be a drug that would be
available.''
</P>
<P>
   _ERIC NAGOURNEY
</P>
<P>
   CONSEQUENCES: Seeing Illness as Retribution for Misdeeds
</P>
<P>
   ``Immanent Justice'' may sound like the title of a Jackie Chan
movie, but it is the name developmental psychologists use for a
widely held, if erroneous, assumption: that illness can be a
punishment for bad behavior.
</P>
<P>
   A new study reported at the annual meeting of the American
Psychological Association last month indicates that under some
circumstances otherwise reasonable adults may adopt this karmic
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Two researchers at Ohio State University presented 239 college
students with the story of a man described as a liar and a cheat
who contracts a ``mysterious, deadly illness.'' Depending on how
the story was presented, the researchers found that 19 percent to
44 percent of the participants agreed with the idea that the man's
illness might be a punishment for his misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   The highest level of agreement came when the interviewer
amplified the tale with a familiar retributive expression _ ``what
goes around comes around'' _ and added a minor character who seemed
to reinforce the link between behavior and illness.
</P>
<P>
   One of the researchers, Lakshi Raman, a graduate student in
psychology, suggested that the study showed that people might
``fall back on unscientific reasoning when rational explanations
aren't readily available.''
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps their belief is just wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   _MICHAEL PORTER
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
