<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bees Buzzing With Data
</P>
<P>
   When a honeybee finds a good source of food, it quickly alerts
its hive mates as to what it is and where to find it. With the
honeybee's cousin the bumblebee, however, foraging has been
considered an every-bee-for-itself affair. Bumblebees were thought
to guard information about food sources, like a New Yorker who has
discovered a great hole-in-the-wall restaurant and doesn't want it
to get overrun.
</P>
<P>
   But new research by scientists from the University of Wuerzburg
in Germany shows that bumblebees aren't that tight-lipped. By
carefully controlling which insects in a nest were able to search
for food and what they were able to find, the researchers
discovered that a returning bumblebee tells its mates about the
type of flower it found. It just doesn't reveal the location.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the researchers found, a successful forager can hardly
contain itself. Upon returning, it spends several minutes bouncing
around the nest, excitedly buzzing its wings from time to time so
that the other bees can detect the odor of the particular flower
species it visited.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, writing in the journal Nature, suggest that it
might not be worthwhile for bumblebees to share information about
location. Honeybees can take up to an hour to decide on which of
several reported food locations to visit. Bumblebees, which live in
smaller colonies and thus have fewer foragers, may not have the
luxury of dawdling. So once it knows the type of flower that is
available, a bumblebee may be able to use its innate searching
skills to find it quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Not So Fast
</P>
<P>
   Highway driving sometimes just isn't fair. On a congested road,
for instance, it always seems like it's the cars in the other lane
that are moving faster.
</P>
<P>
   But that may only be an illusion, say a team of researchers from
the United States and Canada who studied the phenomenon using
computer simulations and video recordings of highway traffic.
</P>
<P>
   On a congested road, two lanes of traffic may have the same
average speed, although the actual speed of each car will vary over
time. Cars that are going faster tend to be farther apart, while
slower cars tend to be closer together. So a driver tends to pass a
bunch of slower moving cars relatively quickly, while it takes
longer for a group of faster cars to pass the driver.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, whose work was reported in Nature, suggest that
this time difference is what makes the driver think the other lane
is faster; the driver is spending more time being passed than
passing.
</P>
<P>
   Other factors are probably at work as well, the researchers say.
Because drivers look forward rather than backward, slower cars that
are passed are out of sight, and thus out of mind, sooner than cars
that are passing. And psychologically, being passed may have more
impact than passing; the losses may outweigh the gains in the
driver's mind. Whatever the reason, the researchers note, it seldom
pays to change lanes.
</P>
<P>
   A Close-up of Cassini
</P>
<P>
   Largely forgotten amid all the hubbub surrounding the near-Earth
approach last month of the Cassini spacecraft was the fact that the
flyby gave the mission's operators the first chance to test the
cameras that will be used when the probe reaches Jupiter and
Saturn.
</P>
<P>
   Cassini came within 700 miles of Earth as part of a plan to use
the planet's gravity to boost the spacecraft's speed for the long
trip to Jupiter, which it will approach at the end of next year,
and to Saturn, where it is due in 2004. Some people were concerned
that if the trajectory was off, the spacecraft could have been
incinerated over the Pacific Ocean, dispersing the on-board
plutonium (used to generate power) into the atmosphere. That didn't
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Cassini scientists and engineers took advantage of the approach
to try out the cameras, aiming them at the Moon. The two cameras,
one a wide-angle model, the other a narrow-angle one, worked
perfectly, the mission operators said.
</P>
<P>
   Images can be seen on the Web, at photojournal.jpl.nasa.gov.
</P>
<P>
   New Roach Repellant
</P>
<P>
   It's not just for cats anymore. Researchers from Iowa State
University have discovered that cockroaches, too, have a thing
about catnip, as some old household bug remedies claimed. Unlike
cats, though, which will keep coming back to a catnip toy that
drives them crazy, roaches will scramble to get away from the
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said that their work might eventually lead to
the development of new bug repellents. But as even they
acknowledged, most people don't want cockroaches to go away, they
want them dead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
