<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WEIGHT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC DIET PILL IS CALLED HOCUS-POCUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By LIZ NEPORENT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Products promising significant weight loss are nothing new. But
the television infomercials for two new diet supplements, Exercise
in a Bottle and Fat Trapper, are remarkable even in that genre.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisements claim that, taken in concert, the two
supplements, sold by Enforma Natural Products of Los Angeles, take
the place of exercise. In the half-hour infomercial, being shown
widely, the former baseball player Steve Garvey and a nutritionist,
Kendall Carson, tell viewers they can consume fattening foods and
still lose weight simply by taking a few pills every day. (The
regimen costs $35 a month.)
</P>
<P>
   Garvey says in the infomercial that pyruvate, a naturally
occurring enzyme that is the active ingredient in Exercise in a
Bottle, works by ``forcing every cell in your body to work harder
whether you're exercising or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Fat Trapper is a combination of chitin, a fiber derived from
shellfish, and chitosome, a plant fiber. ``It literally traps fat
before it gets into your system,'' Garvey says.
</P>
<P>
   But as with so many weight-loss products, these claims have
trouble standing up under scrutiny. The infomercial has been
attacked by consumer advocates and two district attorneys in
California, who have filed lawsuits accusing Enforma of false
advertising. The company denies the charges. Andrew Grey, its chief
executive, said in an interview, ``We vigorously defend our right
to market this product as we see fit.''
</P>
<P>
   To bolster the claim that pyruvate takes the place of exercise,
the infomercial quotes a University of Pittsburgh study finding
that subjects who took pyruvate supplements for 21 days lost fat at
a rate 48 percent higher, and weight at a rate 38 percent higher,
than nonusers.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that claim, Dr. Ronald Stanko, who performed the
study in 1996, replied, ``The information is absolutely on the
level, but I think the way it's being presented is perhaps a bit
misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanko's research looked at obese, bedridden women on
1,000-calorie-a-day diets, hardly normal circumstances for most
dieters. The women in the study were given 36 grams of pyruvate a
day for three weeks; the recommended dosage for Exercise in a
Bottle is just 1 gram. And though the rates of fat and weight loss
are quoted accurately, the subjects who took the pyruvate lost an
average of only 3.52 pounds more than those who did not.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey says Fat Trapper can absorb up to 120 grams of fat. To
demonstrate how the supplement works in the stomach, he pours bacon
grease into a glass of water. When the contents of four Fat Trapper
pills are added to the mix, large blobs of fat form and fall to the
bottom of the glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never mind that oil and water separate naturally,'' said David
Schardt, an associate nutritionist at the Center for Science in the
Public Interest, a consumer advocacy group in Washington. ``This is
a gross distortion of science.'' In reality, he said, the amount of
chitin and chitosome in a daily dose of Fat Trapper can bind bind 3
to 5 grams of fat, the equivalent of a pat of butter.
</P>
<P>
   The few human trials performed on chitin and chitosome seem to
support Schardt's assertions. Two Italian studies concluded that
they may offer a significant but small contribution to weight loss
when combined with a low-calorie diet. Schardt also warned that
long-term use of the supplements might lead to nutritional
deficiencies because they might prevent the body from absorbing
fat-soluble substances like vitamin D and vitamin E.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Enforma Natural Products says it has sold the two
supplements to half a million people this year and is planning a
new infomercial within the next two weeks. Grey, the company's
chief executive, stands behind his company's product and marketing.
``We tell our customers they should no longer have a fear of
restrictive diets, though it is not our intent to imply they can
gorge themselves four meals a day,'' he said. ``The Enforma system
is just that _ a system. Taking everything together is what
produces the greatest effects and benefits.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990906.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2363 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-FRAUD-NETSCAMS-SFCHRO     09-06 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAUD-NETSCAMS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Scams Plague Internet
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By TOM STEIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
Bill Banks, a 42-year-old financial planner from New Jersey, was in
the market for a new set of golf clubs. Like many of today's wired
consumers, he jumped onto the Internet to check out the best deals.
He now wishes he hadn't.
</P>
<P>
   Banks' foray led him to a small Internet company called Gary
Player Direct Inc., named after the famous golf pro. Impressed with
the look of the Web site and the Gary Player name, Banks placed a
credit card order for $719 in April.
</P>
<P>
   The clubs arrived a few weeks later, but after testing them out
at his local golf course, Banks decided they weren't for him. The
company had promised a 60-day money-back guarantee, so he shipped
the clubs back and waited for his Visa statement to be credited.
Four months later, he's still waiting _ and fuming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've phoned their customer service number countless times, but
mostly I've just been hung up on or disconnected,'' he said. ``I
even went back to the Web site and sent them a bunch of e-mails
demanding my money back. I got no response.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks said he feels helpless because he's in New Jersey, and
Gary Player Direct is located on the other side of the country in
San Luis Obispo. ``If this was a traditional retailer, I could go
to the shop and stand in front of them and demand satisfaction,''
he said. ``But in cyberspace, I feel I don't have any control.''
</P>
<P>
   Banks is not alone. As e-commerce sales continue to skyrocket,
more and more consumers are falling prey to dubious business
practices and outright fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The number of online fraud complaints leaped from 1,280 in 1997
to 7,752 last year, according to the Internet Fraud Watch, a
consumer watchdog group in Washington. Susan Grant, who directs the
organization, expects to tally well over 10,000 complaints this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Irate Internet consumers are pouring out of the woodwork. Brad
Clayton, a Portland foundry worker, had a run-in last year with a
Southern California company called Auction-Sales.com Inc., which
sells computer hardware, software and peripherals over the Internet
to the highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton was looking for a new computer chip and submitted a bid
for $101. The company sent him an e-mail confirming that he had won
the auction and the chip would be sent to him within a month.
</P>
<P>
   The product never arrived. When Clayton phoned to check the
status of his order, he first chatted with a ``very cordial,
well-spoken young lady.'' But as soon as he started asking some
questions about his order, ``she adopted a thick Latin accent and
pretended she didn't understand anything I was saying.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, though, the woman let it slip that Clayton's bid
wasn't high enough. ``Basically, they weren't going to honor the
bid because they felt it was too low, even though they told me I
had won.``
</P>
<P>
   Clayton said the company never debited his credit card account,
but it did cause him severe aggravation as well as several wasted
months. He finally went down to his local computer store and bought
the identical product for just a few dollars more than what he had
originally bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like Little Red Riding Hood being led down the path,''
said Clayton. ``The experience didn't sour me on the Net, but it
made me more selective about who I do business with.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of consumer groups, such as the Internet Fraud Watch
and Better Business Bureau Online, are popping up to educate the
public about the perils of conducting business in cyberspace. For
the most part, these groups believe in the power of the Internet
and the convenience it offers consumers. They just want to make
sure people are aware of the risks and take the proper precautions.
</P>
<P>
   One piece of advice is to question out-of-this-world claims made
on Web sites. ``If it's too good to be true, it probably is,'' said
Pat Wallace, president of the Bay Area chapter of the Better
Business Bureau, based in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The most flagrant piece of Internet fraud Wallace has
encountered was a Web page hosted by a fly-by-night company called
National Research Inc. The site was offering 12,000 free computers
on its site, and all consumers had to do to receive one was send
$20 to a certain post office box in Muskegan, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a pure scam,'' said Wallace. ``They were cashing $20
checks from anyone they could, and then they dropped off the face
of the Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Cash and checks are the worst way to purchase goods and services
over the Internet, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
   Grant of Internet Fraud Watch said cash payments allow crooks to
maintain their anonymity. Also, cash, checks or money orders don't
offer the same protection that a credit card does. Once a check or
money order is cashed, there is little to no chance of restitution.
</P>
<P>
   She said credit cards made up a minuscule 8 percent of all
fraudulent transactions reported to her organization, while checks
and money orders made up 38 percent and 33 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the law, if a product never arrives, the consumer
can write the credit card company within 60 days of making the
charge, disputing it,'' said Grant. ``The credit card company can
then remove the charge from the consumer's bill.''
</P>
<P>
   David Wilson is a 72-year-old retiree who got restitution the
old-fashioned way. After ordering _ and returning _ a $400 golf
club from Gary Player Direct, he waited patiently for his refund.
When it never came, he phoned and wrote letters to the company to
no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, on a trip to Southern California from his home in
Carmel, he stopped by the company's physical location in San Luis
Obispo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very solicitous and said they were trying to take
care of people in an orderly fashion,`' said Wilson. ``They said I
would get my money back within 10 days, and that actually
happened.``
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was relieved to finally get a refund but got no
satisfaction from the experience. ``They were playing games with
me,'' he said. ``I'm convinced that if I hadn't marched into their
physical office, they'd still be dodging me today.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gary Player Direct has had 250 complaints lodged against
it at the Better Business Bureau office in Santa Barbara. That's
more than any other company in the area, according to Rick Copelan,
the president of that bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Web-based business in particular there seems to be the
potential for trouble,'' said Copelan. ``These companies seem to
have problems delivering the correct merchandise and doing it on
time.''
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Cervantes, interim president and chief executive of Gary
Player Direct, said the company has been going through a very
difficult restructuring and has experienced ``operating problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still some cleaning up we need to do,'' said
Cervantes. ``But we've paid up $5.9 million in refunds and expect
to have the outstanding balance of $1.2 million cleared up within
the next 30 days.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the company plans to relaunch its Web site in the
near future _ possibly under the name  &LR; www.digitalgolf.com &LR;  _ and
add many new features, such as an online golf catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Still, one former employee who asked not to be identified, is
leery of the new plan. ``The company is nothing but a full-on
scam,'' she said, adding that the relaunch of the Web site
represents ``another avenue for ripping people off and getting away
from a name that has a bad rap.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to make Internet shopping less risky for consumers,
the BBB two years ago unveiled an online reliability program. As
part of the program, a representative from the agency visits each
company, no matter how big or small, at its place of business to
determine whether it can indeed deliver on what it promises on the
Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to meet the people and ascertain the company has a
real physical presence, and is not just a bunch of screens,'' said
Steve Salter, project director for BBBOnLine.
</P>
<P>
   So far 3,700 companies, such as Lands End, Staples, eBay and
CDNow have received the seal of approval, while several hundred
others have been turned down.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bill Banks said his experience with Gary Player
Direct has taught him a valuable lesson. ``I'm much more wary about
doing business on the Internet,'' he said. ``If it's not a company
I know, I won't shop at its Web site.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 1951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990906.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2364 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-FRAUDBOX-NETSCAMS-SFC     09-06 0185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAUDBOX-NETSCAMS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Cybershopping Tips
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TOM STEIN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _Do business with companies you already know and trust.
</P>
<P>
   _Check out the firm's track record with the local Better
Business Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   _Don't judge reliability by how nice or flashy a Web site may
seem.
</P>
<P>
   _Look for the company's physical location, including the mailing
address and phone number.
</P>
<P>
   _Determine the level of the company's security measures and
privacy policies before submitting credit card or personal
information.
</P>
<P>
   _Be extra cautious about deals that seem too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   _Pay by credit card, not cash or check.
</P>
<P>
   _Print out a copy of your order and confirmation number for your
records.
</P>
<P>
   _Know your rights. The same laws that protect you when you shop
by phone or mail apply when you shop in cyberspace. Under U.S. law,
a company must ship your order within the time stated in its
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Internet Fraud Watch (www.fraud.com), Federal Trade
Commission (www.ftc.gov), BBBOnLine (www.bbbonline.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
