<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 12) 
(jt) 
 By RAY CORMIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late-Season Northwest Trip
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I would like to stretch a November trip to the
Napa Valley for a wedding with a cruise or train trip in the
Northwest, perhaps across Canada. What is available then? _ Sylvia
K. Marzolf, Savannah, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A. Cruises up the Pacific Coast are hard to find by the end of
October, but cruises on some of the major rivers of the Northwest
continue. And scenic train rides are always available. You could
easily travel both on water and by rail.
</P>
<P>
   Among the cruises is a seven-day sailing out of Portland along
the Willamette, Columbia and Snake Rivers on the Queen of the West.
This 163-passenger stern-wheeler has outside cabins only. The
cruise includes entertainment and excursions on the Mount Hood
Scenic Railway, to Mount St. Helens and to the Nez Perce Historical
Park. Rates are $1,489 to $4,065 a person, double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, the Victoria Clipper, a high-speed catamaran,
offers shorter cruise-and-tour packages to Seattle, Vancouver and
Victoria, British Columbia, with nights spent on shore in a choice
of hotels. A two-night Seattle-Victoria package, for example,
including a cruise, a champagne breakfast, accommodations and a
tour in Victoria, costs $212 to $294 a person.
</P>
<P>
   An agency that can give you more information on these trips and
book them is Sunshine Travel and Cruise, Post Office Box 970, 100
West Second St., The Dalles, Ore. 97058; (800) 578-1479, fax (541)
296-5561.
</P>
<P>
   To see the Northwest by rail, contact Amtrak, (800) 872-7245,
www.amtrak.com, which has a tour division. The railroad's Coast
Starlight runs between Los Angeles and Seattle; you could pick it
up in Martinez, near Oakland, for an overnight trip and wake up in
Oregon. From Seattle, the Cascades route can take you to Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, Via Rail operates trains throughout the Canadian West
and across the country. Two routes are the 725-mile Skeena, between
Jasper, Alberta, and Prince George, British Columbia, and the
Malahat, which traverses Vancouver Island, south and north. And to
really see Canada _ or at least a good chunk of it _ there is the
Canadian, which runs between Vancouver and Toronto, through
Kamloops, Jasper, Edmonton, Saskatoon and Winnipeg.
</P>
<P>
   Via Rail, unlike Amtrak, does not arrange tours. Brewster Tours
of Calgary, (800) 661-1152, fax (403) 260-4636, www.brewster.ca, is
an agency that works with Via Rail. Shannon Birnie of Brewster said
that customized tours can be arranged, but that among the package
tours you might consider is the Winter Wonderland, a seven-night
rail-and-bus tour that begins in Vancouver and includes two nights
each in Jasper and Banff, and single nights on the train and in
Lake Louise and Calgary. Rates range from $735 to $891 a person,
double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   You might want to look into a joint promotion of Amtrak and Via
Rail, the North America Rail Pass. In fall and winter, the pass
costs $450 and provides 30 days of economy-class travel (upgrades
are possible) on both railroads. Contact Amtrak or the Via Rail Web
site, www.viarail.ca, for more information.
</P>
<P>
   Dublin Pub Tours
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I find out about literary pub tours in the fall in
Dublin? _Selma Kleinman, Rockaway Park, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. To raise a toast or two to Dublin's literary heritage, you
should contact Colm Quilligan, the founder of Dublin Literary Pub
Crawl Ltd., at (353-1) 670-5602 or (353-87) 263-0270, or by fax at
(353-1) 670-5603. There is also www.dublinpubcrawl.com, but at last
check, it had information only on the company's Paris Literary
Promenade.
</P>
<P>
   Quilligan said the Dublin tours are offered nightly at 7:30 and
at noon on Sunday from Easter to the end of October, and on
Thursday to Sunday at 7:30 p.m. and Sunday at noon the rest of the
year. For two and a half hours, two actors lead the walkers to four
pubs and other sites in Dublin to perform scenes by famous
playwrights and novelists and have fun with a literary quiz (there
are prizes).
</P>
<P>
   A typical tour, Qui,~K &QC;  &QC; I9%iMMI%M &QC; M! &QC; ]MQ!I &QC; U! &QC; UQQ!eI%9AI%M9 &QC; Q!I
