<SLUG> BC-SCI-FITNESS-WAKEBOARDING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE BOARD FOR A SPIN AND A SPILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JULIE WALSH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I love endurance sports: marathons, triathlons (even the
grueling Hawaii Ironman competition), bicycle races, swimming
around Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing compares to the feeling that comes at the 23rd mile of a
marathon; the sizzle of Kona's lava fields; the taste, smell and
color of the East River; the calm of Manhattan when pedaling to a
race in the early hours.
</P>
<P>
   But when a knee operation curtailed my running, I decided to try
something exciting and fast-paced, something that relied on power,
coordination and agility more than on tenacity and lung capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Enter wakeboarding.
</P>
<P>
   I had heard about this fast-growing water sport from friends and
had seen the competition on ESPN During gameswakpulwitd scratewak
prto theo flipss and 36mentionameTootsnd McThey got p. I had to tr
i
</P>
<P>
   ly conh an, learwakeboard, which etwfeet loresem in up
watecantebdn't, coign on atin The wa Ank 3ottyth su He assured d
havlems. &QL;  consisginnee from 19. secay fiboaindweightt size _ ththe
the board.rove to nea Candlew
</P>
<P>
   O Andeck Butlycerination, to te b squet into thot-like biilar tr
skiso be tight so yo control td keep it when yl).ind bl. Immi ve
bohope wn tit with toward st, boardar to thw rope my kneet tookf
theposedmy arms, weigwith my didrough f yougoin ARelaxhe boaou e?'
``Butught. I'ed.urchedoarr, ed d I up. oug thed d toard tur0 dng.
as ng ry.le ard, pt rike.y ups 30 I landed face first in the lake.
(So that's what snowboarders call face plants.)
</P>
<P>
   From the boat, Anderson shouted that I was riding the board too
much like a water ski with my hips facing forward and too much
weight on my back leg. Next time, he said, stand straighter, keep
your shoulders square to the boat, hips turned 90 degrees from the
shoulders. (Not unlike the stance of a snowboarder.)
</P>
<P>
   He also said I needed to stop looking at the water and focus on
the boat or the horizon for balance. ``Ride the edges,'' he told
me. ``Toes to heels, toes to heels.''
</P>
<P>
   The same pattern of getting up, falling, getting up and falling
went on for five or six more runs. Finally, I managed to get the
hang of it and could steer the board. I stayed up for several
minutes, and I even made a toe-side cut off the wake, rolling up on
my toes to make the board turn while facing the wake. But when I
leaned back onto my heels for a backside cut, as soon as I neared
the wake, I caught an edge and fell backward.
</P>
<P>
   Don't mess with the wake, Anderson told me. ``Go over it or stay
away from it, but don't try to ride the lip of it.''
</P>
<P>
   On my first run after lunch, I made it over the wake on my toe
side but couldn't cross back on my heel side. My afternoon runs
would be better because I was more relaxed and I had picked up
several tips from watching the others in my group.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson continued to work with me on a more sideways,
hips-forward stance and rolling from edge to edge of the board.
Several more runs, and several face plants later, I decided that I
had had enough for my first day. I could get up, ride directly
behind the boat and cross the wake in one direction, but I had not
mastered the feeling of ``popping'' effortlessly off the wake.
</P>
<P>
   Falling is part of any board sport, but the overall experience
is addicting, and the learning curve levels off once you find your
balance.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a serious athlete to wakeboard, but it is
easier if you are in good physical condition with strong arms,
quadriceps and back and abdominal muscles.
</P>
<P>
   Getting up on the board puts considerable stress on the biceps,
and holding the tow rope at 20 miles an hour or more strains the
chest muscles, forearms and biceps. Riding the board and turning
side to side uses the muscles in the abdomen and the back. The
muscles in your legs also get a workout.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a wakeboarding run is so exhilarating that you won't
notice how taxing it is, until the next day. I was surprised by how
sore my neck, back, arms and legs were, and how much Advil I had to
take. And I was glad I saved the McTwists, Tootsie Rolls and
Slurpees for the 7-Eleven.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
