   &UR; FOR TUESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Sept. 7:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-RIGHTS (Jerusalem) _ Israel's Supreme Court today barred
security service interrogators from using physical force, a
landmark ruling hailed by human rights lawyers as a victory against
methods they describe as torture. They said the Shin Bet security
service has no right to use the interrogation methods, which have
been used on thousands of Palestinians detained over the years on
suspicion of anti-Israeli activities. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-UNREST (Undated) _ Developments: There are reports that a
Jewish settler has killed a Palestinian near Hebron. Also, the
failed suicide bombers were apparently Israeli Arabs, who have not
carried out attacks before. By Joel Geeenberg.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-UNREST (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ Violence continues; one
report says nearly 200 people killed today. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-U.S. (Hanoi, Vietnam) _ Secretary of State Albright says
that if Indonesia can't stop the violence in East Timor, the
international community should. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DAGESTAN (Moscow) _ Developments in the renewed fighting
in Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-UNREST (Pristina) _ Developments: Russian peacekeepers
kill 3 Serbs in firefight. Also, Javier Solana, the departing NATO
secretary general, says Russians are an integral part of
peacekeeping force and he criticizes Albanians who have blocked
them. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-MITCHELL (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ George Mitchell
starts new talks in effort to revive flagging peace effort. By
Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-U.S. (Tokyo) _ A curtain-raiser on talks between the
United States and North Korea in Berlin on Tuesday: The first thing
that American diplomats will want to determine is which North Korea
shows up. Will it be the one that threatens to ``mete out merciless
retaliation'' upon its enemies, or will it be the nation of
starving millions that has gradually, grudgingly accepted the
extended hand of international cooperation? By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congress returns from a monthlong recess
to face many issues, including dividing up the surplus, gun
control, campaign finance reform and managed health care. By Eric
Schmitt. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
