announce a school construction program. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-RATS (Orlando, Fla.) _ Rodents are invading a small town
near Orlando and nothing seems to be working to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIER-ARRESTED (Undated) _ Developments following the arrest
in Hamburg, Germany of Martin R. Frankel, the Connecticut money
manager suspected of defrauding insurance companies of hundreds of
millions of dollars before fleeing overseas. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   (Story offered for page one consideration.)
</P>
<P>
   KIDS-FASHIONS (Undated) Forget about tweens, the 12 and 13
year-olds who were making headlines with the fashion perspicacity
just a few years ago. Parents, educators and merchants say the
newly style empowered are children six to 10. The talk of the
retail world this fall is the new line of clothing by hot designer
Tommy Hilfiger aimed specifically at girls 6 to 12 that is, by all
accounts, evaporating off store shelves. Donna Karan's
fashion-forward kids line, now a year old, is also going like
gangbusters. Ms. Karan's ankle-length waffle-knit skirt in Navy
with an elastic waistband and the DKNY logo, mothers say, is the
hot seller among seven-year-olds at $38 apiece. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   IRIDIUM-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Just nine months after
Vice-President Al Gore inaugurated the Iridium satellite telephone
service with a call to the National Geographic Society, Iridium is
fighting for its life. It may have great, even revolutionary,
technology, but interviews with a broad array of experts suggest
that even the most enlightened restructuring plan may not stave off
liquidation. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-EURO (London) _ In a sign of strong support for the
single European currency that Britain has yet to adopt, Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook said the euro has shown itself to be a boon
for its 11 member nations. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-LABOR (Geneva) _ Americans are still the champions of
work _ they put in the longest hours among the industrialized
countries, said a new report released to coincide with U.S. Labor
Day. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CREDIT (Mexico City) _ Two of the biggest American credit
reporting companies, the Trans Union Corp. of Chicago and Equifax
Inc. of Atlanta, are at work building files and computer systems in
Mexico that will give bankers here the same instantaneous credit
profiles that bankers in New York and Miami and Los Angeles take
for granted. By Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   NATWEST-ACQUIRE (London) _ National Westminster Bank Plc on
Monday unveiled a 10.75 billion pound ($17.27 billion) agreed bid
for British life insurer and fund manager Legal &AMP; General Plc, but
the deal left investors unimpressed. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   Eds, U.S. markets are closed for the Labor Day holiday.
</P>
