<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   Figuring the Ideal Time to Sell Your Stocks 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ARTHUR M. LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am a student, and it has been a year since I started buying
stocks. I read investment books and magazines, listen to and watch
the business news, and have followed each individual stock's
progress before buying. Unfortunately, the stocks I buy often end
up dropping after one or two weeks. All the stocks I own are
well-known, good companies such as Lucent, Cisco, Microsoft and
Merck. Instead of trading them, I have held on, even when they show
a loss, even though I was warned not to get married to any stock. I
need some advice on when to sell. Is there a particular profit or
loss figure that should prompt me to sell? Should I worry about
taxes if I have capital gains?
</P>
<P>
   A: The principal question you pose _ When do I sell? _ is
probably the toughest facing any investor. There is no easy answer.
</P>
<P>
   Many supposed investment experts urge you to ``sell your losers
quickly and let your winners run.'' Along these lines, one commonly
suggested rule of thumb is to dump a stock if it falls 10 percent
below your purchase price. But that can be a terrible blunder if
the 10 percent dip is just part of a normal fluctuation and the
stock is about to come roaring back. Ask some veteran investors how
often that has happened to them.
</P>
<P>
   If a company is financially sound and there isn't any hidden bad
news, a 10 percent dip _ or any dip _ could be an excellent buying
opportunity. Unfortunately, there is no way to know in advance. But
bear in mind that Omaha investor Warren Buffett built his
multibillion-dollar fortune primarily by buying undervalued stocks
that had been scorned by other investors.
</P>
<P>
   You are on the right track when you buy what you consider
``good'' companies _ as distinguished from the horde of dubious,
speculative issues out there. Unless you later learn something that
makes a company seem less good, you might as well hang in there.
The fact that you do a lot of research is certain to help.
</P>
<P>
   As for capital-gains taxes, it is rarely a good idea to make
this a major consideration in deciding whether to sell a stock. If
you think a company is going sour, don't hesitate to sell it simply
because you don't want to pay a capital-gains tax. If the company's
stock indeed heads south, your gain will disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Roth IRA Never Closes
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am single and would like to open a Roth individual
retirement account this year. My current salary is $95,000 _ the
highest salary you can have and still contribute a full $2,000 per
year to the account. However, I am interviewing for a new job where
the salary is $125,000, which would make me ineligible to
contribute any money at all. If I don't take the new job until next
year, and open the Roth this year, will I be forced to close the
account when my salary goes up?
</P>
<P>
   A: No.
</P>
<P>
   Once you open a Roth IRA, you can keep it open as long as you
wish. Whatever you previously put in there will continue to earn
money tax-free, no matter what happens to your salary.
</P>
<P>
   However, as you suggest, you won't be allowed to continue making
annual contributions at your higher salary level. For single
people, the maximum allowable contribution phases down from $2,000
per year to zero as salaries rise from $95,000 to $110,000. For
married couples filing joint tax returns, the phaseout occurs
between $150,000 and $160,000.
</P>
<P>
   If your salary declines in the years ahead, putting you back
below the cutoff, you will be permitted to make further
contributions to the Roth. However, you don't really want that to
happen, do you?
</P>
<P>
   Choices in Index Funds
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whenever I hear people mention index mutual funds, I assume
that they're talking about the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, because
it's the one I hear about most often. Are there mutual funds that
invest in the other indexes as well? I would like to expand my
investment mix.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, indeed. There are funds that track just about any index,
among them the Russell 3000 or Wilshire 5000 indexes, which are
much more broadly based than the S&AMP;P 500. There even is a fund _
the Vanguard Extended Market Index Fund _ that pointedly excludes
all S&AMP;P 500 stocks, while including the rest of the stocks in the
Wilshire 5000. For more information, take a look at the excellent
Morningstar Web site at  &LR; www.morningstar.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 index has been a fantastic performer in recent
years, roughly tripling in value since the end of 1994 and handily
outperforming the great majority of actively managed mutual funds.
However, as your question implies, there no guarantee that it will
turn in a superior performance from here on.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to mutual funds, you might want to consider trust
shares keyed to various indexes. They are similar to closed-end
funds and trade just like stocks, and there are lots of them listed
on the American Stock Exchange. Among the most prominent are the
Diamonds Trust, which tracks the Dow Jones industrial average, and
the Nasdaq-100 Shares Trust, which tracks 100 of the largest Nasdaq
stocks, mainly technology issues. (For more information on trust
shares, see the article headlined ``New Nasdaq Trust Off to a Fast
Start'' in The Chronicle's April 6 Business section.)
</P>
<P>
   Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag(AT)sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
</TEXT>
