<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADING-AFTERHOURS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Trading Day Gets Longer
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By ARTHUR M. LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has always borne more than a passing resemblance to
a gambling casino, and the resemblance is growing stronger now that
several brokerage firms have begun letting their retail customers
trade beyond normal stock market hours.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional investors have enjoyed that privilege for many
years, trading after hours by computer through a dozen or so
self-contained, fully automated electronic communications networks.
The ECNs serve as surrogate markets when the principal markets _
such as the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq _ are closed.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, individuals have been almost totally excluded
from ECN trading.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, that is changing. In recent years, individual
investors have become a major force on Wall Street, and brokers
have realized that it is in their best interest to cater more to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``This market has been fueled by individuals with their 401(k)
plans, their individual retirement accounts and their mutual
funds,'' says Muriel Siebert, chief executive of the Muriel Siebert
&AMP; Co. brokerage firm. ``We have to be sure that the public is
treated fairly.''
</P>
<P>
   Four brokerage firms _ among them San Francisco's Discover _ now
let their retail customers trade outside the normal stock exchange
hours of 6:30 a.m. to 1 p.m., Pacific time, using ECNs.
</P>
<P>
   Several others _ including San Francisco's Charles Schwab _ have
announced tentative plans to offer this privilege. Still others _
among them Ameritrade, a leading online broker _ have publicly
expressed general interest in after-hours trading but have
announced no specific plans.
</P>
<P>
   Siebert says she is a pioneer in this respect, having made
trading on the Reuters-owned Instinet and another ECN, the
Nasdaq-sponsored Selectnet, available to her firm's retail
customers starting about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Siebert customers can trade for two hours before the
exchanges open at 6:30 a.m. and for two hours after the 1 p.m.
close. However, they must pay higher-than-normal commissions for
this privilege.
</P>
<P>
   It may be only a matter of time (so to speak) before insomniacs
will be able to buy and sell stocks 24 hours a day _ just as people
can buy Keno tickets at any hour in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq, which
handle the bulk of trading, say that in theory they favor extending
their hours, and might eventually keep their markets open 24 hours
a day. That would probably eliminate a need for ECNs.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Stock Exchange, which handles about 3 percent of the
nation's stock volume, got the jump on its colossal rivals,
announcing plans to extend its hours to 3:30 p.m. Pacific time,
starting next month.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Board and Nasdaq point out that, in practice, a 24-hour
market would entail tremendous logistic and personnel problems. For
example, how many Big Board specialists or Nasdaq market-makers
would care to work the lobster shift?
</P>
<P>
   Until the leading exchanges change their schedules, after-hours
trading will continue to be dominated by ECNs.
</P>
<P>
   Institutional investors commonly use ECNs to trade on surprise
news announcements issued after the exchanges have closed. Many
companies prefer not to roil the markets by issuing their earnings
reports during normal trading hours _ particularly if the earnings
are disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Individual investors who own stock in companies that report good
or bad news after hours have been forced to wait until morning to
get their orders filled _ by which time the prices may have made
huge moves up or down.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, retail customers of Datek Online, Dreyfus
Brokerage and Discover Brokerage all began trading after hours.
</P>
<P>
   Other brokers that have said they probably will offer
after-hours trading include Ameritrade, Donaldson Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette, E-Trade, Fidelity Investments, Salomon Smith Barney,
Charles Schwab, Spear Leeds &AMP; Kellogg, Waterhouse and Wit Capital.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab spokeswoman Marta von Loewenfeldt said the firm might
offer trading as late as 2:15 p.m. Pacific time _ 75 minutes after
the markets close _ but that details are still being hashed out. No
launch date has been set.
</P>
<P>
   Menlo Park's E-Trade will let its customers trade as late as
3:30 p.m. over Instinet, probably starting in mid-September,
according to spokesman Patrick DiChiro.
</P>
<P>
   Since August 11, Datek has let its customers trade Nasdaq stocks
as late as 2:15 p.m. Pacific time through its own ECN, called
Island. It says it plans eventually to extend after-hours trading
to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus and Discover customers have been trading the stocks of
200 large Nasdaq and New York Stock Exchange companies since August
25 through a new ECN called MarketXT.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Satow, president of MarketXT and a former lawyer with
the Securities and Exchange Commission, notes that up to 40 percent
of customer orders placed with online brokers come in after the
markets close, rather than during normal trading hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many people who work, that is the most convenient time to
make investment decisions,'' he says. Those people should have the
opportunity to get their orders filled right away, rather than
waiting until morning, he contends.
</P>
<P>
   Trading on the MarketXT system doesn't begin until 3 p.m.
Pacific time _ two hours after the exchanges close. It then
continues until 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Dreyfus and Discover customers can't act promptly
on the company announcements that often stream in shortly after 1
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   That was arranged intentionally to protect customers, says Tom
O'Connell, president of Discover. In after-hours trading, when the
markets are less liquid than during the regular market day, prices
can move very far very fast, potentially causing serious financial
damage to novices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Institutions with their heavy trading cause volatility
problems in early ECN trading,'' he explains. ``Right after the New
York close, you see some of the most volatile trading of the day.
That's not the kind of environment we want to expose our customer
base to.''
</P>
<P>
   By waiting a couple of hours before they can trade again,
individual investors have a chance to ``digest'' news
announcements, O'Connell says. ``Our focus is not on the day trader
or aggressive trader; it is more on the conservative individual.''
</P>
<P>
   MarketXT further insulates investors against volatility by
requiring that they post only limit orders. (Datek's Island ECN
also has imposed this rule.)
</P>
<P>
   With limit orders, investors set a maximum price at which they
will buy a stock, or a minimum price at which they will sell.
``That keeps customers from being rudely surprised by the prices
they pay or get,'' O'Connell says.
</P>
<P>
   MarketXT also is trying to discourage institutions from horning
in on its ECN. It will not accept orders greater than 5,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because it is not designed for aggressive or
institutional traders, MarketXT can claim only light volume thus
far. Satow said it has handled an average of only 150 trades per
day since trading began nearly two weeks ago. The volume will have
to be ``much larger'' before the ECN can earn a profit, he says.
</P>
<P>
   But after-hours trading has the potential to produce massive
volume, says Jim Laird, an electronic-commerce analyst with Yankee
Group in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take a little more time,'' Laird says. ``People
are a bit wary now. Also, I don't think all that many consumers
know that it's there.''
</P>
<P>
   As more and more brokers open up the after-hours market to their
retail customers, he says, hordes of investors may flock to it.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
