<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, Sept. 7. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-RIGHTS (Jerusalem) _ Israel's Supreme Court on Monday
barred security service interrogators from using physical force, a
landmark ruling hailed by human rights lawyers as a victory against
methods they describe as torture. They said the Shin Bet security
service has no right to use the interrogation methods, which have
been used on thousands of Palestinians detained over the years on
suspicion of anti-Israeli activities. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-UNREST (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ In what is evidently a
planned campaign of savagery, militias backed by the Indonesian
military continued their attacks today on the people of East Timor,
burning homes, killing residents and forcing many thousands of
refugees to flee into the barren hills for safety. One week after
an overwhelming vote of independence from Indonesia by the 800,000
people of this tiny territory, the military appeared bent on
leaving behind a bloodied, ravaged, broken land, where they had
fought against a separatist insurgency since invading in 1975.By
Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congress returns from a monthlong recess
to face many issues, including dividing up the surplus, gun
control, campaign finance reform and managed health care. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-RDP (Washington) _ A political roundup from across the
nation on major races, candidates and issues at the official start
of the campaign season, Labor Day. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
