<HEADER>
A2386 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-FALL-LEAVES-$A     09-06 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FALL-LEAVES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME STILL OPTIMISTIC ON LEAF SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Sept. 12)  
(jt) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TERRYVILLE, Conn. _ The spring and summer drought lowered the
water table enough so that Joyce and Ken Wood could finally dig a
pond they had wanted for years, allowing them to add ice skating to
the hay rides and other attractions they offer at Woods Acres,
their farm here in the Litchfield Hills, in northwestern
Connecticut. But as they surveyed the excavation at sunset
recently, orange and yellow leaves fluttered down from a 50-foot
ash, a good month ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Woods and others throughout New England, New Jersey and
upstate New York are facing a leaf-peeping season that may turn
into branch-peeping in some areas. The arid year has produced
leaves that are smaller, are dropping sooner, and may not have the
right sugars to produce the fiery show that is the center of so
many autumn travel plans.
</P>
<P>
   Late-summer sprinkles restored some hopes for a storybook fall,
but leisurely drives in late August through northwestern
Connecticut showed wilted, mottled maples and oaks, a few with
leaves huddled as forlornly at their trunks as the needles from
Charlie Brown's Christmas tree. Dr. Robert J. Kohut, a plant
pathologist at the Boyce Thompson Institute for Plant Research at
Cornell University, predicted muddy colors this fall. ``Some trees
are holding their own, but even those leaves aren't
photosynthesizing at the rate they normally would,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents here say they've heard dire predictions before, but
remain confident that no one will be disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year it's something with the foliage _ it's too wet or
too dry, or the spring was too cold or it got hot too quickly,''
said Janet L. Serra, executive director of the Litchfield Hills
Visitors Bureau. ``It drives me crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's threat to the foliage has thrown uncertainty into a
part of the travel industry that usually is quite dependable.
Innkeepers and tour operators in New England say leaf-peepers tend
to be older people who enjoy the peace after youngsters have gone
back to school, and don't want to worry about summer heat.
</P>
<P>
   David Paul, managing director of VBT Bicycling Vacations in
Bristol, Vt., said that he's gotten a lot of questions, but no
cancellations, from the 600 people he expects on his five-day
bicycling tours through the foliage belts in four states. ``The
trees in the yard of the inn where you're staying may not have the
color,'' Paul said. ``But if you go over a pass, you'll see
something. The curtain doesn't come down on a given day.''
</P>
<P>
   In Vermont, Gov. Howard B. Dean has personally shouldered
foliage spin-control duty, trying to reassure potential visitors
that northern New England is wetter than other areas. ``If it rains
too much, the fall colors are great, but people can't get out to
see them,'' he said by telephone. ``We're probably going to have a
dry fall, so I would argue that people will be able to get outside
and enjoy it more.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean was so anxious to reassure leaf-peepers that he revealed
his own secret viewing spot to non-Vermonters for what he said was
the first time. His tip is to take State Route 58, one of the last
two unpaved roads in Vermont, for about 15 miles from Lowell to
Montgomery Center. The huge old-growth oaks and maples reach across
the road to meet each other, forming what Governor Dean called a
tunnel of color.
</P>
<P>
   Other states are issuing reminders that the foliage is just a
backdrop for other rites of fall, including the annual pumpkin
weigh-off in New Milford, Conn., to be held this year on Oct. 9.
(Last year's winner was 907 pounds.) Innkeepers say that although
they are already booked for most weekends in September and October,
they still have openings on weekdays. Marged Higginson, owner of
the Under Mountain Inn in Salisbury, Conn., suggests a trip that
follows the changing leaves from north to south, and she says she
plans to point this year's guests to higher elevations for the most
brilliant colors.
</P>
<P>
   For those determined to find whatever foliage there is, the
Whiteface Mountain Ski Center in Wilmington, N.Y., near Lake
Placid, offers a $7 ride on its chairlift, which rises to 3,676
feet and offers a view for 50 to 75 miles, through Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Woods Acres, Joyce and Ken Wood are gearing up for the
usual crowd of foliage fanatics, who will take horse-drawn carriage
or wagon rides into the woods. For couples, the Woods will pack a
picnic and drop the visitors to enjoy the leaves on their own until
the carriage returns. Groups can finish the night with hot cider in
the great room of the farmhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Wood, who was born on the farm 52 years ago, still talks
reverently about a process so mysteriously dependable that he says
no drought will stop it. ``You get a little orange here, and a
little red there, and the next day it's fall,'' he said. ``Then in
a few weeks, a wind comes up and takes them all off.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
