<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 12) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vive Las Vegas! The Strip's New Hotel
</P>
<P>
   Now you can always have Paris _ sort of _ even if you never get
to France. New York, Venice, Monte Carlo and Luxor have all been
paid homage in the form of Las Vegas hotels, so the Paris Las Vegas
Casino Resort seemed overdue.
</P>
<P>
   Opened Sept. 1 on the Strip, it is next to one of its corporate
siblings, Bally's, and across Las Vegas Boulevard from Bellagio.
The 2,916-room resort is highlighted by a 50-story half-scale copy
of the Eiffel Tower that has a restaurant 100 feet up and an
observation deck near the top from which you can view the neon
version of the City of Light at your feet.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other Paris landmarks copied on the hotel's 24-acre
grounds are the Arc de Triomphe, the Hotel de Ville and the facades
of the Louvre and the Paris Opera. There is no Metro, but there is
a monorail that links the hotel to Bally's and the MGM Grand. Three
of the four legs of the Eiffel Tower rise from the casino floor and
go through the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Among the chefs who will lend their talents are Jean Joho, chef
and owner of Everest and Brasserie Jo in Chicago, and Gabino
Sotelino, another Chicago chef, whose outdoor Mon Ami Gabi at the
Paris Las Vegas takes its name from his home restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   All rooms in the 34-story hotel include two-line telephones, a
data port and a marble bath with separate shower and tub.
</P>
<P>
   Rates at the Paris Las Vegas, 3655 Las Vegas Boulevard South,
range from $129 to $239 for standard rooms, $350 to $5,000 for
suites. Reservations: (888) 266-5687.
</P>
<P>
   Car Rental, Greens Fees Add Up to Miles Three airlines have
recently formed alliances, and bonus miles are being awarded for
booking airline tickets on the Internet.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Northwest has two new car rental partners _ Avis and Hertz. Now,
members of Worldperks can earn 50 miles a day for cars rented from
Alamo, Avis, Budget, Dollar, Hertz and National. A flight is no
longer necessary to earn the mileage with any of the Worldperks
car-rental partners.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TD Waterhouse Group, a discount brokerage firm, has launched a
customer reward program in conjunction with American Airlines.
Since Aug. 2, TD Waterhouse customers have received AAdvantage
miles for depositing additional assets, maintaining minimum
balances and adding to money-market positions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Troon Golf joined America West's frequent flier program in July.
Members of Flightfund earn three miles for every dollar spent on
greens fees, up to 500 miles a round. More than 30 Troon golf
courses in Arizona, California, Colorado, Florida, Georgia,
Illinois, Missouri, South Carolina, Texas, Australia and Scotland
are participating.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To encourage the purchase of airline tickets on line, America
West Airlines (www.americawest.com), American Airlines
(www.aa.com), Delta Air Lines (www.delta-air-.com), Northwest
Airlines (www.nwa.com) and US Airways (www.usair.com) are offering
participants in their frequent flier programs up to 1,000 extra
miles for tickets purchased through their Web sites until the end
of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Copenhagen Celebrates Historic Neighborhood
</P>
<P>
   Through Dec. 12, the Danish Museum of Decorative Art will
observe the 250th anniversary of Frederiksstaden, the stately
Rococo neighborhood in central Copenhagen that is considered one of
the finest examples of 18th-century urban development. Created
during Denmark's Golden Age reign of Frederick V (1746-1766),
Frederiksstaden's elegantly geometric street plan was an
architectural homage to the 300th anniversary of the
Danish-Norwegian throne. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The district's architectural masterpieces include Amalienborg
Palace, the principal royal residence since 1794, and the Baroque
dome of the 19th-century Marble Church. An exquisite octagonal
square in front of Amalienborg Palace is the home of the recently
restored equestrian statue of Frederick V by Jacques Francois
Joseph Saly.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The museum is housed in the former Frederik's Hospital near the
center of the historic quarter; its eclectic exhibition showcases
Frederiksstaden's art, ceramics, glass, furniture and fashion,
along with architectural drawings, city maps, models and documents.
Through a comprehensive display of 18th-century portraits, busts
and woodcuts of Frederick V, the exhibit's final section, ``The
Cult of Royalty,'' illustrates the importance of absolute monarchy
in 18th-century Denmark and attempts to provide an international
perspective on the Frederiksstaden epoch.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the events planned in connection with the anniversary are
a performance by the Vox Nova Ensemble and Concerto Copenhagen of
Frederick V's funerary cantata by Johann Adolph Scheibe at Garrison
Church on Sept. 19 and a concert of 18th-century chamber music by
the Frederiksstaden Baroque Ensemble at the museum on Oct. 24.
Information: Danish Museum of Decorative Arts, 68 Bredgade,
Copenhagen, (45-33) 14 94 52, www.mus-kim.dk. Closed Monday.
Admission $6.50, under 16 free.
</P>
<P>
   Classic Woodies Recall Another World
</P>
<P>
   Bette Davis and Clark Gable drove them, the Beach Boys sang
about them, Southern Californian surfers of the 1960s cruised in
them, and now, after a long public absence, the woodies of
yesteryear are back in the limelight. The Petersen Automotive
Museum in Los Angeles is honoring these curious old cars through
Jan. 17 in an exhibition entitled ``Surf's Up! The Great American
Woody.'' Aptly named, woodies used a substantial amount of wood in
their bodies, creating a unique look.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 restored woody classics, predominantly from the 30's
through the mid-50's, are on display, including a selection of the
popular wood-paneled station wagons and the less remembered, but
notably elegant, sedans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the show's highlights are a customized 1951 Ford Country
Squire ``surf wagon,'' complete with surfboards in back, and a
customized 1948 Chrysler Town and Country convertible that belonged
to the cowboy-actor Leo Carrillo who played Pancho on the
television series ``The Cisco Kid.'' His car features a mounted
steer's head on the hood. There is also a customized 1946 Mercury
station wagon, a rugged ancestor of today's sport utility vehicles.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Background surf music and a large-screen video presentation
(including old surf footage) help recreate a world gone by.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admission to ``Surf's Up! The Great American Woody'' is included
with general admission ($7) to the Petersen Automotive Museum, 6060
Wilshire Boulevard. Information: (323) 930-2277.
</P>
<P>
   In the Loire Valley, Gardens and Nothing But
</P>
<P>
   Garden lovers can enjoy a feast for the eyes and palate at two
fanciful and practical garden projects in the Loire Valley. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until Oct. 30, Prince Louis Albert de Broglie is displaying more
than 400 varieties of tomatoes, 120 types of lettuce and 28 kinds
of melons, along with dozens of examples of basil, mint, thyme,
raspberries and strawberries from his 2.47-acre potager, or
vegetable garden, at the Chateau de la Bourdaisiere in
Montlouis-sur-Loire. There is also a well-stocked garden shop for
seeds, books and garden gear. The garden is open daily, 10 a.m. to
7 p.m.; admission is $4, $3.25 for ages 8 to 12 (at 6 francs to the
dollar).
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can also stay at the proud stone chateau, which serves
as a sort of bed-and-breakfast. The 20 rooms cost $150 to $200 a
night. This Saturday and Sunday, a Festival de la Tomate offers
visitors a chance to sample the season's bounty. Admission: $5.
Information: Le Potager d'un Prince, Le Chateau de la Bourdaisiere,
37270 Montlouis-sur-Loire; (33-2) 47.45.16.31, fax (33-2)
47.45.09.11, or www.chateaux-france.com/bourdaisiere.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Until Oct. 24, visitors to Chaumont-sur-Loire can view some 30
potagers at Rien que des Potagers (Nothing but Vegetable Gardens),
organized by the Conservatoire International des Parcs et Jardins
et du Paysage. The Chaumont conservatory was founded eight years
ago, and is housed in the grand former stables of the Chateau de
Chaumont-sur-Loire (also open for visits). This year's competition
attracted about 300 international contestants, ranging from
sculptors to landscape architects, and the finalists' garden
designs _ classic to innovative _ are installed on the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors may tour the patchwork of small gardens on their own,
or take free hourly guided visits. There's also a good garden shop
and for those who want to eat, an outdoor tea salon, a pasta
restaurant and the more sophisticated Grand Velum, in an elegant
tent, all on the grounds. Grand Velum's inventive chef,
Francois-Xavier Bogard, cooks only with local organic produce.
Meals cost $18 to $24 without wine, but there is a wide selection
of local wines by the glass.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Rien Que des Potagers, Conservatoire International
des Parcs et Jardins et du Paysage, 41150 Chaumont-sur-Loire; phone
and fax, (33-2) 54.20.99.24. The gardens are open daily 9 A.M. to 7
P.M. until Oct. 24; admission: $4, free under age 8.
</P>
<P>
   Both gardens will have special events for the Semaine du Gout
(Week of Taste), Oct. 16 to 24.
</P>
</TEXT>
