<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-TRAVELER-$ADV12-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPS TO EXPLORE THE FAMILY TREE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Sept. 12) 
(jt) 
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In July, Rabbi Bennett F. Miller of New Brunswick, N.J., and two
cousins took a 10-day tour to the family's former village, Sasov,
now in Ukraine, and to Poland. The trip was designed and researched
for them by Miriam Weiner, owner of Routes to Roots in Secaucus,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in Sasov, 800 of 1,200 people were Jews,'' Miller said.
``No Jews are left. But Miriam's people took us to cemeteries and
old synagogues. They took us to where the archives were. We could
have spent days searching, but they knew where to go.'' Rabbi
Miller, rabbi of Anshe Emeth Memorial Temple, said he was proud and
grateful to be able to make such a trip.
</P>
<P>
   Digging into family roots is a popular format for travel these
days. A 30-member Elderhostel genealogy tour to Ireland scheduled
for next June, for example, was full by last month. Ann H. Waigand,
publisher of The Educated Traveler newsletter, said her first issue
on genealogy tours, published earlier this year, got five times
more single-issue orders than any other issue she had put out in
nine years. Caravella Italia, a tour company in Philadelphia and
Bologna, will offer four Jewish Heritage Tours of Italy next year
because of the interest in the two offered this year, according to
David Diliberto, the owner.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the growth in collecting family history is linked to
the Internet, where the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints
in May posted material from its collection of genealogical data,
the world's largest, adding an enormous free resource to existing
research sites and for a time creating a traffic jam at the Mormon
Web site: www.familysearch.org. The Mormons, who believe that
searching for ancestors is a religious duty, have microfilmed
genealogy records of all kinds all over the world to assist in the
tracing of forebears.
</P>
<P>
   Other varied sites like www.Jewishgen.org, give statistics and
records or sources for them. Searchers may be able to contact
people bearing a family name, for example, without leaving home.
</P>
<P>
   Jewishgen, among other sites, gives access to systems that
provide numerical equivalents for names spelled or transliterated
variously; for example, Scherman, Schurman, Sherman, Shireman and
Shurman are indexed together as S655. This safeguards against
missing leads, and many families will need to come to grips with
such code systems. They make it easier to trace family roots to
specific cities and villages.
</P>
<P>
   Here are brief reports on some genealogy trips, and leads for
finding still others.
</P>
<P>
   Caravella Italia designs tours for family groups of 4 to 12 who
want to visit particular areas in Italy. These are not for those
who simply want to find a particular document, Diliberto said, but
for travelers who would like to visit towns and perhaps see
relatives who stayed behind when family members migrated to the
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the families know some names, we can do a little tracing
coming forward,'' Diliberto said. ``We find the records office. We
build this research into the tour cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the customized tours, he said, the company makes a
specialty of Jewish history in Italy, with tours that have been
directed by Prof. Mark Bernheim of Miami University in Ohio, who
has a background in the subject and teaches in Florence in the
summer. Four departures will be offered next year, at dates to be
set. The 13-night tours this year were for groups of 12 visiting
Rome, Pitigliano in Tuscany, Florence, Ferrara _ scene of ``The
Garden of the Finzi-Continis'' _ and Venice.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Genny Bassani-Liscia, sister of Giorgio Bassani, author
of the novel, accompanied the group to Ferrara from her home in
Florence, led a walking tour and gave an account of her girlhood
experiences when the family fled the Nazis. She also led a
discussion after a viewing of the De Sica movie. Mrs.
Bassani-Liscia expects to join this trip again next month. With
hotels and nine meals, land arrangements for the tour cost $4,975 a
person, double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Caravella Italia, 2112 Walnut St., Philadelphia, Pa. 19103;
(215) 665-1233.
</P>
<P>
   Ashton-Drye Associates near Buffalo offers only custom tours,
principally focusing on the arts, said the owner, Marjory Sgroi. It
has started setting up family-history trips in the British Isles as
a sideline. ``We don't do the genealogy research,'' she said.
``When families come to us, they know where they want to go to. We
arrange hotels, transportation, meals and access to records.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sgroi said that most groups, through family newsletters or
reunions, were able to decide in advance what they wanted. Prices
for trips of one to two weeks range from $1,800 to $2,500 a person
without air fare; groups range from 15 to 85 people.
</P>
<P>
   Ashton-Drye Associates, 95 Squire Pl., Orchard Park, N.Y. 14127;
(800) 785-7785.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Weiner of Routes to Roots does only custom tours, like
the one for Rabbi Miller and his cousins. She does extensive
genealogical research in advance, and in 1996, found a second
cousin in Rovno, Ukraine, for a professor from Chicago. She
maintains two American automobiles in Ukraine, and employs a driver
who provides security as well as guide-translators. The tours are
priced by the number of people, places visited and number of days.
</P>
<P>
   Routes to Roots, 136 Sandpiper Key, Secaucus, N.J. 07094; (201)
866-4075; www.routestoroots.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Mir Corp. in Seattle designs custom trips and operates small
group tours in Eastern Europe and the Far East. It has offices in
Moscow, St. Petersburg and four other cities abroad, says Douglas
Grimes, Mir's president. The company's Volhynian Ancestral Village
Adventure Tour, in Western Ukraine and Poland, visits Kiev, small
German villages in the area and Lublin and Warsaw. Postponed
because of the fighting in Kosovo this year, the tour is expected
to run next year. Land arrangements were $1,995 a person, double
occupancy, this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mir Corp., 85 South Washington St., Suite 210, Seattle, Wash.
98104; (800) 424-7289.
</P>
<P>
   A useful Internet site is maintained by the Jewish Genealogical
Society branch in New York at members.aol.com/jgsny. This group
organizes conferences and has ties to organizations like Routes to
Roots that design family trips.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish Genealogical Society, Post Office Box 6398, New York,
N.Y. 10128; Estelle Guzik, president, (212) 330-8257.
</P>
<P>
   Elderhostel's Irish genealogy tour got twice as many
applications as there were spaces, and it was filled by lottery on
Aug. 13, under the organization's usual procedure. Richard Harris,
the director for international programs, and Birgitta Zissis, who
directs both domestic and foreign programs, said that there had
always been a major interest in family history, but it is on the
rise, and Elderhostel is responding with more trips.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's new genealogy trip to Denmark next year, May
13 to 27, is virtually full. The Swedish version is being offered
May 6 to 21 for the second time and still has space. By 2001,
Harris said, there will be an English program as well.
</P>
<P>
   Elderhostel currently offers several programs to assist those
undertaking research in the United States, notably at Brigham Young
University south of Salt Lake City, where the world's largest
genealogy library is housed. Catalogs are available from
Elderhostel, 75 Federal St., Boston, Mass. 02110;
www.elderhostel.org.
</P>
<P>
   For those just getting involved, the New England Historic
Genealogical Society in Boston offers free sessions, ``Getting
Started in Your Family History,'' at noon and at 7 p.m. on the
first Monday of each month. It also conducts twice-yearly trips to
Brigham Young University, and offers other genealogy tours. The
next Utah trip, Nov. 14 to 21, will cost $810 a person in double
occupancy, not including air fare.
</P>
<P>
   For those interested both in the Internet and in using computer
software to trace family records, this group is offering an all-day
class this month on Sept. 24 and Sept. 25 in Boston. ``Computer
Resources for Genealogists'' costs $80 a person. This class touches
on many software programs that can be purchased for prices that
begin around $20 and run quite a way up. Our older son, a
programmer, has been working with the Broderbund Family Tree Maker
for some years. This program and two others, Sierra Home
Generations Grande Suite and Mindscape Family Tree Creator Deluxe,
are reviewed on the Web at www.zdnet.com/familypc. (Search for
``genealogy.'')
</P>
<P>
   Jane Schwerdtfeger, the education director at the New England
genealogical group, said it was taking its act on the road with
more advanced four-session classes. On Nov. 5 and 6, it will offer
its second-level program at Connecticut College in New London, and
later that month in Concord, N.H. This organization has an
entertaining Web site; the ``getting started'' schedule is headed:
``Take Your Late Aunt Bessie to Lunch?''
</P>
<P>
   New England Historic Genealogical Society, 101 Newbury St.,
Boston, Mass. 02116; (888) 286-3447 or in Massachusetts (617)
536-5740; www.nehgs.org.
</P>
<P>
   The Educated Traveler published its modest directory of
genealogy tours and resources in May and June. The cost is $8,
which is deducted from the $57 annual rate if the buyer later buys
a subscription. The Educated Traveler, Post Office Box 220822,
Chantilly, Va. 20153; (800) 648-5168.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
