<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2452 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-AIDS-INDIANS-NYT &LR;      09-06 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-AIDS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS OUTBREAK FEARED FOR U.S. TRIBES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla., Calif., N.Y., Ariz.)  (The Science Times) 
(th) 
 By DAVID FRANCE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before Lisa Tiger got the awful news late in the afternoon of
July 5, 1992, neither she nor any of her friends or relatives had
heard of a Creek-Seminole Indian's getting a diagnosis of HIV.
Though the AIDS epidemic was already a decade old, the disease was
hardly ever discussed among American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tiger, then 27, set about to change that. That year, she
told her own story about contracting the AIDS virus to 300 tribal
leaders attending the annual National Congress of American Indians,
who listened in stunned silence, then embraced her, and flooded her
with invitations to speak at their reservations. ``I was booked
solid for the next three years all over the country,'' Ms. Tiger
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, however, and despite her frenzied efforts,
the interest in AIDS among the nation's 1.9 million Indians has
withered. Ms. Tiger, who lives in Muskogee, Okla., had only one
speaking engagement booked last month, then nothing for the rest of
the year. ``This doesn't seem to be a concern to anybody anymore,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some health experts say they fear that AIDS is about to
explode among the 500 tribes in the United Sates. Last year on the
Navajo reservation, for instance, AIDS cases grew by 25 percent to
the current 101 cases, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know HIV is being transmitted on the reservations, but the
tribal leaders are just not paying attention,'' said Ron Rowell,
executive director of the National Native American AIDS Prevention
Center in Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a decade behind the rest of the country,'' he added.
``Everything in Indian country has been late in the game in this
epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that the number of acknowledged cases
remains relatively small. As of December, according to the Centers
for Disease Control and Prevention, AIDS had been diagnosed among
1,939 American Indians and Alaskan Natives since the beginning of
the epidemic in 1981. Among all Americans, cases totaled 688,200.
</P>
<P>
   The figures suggest that American Indians are at lower risk for
infection with HIV than other populations. But Rowell, a Choctaw
Indian from Oklahoma who is openly gay, said he believed the
official numbers were low, artificially held down by spotty
surveillance data and by the stigma still attached to homosexuality
among many Indians.
</P>
<P>
   One major impediment is that Indians, more than half of whom now
live away from reservations, are often misclassified in health
reports. Dr. Doug Thoroughman, an epidemiologist with the CDC
assigned to the Indian Health Service, recently re-examined 1995
figures for sexually transmitted diseases reported to officials in
a state with a large Indian population. The name of the state has
not been disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found a huge number of people who were listed as white or
black or Asian were in fact Native American,'' he said. His
findings, which have yet to be published, showed that the real
number of gonorrhea cases was 82 percent higher than reported. For
syphilis the figure was 36 percent, and for chlamydia 45 percent.
Although he did not measure for AIDS, he said he would expect to
find a similar pattern.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, the burden of disease is a lot higher than
is being reported,'' Thoroughman said.
</P>
<P>
   Another new study suggests that tribal health officials are
simply not reporting cases of AIDS. A survey by the Intertribal
Council of Arizona and others last fall found that 58 of 92 tribal
health departments surveyed were not reporting their HIV or AIDS
statistics to any state or federal health authority.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the incidence among Indians still seems minuscule.
The National AIDS coordinator for the Indian Health Service, Daniel
Simpson, said only 97 new HIV infections were reported to the CDC
last year from clinics affiliated with the Indian Health Service,
many of which are operated by tribal health departments.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, where some 30,000 Indians live, only 40 AIDS
cases among Indians have been reported to date. But the state
health department randomly tested more than 250 people at the most
recent Five-Borough Powwow in Queens last fall and found the rate
of infection was at least 3 percent, three times what was
previously believed, according to Diana Gubiseh-Ayala, the
coordinator of AIDS services for the American Indian Community
House, which collaborated in the anonymous study.
</P>
<P>
   Without accurate information spurring them to action, most
tribes have tended to ignore the dangers, dedicating little concern
to the epidemic and fewer resources to HIV prevention than any
other population in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're stuck in this vicious circle of bad surveillance feeding
into the notion that this is not a problem,'' Rowell said. ``It
keeps us from getting the resources into the community, and keeps
the epidemic spreading.''
</P>
<P>
   One notable exception is the Navajo nation, based primarily in
Arizona. There, an official tribal office promotes prevention
efforts and the nonprofit Navajo AIDS Network provides client
services to 53 people with HIV, most of them secretly gay men with
wives and children, said Melvin Harrison, the network's director.
</P>
<P>
   Several are Hopis who have left their own more restrictive
communities for treatment, he said. Dr. Lisa Sumner, clinical
director of the Keams Canyon Indian Health Service Hospital serving
the Hopi reservation, said no Hopi had ever tested positive or been
treated while on Hopi land.
</P>
<P>
   But even among the Navajo, the oppression of homosexuals is so
overt that Harrison believes there are many more people with HIV
living on the reservation in shamed silence. Of a total population
of 230,000 Navajos, 130,000 live on the reservation covering more
than 26,000 square miles, giving life there all the anonymity of an
intimate small town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real homophobic here on the reservation,'' Harrison said.
``I'm the only person who knows about these individuals, and I
carry that with me. The other day a friend came up to me and said:
`Melvin, I want to ask you a question. Did my brother die of AIDS?'
And I can't say anything even after they're dead.''
</P>
<P>
   These are just the conditions that allow the epidemic to take
hold. Last year, Harrison said, there were 25 additional known
cases among Navajos, including three young women who almost
certainly contracted HIV on the reservation from their steady
sexual partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that really got the attention of the Navajo people,''
Harrison said. ``People are beginning to listen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
