<HEADER>
A2468 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PERU-ORPHANS-ART-500&AMP;     09-06 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-ORPHANS-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMES AND SONGS OF WAR HELP PERU'S CHILDREN HEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  map  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VICUS, Peru _ Wilmer Ochoa Navarro, 13, raised his hand, walked
to the front of the classroom and announced before 25 other
children, ``I'm sad because the terrorists murdered my mother and
my father.''
</P>
<P>
   There was not a stir in the room, not even a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   Then Teodosio Chavez, 11, came forward, and said, ``I'm sad
because they burned down our house.'' Nelson Vilcapoma, also 11,
took his turn and said, ``I'm sad because they killed my mother and
my dog.''
</P>
<P>
   And on and on it went in numbing repetition, one
Quechua-speaking Indian child after another pouring out grief over
a series of attacks by Shining Path guerrillas that would overwhelm
any adult, no less a child.
</P>
<P>
   Wilmer, Teodosio and Nelson are three of an estimated 500,000
Peruvian children who have suffered in the last 20 years of
guerrilla warfare and sometimes brutal army counterinsurgency.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 50,000 Peruvian children have been orphaned in
fighting that raged with particular intensity between 1987 and 1993
but still goes on sporadically here in Ayacucho Province. One
hundred thousand youths have been displaced, 5,000 have been
forcibly recruited for combat by the Maoist-inspired rebels and
countless more have lost brothers, sisters and friends in the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Peruvian psychologists speak of a coming harvest of resentment,
drug abuse and alcoholism from children who have been traumatized
by the fighting. And in a country with precious few resources, few
youths receive counseling or any help at all.
</P>
<P>
   But here in the Andean mountain village of Vicus, and in 17
other rural communities and Lima shantytowns, a small
three-year-old pilot project appears to be making headway in
relieving the pain of at least a few children.
</P>
<P>
   With money from the Peruvian government and two Dutch
foundations, a private Peruvian group called the Center for Popular
Promotion and Development has organized what amounts to group
therapy for 1,500 children from age 4 to early adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   Young social workers encourage children to express their fears
and joys in a friendly classroom setting. They play mock war games
that include guerrilla attacks on villages and successful village
militia and army counterattacks. The counselors sing songs about
war and peace, and they take the children through spontaneous,
dramatic role-playing to break down psychological barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Grimaldo Rios, 35, a psychologist and the director of the
Peruvian group running the program, said the central idea was
promoting resiliency in children by encouraging positive thinking,
self-esteem and a balance of autonomy and mutual support. Much of
the program's theory was developed by Edith Grotberg, an American
psychologist affiliated with the University of Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to discuss pain than let it paralyze,'' Rios said.
``We want the children to express their trauma and adopt a more
hopeful and positive attitude so they can build successful lives in
the future.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A morning of treatment here begins with a cat-and-mouse game on
a dusty, windblown soccer field in the middle of the village. All
of the children hold hands and make a circle, except for a little
child who plays a mouse and a much bigger, older child who plays a
cat.
</P>
<P>
   The children pulled together to defend the mouse from the cat,
who tried to break into the circle. A 22-year-old social worker
named Carolina Cardenas told them, ``When there is danger we must
all work together to protect each other.''
</P>
<P>
   From cats and mice, the children moved on to harsh reality as
Miss Cardenas said, ``Now let's see how we protect the community
when it comes under attack.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of children dressed as guerrillas in ponchos and
mountain hats and wielding hand-carved wooden toy rifles run down a
hill and attack the rest of the children. To the rescue comes a
second band of children, dressed in military green to look like the
village's self-defense militia. The militia children fire back and
save the village.
</P>
<P>
   The exercise was a rough replay of 15 Shining Path attacks on
this farming community from 1985 to 1993 in retribution for its
organizing a self-defense militia to resist the rebels. A total of
18 villagers were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons and purposes of what at first appear to be
unnecessarily violent games for young war victims are many. The
children learn that despite their losses, they are able to resist,
survive and live another day. They also learn that the people who
victimized them and their families were the losers in the end. And
perhaps most important, the weekly replays of their battles and
shared pain serve to vent anxieties that might otherwise fester.
</P>
<P>
   When one of the children started crying uncontrollably during
the play attack, Rios said, ``We have to work with him and give him
individual attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Miss Cardenas took the children to a one-room adobe
house to discuss the war game. The children wrote down and talked
about what makes them sad, and what made them happy, in what the
program calls juvenile parliament. The idea is to share hardship
but at the same time emphasize the positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy because even though I am an orphan, the militiamen
bring me clothes,'' said Rolando Escobar, 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy because there are no more terrorist attacks,'' said
Gelacio Huamani, 12.
</P>
<P>
   Then the children voted to come to a communal decision on what
makes them the saddest and what makes them the happiest. By large
margins the orphans voted that what made them sad was losing their
parents, while those who still had parents voted that having a
mother and father was what made them happy.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the children lucky enough to still have parents vote,
Wilmer, the 13-year-old orphan, rubbed his neck nervously as tears
welled up in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a sad boy,'' he said later, while telling how he and his
four brothers watched Shining Path rebels hack their parents to
death during a raid in 1993. ``But playing makes me happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents said the program was helping their children be more
attentive in school and more talkative at home and among friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've observed a change in the children,'' said Jorge Chavez
Oriendo, 59, president of the village communal council. ``They are
learning faster and behaving better. It's a relief to everybody in
Vicus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
