<DOCNO> NYT19990906.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2461 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-LATIN-REALITY-CHECK-E     09-06 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-REALITY-CHECK-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING A BROOM TO LATIN GLOOM AND DOOM  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 750-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 4 Sept. 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are bleak times for South Americans. Brazil is recovering
from its chaotic January devaluation, but living standards have
fallen. Most of Spanish-speaking South America is in deep
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador has announced the first-ever default on Brady bonds, the
instrument created to forgive (mainly) Latin American countries
some of their debts to commercial banks from the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Markets have become increasingly nervous about Argentina's
ability to maintain the fixed exchange rate that has underpinned a
decade of growth.
</P>
<P>
   There are worries about political stability too. In Colombia,
peace talks with the largest guerrilla group seem to have foundered
before they have properly started.
</P>
<P>
   In Venezuela, President Hugo Chavez is acting like an elected
dictator: in August a constituent assembly dominated by his people
dissolved Congress and intervened in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everywhere, governments are deeply unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   Since it is now more than a decade since much of Latin America
embraced democracy and liberal economic reform, such a panorama is
disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, some Latin American politicians _ such as Chavez,
Roberto Madrazo, a populist challenger for the presidential
candidacy of Mexico's ruling party, and the leaders of Brazil's
Workers Party _ go on to claim that what they call ``savage
neo-liberalism'' has failed.
</P>
<P>
   Financial markets, too, have been severe. For example, Brazil's
sovereign bonds are trading at a punishing 11 percentage points
over those of the United States Treasury, while a rally earlier
this year in the region's stock markets petered out when the United
States raised its interest rates in May.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is far more nuanced. Note first the strength of
Mexico's economy: thanks to NAFTA, it now follows that of the
United States, rather than those to the south, as investors have
started to recognize. The same goes, to a lesser extent, for
Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, the severity and length of South America's recession
owes much to external shocks and cyclical factors. These include
investors' 1997-98 flight from all emerging markets, low prices for
commodities, and last year's devastating El Nino weather.
</P>
<P>
   As such factors recede, growth will resume. And a return to
authoritarian rule is unthinkable in much of southern South
America.
</P>
<P>
   Yet neither can the current setbacks be quite so easily
dismissed. Even in the better-placed countries, economic recovery
may not be swift.
</P>
<P>
   South America remains uncomfortably dependent on commodity
exports and on foreign capital. It needs further reform, especially
of financial systems (to reduce the cost of credit), and to foster
entrepreneurship.
</P>
<P>
   A particular question mark hangs over Argentina. Advisers to
Fernando de la Rua, the front-runner for next month's presidential
election, say their man would quickly push through radical fiscal
and other reforms, to boost competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   But they must act quickly, if Argentina is to grow again _ the
main test for its exchange-rate policy.
</P>
<P>
   In the northern Andes, the worries go even deeper. Colombia's
normally robust economy is in its worst recession since the 1930s,
brought low by fiscal and banking problems but also by worsening
civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas' increased strength (which owes more to drug
money than political support) has undermined confidence. This week,
a general strike added to the government's problems. Colombia's
best hope is to try to contain the guerrillas militarily, and to
try again to coax them into talks.
</P>
<P>
   Ecuador is a mess: banks have collapsed, GDP may shrink by
perhaps 7 percent, and Jamil Mahuad, the fourth president in as
many years, will struggle to get congressional approval for the
fiscal and banking measures needed to secure IMF aid.
</P>
<P>
   In Venezuela, Chavez has swept away a corrupt and self-serving
political elite, but risks making matters worse. He shows few signs
of fostering independent democratic institutions, or of addressing
Venezuela's economic woes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a doubling of the oil price, the economy may contract by
6 percent this year, largely because of business mistrust of his
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ecuador and Venezuela, both accustomed to the easy money of
oil, have been notoriously resistant to free markets and fiscal
discipline. And until Chavez has more economic success, he is
hardly likely to inspire imitators.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries are testament to lack of reform, rather than to
its failure. But they are also reminders of just how hard a task
would-be reformers can face ) _ and of how far much of the rest of
South America has come, despite its current ills. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 750-word ECONOMIST article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you
prefer, she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
