<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2463 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-GODSEND-SCHOOL-VOUCHE     09-06 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GODSEND-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOUCHERS ARE A GODSEND _ BUT NOT FOR PAROCHIAL SCHOOLS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors....and Cleveland)   (This excellent 775-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 4 Sept. 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general/religion news and ``k'' commentary news
files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In education, only one thing counts: the chance of a good school
for every child. This is the thinking behind America's voucher
schemes, which use public money, voted by state legislatures, to
provide education credits for poor families.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with these, parents can send their children to whatever
schools they choose, public or private.
</P>
<P>
   More power to them, you might think. But vouchers are so
controversial that their spread around the country has been
glacial.
</P>
<P>
   In principle, vouchers simply allow parental choice to operate,
forcing the worst public schools to improve themselves if they want
to keep pupils (and the education money that follows them).
</P>
<P>
   But some inevitably sink; and this has created opposition to
vouchers not only among teachers' unions, but the public at large.
Polls show Americans equally divided for and against them and, as a
result, every scheme ends up in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest decision, on Aug. 24, a federal judge in Ohio
struck down the voucher scheme in Cleveland, giving parents one
term's grace before suspending it. The judge did not argue that the
scheme had hurt the public schools, but that it constituted an
``advancement of religion.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cleveland the vast majority of the 4,000 children in the
voucher plan have left public schools for Catholic ones. This means
that taxpayers' money, previously allocated to the public schools,
has been transferred to parochial ones, often run by nuns and with
crucifixes prominent in the classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Such a transfer appears to contradict the First Amendment to the
Constitution, which requires that the government stay neutral and
distant from all religious matters.
</P>
<P>
   It means that state money, hedged about with state conditions,
ends up in schools whose first purpose is to teach the tenets of a
particular faith.
</P>
<P>
   Why this has happened is no mystery. Parochial schools, although
often in the distressed centers of cities, have better discipline
and get better results.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, in a long line of cases the Supreme Court has
insisted not only that government should not help in advancing
religion, but that it should avoid ``excessive entanglement'' in
it. This has been applied even in the most minor cases, such as
lending secular textbooks or reimbursement for state tests.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever state money comes close to religious schools,
government regulation is called in to check that religion is not
thereby promoted. Hence ``entanglement.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet America's government is hardly consistent in its behavior.
Even while excluding most support for religious schools, the Court
has raised no objections to individuals getting tax breaks for
donating money to their churches or synagogues (which in turn
support schools).
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Court has extended tax exemptions to churches as
charities, and decided that it must not discriminate between
religious charities and the rest; but the effect is the same, that
state money is funnelled towards religious institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Should not the Court, by the same token, rule swiftly in favor
of voucher schemes like Cleveland's? So far it has been silent,
which is increasingly unhelpful.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, the Court should either ban both religious tax breaks
and the use of vouchers for religious schools, or neither.
</P>
<P>
   If it is to be truly zealous about separating church and state
in its traditional sense of outlawing the indirect flow of public
money to sectarian schools (as opposed, say, to preventing the
establishment of a state religion) then the logic of its position
is that it should also outlaw tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   But this is unlikely in the near term. So advocates of vouchers
_ which include this newspaper _ had better settle for second best:
a swift ruling, in line with its previous position, that vouchers
cannot be used in religious schools. And then vouchers will be free
to help improve the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is worse: that, embroiled in religious
controversy, voucher schemes could become so contentious that they
might disappear.
</P>
<P>
   This would be a great pity, since vouchers provide many of the
poorest children with their only means of escape from awful
schools.
</P>
<P>
   And by restricting vouchers to secular schools, the Court would
at least encourage the creation of a thriving market in secular
education, public and private, which could attract more of the
corporations and philanthropists who are already interested in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Every American _ in time _ would then acquire the opportunity to
choose good secular schools over bad. Religious schools would feel
the pressure of more competition. But that might just make them try
even harder. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 775-word ECONOMIST article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you
prefer, she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
