<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2483 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-VELAZQUEZ-BONES-NYT &LR;      09-06 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VELAZQUEZ-BONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MARKING HIS 400TH ANNIVERSARY, SPAIN DIGS FOR THE BONES OF
VELAZQUEZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By AL GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ Spain's celebration of the 400th anniversary of
the birth of the painter Diego Velazquez de Silva includes major
exhibitions of his work at the Prado Museum. But officials want
something else for the festivities: his bones.
</P>
<P>
   They have been digging around Madrid for five months searching
for his long-missing remains, enthralling the capital with the big
hunt. Newspapers report on every development. Locals take their
children to observe the ever widening excavations where some think
he is buried among the remains of a razed church, while others
insist that a mummy with a sword discovered in another church could
be that of Velazquez.
</P>
<P>
   The search has fueled interest in the activities to commemorate
the legacy of the master, whose 1656 masterpiece ``Las Meninas''
(``The Maids of Honor''), depicting the court of Philip IV, is
considered not only a national treasure but one of the great easel
paintings in the history of art. It hangs permanently in the Prado,
along with many of the artist's other paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hoopla, the secretary of state for culture, Miguel
Angel Cortes, complained last week that the Year of Velazquez, as
the commemoration is known, is getting too little attention abroad.
The Prado's director, Fernando Checa, quickly retorted that the
museum was doing quite enough with its newly refurbished Velazquez
galleries and two large Velazquez exhibitions to begin in October
and December.
</P>
<P>
   The Madrid regional government started the digging on April 30
at the Plaza de Ramales, one block from the Royal Palace, because
that is where the medieval Church of San Juan stood until it was
wrecked during the last century. Records show that Velazquez was
buried in the church a day after his death in 1660, in a black cape
and hat, with a sword.
</P>
<P>
   Two or three poorly documented digs at the same site since the
mid-19th century apparently also searched for Velazquez's remains
in the church, which was razed around 1809 to make room for a plaza
ordered by Joseph Bonaparte, Napoleon's brother and then ruler of
Spain. Regional officials exuded confidence at the outset of the
latest investigation, arguing that modern research techniques might
lead to Velazquez's tomb, marked with an epitaph in Latin, in time
for the 400th anniversary. Velazquez was born on June 6, 1599.
</P>
<P>
   Madrid City Hall initially helped, but stopped after spending
$38,000. Then the Ministry of Education and Culture dropped a
bombshell, announcing in June that it had discovered the mummy at
the 16th-century Church of San Placido.
</P>
<P>
   Ministry officials thought that Velazquez's remains might have
been moved to San Placido when the other church was wrecked, and
suddenly the cultural officials from the national and regional
administrations, both governed by the conservative Popular Party,
seemed to be jostling for prominence in the search.
</P>
<P>
   But Juan Carlos Doadrio, a senior regional official in charge of
the digging at the razed church, said, ``Since the Ministry of
Culture pulled out the mummy, we have to check it. But the mummy is
not Velazquez. I know it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic cardinal of Madrid, Antonio Maria Rouco, gave
permission on Wednesday to exhume the mummy, Doadrio said. It will
be studied at the Complutense University of Madrid, and if some 20
initial tests indicate that it might be Velazquez's remains,
officials may seek DNA samples from Velazquez's descendants, who
are said to be living in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But Doadrio and his boss, Gustavo Villapalos, who is in charge
of education and historical landmarks, are betting that Velazquez's
remains might still be in the ruins of the San Juan church. It was
razed in just three or four days, and no record has been found that
the artist's bones were moved.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts said that the previous excavations had focused on
the church's main altar, but no one has ever dug up the middle nave
where Velazquez might have been buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have to open it all up,'' Doadrio said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Plaza de Ramales, where four tile street signs depict
Velazquez's face, with long black hair and a mustache, as he
painted his self-portrait in ``Las Meninas,'' there are three
open-pit archeological dig sites. The smallest measures about 21 by
13 feet, and the three represent all but one corner of the old
church.
</P>
<P>
   The bones of some 50 people have been found, along with many
ceramic pieces. Exposed red brick and stone marks the old church's
foundation. ``We're looking for the remains of the church,'' said
Miguel de Aguila, a dig worker, puffing a cigarette and echoing the
official line about the purpose of the excavation. ``If Velazquez
turns up, he turns up.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics don't buy it. Franco Gonzalez, a Madrid regional
assemblyman from the Communist-led United Left coalition, blasted
the dig as an ill-conceived ``Indiana Jones'' adventure whose real
purpose might be to install an underground parking lot or at least
score political points.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were trying to sell to public opinion that they were
going to find Velazquez's remains,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   And Francisco Ayala, one of Spain's most respected writers,
wrote in an opinion article on the Velazquez events for the
newspaper El Pais: ``Do we really know where the remains of
Cervantes are buried, if they are still buried? Let the illustrious
dead rest in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are still nearly four months left in the Year of
Velazquez.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
