<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-NC-KICKS-BUTT-875&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO ROADKILL: NORTH CAROLINA BREAKS ITS NASTY HABIT  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: NORTH CAROLINA, Tobacco-State Editors)   (This excellent ``separate buy'' article is from the current (week
beginning 4 Sept. 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS ARTICLE
STANDS IN 875 WORDS. TOTAL UNCUT IS 1,025 WORDS.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM _ On the roads of North Carolina it is not unusual
to see cars sporting bumper stickers that pointedly proclaim
``Tobacco pays my bills'' or ``I smoke and I vote.''
</P>
<P>
   This state leads the nation in tobacco production, and three of
the country's five biggest cigarette manufacturers are based here.
The state's leaders have never shown much enthusiasm for the
campaign against tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina did sign on to last year's $360 billion
settlement of lawsuits against cigarette makers, but according to
the attorney-general's office it did so primarily ``to bring
much-needed stability to the tobacco industry and the tobacco
farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   As one state legislator put it, ``In North Carolina, tobacco is
as sacred as a cow in India.''
</P>
<P>
   Many North Carolinians think of the cigarette companies as good
corporate citizens. The tobacco industry is still widely seen as a
positive force in places like Winston-Salem, which has lent its
name to two leading cigarette brands.
</P>
<P>
   The state's fourth-largest city owes its place as a commercial
and industrial center to the R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Company, which
was established there in 1875.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say that the impact of the tobacco industry on
Winston-Salem has been huge would be an understatement,'' says a
former mayor, Martha Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of the tobacco industry's influence on Winston-Salem's
development is easy to find. Tobacco leaves feature in the city's
seal, and a statue of the young R.J. Reynolds riding into town on
horseback stands outside the city hall.
</P>
<P>
   A high school, an auditorium, a park and the airport are named
after members of the Reynolds family, and R.J. Reynolds's summer
home is now an art museum.
</P>
<P>
   Profits from cigarette sales helped to establish three
charitable foundations, and tobacco money went into bringing Wake
Forest University to the city in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The cigarette company continues to have a major impact on
Winston-Salem's civic life. RJR provides high-paying jobs to more
than 7,000 people in the area, and the company has given $16.9
million to community groups over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   As a grateful executive at a Winston-Salem charity told a local
newspaper, ``We would not enjoy the fine quality of life that we do
without the presence of RJR.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in cities that owe their existence to the tobacco industry,
however, times are changing.
</P>
<P>
   With domestic cigarette consumption down by about a third since
1970, and a series of lawsuits aimed at cigarette makers,
communities that have long relied on tobacco now want to diversify
their economies.
</P>
<P>
   In Winston-Salem, cigarette manufacturing is no longer the
primary engine of growth. RJR has lost much of its market share
since the early 1980s, and it closed its downtown factories more
than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company's share of the city's tax levy dropped from 18
percent in 1988 to 6 percent in 1998, and the size of its local
work force has fallen by half.
</P>
<P>
   As tobacco has slipped, medicine and banking have grown in
importance. The university-affiliated hospital has surpassed RJR as
the largest employer in the county.
</P>
<P>
   As the home of two large regional banks, this city of 171,000
people is the 11th-biggest banking center in the country, just
behind Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Attitudes are changing, too. In a move that would have been
unthinkable a few years ago, the city's largest shopping mall
banned smoking earlier this year. City leaders who were once
content to depend upon the tobacco industry to provide jobs are now
seeking to attract new businesses to the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a real wake-up call'' when RJR began to scale down its
operations in the late 1980s, says Allen Joines, the official
responsible for economic development: ``We have become much more
aggressive since then.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other signs that the tobacco era is coming to an end.
At the beginning of last year, RJR stopped offering free public
tours of its Whitaker Park cigarette plant: the number of visitors
had fallen by two-thirds over the previous decade.
</P>
<P>
   And, if you are looking for symbols, the fire that ripped
through a downtown block of disused RJR factories last August
destroyed Factory Number 256, which stood on the site of the
``little red factory'' in which R.J. Reynolds launched his business
more than a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Not much more than an hour down the road from Winston-Salem,
Durham has moved even further away from its roots as a tobacco
town.
</P>
<P>
   The city was once the home of James B. Duke's American Tobacco
Company, which controlled more than 90 percent of the world tobacco
market until regulators broke it up in 1911. Tobacco money financed
the development of a small Methodist college, subsequently renamed
Duke University in honor of its patron.
</P>
<P>
   Durham is still the headquarters of the Liggett Group, the
fifth-largest cigarette maker in the country, but the tobacco
industry now employs less than 1 percent of the city's workers.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech firms based in the nearby Research Triangle Park
account for 42,000 jobs in the Durham area, and Duke University
Medical Center is the county's biggest employer. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 875. OPTIONAL COPY FOLLOWS TO 1,025) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
 &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   In rural areas, too, the economic landscape is changing. Tobacco
growers are looking for ways to diversify their operations as the
federal government scales back its tobacco price-support programs.
</P>
<P>
   Much to the chagrin of those of their neighbors who object to
strong odors, farmers in the state now make more money from poultry
and pig farming than they do from tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Yet many tobacco growers, deep in debt, have failed to find new
sources of income. The challenge of diversification is particularly
acute in the hilly Piedmont region, where farms are smaller than in
the flat eastern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians hope to ease the fears of nervous farmers by
directing much of the $4.6 billion that North Carolina is due to
receive from the tobacco settlement to communities that depend on
tobacco. Everybody hopes the tobacco companies survive long enough
to make all the payments. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
