<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSTON-SALEM _ On the roads of North Carolina it is not unusual
to see cars sporting bumper stickers that pointedly proclaim
``Tobacco pays my bills'' or ``I smoke and I vote.''
</P>
<P>
   This state leads the nation in tobacco production, and three of
the country's five biggest cigarette manufacturers are based here.
The state's leaders have never shown much enthusiasm for the
campaign against tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina did sign on to last year's $360 billion
settlement of lawsuits against cigarette makers, but according to
the attorney-general's office it did so primarily ``to bring
much-needed stability to the tobacco industry and the tobacco
farmers.''
</P>
<P>
   As one state legislator put it, ``In North Carolina, tobacco is
as sacred as a cow in India.''
</P>
<P>
   Many North Carolinians think of the cigarette companies as good
corporate citizens. The tobacco industry is still widely seen as a
