<HEADER>
A2485 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-HANOI-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      09-06 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HANOI-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PETE PETERSON: ASSIGNMENT HANOI': RETURN TO VIETNAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time and station are
for New York area; see local listings.) 
(mk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An ambassador's life can be a busy one, even as it makes for
tedious television. So, at least, it appears from ``Pete Peterson:
Assignment Hanoi,'' Tuesday night's tribute to the first U.S.
ambassador to Vietnam. Douglas ``Pete'' Peterson took up his post
in 1997; the last time he resided in that country, for
six-and-a-half years, had been as a prisoner of war, captured in
1966 when his fighter plane was shot down.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson is seen being lobbied by American businessmen who are
having trouble making investments pay off in Vietnam, and relaying
their appeals to Vietnamese officials who are resistant to
capitalism. He stands tall at ceremonies of every sort, shakes
hands all around and testifies before Congress on the virtues of
Vietnamese-American friendship. He attends the cocktail parties of
other ambassadors in Saigon, at one of which he met his second
wife, a Vietnamese-born Australian diplomat. ``Now his life has
taken a new turn,'' announces the narrator, and in a private moment
the couple share a bowl of soup.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson appears to be an earnest and dutiful public servant. If
he were running again for Congress, where he served for three
terms, Tuesday night's portrait might do as a campaign commercial.
We are informed that he works long days.
</P>
<P>
   Due attention is given to his tortures by his captors (the worst
was kneeling and holding his hands in the air for hours at a
stretch) and to his personal tragedies (the deaths of his first
wife and their 16-year-old son within a few years). But mainly the
program is devoted to the virtues of reconciliation, or what he
calls in ambassadorial lingo ``a peaceful and constructive approach
to our relationship'' and what the scriptwriter could not forbear
from calling ``a search for closure.''
</P>
<P>
   The program's treatment of Vietnam, although it touches on
continuing areas of friction with the United States, doesn't go
much deeper than a travelogue. The big news is that many young
people are riding around on motorbikes and carrying cellular
phones. The hour is shot through with banalities: ``A new era in
United-States-Vietnamese relations has begun.'' The narrator can't
resist salutes: ``Pete Peterson had survived!'' ``Pete Peterson has
returned!'' And we are told, ``He welcomes every opportunity to
talk to Vietnamese.''
</P>
<P>
   There are affecting scenes, particularly of a solemn ceremony of
the return from Vietnam of coffins of American servicemen who had
been listed for decades as missing in action.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, Peterson is shown to be the sort of representative
who gives the United States a good name. Unfortunately that does
not translate into enjoying the pleasure of his on-screen company.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `Pete Peterson: Assignment Hanoi'
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Tuesday on PBS (Channel 13 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Northrop, producer, director, editor and cinematographer.
Joan Owens-Meyerson, writer. Jim Kessler, composer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
