<HEADER>
A2472 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-WHY-NOT-WARREN-BEATTY     09-06 1345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHY-NOT-WARREN-BEATTY?-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RONALD `BONZO' REAGAN. WHY NOT WARREN `BULWORTH' BEATTY?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 1,100-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 4 Sept. 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most aspiring politicians test the ground by releasing position
papers. Warren Beatty released a film featuring a man in a woolly
hat and baggy trousers instead.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Bulworth,'' Beatty played a Democratic senator who is
finally driven mad by Washington's evil ways.
</P>
<P>
   He swaps his suits for ghetto gear, tears up his speech about
``standing at the dawn of a new millennium,'' and starts rapping
about the ``real issues'' instead: the hold of big money on
politics, the lack of universal health care, the export of jobs to
the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   This exercise in truth-telling naturally goes down famously with
the voters, and Senator Jay Billington Bulworth prepares to return
to Washington to clean house. The fictional Bulworth is inevitably
assassinated by big money before he can fulfill the people's
wishes.
</P>
<P>
   But there are growing signs that the real Beatty is preparing to
go to Washington in his place _ and go, moreover, as president
rather than a mere senator.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty has not yet announced his candidacy _ indeed, he has not
yet decided whether to run as a Democrat or a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   He is also being advised not to run by influential Democrats
(who think that he will split the left of the party) and by some
close friends (who warn the self-confessed perfectionist that you
cannot control a campaign as you can a film).
</P>
<P>
   But Beatty has been arguing for years that American liberalism
has been destroyed by the influence of money on politics, and he
thinks that the groundswell of support for campaign-finance reform
provides a chance of changing that.
</P>
<P>
   He is vigorously consulting activists in both the Democratic
Party and the Reform Party, and has sought advice from Pat Caddell,
the pollster who helped to bring New Coke into the world.
</P>
<P>
   He has written a somewhat elliptical piece for the New York
Times condemning the grip of big money on American politics, and
has another piece coming out in the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Ventura, the governor of Minnesota, is apparently courting
him as the Reform Party's candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Arianna Huffington first floated the idea of a Beatty
candidacy, it has been the cause of mirth. How can a man who lives
in a mansion in the Hollywood Hills take himself seriously as a
champion of the poor?
</P>
<P>
   And how can a man who is admired more for his womanizing than
his contribution to public life hope to fill the shoes of such
paragons as William Jefferson Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   One joke making the rounds is that Beatty will be able to win
the California primary even if the only people who vote for him are
women who have slept with him. (His paramours range from Madonna to
Diane Keaton.)
</P>
<P>
   The mirth is the result of more than just Beatty's record as an
inveterate liberal and retired roue. (He has now settled down with
Annette Bening, an actress.) It is the result of his profession.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan never lived down the fact that he starred in
``Bedtime for Bonzo,'' despite changing America more radically than
any president since Franklin Roosevelt, and today's Hollywood crowd
is regarded as much more of a joke than Reagan's ever was.
</P>
<P>
   There is no permutation of political correctness that does not
have some celebrity's name attached to it. Yet Hollywood is one of
the most ruthless industries in the world: a place where giant
multinationals package pap for the masses, slippery agents carry
the art of the double cross to levels undreamed of by Talleyrand,
and nobody bats an eyelid when the stars make millions and the rest
of the crew is thrown on the dole at the end of a production.
</P>
<P>
   Rich liberals always have a hard time dealing with the hypocrisy
charge. But Beatty is very far from being an airhead. Politics is
the other of his two great interests in life.
</P>
<P>
   He stumped for Robert Kennedy in 1968, strategized for George
McGovern in 1972, and worked as a key adviser for Gary Hart in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   His dinner conversation is more Washington than Hollywood,
focused on the hot topic of the day with occasional excursions into
political lore. (He tells a nice story about a friend bumping into
Richard Nixon on a beach at the height of the Watergate crisis. He
asked the embattled president whether he was ever tempted to press
the button. Nixon went silent for a while and then replied, slowly
and deliberately, ``No, that would be wrong.'')
</P>
<P>
   Beatty has the political skills it takes to rise to the top of a
brutal industry. He made a fortune out of ``Bonnie and Clyde''
(1967) by negotiating a contract that gave him 40 percent of the
gross.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, with the Cold War still raging, he persuaded Gulf +
Western to produce $25 million for ``Reds,'' a film that came close
to endorsing the philosophy of the other side; and the man who
financed Bulworth's anti-capitalist rants was none other than the
arch-capitalist himself, Rupert Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   If Beatty's involvement in politics is not quite as silly as it
sounds, neither is Hollywood's. Hollywood is one of America's most
successful industries, accounting for three-quarters of the films
shown in Europe and more than half of those in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the country's most controversial industries, too,
provoking fury in everybody from middle-of-the-road Americans, who
blame it for encouraging violence, to French bureaucrats, who
accuse it of destroying their film industry.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood has no choice but to woo Washington, and to keep the
fires of both political parties stoked with heaps of money. The
resulting nexus between Hollywood and Washington is inevitably
blamed for trivializing politics. But it is not entirely clear who
is doing the trivializing.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians usually become infatuated with Hollywood only when
they have to disguise failed policies with star power: the decline
of the Clinton presidency can be dated from the time when the
celebrities started outnumbering the Ivy League professors at White
House dinners.
</P>
<P>
   But Hollywood figures often become preoccupied by Washington
because they want to prove that they are serious: Reagan was
attracted to politics by the idea of ``getting government off
people's backs,'' just as Beatty is by the idea of reforming
America's money politics.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of reasons to oppose a Beatty candidacy, not
least that he is going to do more harm than good to his own cause
by taking votes from Bill Bradley; but the fact that he lives in
the Hollywood Hills is not one of them. &QL; 
