<HEADER>
A2477 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-WHAAA!-BEANIE-BABIES-     09-06 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHAAA!-BEANIE-BABIES-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU'VE BEANIE HAD, BABY  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 575-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 4 Sept. 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Ty's probably laughing his head off,'' whined one
distraught collector. ``I just can't imagine being without them.''
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, the news on Aug. 31 that Ty Warner, the
founder of Ty Inc., is retiring all of his toy company's Beanie
Babies by the end of the year looks like inspired marketing _ and
great news for collectors.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it is going to make these hugely popular and scarce
little bean-bag animals, with names like ``Honks'' the goose and
``Slowpoke'' the sloth, even scarcer.
</P>
<P>
   Since he introduced Beanie Babies in 1993, Warner has proved a
superlative marketer, manipulating demand by supplying restricted
quantities of Beanies to small, specialist toy shops, bypassing big
toy chains and periodically ``retiring'' animals to boost their
value.
</P>
<P>
   He has added a touch of exclusivity too, by never advertising,
relying on word of mouth, and building a mystique about himself and
his private firm, based in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been startling. Although Beanies were
originally a children's toy, 70 percent of collectors are adults.
Many have sunk large sums, trading the 212-strong range of animals
on the secondary market, taking out insurance policies in case
their Beanies are stolen, and writing in for legal advice about how
to divide their collections when they get divorced.
</P>
<P>
   Beanies that sell new for $4-5 can trade for thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Beaniex.com, an auction website for Beanies
(http://www.beaniex.com), features ``Peanut,'' a Royal Blue
Elephant, for $5,200, and ``Brownie Brown Bear'' for $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   The craze has generated a whole spin-off industry from sellers
on the street to people such as Mary Beth Sobolewski, who left a
job at IBM to start ``Bean Bag World Monthly,'' a magazine with a
circulation of more than a million and the biggest of several
Beanie publications.
</P>
<P>
   This latest, carefully crafted announcement made on Ty's website
(http://www.ty.com) is guaranteed to send the price of Beanies
rocketing.
</P>
<P>
   For a start, the statement is a huge teaser. The company refused
to clarify whether ``retirement'' meant the end of Beanie Babies
for good or merely a clearing of the shelves for a new collection.
A new black bear called ``The End'' coinciding with its statement
merely added to the confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Ty then blacked out its site for more than 12 hours before
reposting the news. Children and collectors sat up all night in
case the news was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Creating panic buying is astute at a time when the Beanie Babies
craze has started to wane and competition for new collectible toys
such as the Pokemon characters has intensified.
</P>
<P>
   A renewed buying frenzy could, however, turn out to be nothing
more than a short-term bounce. Perhaps these little bean bags
really are like tin soldiers, baseball cards or Picasso paintings,
which become more valuable the scarcer they get. But the suspicion
is that, by choking off the supply of Beanies, Ty is stabbing its
customers in the back.
</P>
<P>
   Once the hype dies and collectors move on to something else,
there will be no new buyers to keep the market liquid. Prices could
plummet; and collectors who have not already sold will be left with
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that happens will decide if Beanie Babies were a genuine
collectible or just a well-marketed fad. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 575-word ECONOMIST article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you
prefer, she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
