<SLUG> BC-ART-MARKET-ART-1125(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEASONAL LULL IN ART SALES? WELL, NOT ANYMORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like Broadway, baseball and big-game hunting, the art
trade has always had a season. It began in mid-September, rose to
heights each fall and again each spring, then tailed off at the end
of June, when rich collectors headed for a summer of leisure at
their country homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``August,'' said Arnold Glimcher, the chairman of the Pace
Wildenstein Gallery, ``was a time when you could pull in the
sidewalk, and some galleries would even close for the whole
month.'' Certainly, big-name dealers left town, leaving skeleton
crews in charge of their galleries.
</P>
<P>
   But not last year, and especially not this year. ``It's been
insanity this summer; our business has not let up at all,''
Glimcher said, still working one day in mid-August and willing to
reel off sales of major works by Rothko, de Kooning and
Lichtenstein.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers all over Manhattan related similar experiences. And
Nancy Rosen, an art adviser who makes regular visits to Chelsea,
SoHo, midtown and uptown to look at all kinds of art, witnessed the
same thing. ``I go to galleries all the time, and this summer
they're not empty,'' she said. ``Almost all the dealers I know have
said they've had more activity this summer than they've ever had
before.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last few years, art dealers and auction houses have
gloried in the exuberant economy and the ever-ascending stock
market, which have created many multimillionaires and billionaires
eager to plow their excess cash into paintings, sculpture and
decorative art. People like Michael Dell from the high-tech sector
and Gwyneth Paltrow and Leonardo DiCaprio from the entertainment
industry have been bitten by the collecting bug.
</P>
<P>
   Now these new collectors, along with many executives and
entrepreneurs who began collecting in the 1980s and have since
grown richer, are so strong in number and buying power that they
are changing the art world.
</P>
<P>
   For a start, the business, which once followed the rhythms of
the carriage trade, is instead moving to the beat of Wall Street.
That means that art buying has become a year-round activity, and
lazy Augusts are a thing of the past, even when dealers do go on
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the phone every single day for work,'' said Jennifer
Vorbach, a partner at C&AMP;M Arts, about her two recent weeks on
vacation in the Hamptons. ``These were significant pieces of
business wanting to happen, and the business had to go on no matter
where I was.'' C&AMP;M's August sales included a major Warhol painting,
a Rothko painting and a Cornell box.
</P>
<P>
   ``With mobile phones and the Internet, I don't think business
stops anymore,'' agreed Rachel Kaminsky, the director of Otto
Naumann Ltd., an old-masters dealer that also had visits in August
from collectors she called significant.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Brooks, who as the chief executive of Sotheby's sees a lot
of collectors, new and old, is not the least surprised by the
gallery activity. ``The new collectors are people who work 12
months a year, and if they work 12 months a year, they want to buy
art 12 months a year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So far neither Sotheby's nor its archrival, Christie's, is
holding sales in New York during the summer. But both auction
houses, concerned that the big sales of impressionist, modern and
contemporary art in New York and London are bunched too closely in
November-December and May-June, are considering spreading the sales
more evenly throughout the year. They are also counting on Internet
sales to cater to people who simply must buy between auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Besides buoyant sales, dealers and auction houses alike are
seeing a second effect of the influx of new money: Their business
is more volatile. Ms. Brooks said that when she joined Sotheby's 20
years ago, she was told the art market did not follow the stock
market. Then, the art market was said to lag the stock market by a
couple of years. ``Now we track the stock market much more
closely,'' she said, ``and we have more ups and downs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the stock market was off its record highs for six or
eight weeks earlier this year, it had an impact,'' she added.
``Even in that short period of time it had an impact
psychologically. Those ups and downs affect people who are willing
to spend $500,000 or $1 million or $5 million on a picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Burge, the chairman of Christie's in the Americas,
who used to make a strong case that the art market rose and fell in
fairly predictable cycles lasting about seven years, said he had
long since given up that theory. ``We're a full nine years into
this cycle,'' he said, thanks to the prosperity of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   This newfound dependence on the whims of the stock exchanges is
widely acknowledged. ``Why are you calling me?'' asked one dealer
when queried about the market outlook. ``You ought to be
interviewing Alan Greenspan.''
</P>
<P>
   With Greenspan and his colleagues at the Federal Reserve Board
so far keeping their cool, the art world is counting on a strong
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is early for announcements, Sotheby's, for example,
said it would offer a Cezanne still life, ``A Stoneware Pitcher,''
estimated at $18 million to $25 million, and Monet's landscape with
his wife, ``In the Meadow,'' estimated at $15 million to $20
million, both from private collections. Christie's has a van Gogh,
``The Bridge at Trinquetaille,'' from the estate of Akram Ojjeh,
which has an unpublished estimate said to be $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   In the galleries, Pace Wildenstein will have new work from the
estate of Saul Steinberg, while Alexander and Bonin, Luhring
Augustine and others will have shows by young British artists
featured in the ``Sensation'' exhibition that opens at the Brooklyn
Museum of Art in October.
</P>
<P>
   But that is a small sampling, since the new collectors' tastes
are broad. While many of those with megadollars to spend do want
trophies by impressionists and 20th-century masters, many more,
with smaller budgets, seem to be interested in contemporary art,
especially the youngest collectors. ``They focus more on the highly
publicized sectors, to young artists they have heard about,'' said
Francesca Guglielmino, the business head of Citibank's Art Advisory
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Not every artist has benefited, of course, but some have noticed
the difference. ``Things have gotten better, definitely,'' said
Lisa Yuskavage, a painter whose work has won critical praise.
``When I started showing in the early '90s, it was hard to sell a
painting. But now I see brand-new artists' shows selling out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Yuskavage, though, is a little wary. ``This is a capitalist
country, and everything goes from that, and that's not bad,'' she
said. ``But I'm a little nervous about it. You want people to be
able to buy your work even after the stock market fizzles.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
