<HEADER>
A2490 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-MARKET-ART-2NDTAK     09-06 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-MARKET-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: market fizzles.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   How beholden the art market is to the new class of collectors is
difficult to say, although some dealers say they are posting record
sales. Many more say they are having their best year since the
market peak of 1989-90, when vigorous buying from Japan sent prices
for even mediocre art to unprecedented highs. But dealers, as
private businesses, do not report their sales as public companies
do.
</P>
<P>
   Yet signs that the art business is strong are everywhere. At the
auction houses, for example, combined North American sales of
Christie's and Sotheby's climbed from $1.68 billion during the
1996-97 season (from July 1, 1996, through June 30, 1997) to almost
$2.15 billion in the year ended June 30, 1999. That is an increase
of nearly 30 percent in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Art insurers are also smiling. ``Business really picked up in
1996,'' said Dietrich von Frank, president and chief executive of
AXA Nordstern Art Insurance. He said the average increase of
private collection holdings among his clients was up about 10
percent in the last year, after a jump of about 7.5 percent the
previous season.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Haber, an expert at Acordia, which also specializes in
art insurance, said his clients had on average increased the
insured value of their holdings by 15 percent to 20 percent in the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
   And those figures do not capture the effect of many beginning
collectors, who tend to insure their early art purchases by adding
to their homeowner policies, rather than buying special policies to
cover their art.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the economy, while consumer spending continues to be
robust, conspicuous spending is even more so. Spending on luxury
goods like art, according to Robert Frank's recent book, ``Luxury
Fever,'' is increasing four times faster than spending overall.
</P>
<P>
   Art buying is always tied to real estate, and the size of new
homes _ first, second and sometimes third _ is exploding. Twenty
thousand square feet, which used to sound baronial, is
unexceptional nowadays. Homes of 40,000 square feet to 60,000
square feet, with yards of walls to cover, are being built not just
by Bill Gates but also by people whose names do not sell magazines.
The Whitney Museum of American Art, meanwhile, has only 42,000
square feet of exhibition space.
</P>
<P>
   Experts agree that collectors are filling these homes with art,
but they insist that new houses are not driving the market. ``I
don't have the sense that it's people decorating,'' Ms. Brooks
said. ``Collecting is a lot more focused today. New collectors are
driven people who are very intense about everything they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Dealers report that during the last two summers it has been the
browsers who have disappeared, not the collectors. ``The people
coming in aren't surprises,'' said Andrew Fabricant, a director of
the Richard Gray Gallery. ``It's not walk-in trade.'' Some seem to
come to New York, often from the Hamptons, but sometimes from the
West Coast, specifically to look and buy, several dealers said.
</P>
<P>
   Still other buyers apparently are intense enough to go
collecting on their real vacations. ``Rich people get bored,'' said
Thea Westreich, an art adviser. ``They're on vacation, and spending
money is a kick.'' She said she was busy all summer with ``high-end
business, significant money, willing to buy $5 million to $10
million pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Another new factor, during August especially, was European
collectors, who by all signs were in the United States primarily
for vacation and decided to go shopping for art, too.
</P>
<P>
   Delighted by all this activity, dealers and auctioneers
nevertheless take pains to make distinctions between the '90s and
the '80s, when speculators inflated the market, and anything and
everything sold. The whole thing fell apart when the Japanese
economic bubble burst.
</P>
<P>
   This market, by contrast, remains more orderly and rational,
they said. ``Now,'' Burge said, ``collectors are so well advised.
They have advisers, curators, restorers, conservators following
them around in packs. Anyone with serious money is buying with
advice.'' For the most part the frenzy is gone, except perhaps in
contemporary art, some experts said, although not for attribution.
</P>
<P>
   The market is so strong that some collectors are starting to
sell. For example, in July _ also an unusual occurrence _ Richard
York, an American art dealer, received an 1871 Hudson River
painting by Jasper Cropsey from ``one person who thinks it's a good
time to sell.'' Both the Monet and the Cezanne at Sotheby's are
voluntary sales. And Burge promised, ``It will be a rich fall
because of discretionary selling. You'll see.''
</P>
<P>
   The appearance of discretionary selling has both positive and
negative implications. It is desirable because dealers and
auctioneers have had a hard time finding good, fresh material to
sell. On the other hand, it does mean that some people think prices
are peaking. Or perhaps, everyone hopes, the sellers simply want to
trade up to better, more expensive works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
