<HEADER>
A2493 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-RIGHTS-ART-725     09-06 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-RIGHTS-ART-725(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI COURT OUTLAWS PHYSICALLY COERCIVE INTERROGATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a watershed ruling, the Israeli Supreme Court on
Monday unexpectedly outlawed the Israeli security service's
practice of using physically coercive interrogation methods that
critics have long denounced as forms of torture.
</P>
<P>
   A nine-judge panel led by Chief Justice Aharon Barak unanimously
banned several of the General Security Service's admitted
techniques for obtaining information from suspected terrorists.
These include violently shaking the suspects' upper torsos, forcing
them to crouch like frogs and shackling them in contorted positions
with opaque sacks over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling is unprecedented in a country where repeated
terrorist attacks have long created a perceived conflict between
the security interests of the state and the human rights of
suspects. Until this decision, the court has shied away from
imposing restrictions on Israeli security agencies, effectively
condoning their practices.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, civil rights lawyers were stunned when, years after the
lawsuits were filed but only four months after their hearing, the
court not only ruled decisively that the interrogation methods were
illegal but immediately enjoined the government from using them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly surprising,'' said Dan Yakir, lawyer for the
Association for Civil Rights in Israel. ``On the one hand, it was
the only legal decision they could have handed down. On the other,
the supreme court doesn't have a very impressive record in
defending human rights in light of security claims.''
</P>
<P>
   The court, clearly made uneasy that it had come to an
unequivocal legal decision, acknowledged mixed emotions in its
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deciding these applications weighed heavy on the court,'' the
decision said. ``Our apprehension is that this decision will hamper
the ability to properly deal with terrorists and terrorism, which
disturbs us. We are, however, judges. Our brethren require us to
act according to the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The supreme court suggested that the parliament draft
legislation if it wanted to override the ruling by sanctioning the
use of physical force in interrogations. Barak has long believed
the issue should be addressed in the legislature and not the
courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Minister Yossi Beilin is unlikely to advocate
legislation that undoes the court's ruling. Speaking from the Gaza
Strip, where he was meeting with his Palestinian counterpart,
Beilin, a political leftist, said he was ``very proud'' of the
court's decision to withdraw unconditional authorization for
routine use of coercive interrogation methods.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took a decision that was not easy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak issued a statement Monday night saying
that the decision appeared to be problematic.
</P>
<P>
   ``A way must be found to allow for interrogation when bombs may
be detonated in order to save lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli government has long argued that forceful
interrogations are legal and desirable tools for extracting
information that can prevent terror attacks; violent shaking and
other techniques do not constitute torture, they say. Rather, they
are emergency methods when faced with suspects who know of a
``ticking bomb.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics, however, argued that the emergency methods were used
routinely, and that routine use is what the court outlawed Monday.
The judges still left the door open for agents to use these methods
when a bomb was really ticking, by suggesting they could invoke the
emergency conditions as a defense if criminal charges were later
brought against them.
</P>
<P>
   During the administration of former Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, the supreme court was under constant attack for being
too judicially active in matters of state and religion. It was not
immediately clear whether the change of government contributed to
Monday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Several right-wing members of parliament condemned the court
Monday, saying it had given improper weight to the human dignity of
terror suspects when compared with the security of Israel. Members
of the opposition Likud Party said they would immediately draft
legislation seeking to bypass the high court decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this response is dangerous, even absurd,'' said Yuval
Steinitz, a member of parliament from the conservative Likud Party.
``Israel is setting a precedent as a country losing its ability to
defend itself.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many cases against the methods of Shin Bet, as the General
Security Service is better known, have been pending for years. The
judges combined seven in issuing their ruling. Among the
petitioners were human rights organizations, like the Public
Committee Against Torture in Israel, and individual Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   One, Hatem Abu Zayda, who challenged the Shin Bet's use of
interrogation methods such as sleep deprivation, shaking and
beatings, was later convicted and sentenced to 74 months in prison
for his activities as a member of the military wing of Hamas, the
Islamic fundamentalist group. The government argued before the
court that information obtained during Abu Zayda's interrogation
led to the thwarting of a terrorist plan.
</P>
<P>
   Another was a suspect who the Israeli government acknowledged
was shaken to death by Shin Bet agents during an interrogation, the
court said.
</P>
<P>
   In its decision, the court, although it detailed the history of
recent terror attacks, concluded that security agents can use no
more force than regular police investigators. It also described the
interrogation methods in unflinching detail.
</P>
<P>
   According to the court, forceful shaking, which causes the
suspect's head to whip back and forth, is the security agents'
harshest technique. The General Security Services claimed that
``shaking is indispensable to fighting and winning the war on
terrorism,'' the court said. Violently shaking suspects had allowed
agents to procure information that thwarted fatal attacks, the
government claimed.
</P>
<P>
   But the justices found that, ``Plainly put, shaking is a
prohibited investigation method. It harms the suspect's body. It
violates his dignity. It is a violent method which does not form
part of a legal investigation. It surpasses that which is
necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The judges also described and proscribed an interrogation
technique whereby Shin Bet agents seat a suspect on a child-sized
chair that is tilted forward, tie one hand behind his back and one
behind the chair, cover his head with a suffocating sack and play
powerfully loud music for a protracted period of time.
</P>
<P>
   In criticizing the court's decision Monday, Gideon Ezra, a
member of parliament and former General Security Services official,
said that Shin Bet would find ways to get around the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that the GSS will find new methods,'' he said.
``Maybe they find a chair that is a little higher.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Dan Meridor, the former justice minister and
head of the Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee, said the
decision ``constituted a certificate of honor for the state of
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Meridor recalled when Menachem Begin, a former prime minister,
summoned a security chief in 1977 and instructed him to use
``wisdom rather than violence'' in interrogations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps that was the first prime minister that gave an
instruction like this, more than 20 years ago,'' Meridor said.
``What the high court ruled is that in an interrogation, even
during a difficult war against terror where the interrogation is
vital, one must preserve basic standards of behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from within and internationally, Israel has long
debated the legitimacy of the Shin Bet security agents' methods.
The government says they are used only rarely and under high-level
supervision. Human rights groups, however, say forceful
interrogation methods are used against hundred of Palestinians a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, a state commission began an inquiry into the
practices, and ended up legitimizing the security investigators'
use of a ``moderate measure of physical pressure'' as a last resort
to prevent violent attacks.
</P>
<P>
   International human rights groups considered this tantamount to
legalizing torture and kept up a steady stream of pressure against
the Israeli government, backing up the dogged efforts of Israeli
human rights groups who kept filing legal petitions.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, from London, Amnesty International officials called the
decision, which effectively overturns the state commission's
authorization of force, a milestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under no circumstances can you torture,'' said Elizabeth
Hodgkin of Amnesty's London headquarters. ``That is what the
Convention against Torture, which Israel ratified, said, and now at
last the Israeli Supreme Court has concurred. What they've been
doing there is simply unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed by Channel Two on Israeli television, Abdel Rahman
al Rahman, a former detainee who said he was subjected to physical
coercion by Shin Bet agents, did not applaud the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``A prize should not be awarded to the supreme court justices,''
he said. ``It's only natural that torture should not be allowed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
