<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2500 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHINA-THEATER-585&AMP;ADD     09-06 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-THEATER-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEIJING CHOOSES A FRENCHMAN'S MODERN DESIGN FOR ITS NATIONAL
THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France)  (lb) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Chinese officials have settled on a stark modern
French design for China's new national theater complex in a
startling denouement to an epic decision-making process that has
lasted 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   The design, a titanium and glass bubble-shaped structure that
will sit in the middle of a vast lake and will be entered via an
underwater tunnel, most resembles a giant sleek UFO. Sitting next
to the Greco-Stalinist architecture of Tiananmen Square and
catty-cornered from the Qing facade of the Forbidden City, the new
structure will certainly seem otherworldly.
</P>
<P>
   It will quickly redefine the landscape in the sedate,
conservative political heart of Beijing, adding the first touch of
modern Western architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The selection, which was confirmed by officials at the Chinese
Ministry of Construction and Ministry of Culture, has not been
announced in China. But it is all the buzz among architects, and
many people here have heard at least that a foreign architect has
been chosen for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never expected that a design like this would be selected,
and a foreign design, too,'' said Wang Mingxian, an expert on
architecture in Beijing. ``Initially the fear was that the
selection would be too conservative, but now some people are
worrying that there is not enough attention paid to traditional
architectural relations with other structures.''
</P>
<P>
   The building, designed by Paul Andreu of Paris, was selected
from dozens of entries, about half from Chinese architects, after a
yearlong design competition. It is unclear who gave the final
approval, but Lin Xiaolan of the Ministry of Construction Foreign
Affairs office said the plans were first screened by a group of
architects and then ``submitted to the central leadership for
consideration and approval.''
</P>
<P>
   The choice to erect for the first time a modern Western-style
building as a national landmark and symbol of national pride is
likely to arouse considerable controversy: Patriotic spirit is
running high as China approaches the 50th anniversary of Communist
rule on Oct. 1. And the new theater is more evocative of Disney's
Epcot than of a proud Communist past.
</P>
<P>
   Also a significant anti-Western popular undercurrent had
remained since NATO accidentally bombed the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia, in May.
</P>
<P>
   But some people pointed out that the ultramodern theater was in
some ways suitable, a symbol of China's ultra-rapid modernization
over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is surprising that this could be chosen, but in a way it
fits,'' said Wu Hung, a professor of art history at the University
at Chicago who is now a visiting scholar in Beijing. ``Beijing is
no longer a traditional city. It is modern and international.
They've been experimenting with modern architecture in other parts
of the city. Now it's broken into Tiananmen Square.''
</P>
<P>
   The government plans to start construction of the new theater
complex in March with the goal of completing it by 2002. The
project, which includes a 2,700-seat opera theater, as well as a
music hall and two smaller theaters, is budgeted at more than $362
million.
</P>
<P>
   Some commentators have suggested that the government is delaying
announcement of the plan until after the 50th anniversary
celebrations to avoid igniting popular outrage. But Ms. Lin of the
Construction Ministry said the plans had not yet been announced in
China because ``all of the official procedures have not yet been
competed, and there still may be some amendments.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Prime Minister Chou En-lai first proposed building an opera
house on the site in 1958, and soon after, workers began digging a
foundation. But the plan was then waylaid for the next three
decades, first by politics and later by proposals to build other
government buildings on this prime piece of real estate.
</P>
<P>
   And so for 30 years this parcel of land has been home to a
partly dug pit and an array of small run-down houses. The plan to
build an opera-house complex was last revived in 1997, and the
government organized an invitation-only international design
contest in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But even before the judging, some Chinese architects publicly
criticized the project's extravagant size and cost at a time when
state industries are ailing and unemployment is on the rise. With
the unveiling of the new plan, there are more dissatisfied voices,
with some architects deriding the theater as ``a giant duck's
egg.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wang, the architecture critic, said it was inevitable that
some people would be dissatisfied with the plan, given the
theater's politically and emotionally charged location. ``This
decision is one of the big challenges to architecture in the 20th
century,'' he said. ``Beijing is an ancient capital, so we want
coherence and unity. But it is also an international capital, so we
want it to have a vibrant feel. Those demands create
inconsistencies.''
</P>
<P>
   But the working-class Beijingers who live on the south side of
the future site have more practical concerns. Many residents of the
small Yu Fu area, a tangle of low gray-brick buildings that lack
indoor plumbing, said they had been told they would have to move
next year.
</P>
<P>
   News travels fast in Beijing's old alleyways, and most residents
already knew that a European design had been chosen. A few said
that Beijing did not need an opera house.
</P>
<P>
   But most were speechless when shown a picture of the building
that would someday occupy their space, and whose grand titanium
shell presented such a contrast to their dusty homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing like this in Beijing,'' said a man who gave
only his surname, Xiu. After a bit more contemplation, he added,
``It's pretty, though.''
</P>
<P>
   But others were perplexed by the alien structure. ``Oh, so this
is it,'' said a man named Zou, sunning himself on a ledge outside
the public toilets. He studied the smooth surface of the bubble
dome for several minutes, and then ventured: ``That can't be all.
What goes on top?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
