<P>
   Berlin: Century of Art, Up-to-the-Minute Dining
</P>
<P>
   By ROGER COHEN
</P>
<P>
   It is now a decade since the Berlin wall fell, time enough for
the tremendous discharge of energy resulting from this city's
unification to find expression in a host of new museums,
restaurants and developments occupying the space that was long the
cold wilderness of Europe's fault line. To wander this area is to
discover Berlin's essential fascination: the city's restless flux.
</P>
<P>
   From a disused railroad station that once abutted the west side
of the wall, the Hamburger Bahnhof museum of contemporary art
emerged three years ago. As bold in conception as that other
junction-turned-gallery, the Musee d'Orsay in Paris, it has a
remarkable collection, including some of the finest works of Joseph
Beuys and Anselm Kiefer.
</P>
<P>
   From Sept. 4 until early next year, the museum will house part
of a show called ``The 20th Century: A Century of Art in Germany''
that is as ambitious as the Whitney's current evocation of the
American century. The Bahnhof exhibition, ``Collage-Montage,''
groups works using these techniques by artists including Jean Arp,
Oskar Schlemmer and Jean Tinguely. Other parts of the show are at
the Altes Museum (``The Power of Art'') and the Neue
National-galerie (``Spirit and Matter''). From Beckmann to
Baselitz, nothing has been omitted.
</P>
<P>
   Hamburger Bahnhof, 50-51 Invalidenstrasse, Tiergarten district;
Altes Museum, Am Lustgarten, Mitte district; Neue Nationalgalerie,
Matthaikirchplatz, Tiergarten district. All open Tuesday to Sunday.
Admission $6.70 at each museum or $11.10 combined entry. Telephone
for all three: (49-30) 266-2690 or 266-2651.
</P>
<P>
   Just to the east of where the wall stood, the area called Mitte
is still very much a construction site. Restaurants, clubs and bars
open daily, burying without trace the drab uniformity and culinary
stodginess of the former East German state. Try Cantamaggio, where
Italian generosity in the kitchen meets German minimalist design;
Angela Giampa of Como and Noemi Anastasi of Genoa prepare their own
pasta and it is memorable. The bar is always packed.
</P>
<P>
   On the banks of the Spree, the Standige Vertretung, or Permanent
Representation (as the West German diplomatic presence in the East
was once called), has become an institution in less than two years.
The restaurant serves such German classics as knuckle of pork and,
on a lighter note, delectable Flammekuchen, thinly rolled,
flame-cooked dough covered with anything from ham and onions to
perch. With them, beers from east or west, perhaps a Kostritzer
from Saxony or a Cologne lager, Kolsch.
</P>
<P>
   Cantamaggio, 4 Alte Schonhauser Strasse; (49-30) 283-1895.
Standige Vertretung, 8 Schiffbauerdamm; (49-30) 282-3965.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest single development on the former no man's land
between East and West is the Potsdamer Platz, the heart of prewar
Berlin. Lacking grandeur and unabashedly commercial _ a McDonald's
and a Tony Roma's are prominent _ it has proved hugely popular. A
Walt Disney musical, ``The Hunchback of Notre Dame,'' whose world
premiere took place here in June, is proving a big attraction. The
theater stands on a part of the development called the
Marlene-Dietrich-Platz. Although this is still a more provincial
place than in the time of its most famous daughter, the message of
such lavish productions is clear enough: Berlin rising.
</P>
<P>
   Musical Theater Berlin, 1 Marlene-Dietrich-Platz; (49-180)
54-444. Tickets, $44 to $97.
</P>
<P>
   _ROGER COHEN is chief of the Berlin bureau of The New York
Times.
</P>
<P>
   Rome: Modern Art in a City of the Ancient
</P>
<P>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY
</P>
<P>
   In Rome, all roads seem to lead to ruins. By the time a visitor
has toured the Colosseum, stumbled around the stones and columns of
the Forum, and inspected the newly restored Nero's palace, the
Domus Aurea, there is often little energy left to explore
Renaissance palaces, let alone 19th- and 20th-century art
collections.
</P>
<P>
   Which is too bad, because one of the most pleasant museums in
Rome is the National Gallery of Modern Art, an imposing white
marble building overlooking the Villa Borghese. Over the last few
years, the gallery has undergone an extensive renovation, which is
almost complete, and which already offers visitors a beautifully
displayed introduction to Italian art from the 1780s through the
present, from Antonio Canova, the 18th-century sculptor, to Lucio
Fontana, one of Italy's best-known modern artists.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, the museum reopened its collection of 1950s and 1960s
artworks, offering a rare chance to see Op Art Italian-style, as
well as the works of Alberto Burri, who was one of the first in
Italy to use ordinary objects, like gunnysacks, to create art. Many
tourists believe that great Italian art ended with Bernini. Here,
without waiting in long lines, they can see conceptual art and
contemporary installations usually associated with New York or
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   By Dec. 15, the last renovation of the wing that contains art
dating from 1911 to 1945 should be complete. That part of the
collection includes well-known works by Giorgio de Chirico and
Giorgio Morandi and the Italian futurists Giacomo Balla and Umberto
Boccioni.
</P>
<P>
   The museum also has a collection of non-Italian works, including
two Van Goghs that were stolen in 1998 but returned, and a Gustav
Klimt.
</P>
<P>
   Set inside the vast public park known as Villa Borghese, the
museum is only a few minutes' walk from Villa Giulia, one of the
most important collections of Etruscan art in the world. It is also
close to the recently reopened and very popular Galleria
Bor- &QC; ghese, where Canova's scandalous nude sculpture of Pauline
Borghese is proudly displayed. The Villa Borghese also offers more
prosaic pleasures, walking paths, a small lake where rowboats can
be rented, and a carousel and Punch and Judy puppet show for
children.
</P>
<P>
   One of the National Gallery of Modern Art's other charms is its
excellent art bookstore, and its good restaurant, Il Caffe delle
Arti, which serves well-prepared food in a lovely setting. The
outdoor terrace allows for leisurely lunches and dinners surrounded
by trees, and no ruins.
</P>
<P>
   Rome National Gallery of Modern Art, 131 Viale delle Belle Arti;
(39-06) 322981. Closed Monday. Admission $6.70. Il Caffe delle
Arti, (39-06) 3265-1236. Open daily.
</P>
<P>
   _ALESSANDRA STANLEY is chief of the Rome bureau of The New York
Times. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
