1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Islamic rebels continued their assault on Dagestan on
Monday, spurring fears that the Kremlin might lose control of the
region.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic militants have seized six villages in western
Dagestan, including Novolakskoye. Fourteen Russian troops were
killed on Sunday in fighting in that region.
</P>
<P>
   More rebels were reported to be massing on the Chechen-Dagestan
border. Some experts worried that even the Dagestan capital,
Makhachkala, might not be safe from attack.
</P>
<P>
   All of Dagestan seemed to be vulnerable after a bomb attack
Saturday night at a housing complex for military officers and their
families in Buinaksk, Dagestan's second largest city. Monday, the
death toll from the Buinaksk bombing rose to 52, and it could rise
again since rescuers are still combing through the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   The dire reports from Dagestan are a marked turnabout from two
weeks ago, when the Russian military proclaimed that it had the
rebels on the run.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the Russian military's initial success led it to
make several blunders, including switching the focus of its efforts
in Dagestan away from repelling Islamic rebel incursions across the
border with Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody could have expected this even three months ago,'' said
Emil Pain, who served as an adviser to President Boris Yeltsin on
Chechnya. ``But it has taken place, and the likelihood of the very
worst scenarios is extremely high.''
</P>
<P>
   Gennady Seleznyov, the Communist speaker of Parliament, signaled
that the debate over Dagestan had taken a partisan turn when he
vowed to begin a parliamentary inquiry, saying Russia's
intelligence services and forces had failed to anticipate the rebel
campaign against Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed the rebels' invasion into Dagestan altogether,'' he
said. ``Prevention is not part of our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Yeltsin said the Russian leader might address
Parliament on the issue. The president, he said, believes that the
fighting in Dagestan is a ``real threat to the integrity of
Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   But the initial sense here was that the Russian government,
already distracted by allegations of scandal and by maneuvering
over next year's presidential elections, had been caught off guard
and had no ready response to re-establish order in the northern
Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis in Dagestan began last month when Islamic rebels
crossed into the Botlikh region of the Russian republic from
Chechnya, vowing to create an Islamic state.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   They were led by Shamil Basayev, a Chechen commander, and
Khattab, a Jordanian-born Chechen. After several weeks, the rebels
appeared to have been beaten back. The Russian military declared
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Russian military switched its strategy. Instead of
trying to consolidate its control of the border region and of
western Dagestan, it began a campaign against several villages
controlled by the Wahhabi sect in central Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   The Wahhabis, an Islamic sect, had enjoyed relative autonomy and
were thought to have some sympathy for the Chechen-based rebels.
But they had not emerged as a major threat to the authorities in
Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   Vowing to bring the Wahhabis to heel, the Russian military
assaulted their villages, Karamakhi and Chabanmakhi, which are
southwest of Makhachkaka.
</P>
<P>
   Pain, the former Yeltsin adviser, argued Monday that this was a
mistake. For one thing, he said, the assault was more likely to
turn people against the Dagestani authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``People turn to Wahhabism not because they are seeking out the
details of Islam,'' he said. ``They turn to it for protection. With
attack aircraft you cannot halt such a movement. You only make it
grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Pain speculated that the Russian military might have been
influenced by Dagestani authorities eager to reassert their control
over some of the more prosperous Wahhabi-controlled areas.
</P>
<P>
   The military's concentration on the Wahhabis also distracted it
from the fragile peace in western Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military was surprised this weekend when about 1,000
militants left their bases in Chechnya and crossed into Dagestan
again, according to Russian news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Russian warplanes pounded targets along the
Dagestan-Chechen border and, according to the Chechens, villages
inside Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most intense fighting centered on a group of 50
policeman who found themselves surrounded by the rebels in western
Dagestan. Cut off and low on ammunition, the police mounted a
desperate fight. Finally, they broke through the militants' lines,
helped by the arrival of reinforcements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
