<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UNREST-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS KILL THREE SERBS IN KOSOVO SKIRMISH 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Russian peacekeeping troops shot and
killed three armed Serbs on Monday in a firefight in eastern
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, frequently accused by local Albanians of siding
with the Serbs, came under fire when they surprised three Serbs who
had ambushed a car, killing a passenger, a spokesman for the
NATO-led peacekeeping force said.
</P>
<P>
   As the spokesman described the episode, the three Serbs were
beating two wounded Albanians when the Russian soldiers arrived on
the scene. Ordered to stop, the Serbs instead opened fire on the
Russian soldiers, who returned fire and killed the three Serbs. The
Russians had no casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the NATO secretary-general, Javier Solana, who is
on a visit to Kosovo, singled out the 3,000 Russian troops for
praise.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement that disappointed local Albanians, Solana
emphatically supported the Russian presence. ``We are particularly
happy they are here and that Russian and NATO troops are working
side by side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Solana said that their performance in the firefight was proof
that the Russians were professional and deserved NATO's full
support.
</P>
<P>
   The role of Russian troops in Kosovo has brought no end of
complications to the peacekeeping mission, in particular when they
stole the march on NATO's entry into Kosovo on June 11, occupying
the airport in Pristina, the provincial capital, ahead of a British
contingent. The airport remains under effective Russian control.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian peacekeepers have also met with public protests by
Kosovo Albanians, who accuse Russia of siding with the Yugoslav
president, Slobodan Milosevic, and who contend that Russian
mercenaries fought alongside Serbian forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two weeks, hundreds of protesters have prevented
Russian troops from entering Orahovac to serve as peacekeepers
there. The Russians have also come under fire more often than the
other peacekeepers, possibly from Albanians opposed to having them
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But Solana, who has been championed here as a savior since the
NATO bombing campaign forced the withdrawal of Serbian forces, made
no concessions to Albanian sensitivities. He met with
representatives of the demonstrators, including the Albanian mayor
of Orahovac, and told them that Russian troops were part of the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This incident this morning proves that the Russian troops
behave according to the obligations'' that all peacekeeping troops
have, he said at a news conference in Pristina. He said they
deserved the same respect as peacekeeping troops from any other
country.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Solana also voiced his support for transforming part of the
Albanian guerrilla force, the Kosovo Liberation Army, into a
civilian emergency force, but said it was essential that the group
demilitarize first.
</P>
<P>
   During his visit he met with Gen. Agim Ceku, commander of the
KLA, and said he had spoken several times to Hashim Thaci, its
political leader. ``We still have days to develop the details'' of
the transformation to a civilian force, Solana said, ``but the
philosophy is not going to be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   It has not yet been determined how funds would be provided for
the force, which would eventually come under control of the United
Nations. Solana suggested that money could be provided bilaterally
by individual countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
