<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2522 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t BC-TRAVEL-LONDON-THEATER     09-06 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LONDON-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV12-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONDON THEATER CONTINUES TO PROLIFERATE WITH BOTH QUANTITY AND
QUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., Sept. 12)  
(jt) 
 By BENEDICT NIGHTINGALE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ If you want an example of the extent to which London
has superseded New York as the capital of the English-language
theater, and maybe also an indication of why we critics sometimes
suffer from a medical syndrome known as drama fatigue, consider
just one week of openings this fall. It's that of Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Monday: we trot cheerfully off to the Old Vic, which will have
been transformed into a theater-in-the-round for Sophocles'
``Antigone.'' The rebellious heroine will be played by Tara
Fitzgerald, who is best known as a movie actress but got excellent
reviews for the Ophelia she performed opposite Ralph Fiennes in New
York in 1995. The director is Declan Donnellan, whose Cheek by Jowl
company had a huge success when it brought that Jacobean thunderer,
John Webster's ``Duchess of Malfi,'' to New York four years ago.
And though there will be a nine-member chorus, all the characters
will be performed by four actors, which is just one more than would
have been the case in the Athens of 442 B.C., when the tragedy
probably had its premiere.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday: still resilient, we amble off to the Piccadilly to see
the musical ``Spend, Spend, Spend,'' so-called because that's what
a housewife called Viv Nicholson famously told journalists she
planned to do when she won a vast fortune gambling on soccer
results in 1961. The tale of her triumph and decline got stunning
notices when it was staged in Leeds last year _ and everybody is
hoping that in its creators, the unknown Steve Brown and Justin
Greene, the British impresarios may at long last have ended their
search for plausible heirs to Andrew Lloyd Webber's musical throne.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday: we lope gamely to the Lyric for ``Comic Potential,''
the latest piece by Britain's most prolific and successful comic
dramatist, Alan Ayckbourn. The word from the Yorkshire resort of
Scarborough, where the playwright first presents all his work in
the theater he runs himself, is that it is set in a futuristic
Britain where television soaps are performed by android actors. The
hope is that, as one visiting London critic extravagantly put it,
the comedy will ``hurt you with the exuberance of its laughter and
liberate you with its seriousness.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: we trudge to the New Ambassador's for ``Some Explicit
Polaroids'' by Mark Ravenhill. Heard of him? In 1996 he won glowing
reviews and considerable notoriety with a play about rough sex and
consumerism whose very title most newspapers found too obscene to
publish, even though it ended up in lights on Shaftesbury Avenue.
Reportedly his latest piece is still more acerbic, this time
describing how six people ``mix their own peculiar cocktails of
love, honor, happiness, sex and money''; but at least the title is
printable.
</P>
<P>
   Friday: we dodder off to the National Theater for the premiere
of ``Remember This'' by Stephen Poliakoff, a dramatist with a sharp
eye for aspects of the late 20th century others tend to ignore:
technological innovation, shopping malls, concrete-and-glass office
blocks and the people doomed to inhabit them. His latest involves a
man, played by Stanley Townsend, who makes and collects videos of
weddings and bizarre consequences of the destruction of his tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday: we stay at home, pouring warm water onto our feet and
cold drinks down our throats. But very likely we're feeling a bit
guilty about our failure on Oct. 12 to have made the 60-mile trip
to Chichester's Festival Theater for ``The Retreat From Moscow,'' a
new play about marital discord by the author of ``Shadowlands,''
William Nicholson. But we need our weekend, because the next days
will keep us busy, too. Tuesday, Oct. 19, brings maybe the most
eagerly awaited event of the fall, the opening at London's Lyceum
of the most visually inventive show now on Broadway, Julie Taymor's
production of Disney's ``Lion King.'' And on Wednesday, Oct. 20, at
the Gielgud, we'll be seeing Noel Coward's ``Song at Twilight,''
with Corin Redgrave as a grumpy old writer, glancingly based on
Somerset Maugham, and his sister Vanessa as the ex-mistress who
owns letters revealing that he was a closet gay. Maybe we critics
will find ourselves having to go to matinees in order to stay
abreast of things _ and maybe drama fatigue will escalate into
theater nervosa or even theater delirium, a condition in which
overwrought reviewers start muddling plays with their own feverish
dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Does it sound chauvinistic or triumphalist to point out that
within eight or nine fall days London will see roughly one-sixth of
the new productions Broadway sometimes gets in a year? And I've yet
more boastful news to impart. Late October brings Nigel Hawthorne
to the Barbican in a role surely made inevitable by his starring
performance in ``The Madness of King George'': the most demented,
tormented monarch in dramatic literature, Shakespeare's King Lear.
In early December Maggie Smith comes to the West End in the latest
play by the author of ``King George'': Alan Bennett's ``Lady in the
Van,'' based on an aged eccentric who spent several years living in
the dramatist's own London driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Add Antony Sher's Macbeth, to be seen at Royal Shakespeare
Company headquarters in Stratford in November; throw in Helen
Mirren, who comes to the West End the same month in Donald
Margulies' ``Collected Stories,'' about a famous novelist and her
protege; finish off with Zoe Wanamaker, recently a successful
Electra on Broadway, as the rejected wife of Simon Russell Beale's
King George IV in ``Battle Royal,'' a new play due at the National
in early December; and it's clear that several important
performances are in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   Myself, I'm especially looking forward to another major event at
the National, the poet Ted Hughes' version of the first great
Western drama: Aeschylus' ``Oresteia,'' this time staged by Katie
Mitchell, who is maybe the brightest and most interesting of
Britain's younger directors. The first part starts previews as
early as Sept. 24, but not until the second is deemed ready will
both open officially, and that could be as late as early December.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What else will be joining Trevor Nunn's productions of Gorky's
``Summerfolk'' and Shakespeare's ``Merchant of Venice'' (Henry
Goodman a fine Shylock) at the National, Julian Barry's ``Lenny''
at the Queen's (Eddie Izzard funny and touching as the ``sick''
comic Lenny Bruce), the all-male ``Antony and Cleopatra'' (Mark
Rylance a sprightly queen of the Nile) at Shakespeare's Globe on
the South Bank, and London's other summer holdovers? Well, the West
End brings us a revival of ``A Penny for a Song,'' John Whiting's
charming tale of English eccentrics in the Napoleonic era
(Whitehall, Sept. 30); a revival of that great American musical
``The Pajama Game,'' directed by Simon Callow (Victoria Palace,
Oct. 4); ``Great Balls of Fire,'' a song-packed recreation of the
Jerry Lee Lewis story (Cambridge, Oct. 6); the imaginative touring
company Shared Experience in a version of Charlotte Bronte's ``Jane
Eyre'' (New Ambassadors, Nov. 25); and, at some still-unspecified
theater and date, a bunch of Noel Coward's livelier revue sketches,
``Masterpieces.''
</P>
<P>
   And by November, the Royal Shakespeare Company, which these days
spends its summers out of London, should be firmly ensconced in the
Barbican. After Yukio Ninagawa's production of ``Lear'' come
several transfers from Stratford, the most striking of which are
Aphra Behn's ``Oroonoko'' and, surprisingly, the latest of the
seemingly endless series of revivals of ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream'' to have hit London in recent years. ``Oroonoko,'' the
adaptation of a little-known story by the most famous of women who
were dramatists in the 17th century, is of exceptional interest,
involving as it does a black slave with moral and intellectual
gifts far surpassing the white colonials who exploit him. Michael
Boyd's revival of ``The Dream'' finds a powerful new eroticism in
the play, notably in Titania's amour with Bottom, which usually
packs the sexual charge of the ``Teddy Bear's Picnic.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the most exciting work is often to be found in the
smaller London theaters, such as the Donmar, the Royal Court and
the Almeida. The latter will have the estimable Ian McDiarmid
playing the ferocious title role in Marlowe's ``Jew of Malta'' at
its home in Islington on Oct. 5. Covent Garden's Donmar becomes
rather more stellar on Nov. 9, since the major roles in Richard
Greenberg's tale of American fathers and sons, ``Three Days of
Rain,'' are being taken by Elizabeth McGovern and Colin Firth, who
played a sensuous Darcy in British television's version of Jane
Austen's ``Pride and Prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   But nothing in the British theater matters more than the
reopening of the Royal Court, which has been in exile in the West
End while its 400-seat playhouse in Chelsea has been rebuilt. After
more than $35 million has been spent on everything from offices to
a fly tower to a restaurant stretching beneath Sloane Square, the
place will be back in business this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The play won't be officially announced until Sept. 21, but the
word is that the favored dramatist is Conor McPherson, the
27-year-old Irishman whose ``Weir'' has recently proved quite a
success on both sides of the Atlantic. If he can produce anything
as stirring and unpretentiously wise this time, the omens for ``the
national theater of new writing,'' as the Court likes to style
itself, have to be good.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
