<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2524 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-ART-1050(TRI     09-06 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-ART-1050(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMEN MUST CHOOSE COMPROMISE OR CONFRONTATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.M., Texas, Miss.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Congress returns this week from its August
recess, Republicans and the White House face difficult choices
between compromise and confrontation on issues from tax cuts to gun
control to regulation of managed health care.
</P>
<P>
   Over the break, Republicans also promised to begin a series of
contentious and, for the Clinton administration, potentially
embarrassing hearings into allegations that Russians laundered
billions of dollars through the Bank of New York, and into new
revelations about the siege of the Branch Davidian compound near
Waco, Texas, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The first big step, however, will be President Clinton's. He is
eager for Republicans to send him their $792-billion tax cut bill
so he can veto it on the ground that it is too expensive. After
that, the battle will begin over the fall's dominant issue: how to
divide the projected $3 trillion federal surplus among tax relief,
federal programs and debt reduction through the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans had counted on whipping up support for their tax
bill in town meetings and other events across the country in
August. But the campaign apparently failed to stir constituents
from their summer diversions or to shift the White House's
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with polling data and past experience, the White House is
confident that the public is on its side on the issue of taxes and
spending. Clinton said in his weekly radio address on Saturday that
he would support a smaller tax package in return for Republican
concessions on Medicare, the federal health insurance program for
the elderly, including a voluntary prescription drug program for
senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there may be the basis for looking at a middle-class
tax cut at a level we can pay for, once we've done the important
things on Social Security and Medicare,'' White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart said on Sunday. Lockhart said $300 billion is the maximum
tax relief the president is willing to accept.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans are divided over whether to adopt a
conciliatory approach and produce some legislative gains, or stick
to their core principles going into the 2000 campaign season. Aides
say that Speaker J. Dennis Hastert and some key Senate Republicans,
like Pete Domenici of New Mexico, chairman of the Budget Committee,
are willing to discuss a smaller tax package. But Rep. Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, the majority whip, and Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the
majority leader, are counseling a hard line, Republican aides say.
</P>
<P>
   Many congressional Republicans also express suspicions that the
president may be less interested in a grand bargain than in a
legislative train wreck that he and Vice President Al Gore could
use as a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This latest exercise is further proof that the president does
not want to admit that he is dead set against giving any tax relief
to married couples, small business owners, investors and millions
of other Americans,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who heads the
House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the greater worry both inside the White House and
among some Democrats on Capitol Hill is that the president, in his
eagerness to strike a deal, will compromise both his and his
party's principles, said one White House official. Aides are
working to make sure he does not reach an agreement that robs them
of a potent campaign issue, or that forces Democrats to choose
between their president and their constituents.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sorting out the nation's fiscal priorities into
the new millennium, Congress must pass 13 appropriations bills to
keep the government running after Sept. 30, the end of the current
fiscal year. The House has approved 11, the Senate nine. Only two
are ready to be sent to the president.
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate, convening on Wednesday in what will be a
light first week back to work, each resumes work on spending bills
as the first order of business.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional appropriators have tried to devise a budget
beneath stringent spending limits outlined in the 1997 balanced
budget agreement, but they now concede it is likely Congress will
have to borrow from Social Security to pay for its operations next
year. Each party will likely blame the other if this happens.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the pressure on the budget caps, Clinton later this
month will request from lawmakers several billion dollars in
additional spending for fiscal 2000, including new money for
drought relief, aid to earthquake victims in Turkey and
peacekeeping and rebuilding efforts in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have a long list of non-budgetary priorities whose
fate remains in limbo, including gun control, managed-care
regulation and an overhaul of the campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate negotiators are to meet this month to try to
reconcile juvenile justice bills. The Senate version tightens gun
control; the House bill is silent on the matter. The Senate has
approved a managed care bill; the House will likely debate and vote
on at least one version later this month. The House is set to
debate campaign finance next week; the Senate most likely will do
so in October.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders see little political gain in any of these
three divisive issues, and are likely to try to thwart all but the
most minimal changes.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats and White House aides acknowledge that
prospects are slim for any major policy achievements next year,
Clinton's last in office. So Democrats have a narrow window to
broker any compromises this year before the presidential campaign
season seizes all the political attention.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Yet the White House has signaled that it does not need
Republican cooperation to notch policy successes. ``If the
Republicans come back and they're not interested, and they want
gridlock, well, we're going to keep moving forward,'' Lockhart
said. The administration is considering executive actions on
initiatives like clean air regulations and parental leave.
</P>
<P>
   With such an ambitious fall agenda, few lawmakers or aides are
hopeful that the House, at least, will meet the Oct. 29 adjournment
date tentatively scheduled by Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, the
majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, John Pitney, a political science professor at Claremont
McKenna College in California who follows Congress closely, summed
up his forecast for the fall legislative season in one word:
``Pain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
