<HEADER>
A2527 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-COMETS-FOLO-HNS &LR;      09-06 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-FOLO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Go ahead. Start calling the Comets, who reached a pro basketball
milestone Sunday with their third straight WNBA world championship,
a dynasty.
<TEXT>
<P>
   After winning the league's first crown in 1997, the Comets have
posted regular-season records of 27-3 and 26-6, the latter under
the most difficult of circumstances. In the process, they've
annexed another couple of titles to establish what must be
considered a dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   And as scary as it may seem to some, there are plenty of signs
the Comets' indomitable spirit, tremendous talent and abilities
will keep ruling the WNBA for at least a few more years.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's 59-47 victory over the New York Liberty in front of a
wild sellout crowd of 16,285 at Compaq Center gave the Comets their
third silver Tiffany-designed trophy. There had been only three pro
basketball franchises before the Comets to win three consecutive
world championships.
</P>
<P>
   The famed George Mikan hook shot was the catalyst to the
Minneapolis Lakers' becoming NBA champs from 1952-54.
</P>
<P>
   After Bill Russell was drafted by the Celtics out of the
University of San Francisco, a string of NBA titles soon followed
to Boston Garden. The Celtics won eight championships in a row
beginning in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   And Michael Jordan put aside his endorsements and dark glasses
long enough to pilot the Chicago Bulls to three straight titles
from 1991-93 and again from '96-98.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Comets? There's no end in sight to how many WNBA
titles they can reel off.
</P>
<P>
   There were many disbelievers who predicted that because of a
league that got stronger from the influx of former American
Basketball League performers, the Comets were doomed in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But aside from the Yolanda Griffith-led Sacramento Monarchs and
the Los Angeles Sparks, who counted Lisa Leslie and ex-ABL
sidekicks DeLisha Milton and L'Keshia Frett among their numbers,
the doomsayers believed the Comets had an even greater foe to
overcome: Kim Perrot, the point guard who led the Comets to
back-to-back WNBA titles, had announced in February she was
battling lung and brain cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But after Perrot died Aug. 19, Van Chancellor _ the only Coach
of the Year the WNBA has known _ deftly guided the Comets through
the tail end of the season and the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly, the immediate future looks ripe for adding a
fourth crown.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Cooper, the two-time league Most Valuable Player,
three-time scoring champ and three-time Championship Series MVP,
will be 37 next season. She may not be as speedy as before, but, as
she is fond of saying, ``I haven't forgotten how to play the game
of basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   WNBA opponents have yet to figure out a way to stop her. Double
and triple teams are merely a challenge that test Cooper's
mentality and mettle yet falter in a hail of 3-pointers or driving
layups.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Cooper hasn't enjoyed a stretch like the three-game sortie
in her and the WNBA's ``rookie season,'' when, in the span of a
week, she scored 42 points at Sacramento, 40 at Phoenix, then a
WNBA-record 44 on a return trip to Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   But the night of Aug. 14, 1999, at Compaq Center won't soon be
forgotten. Twenty-four hours after her dear friend Perrot had been
airlifted from Mexico to M.D. Anderson Cancer Center, Cooper scored
an amazing 42 points in a 71-53 Comets massacre of the Minnesota
Lynx.
</P>
<P>
   And she is just one part of the Comets juggernaut that returns
next season.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Swoopes, runner-up for the 1999 MVP award and the first
player to log a triple double in the league, will be back at age
29.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Thompson, 24, twice an All-WNBA first-teamer who this year
made the second-team squad, brings back her 3-point bombs, powerful
inside moves and tremendous defensive acumen.
</P>
<P>
   How the rest of the 11-woman lineup looks lies largely in the
hands of the WNBA. Because of expansion by four teams next season,
there are a number of Comets who will probably find their way onto
other rosters.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no indication as to how many players each of the
present 12 teams can protect from the expansion draft. But the
draft process will be a direct determinant on the face of the 2000
Comets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we have to make a judgment as to how do we best
balance the need to make our expansion teams reasonably competitive
and yet give the existing teams the benefits of all their efforts _
in some cases over the past three seasons,'' said WNBA president
Val Ackerman.
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, expansion by four teams _ and so quickly
following the addition of Minnesota and Orlando this season _ may
weaken the level of competition leaguewide. And that could be
advantageous to the Comets' hopes for a fourth title, depending on
potential realignment and several other factors.
</P>
<P>
   But the Comets have so far proved that no obstacle, on the court
or off, can keep them out of the WNBA throne room.
</P>
<P>
   And the Comets' dominance, said Ackerman, isn't all bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at it in a lot of ways as a plus, much like dynasties
in other sports have drawn attention, which has made people focus
on the excellence of the top teams,'' she said. ``I think the
efforts of Houston have been a positive for the league, and
particularly this year, when so many talented new players came into
the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that in the future, there would be some
additional opportunities for teams to get closer, and I do expect
that to happen. For now, I think this (Houston) is a great story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
