<HEADER>
A2529 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TEN-CAPRIATI-STATEMEN     09-06 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-CAPRIATI-STATEMENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tearful Capriati seeks to look forward, not back
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jennifer Capriati, by reaching the fourth round, used
the 1999 U.S. Open to prove she's ready and finally able to take
her tennis game back to the top.
</P>
<P>
   But she proved in an emotional post-match news conference
Monday, after losing to fourth seed Monica Seles 6-4, 6-3, that her
psyche may still be too fragile.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati, 23, began by reading a prepared statement and then
telling reporters she wishes to ``close the envelope of my past''
and would no longer discuss the memories, matches, feelings or
details of her youth or two-year hiatus from tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of, every time I read something about myself, I
always read that little tidbit about the past,'' she said,
explaining why she made the statement. ``I just hope by doing this,
it will end that chapter and I can start new.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati spoke for about 10 minutes and explained that she
hasn't found healing in talking about her past ``I really thought
that's what it was going to do,'' she said. ``(But) I just really
didn't know how to handle it, just how to go about saying it,
afraid I was going to say something wrong. Maybe that's why I've
played with a lot of anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   She couldn't answer the next question, but it had nothing to do
with the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to start crying,'' she squeaked out before covering
her face. ``It's nothing bad, it's just . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati turned red and put her face on her arms on the desk in
front of her for several seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a little overwhelming, that's all,'' she said
through tears while her father and former coach, Stefano, stood
teary-eyed in the back of the room.
</P>
<P>
   A tour official asked if she wanted to end the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needs to be done,'' Capriati answered.
</P>
<P>
   But she continued crying and didn't move. The tour official
repeated that she could end the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish I didn't have to talk about this stuff all the
time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati looked again like the overachieving but overwhelmed
teenager whose career went from shining star to burn out in four
years.
</P>
<P>
   She turned pro in 1990, just before her 14th birthday, as one of
the greatest phenoms ever. She reached the semifinals of the French
Open a few months later and quickly became a media darling.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1993, her struggles began, in the form of shoplifting and
possession of marijuana citations and a night in jail. She lost in
the first round of the U.S. Open that year and didn't play another
professional match until February 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has played intermittently because of injuries
and motivational problems. This year, since March, marks the first
steady rise of her return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there is much mystery, much question to what happened,
and I must also say many lies,'' Capriati's statement read. ``Yes,
I made mistakes by rebelling, by acting out in confused ways. But
it was all due to the fact that I was very young and I was
experiencing my adolescence. Most of you know how hard that can be.
When you do it in front of the world, it is even harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Her time off did not involve ``reckless drug use, hurting
others,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a path of quiet rebellion, of a little experimentation
of a darker side of my confusion in a confusing world, lost in the
midst of finding my identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Capriati called her past ``sacred'' and declined to answer a
question about a 1991 match against Seles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what happened with me doesn't happen too often,''
Capriati said.
</P>
<P>
   But other players talk about it almost as much. Andre Agassi's
career has been like a roller coaster. Steffi Graf and Mary Pierce
endured troubles with their fathers. Seles got stabbed and lost
years of her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine how tough that must be, having that done to
you,'' Capriati said of Seles. ``She was in no control over it. My
situation was different. I was in complete control or . . . I don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the essence of the stories of athletes and even regular
folks is where they've been, whether in or out of their control,
and where they've ended up.
</P>
<P>
   Capriati will end up with a ranking in the low 30s after this
tournament. She said she plans to continue working hard on her
tennis, which improved more this summer than she had expected. The
match with Seles was a good one. Capriati fought back once in each
set to pressure Seles but said she needs more mental strength
against top players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a little nervous there a few times in the match and just
didn't really know how to handle the big points,'' Capriati said.
</P>
<P>
   She hoped her statement would provide a cleansing moment for
her. It might not have done that, but the whole of her 1999 Open
did reveal an older, better-spoken Jennifer Capriati.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a new person completely,'' she said. ``I just feel
like a real mature adult now.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Clarke writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
