<HEADER>
A2531 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT &LR;      09-06 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROGERS HURLS SHUTOUT AS METS DOWN GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bit by bit, Kenny Rogers puts dings in the myth, each
strong outing burying the notion that there is something a little
different about him, something that prevents him from succeeding in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the cloak-and-dagger personality, the enigmatic hushed
answers, were left in the Bronx, because since arriving at Shea
Stadium in July, Rogers has been a mystery almost exclusively to
opposing hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the San Francisco Giants shook their heads at Rogers the
way the Yankees once did. Moving his pitches inside and out,
lulling the Giants with pitches that dotted the outside corner of
the plate only to freeze them by banging his best fastball of the
last month inside, Rogers threw a four-hit shutout and the Mets
won, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Mets' first complete-game shutout in a year and just
their third complete game of the season; Rogers has two.
</P>
<P>
   In his eight starts for the Mets, Rogers is 4-0 and the team is
7-1. The Mets remained four games ahead of the Cincinnati Reds in
the wild-card race and two games behind the Atlanta Braves in the
National League East before Atlanta's game Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine this success from Rogers, the man who admitted upon his
return to New York that it was important for him to prove to
himself he could succeed here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had an issue with where I pitched,'' said Rogers, who
pitched for the Yankees in 1996 and '97 and was acquired by the
Mets from Oakland. ``I think it was everybody else's hang-up. It's
New York, it's always different. Maybe it's a little more intense.
Sometimes you need this. I knew I could pitch here. I thought it
wasn't where I pitched. I thought it was how I pitched.''
</P>
<P>
   There can be little doubt how he is pitching now, with
confidence and ease.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said that one of the most important things a pitcher can
do when he joins a new team is to earn his teammates' trust. Then
they will be relaxed when playing behind him and may even swing
more easily when they are at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can feel it when they have confidence in you and there's a
reverse,'' Rogers said. ``You can feel it when nobody has
confidence in you.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers is familiar with both sensations, but with the Mets he
has given his teammates nothing but reason to relax and scoop up
the groundballs he produces. Since he suffered back spasms that
shortened his outing to three innings on Aug. 21, Rogers has
allowed just two runs in 241/3 innings, plunging his earned run
average as a Met to 3.15.
</P>
<P>
   Monday he had complete control of his fastball, sinker and
curve. Rogers struck out nine _ Barry Bonds went down three times _
and walked just one. He was moving the ball around the plate so
successfully _ particularly the sinker _ that the Giants were
helping him expand the strike zone, swinging at pitches that were
off the plate. And, because he is a groundball pitcher anyway,
Rogers was the beneficiary of the Mets' stellar infield, which
recorded 12 outs on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers held the Giants at bay while Rickey Henderson generated
enough offense to win the game. He hit a leadoff double and later
scored the Mets' first run in the sixth inning, then hit a two-run
single to shallow center in the seventh. ``This is a new Rickey,''
manager Bobby Valentine said. ``A reborn guy, a hitter who looks
like he has a lot left in the tank.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the report Valentine got about Rogers when the Mets
traded for him. Valentine was unconcerned about Rogers' history in
New York _ he was 18-15 with a 5.11 ERA as a Yankee _ only worried
about his arm. But Valentine said the people he talked to told him
Rogers' ``arm would have plenty of tosses left.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of them worked against the Giants, and his mastery of
Bonds, by keeping the ball bouncing around the plate like a
pinball, was exceptional. On the first strikeout, Rogers got Bonds
to chase an 87 mph fastball up. In the fourth inning, he stunned
Bonds with a four-seam fastball on the outside corner that Bonds
took for a called third strike. ``That's as good a pitch as I can
throw,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Mike Piazza said: ``The pitches Barry was looking for,
he was giving them to him. But they were a few inches from where he
expected them and he couldn't do anything with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' best inning was the ninth, when he retired the heart of
the Giants' lineup and, by his own admission, threw harder than
usual. He struck out Bonds first, this time by spinning him around
when he reached for an 88 mph fastball that was up. Jeff Kent went
next: after sinker after sinker, the strikeout pitch was a slider
that dropped away. Finally, Ellis Burks lined out to Robin Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, reliever Pat Mahomes walked by to give Rogers a tap,
and Rogers said to him, ``I told you I would give you the day
off.''
</P>
<P>
   He has had better stuff before, Rogers said, but this time he
moved the ball better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used both sides of the plate so well,'' Piazza said.
``Maybe there are two or three hitters in the history of the game
who can, but I don't think a hitter can cover both sides of the
plate. If he is hitting inside and outside and he throws the curve
for strikes, what do you look for?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
