<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Four receivers not enough, so Falcons scouting for more
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons pro personnel chief Ron Hill was
``crunching'' film Monday looking for wide receivers, and trade
talks continued in an effort to erase the biggest question mark for
the team.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, who begin the regular season Sunday in the Georgia
Dome against the Minnesota Vikings, have four receivers on the
roster, and it's one of the smallest and inexperienced groups in
the NFL. Starters Terance Mathis (5 feet 10) and Chris Calloway
(5-10) have a total of 836 catches in their careers. Reserves Tim
Dwight (5-8) and Ronnie Harris (5-11) have combined for 12.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Atlanta carried five wide receivers. Some teams carry
six.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Carrying four receivers) is not one of the more comfortable
things,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``It's difficult when you know
it's not the squad you're going to be with the whole time. You've
got to be flexible enough to make some changes later.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons began training camp wondering who would replace
starter Tony Martin, who was released in February in connection
with his legal problems, and now they have more questions.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight and Harris have outstanding speed, but Dwight has learned
speed doesn't overcome a lack of technique. Both are learning the
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've slowed down a lot,'' Dwight said. ``You don't have to be
fast to get open; you've got to be smart. I'll be in the slot a lot
more, and I've learned you've got to be more in control. I've tried
to harness my speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Passing game coordinator Jack Burns, who is in charge of
play-calling, said having four wideouts instead of five won't
change the Falcons' gameplan. The team typically dresses four
receivers per game.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that tight ends Brian Kozlowski, 6-3, 250, and
tight end O.J. Santiago, 6-7, 267, can split wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be in the same packages we normally would be,'' Burns
said. ``Brian can overlap and do some things for us there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't know what we're going to carry until maybe the end of
the week. We're not sure how many we'll carry, or what we'll do,
but whichever way we go, we'll be able to function.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL teams began assembling their practice squads on Monday
night, and there's a good chance Eugene Baker and/or Jammi German,
who were cut on Sunday, will return to the team that way. Both have
practice squad eligibility. Rondel Menendez, who will agree to an
injury settlement today, cannot be re-acquired.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons also could find a receiver recently released by
another team.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as no one gets injured, we should be OK,'' quarterback
Chris Chandler said. ``They're all good players. Maybe that's one
of the things to look forward to this season, to see how that story
goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis and Burns have seen improvement from the backups.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're more confident, more aware,'' he said. ``Last year,
they were just running routes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim has the great push,'' Burns said. ``He gets defenders on
their heels, moving around, and then he can run past them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronnie can really run, too. He's fast enough to threaten the
goalline. He's much farther along than when he came to us last
year. He's also a little stronger physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
