<DOCNO> NYT19990906.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2559 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-HISPANICVOTE-COX     09-06 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-HISPANICVOTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Border leaders give Bush mixed reviews
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Fresh from his success among Texas Hispanic
voters in the past fall's re-election bid, Gov. George W. Bush has
taken his Spanish-laced stump speeches to the national stage, and
the Republican Party sees him as a bona fide crossover hit.
</P>
<P>
   In his bid for the presidency, Bush is energetically courting
the nation's fastest-growing voting group. And he's creating great
expectations in key states such as California, where local GOP
officers consider Bush a potential savior as they try to patch up
relations with Hispanics following former Gov. Pete Wilson's
anti-immigrant crusades.
</P>
<P>
   The courtship hasn't been completely smooth. Bush has been
criticized by some Hispanic groups for skipping their national
meetings, and he disappointed some Texas border leaders who felt he
didn't support their agenda during this year's legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bush used a speech before 3,000 people at the Latino
Business Association's annual meeting in Los Angeles to lay out the
first portion of his education platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was very, very important for him to be here, and I
think he did a good job,'' said Los Angeles insurance man Hector
Barreto, the association's chairman. ``One of the things people are
noticing about this candidate is, he is different. He is not the
traditional conservative Republican politician. His message is one
of inclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush supporters, including Barreto, think the governor can
replicate the strong numbers he posted among Texas Hispanics in his
1998 re-election bid. One poll showed him taking 39 percent of the
Texas Hispanic vote. Another _ the one his campaign quotes _ gave
him 49 percent. Both numbers are unprecedented for a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   What's unusual is that Bush did it without tailoring his
positions or making specific promises to Hispanic voters, a
strategy that top Bush adviser Karl Rove said is at work again in a
presidential campaign targeting Hispanics nationwide. In Los
Angeles last week, Rove said it's a broad audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They share a lot of common values,'' he said when asked to
compare Texas Hispanics and California Hispanics. ``There is some
poll data that indicate that Latinos in California are more
Democratic in orientation than in Texas. In Texas, they tend to be
less affiliated with either party, or more likely to be less
partisan in their affiliation if they are Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   A foothold for GOP Last year, Bush translated his message into
Spanish in heavily Hispanic parts of the state, including the
border area, traditionally a Democratic stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spent a lot of time down here. That's unusual for a
Republican candidate,'' said Jerry Polinard, a political science
professor at the University of Texas-Pan American in Edinburg. ``He
was not pandering to the Latino vote; I think that was important.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign says the governor's core message, with its
emphasis on improving education, fighting crime and promoting
individual responsibility, resonates with Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Hispanic community, like communities all over
America, is responding to his message of prosperity with a
purpose,'' Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said. ``He is actively
reaching out to new faces and new voices as he campaigns for
president.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Pete Gallego, a Democrat from Alpine, said Bush's
strategy of sticking to a broad message and making no specific
promises to border-area voters will translate well to a national
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of his strengths is, he's really good at generalities,''
Gallego said. ``He's good at painting a big picture and leaving the
details (to others). In Bush's case, I think (Hispanics will)
overlook a lot of the details because they think he's a good guy _
and he is,'' Gallego said.
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll by the William C. Velasquez Institute of Hispanic
Voters in California and Texas showed Bush leading Vice President
Al Gore 40 percent to 38 percent in Texas but trailing Gore by a
2-to-1 ratio in California _ which, according to the institute, is
a good showing considering that California Hispanics chose
President Clinton over Republican Bob Dole by a 10-to-1 ratio in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, nowhere was Bush's reach into Hispanic Democratic
strongholds more stark than in El Paso and the Rio Grande Valley,
where Bush rebounded from his 1994 defeat by Ann Richards in those
regions to win the three most populous border counties.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some border leaders felt let down after Bush's big
buildup during last year's gubernatorial race. Although he didn't
promise specifics, many expected Bush's aggressive campaigning
would lead to his active support for their agenda, which sought
significant state money for roads, job training and economic
development on the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``George is charismatic, but looking beyond his charisma, I find
that he didn't do very much for the border,'' said McAllen Mayor
Leo Montalvo. ``Deliver, then ask for my support.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign points to his leadership on pushing through
legislation to help colonias, substandard housing developments
concentrated near the border. However, Montalvo and others thought
Bush should have stepped in when their $1 billion highway proposal
was being shot down by lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his misgivings, Montalvo doesn't think disappointing a
few elected officials on the border will put a dent in Bush's
appeal to Hispanics there or elsewhere. ``The issues get lost in
the shuffle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For some national Hispanic groups, Bush's lack of specifics on
some of their main issues _ and his absence at their annual
conventions _ have tempered their earlier praise for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His support among the Latino community is very real, but it's
also very fragile,'' said Lisa Navarrete, spokeswoman for the
National Council of La Raza, one of the country's most powerful
Hispanic groups.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, Enrique ``Rick'' Dovalina, president of the League
of United Latin American Citizens, said the governor missed an
opportunity to explain his position on issues such as immigration
and school vouchers to thousands of politically active Hispanics at
LULAC's annual meeting last month in Corpus Christi.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what his stance is (on those issues) because he
hasn't talked to us,'' Dovalina said. ``Right now, we're very
disappointed with the way he's parading around with his taco
politics. He doesn't have the Hispanic vote sewn up just because
he's speaking Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither LULAC nor NCLR is a partisan group, but neither has been
seen as friendly to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign said he is bombarded with requests to appear at
events and can't accept every one. The governor has gone out of his
way to meet with Hispanics around the country, said spokesman
McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Bush sought out Iowa Hispanics to urge them to vote
in the presidential straw poll. He has scheduled meetings with
local Hispanic leaders as he crisscrosses the country, and on
Friday returned to the border to attend the opening of a new
international bridge linking Eagle Pass and Piedras Negras,
Coahuila.
</P>
<P>
   In Starr County _ a Democratic stronghold where Richards beat
Bush by a 3-to-1 ratio in 1994 _ merchant Noel Benavides said he's
seeing underground support building for the governor. While
Democrat Garry Mauro also beat Bush soundly in Starr County in last
year's governor's race, the governor won 37 percent of the county,
up from 22 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people say they're Democrats, but when it
comes down to it, I get the impression from talking to people in
this area that they will vote for Bush,'' said Benavides, owner of
the J.C. Ramirez store in downtown Roma.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Harmon writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
