<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 09/06/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) UNDATED -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- OBIT-MACLEECH-B&AMP;W, 09-06 --
Bert MacLeech, an associate professor emeritus at the University of
Southern California and a leader in the 1950s movement to provide
community-based services for handicapped young people, died on Aug.
26 at his home in Los Angeles. He was 90. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) UNDATED -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- OBIT-FUNT-B&AMP;W, 09-06 --
Allen Funt, the host and creator of television's ``Candid Camera,''
conducting an interview for a segment of the show in 1963, during
the peak of its popularity. The concept for the series was first
developed for radio in 1947. Funt died Sunday at his home in Pebble
Beach, Calif. He was 84. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK-- Sept. 6, 1999 -- TEN-USPOEN, 09-06 --
Jennifer Capriati reacts during her loss to Monica Seles at the
U.S. Open on Monday. An hour after losing to Seles 6-4, 6-3,
Capriati held a news conference to talk about the collapse of her
career in 1993, her subsequent arrests on shoplifting and drug
possession charges, and her rehabilitation. (Barton Silverman/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- ADELI-FASHION-3, 09-06 --
These clothes by Katayone Adeli won't be seen on the runway: the
designer doesn't believe in fashion shows. One model is wearing
zip-front pants and a close-fit sweater; another model, seated,
wears a chiffon crepe dress. (Susan Farley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- ADELI-FASHION-2, 09-06 --
Katayone Adeli, fashion designer, in her publicity picture. ``I
have a certain cult following, without having done fashion shows
and without any advertising,'' says Ms. Adeli, 36. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- ADELI-FASHION-1, 09-06 --
From the fall collection of Katayone Adeli, a brown suede coat is
worn over a fuchsia crepe dress. ``I have a certain cult following,
without having done fashion shows and without any advertising,''
says Ms. Adeli, 36. (Susan Farley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) MILFORD, N.H. -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- CAMPAIGN-RDP, 09-06 --
Sheila Copeland of Manchester, N.H., a Steve Forbes supporter,
sizes up former Vice President Dan Quayle as he tries to convince
her to support him as he marched in the town's Labor Day Parade on
Monday. Presidential candidates kissed babies, marched in parades,
munched at picnics and made speeches today as they observed what
has been called the traditional kickoff of the campaign on Labor
Day - a year early. (Jared Leeds/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WILDWOOD, N.J. -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- LABOR-DAY-END-3,
09-06 -- Students who spent the summer as lifeguards at Morey's
Pier Raging Waters Theme Park pose for pictures as staff members
try to get a group shot with all their cameras on Monday. The
students started work at the park on Memorial day and were
celebrating their last day before returning to school. (Laura
Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- NY-ANCIENT-SKULL, 09-06 --
A customer checks out a display at Maxilla and Mandible, Ltd., run
by Henry Galiano, right. An intriguing fossil skull, presumably
from a Homo erectus and possibly a revealing piece of evidence for
understanding human evolution, has been found not on a parched hill
in Africa or along a river in Java, but at this cozy little shop on
the Upper West Side of Manhattan which specializes in selling bones
and fossils. (Elizabeth Lippman/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NY24) EAST ISLIP, N.Y. -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- LABOR-DAY-END-2,
09-06 -- As Labor Day drew to a close, lifeguards moved signs to
storage bins on the beach in Heckscher State Park. Traditionally
seen as the end of summer, many lifeguards at beaches and pools
around the nation marked their last day of work on Monday. (James
Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- NAILS-SPI, 09-06 -- Nail
purists who spent years hiding their unadorned nails while long red
talons flashed their way through fashionland are having the last
laugh. Long, brightly colored nails are dust. Real or fake, they
have been filed away, grown out, shed like an old snakeskin. Leaf
through a fashion magazine and you'll see almost very model and
celebrity featured is sporting natural nails. (Meryl
Schenker/Seattle Post Intelligencer)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) SAN JOSE, Calif. -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- COLLEGE-GUIDANCE,
09-06 -- Students at Silver Creek High School listen to Jeff
Livingston, counseling director for Achieva, about college
application requirements last month. In a trend that educators say
is sure to spread, a growing number of public schools, most of them
in California, as well as others in Michigan, Illinois and
Missouri, are engaging firms like Achieva and the better-known
Princeton Review to relieve guidance counselors of major aspects of
college and career advising. (Thor Swift/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-4, 09-06 -- No.
5 seed Mary Pierce of France serving during her match against
Sabine Appelmans of Belgium at the U.S. Open on Monday. Pierce
defeated Appelmans 6-3, 7-6 (8-6) to reach the quarterfinals.
(Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-3, 09-06 -- No.
2 seed Andre Agassi bends for a backhand during his match against
Arnaud Clement at the U.S. Open on Monday. Agassi advanced to the
quarterfinals with a 6-4, 6-4, 6-3 victory over the unseeded
Frenchman. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN-2, 09-06 -- No.
4 seed Monica Seles, right, advances to the quarterfinals of the
U.S. Open on Monday with a 6-4, 6-3 victory over fellow American
Jennifer Capriati in one hour and 14 minutes. Seles, a three-time
winner here, will play seventh-seeded compatriot Serena Williams
for a spot in the semifinals. (Barton Silverman/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- TEN-USOPEN, 09-06 -- Serena
Williams of the U.S. reacts to a point against Conchita Martinez of
Spain during their U.S. Open match at Flushing Meadows on Monday.
Williams, No. 7 seed, defeated Martinez, No. 16, 4-6, 6-2, 6-2.
(Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- CAGE-ANNIVERSARY, 09-06 --
About 30 people read John Cage's tiny stories on Sunday at a
birthday tribute for Cage, who died in 1992, at St. Mark's Church
in the East Village. Cage left us no important music, and yet no
composer of our time was more influential. This is the principal
paradox of the man, but only the first of many. (Rob Schoenbaum/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- SCI-NEANDERTHALS, 09-06 -- A
radiograph of the Neanderthal skull ``C'' reveals the shape and
structure of its interior. ``This is exciting new data, and the
first time researchers have had an opportunity to view, in total,
so many radiographic images of fossils from an entire group of
Neanderthals,'' says Dr. Alan Mann, an anthropologist at the
university. (University of Pennsylvania Museum/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- ART-MARKET, 09-06 --
Cezanne's ``Stoneware Pitcher'' will be among Sotheby's auction
offerings this fall. The art-collecting business, which once
followed the rhythms of the carriage trade, is instead moving to
the beat of Wall Street. That means that art buying has become a
year-round activity, and lazy Augusts are a thing of the past, even
when dealers do go on vacation. (Sotheby's New York/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- SCI-ELECTRONIC-BONDS-2,
09-06 -- A direct image of an electronic bond (aka an orbital) of
copper and oxygen as published last week in the journal Nature.
Future applications of the new imaging technique, chemists said,
may eventually shed light on one of the most intractable mysteries
of solid-state physics: why it is that certain compounds of copper
and oxygen can conduct electricity without resistance at relatively
high temperatures. (Arizona State/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- SCI-ELECTRONIC-BONDS, 09-06
-- Of the roughly 20 million chemical substances scientists have
cataloged, nearly all are assemblages of atoms linked together by
electronic bonds. Last week, the journal Nature published the
sharpest direct images ever made of electronic bonds, known as
orbitals. The shapes revealed by these images confirmed theoretical
predictions of what these bonds should look like. (Arizona
State/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEAR WACO, Texas -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- WACO-SCENE-4-COX,
09-06 -- A swimming pool on the grounds of what is left of the
former Branch Davidian compound. Six years after fire swept through
the complex, killing around 80, the old television footage is
airing once again as politicians and bureaucrats in Washington try
to reconstruct what happened. With a new focus on Waco, this piece
of ground is once again drawing the curious. (John Reetz/Cox News
Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEAR WACO, Texas -- Sept. 6, 1999 -- WACO-SCENE-3-COX,
09-06 -- An entrance to underground tunnels on the grounds of what
is left of the former Branch Davidian compound. Six years after
fire swept through the complex, killing around 80, the old
television footage is airing again as politicians and bureaucrats
in Washington try to reconstruct what happened. With a new focus on
Waco, this piece of ground is once again drawing the curious. (John
Reetz/Cox News Service Photo)
