<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990906.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2572 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TEN-US-OPEN-COX     09-06 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-US-OPEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Williams advances, awaits Seles
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Powerful Serena Williams met her tennis opposite
Monday in the fourth round of the U.S. Open in 16th seed Conchita
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach Gardens, Fla. resident eventually adjusted to
Martinez's unfamiliar and off-pace game, winning 4-6, 6-2, 6-2, but
it was not a pretty or particularly entertaining couple of hours of
tennis.
</P>
<P>
   For every moonball from Martinez, Williams would over-crank and
hit 6 feet out. For every swirling forehand from Martinez, Williams
would slow down and hit a dribbler that would run down her side of
the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, (it was) just a matter of making some adjustments,
getting my consistency together, getting myself together,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   She reduced her unforced errors from 21 in the first set to 17
in the second and 14 in the third. She also improved the number of
winners but still struggled to convert break points. She won just
5-of-15.
</P>
<P>
   And after just two aces in the first set, Williams hit 10 in the
final two sets, many at deuce or on other important points.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's stats changed little throughout the match, and she
finished with just seven winners to her opponent's 45.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these kinds of tests are important,'' Williams said.
``(They) can also kind of cut your career short, playing too many
hours out in the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was an important win for the seventh seed. It puts her
into her first Grand Slam quarterfinal in nearly two years on the
professional circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who is ranked No. 6 this week, plays fourth seed
Monica Seles on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really looking forward to it,'' she said. ``I love playing
Monica. Whenever we play, it's always very intense and very fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has won both times she has played Seles.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth seed Mary Pierce also advanced to her first U.S. Open
quarterfinal since 1994. She came back from a 0-4 lead in the
second set, and then set point down, to defeat unseeded Sabine
Appelmans 6-3, 7-6 (8-6).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think today was more of an intensity thing,'' Pierce said.
``Against someone like Sabine, you can't do that because she's a
fighter. I decided not to let it go any farther and wake up, just
try to win it in two sets.''
</P>
<P>
   Second seed Lindsay Davenport also managed to do that, holding
off a second-set rally by ninth seed Julie Halard-Decugis.
Davenport won 6-1, 6-2 and will play Pierce in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Clarke writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
