<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-CARDS07-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Maddux goes 9 innings, gets win over Cards
</P>
<P>
   By Carroll Rogers
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The one thing the Braves needed on Monday night was
some distance, and not the Mark McGwire tape measure kind.
</P>
<P>
   The farther away they could get from that botched third strike
play on Sunday afternoon that cost them a win against Arizona in
the game, the series and off Randy Johnson, the better.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Greg Maddux, his seven-game win streak and a fresh start
against the Cardinals on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Once again showing little problem with his bum wrist, Maddux
held off the Cardinals for a 4-1 win in front of 41,678, snapping a
two-game Braves losing streak and starting this series well.
</P>
<P>
   With the Mets' 3-0 win over the Giants, the Braves got to hold
at 2 1/2 games up in first place.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Maddux lost a game was when the Braves were
shutout by the Marlins Dennis Springer 2-0 on July 21 on the tail
end of that five-game losing streak on the roadtrip to open the
second half. The Braves haven't lost more than two in a row since
and Maddux made sure of it Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The National League's pitcher of the month in August made his
first September start a dandy, from allowing only three hits and a
run over the first eight innings to sitting down 23 batters in a
rowto collect his 18th win of the season. Two of the singles came
back-to-back which cost him the run on a Joe McEwing sacrifice fly
in the second inning. But McEwing became the first of 20
consecutive batters retired by Maddux as he and the offense
rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux had a 1-0 lead on a Gerald Williams homer to leadoff the
game _ which stretched his career-high season total to 13 _ and
lost it on that manufactured Cardinal run in the second inning. But
he got it back with a single up the middle in the third inning, his
11th hit of the season. He was bunted over to second, advanced to
third on a Bret Boone fly and scored on an infield hit by Chipper
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   First in line for forgetting Sunday was Eddie Perez, who was
charged with a throwing error on that critical play when Randall
Simon failed to cover first base. Perez helped that cause with a
bases loaded sacrifice fly in the sixth to stretch Maddux's lead to
3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones collected his 38th home run of the season and
third in the last two games to give Maddux a 4-1 cushion and help
seal Garrett Stephenson's fate. The Braves, who got past Stephenson
10 days before only after Bret Boone's heroics against the
Cardinals bullpen, handed Stephenson his first loss in seven starts
since he was recalled from AAA early last month.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
