<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER BLOWOUT, IT'S A BYE FOR USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC has plenty of momentum after its 62-7 rout of
Hawaii, but the Trojans will be forced to sit back and watch TV
this weekend with a bye on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   They return to action on Sept. 18 against San Diego State at the
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get lax. Or just settle for this win,'' wide
receiver R. Jay Soward said. ``If we do play like we did, we'll
make football interesting in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans would rather play a game this week, something that
almost happened last spring when USC agreed to move up its November
game with Washington State to Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cougars were unable to get other opponents to agree to
alter their schedules, canceling the proposed early contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd prefer to play, but a bye will help us,'' offensive
lineman Travis Claridge said. ``It'll help guys who are banged
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Road warriors: USC didn't let the atmosphere of playing in
Hawaii become a hindrance, which was a concern before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, we were prepared and ready to play,'' said
coach Paul Hackett said. ``We didn't let Waikiki and stuff on the
road distract us.''
</P>
<P>
   On target: Quarterback Carson Palmer has become so familiar with
the offense, Hackett has basically given him free reign to utilize
much of the playbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no limitations on the play calling,'' Hackett said.
``He is more in sync. All this offseason, the spring, the summer
and training camp have changed his dimension.''
</P>
<P>
   Poll numbers: USC moved up three spots to No. 18 in the
Associated Press poll. It's still too low for Palmer, but he's
beginning to like the anonymity of being in the lower half of the
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we deserve some respect,'' Palmer said. ``Being (18th)
is not a whole lot of respect there, but I do like being in the
background, too.''
</P>
<P>
   He's back: The sentimental hero of the Hawaii game was tailback
Malaefou MacKenzie, who scored three touchdowns after being out the
final 12 games last season with a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The butterflies came. I hadn't touched the ball in a year,''
MacKenzie said. ``It was exciting. I hadn't played in a while. I
just got the jitterbugs out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   With Frank Strong back in the doghouse after fumbling twice
against Hawaii, MacKenzie has no other competition for the role of
short-yardage tailback.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
