<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-JUNKMAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE PERILS OF IGNORING JUNK MAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt.)  (lb) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the record, Allan L. Jordan of Charlotte, Vt., is
not presented here as an unblemished hero, a woeful man whom the
unrelenting Furies of municipal bureaucracy set out to hound. On
the contrary, one could say that Jordan planted the seeds of his
own troubles when he tried to duck out on a parking ticket that he
got while on a visit to New York City in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Make that two parking tickets _ one on the Upper West Side, the
other in Greenwich Village. Jordan insists he never saw the one in
the Village. Maybe a prankster swiped it from the windshield, he
says.
</P>
<P>
   But he certainly knew about the other one and, like ticketed
drivers the world over who think they can skip town scot-free, he
chose to ignore it. Clearly, he underestimated the long reach of
the computer.
</P>
<P>
   The city's Finance Department, the parent agency of what is now
called Parking Violations Operations, tracked him down without
breaking a sweat. Letter after letter went out, informing him that
he owed the original fines plus penalties and interest _ a total of
$230 at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Here is where it gets interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, 64, a builder by trade, says he never saw those dunning
letters, so he had no idea that he owed penalties or, for that
matter, that there was a second ticket. The reason he knew nothing,
he says, is that the letters came in bulk-mail envelopes bearing no
markings to indicate they were from an agency of the city of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing official-looking about them. The sender was
listed in the upper left corner only as ``Cooper Square Station,
P.O. Box 915, New York, N.Y. 10276-0915.''
</P>
<P>
   To Jordan, it looked like junk mail. And his attitude toward
junk mail is that it goes straight into the trash, unopened,
``everything from Ed McMahon to credit-card solicitations.''
</P>
<P>
   He discovered the city was after him, he said, only when his
wife, Gertrude, happened one day to open a ``Cooper Square
Station'' envelope. By then, he figures, he had chucked out half a
dozen such notices. On discovering that the Finance Department had
him in its sights, he paid the original $55 fine for the Upper West
Side summons. But he challenged the penalties and the theretofore
unknown Village ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the envelopes had said `City of New York' somewhere, I
would have opened them,'' Jordan said. ``We pay our bills.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, some will dismiss all this as an attempt to beat a
bill by a man who should have paid his tickets in the first place
and should have known that he risked penalties. Still, he has
raised an intriguing question:
</P>
<P>
   Should a person be held accountable for not recognizing a
government agency that does not announce itself?
</P>
<P>
   He and the city have exchanged many letters. Lately, the Office
of the Sheriff has warned _ in envelopes marked only ``Cadman Plaza
Station'' _ that his property could be seized. At no point, Jordan
said, has any New York official acknowledged his basic point about
junk mail.
</P>
<P>
   Does his argument hold water? You may not be shocked to hear
that law professors disagree with one another.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Whelan of Fordham University, a friend of Jordan, saw
merit in the Vermonter's position. ``Decent notice is one of the
most fundamental components of due process of law,'' he said. But
Larry Kramer of New York University, while expressing some sympathy
for Jordan, said the city had good reason to expect a reply,
regardless of the envelope it used, because ``most people open
their junk mail.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is ``what responsibility each side bears,'' Kramer
said, and he believes that city officials ``haven't done anything
wrong, even if they could have done it better.''
</P>
<P>
   You may wonder why the city sends out important mail in this
fashion. Various agencies have used such envelopes in certain
situations since 1986, said Denise Collins, a spokeswoman for the
Department of Citywide Administrative Services. Experience, she
said, shows that people are more likely to open letters that do not
scream ``parking violations'' on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, Jordan said. But he is not one of those people.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some would advise him to pay up and get the city off
his back. ``But then,'' Jordan said, ``I would in effect be saying,
`Yes sir, I will open each and every piece of junk mail that comes
to my door,' which I refuse to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
