<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2685 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LB     09-06 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESPN TURNS 20
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A viewer would have to be pretty jaded to look at ESPN in the
twilight of the 20th Century and not marvel at its role in American
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Can you remember back to what TV sports was like before the
advent of cable and the Entertainment and Sports Programming
Network (ESPN)? Are your kids as shocked to learn the baby boomers
grew up without SportsCenter as you were when your parents said
they grew up without television?
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1979, baseball had this quaint game-of-the-week series
on Saturday afternoons. If you wanted to watch a USC or UCLA
football game, you usually needed a ticket. CBS used to televise
NBA playoff games on a tape-delayed basis.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN changed more than viewing habits. It changed programming
habits. ESPN and regional cable outlets changed the way leagues and
franchises look at their product, showing them how to enjoy the
riches of gate receipts and TV rights at the same time. It is now
more notable when a sports event isn't
</P>
<P>
   televised.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Dodgers, for example. When Walter O'Malley moved the
team west, he allowed only those games at San Francisco to be
televised locally. (He actually arrived with plans for a forerunner
of pay-per-view, but never overcame delivery problems.) In 1999,
around 140 Dodgers games will be televised, and the team itself is
owned by a media company (Fox).
</P>
<P>
   From an initial programming lineup that featured things like
monster trucks, softball and hurling, ESPN developed into an entity
strong enough to be purchased in 1984 by the dominant media company
of the time, ABC/Capital Cities, and then again in 1996 by the
dominant brand name corporation, Disney. Michael Eisner so loves
ESPN that it ranks higher on the Disney corporate ladder than its
over-the-air network, ABC.
</P>
<P>
   So when you tune in SportsCenter tonight, or ESPN's three-hour,
self-indulgent birthday special (4 p.m.), give the network its due
for all that it has accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   My personal appreciation changes direction when I consider what
ESPN has become.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a person or a product becomes part of the culture,
there is the danger of narcissism. ESPN is very smitten with itself
at the moment, and borderline arrogant. It takes several different
forms.
</P>
<P>
   Back when SportsCenter was the clearing house for news and
highlights, its anchors were dependable and unobtrusive. Fellows
like Bob Ley, the late Tom Mees, Charlie Steiner and even the
bombastic Chris Berman knew they were chauffeurs. If they were good
drivers at the same time, all the better.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere during the Keith Olbermann-Dan Patrick era, ESPN
drifted off the road. This tag-team took SportsCenter's substance
and gave it a sly personality. But it was always grounded.
Olbermann's historical and non-sports tangents always returned to
home plate, and Patrick's inflections were understated.
</P>
<P>
   Very little of SportsCenter now is understated. If the anchors
aren't yelling at the camera, they're showering you with personal
catch-phrases or styles that shudder in comparison to those of
Olbermann, Patrick and even (I can't believe I'm writing this)
Berman.
</P>
<P>
   An ESPN exec, after Olbermann departed for MSNBC (and then Fox),
tried to minimize the role of anchors by saying anyone could do
SportsCenter. Obviously, he is trying to prove this point by
putting just about anyone on air.
</P>
<P>
   With Patrick making a lateral move to ESPN radio, ESPN's
signature SportsCenter talents now are Stuart Scott (boo-yah), Rich
Eisen (Olbermann Lite) and the painfully droll Kenny Mayne. Eisen
is so much a copy of Olbermann that he's liable for trademark
infringement. And while I'm warming up to Scott, he needs to rotate
his boo-yah and cool-side-of-the-pillow sayings more often. I also
wonder if anyone else knows boo-yah can be dated to a '90s B movie
that featured late rapper Tupac Shakur?
</P>
<P>
   Back when it was a mere 10-year-old, ESPN's ``worldwide leader
in sports'' motto seemed bracing, a cool elbow in the ribs of the
over-the-air networks that had lost their punch to the kid with all
the inventory. ESPN was never brighter than during the too-brief
era when it aired the first two rounds of the NCAA basketball
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a stinky air to the same motto. The relationship
between ESPN and Major League Baseball, for example, was
deteriorating long before ESPN decided it could bid on the NFL
package knowing it would cause conflicts (on Sunday nights) with
its baseball package.
</P>
<P>
   And ESPN showed even more hubris when it matter-of-factly told
baseball it would move those games to ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN now uses its strength to muscle cable affiliates for higher
subscriber fees and channel space for other outlets which are of
little use (ESPNews). It has created restaurants, sports stores and
magazines, spreading its brand name with abandon, and always with
more style than substance.
</P>
<P>
   Disney views ESPN as a more valuable property than ABC, which
short-changes the once-proud reputation of ABC Sports and its
people. Disney wanted to put the ESPN brand on Monday Night
Football before, and it has treated several long-time ABC
sportscasters and production problem rudely.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of things to like about ESPN. ``Outside the
Lines'' is still a great series. Dick Vitale's heart still beats
pure for college basketball. The network still makes room for guys
like Charlie Steiner and Chris Fowler, and the occasional
ex-newspaperman, like Chris Mortensen. And the scope and quality of
the current ``Century'' series has been as good as any of HBO's
documentaries and Ken Burns' 18-hour baseball series.
</P>
<P>
   I just wish the network would get back to the things that made
it part of the culture, and less of a brand name vulture. After
all, it's 20 years old now. It's time to stop acting like a
teen-ager.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
