r s BC-BBA-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     09-06 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGEL TALK NOT TOO PLEASING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are jobs on this planet that inspire me to hyperventilate
just at the thought of having them.
</P>
<P>
   I'd rather be stuck in an elevator with Dick Vitale than be
forced to peddle cars and endure the constant rejection endemic to
such a pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Reading meters isn't exactly a stroll in the park, either, with
growling dogs nipping at your heels and killer bees now presenting
a possible new hazard.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure I have a steely enough constitution to be a prison
guard nor an imposing enough anatomy and the same goes for being a
short-order cook at a roadside hash house.
</P>
<P>
   As for being a cop, I get goose bumps at the mere thought
because that would mean having to grow a mustache. And, as for
being a fireman, such an occupation never even enters my mind
because I don't play checkers, pinochle or crazy eights.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I'd prefer selling cosmetic products door to door, or
even locking down John Gotti, than do what the veteran radio
announcer, Larry Kahn, has been doing this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The ill-starred Mr. Kahn has served as the pre- and
post-game-show host on the KLAC broadcasts of the Anaheim Angels,
who have deteriorated into the Los Angeles Clippers of major league
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It's agonizing enough that Kahn must engage in Angel-oriented
talk for 30 minutes before the team goes out and embarrasses
itself, but then he must come back afterward and take phone calls
for an hour from fans disgruntled about the team's latest
misadventure.
</P>
<P>
   He has been following such a ritual week after cloying week,
Angel loss after cloying loss in a harrowing assignment rife with
futility, frustration and disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``To put it mildly, it's been grueling,'' admits Kahn, who not
only has to discuss the Angels, which is difficult enough, but also
has to actually watch the sadsack team perform on a daily basis,
which has to be downright intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   And, working for a station that broadcasts the Angels, it is
Kahn's duty, of course, to put as positive a light on the team as
possible, a most daunting challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not Harry Houdini,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   I mean, what nice things can Larry Kahn say about these Angels?
That they forced their manager, Terry Collins, into a premature
vacation? That their latest loss was an improvement because it
wasn't as one-sided as the one preceding it? That Tim Salmon is
overrated and can't field? That Darin Erstad is a bust? That Garret
Anderson doesn't deliver hits when his team needs them most? That
Ken Hill should be released? That Chuck Finley is the team's only
legitimate starting pitcher? That the team would have been far
better off had it given Randy Johnson all the money it wasted on Mo
Vaughn? That the team is in desperate need of a second baseman and
catcher? That the team has become such an abomination that Disney
wants to dump it?
</P>
<P>
   ``You do get some bizarre calls,'' says Kahn, a 44-year-old Los
Angeles native who graduated from Fairfax High. ``The other night a
guy calls and says, `I got the solution to all the Angels'
problems.' I said, `Please, let us know.' And he says, `They gotta
move Darin Erstad to second base.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guy, `No way.' And he says, `Why not?' And I say,
`Well, he's left-handed, and left-handers don't play second base.'
Of course, I get some intelligent calls, too, but you get some that
get you to thinking about what direction our nation is headed in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a guy earlier in the season who called in and said
the reason the Angels signed Mo Vaughn was to trade him to Toronto
for Roger Clemens, that the New York Yankees ruined the whole deal
when they gave up David Wells to the Blue Jays for Clemens. And
what's scary is the guy honestly believes that's what the Angels
intended to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kahn has been around long enough the former USC football
announcer has been in the broadcasting business for a quarter of a
century to realize the sports team he's covering would prefer to be
described in optimistic tones.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to tell the truth,'' says Kahn. ``And that's what
I've attempted to do this season. I've never been pressured by any
Angel people in any respect, and Tony Tavares has been 100 percent
supportive of everything I've said. And there have been times when
I haven't said complimentary things.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time last week after the Angels had been swept by
the Cleveland Indians when Larry Kahn didn't mince words.
</P>
<P>
   ``The constant losing gets to you after a while,'' he says.
``The Angels were pretty bad in Cleveland, and I began my post-game
broadcast by saying, `I'm not going to sugarcoat this. This is a
bad Angel team.' Would you believe some guy calls in and takes me
to task? `Where do you get off saying that the Angels are bad?' he
said. `I think the Angels are a wonderful team that has been hurt
by untimely injuries.' The guy actually got mad at me for saying
the Angels weren't very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports talk radio, at its best, can become a tedious grind to
those behind the microphones who must deal with the opinionated
dim-wits with loud voices who delight in engaging in mindless
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   At its worst, it forces its interlocutors to discuss unappealing
subjects with unappealing people like poor Larry Kahn has been
forced to do throughout this undistinguished Angel season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five days after the season is over with I'm in Maui for 10
days with my wife,'' says Kahn. ``This has not been an easy gig.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'd rather write a book on Mo Vaughn's favorite
culinary recipes all those Angel losses certainly haven't resulted
in any weight loss on Mo's part than spend my evenings taking phone
calls on the natural disaster that have become the Angels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
