<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLEANAIR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NO SURRENDER ON CLEAN AIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS `heaviest' in 2nd graf) 
(ATTN: Northeast, Midwest)  (th) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, Sept. 7:
</P>
<P>
   The Clean Air Act gives the federal Environmental Protection
Agency clear authority to deal with air pollution that blows across
state lines. This is a huge problem in the Northeast, where states
like New York cannot meet federal air quality standards because
much of their pollution originates in the Midwest and is thus
beyond their control. After ducking the issue for years, the EPA
last year produced a tough but fair plan, ordering 22 states east
of the Mississippi to sharply reduce emissions of nitrogen oxides,
the main cause of smog, beginning in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Although reductions would be required of every state, the burden
of the order fell heaviest on the Midwest and its older, coal-fired
power plants, many of which would be required to make expensive
investments in clean-air technologies. Predictably, the utilities
went to court, and in May a three-judge panel of the U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia temporarily suspended
the order pending further arguments over the merits of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Because the case could drag on _ and indeed could eventually go
against the EPA, given the increasingly anti-regulatory bias of the
D.C. circuit _ the agency and some Northeastern states have been
seeking a compromise with the Midwestern states. Their goal, an
honorable one, was a negotiated agreement that could withstand
legal challenges and deliver at least some interim relief from
windblown pollution. But the Midwest wants many more concessions
than the Northeast is willing to offer, and at the moment the talks
are off.
</P>
<P>
   The talks should stay off. For one thing, negotiated solutions,
however well intentioned, have a way of getting re-negotiated
later, often for the worse. Second, any compromise _ even one
favorable to the Midwest _ is certain to be challenged by one
utility or another in that region. The EPA may thus find that it
has simply traded one lawsuit for another. Finally, as a matter of
historical justice, there is no reason for a compromise. The
Midwestern states have had a cushy ride for a long time. Their
older power plants were ``grandfathered'' under the Clean Air Act
in the expectation that they would be replaced. But nearly 30 years
later, they are still belching nitrogen oxides and sending them
downwind.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's 22-state plan would force these plants, over a
reasonable time frame, to make the kinds of investments in
pollution controls and cleaner fuels that they should have been
asked to make years ago. If the D.C. circuit strikes down that
plan, so be it. The EPA can then appeal to the Supreme Court or go
back to the drawing board. But there is no need to devise a lesser
plan until forced to.
</P>
<P>
   The administration has other weapons as well. Under the Clean
Air Act, as a legal hammer of last resort, the states that suffer
from windblown pollution can petition Carol Browner, the EPA
administrator, to impose controls on specific industrial sources
that are sending pollution eastward on the wind. The Northeastern
states have filed such petitions. All Browner has to do is act on
them. That will take courage. What administration official, a year
before a national election, wants to march into the states and
start telling its big utilities to clean up or close down? But it
is a far more admirable alternative than a mushy compromise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990906.0318 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2728 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DETROIT-SCHOOLS-1STLD     09-06 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DETROIT-SCHOOLS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ADDS details in   5th graf; ADDS 6th graf with unsure amount of
raises.) TENTATIVE PACT REACHED IN DETROIT TEACHERS STRIKE  
(lb) 
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The union representing Detroit's public school
teachers announced a tentative settlement on Monday night to a
strike that kept the city's 180,000 schoolchildren on an extended
summer vacation last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider it to be not only a victory for teachers but for
the students that we teach,'' said John M. Elliott, president of
the Detroit Federation of Teachers, which represents 11,500 public
school workers, including 8,000 teachers.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear when teachers will return to work, but they
could be back in classrooms as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The schools were due to open last Tuesday, but teachers refused
to return to work without a contract, defying union leaders'
recommendations that they grant a 10-day extension in contract
talks. .
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was unclear Monday night whether the tentative
three-year agreement would pass muster with the teachers and
support staff. The union leadership has scheduled a meeting
Wednesday morning, when the rank and file will be told details of
the agreement. and teachers will vote on whether to return to work.
No vote has been scheduled on the contract.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for raises in each of the three years of the
contract. The size of raises was not clear Monday night, but union
leaders had said the amount in the final two years would depend on
prevailing wages for teachers in Detroit's suburban areas. The
disparity between Detroit teachers' pay and that in the surrounding
areas was a sore point in contract talks.
</P>
<P>
   The school board last week offered raises amounting to 95
percent of what the union sought, which would translate to salaries
of $35,600 to $64,000 a year depending on seniority for teachers
with master's degrees. The new offer improves on that slightly.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would also reduce class size starting a year from now
in 44 elementary schools where space is available for additional
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Some classes will be reduced to 17 students from more than twice
that size. In negotiations last week, the school board had only
offered to study class sizes.
</P>
<P>
   The school board leader, David Adamany, said Monday night that
the agreement would help the district retain experienced teachers
and ``moves us along the path of reduced class sizes.''
</P>
<P>
   Adamany added that the agreement included a number of measures
that would increase teachers' accountability for performance,
including ``the ability to close failing schools.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there's quite a bit of reform here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was announced on a day when more than 3,000
teachers marched up front in this union-proud city's Labor Day
parade.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations had floundered until this weekend, when they picked
up speed, perhaps prompted by state legislators' threats on Friday
to seek sanctions against the teachers, who were striking in
defiance of state law.
</P>
<P>
   A 1994 state law makes the strike illegal and punishes teachers
with fines of a day's pay for every day on strike.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   This is not the first time this year that state legislators have
gotten involved in Michigan's largest school district. In March, a
new school board was appointed after the Legislature, controlled by
Republicans, voted to transfer control from an elected school board
to the mayor of Detroit, Dennis Archer, and the governor of
Michigan, John Engler.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, Cleveland and five school districts in New Jersey,
state legislatures have similarly removed school boards.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians have accused Detroit's school board of being
top-heavy and of mismanaging money and engaging in cronyism as the
schools largely failed their students. Just half the district's
students graduate from high school and only a third of the city's
seventh-graders can read or do math at their grade level.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Archer on Monday night expressed relief over the
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real winners will be the children and parents of the
district and those of us who will depend upon the education that
they will receive, because they are the future of our city, state
and nation,'' the mayor said after the settlement was announced.
</P>
<P>
   The union said its strike was not in opposition to changes the
new board sought to help students.
</P>
<P>
   ``This strike was not about opposition to school reform,'' said
Elliott. He denied that the threat from legislators had
jump-started negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   While the Detroit Federation of Teachers initially supported the
new school board's efforts to improve the system, by this fall many
union members became worried that the board was ignoring their
concerns. Members of the union came to resent the refusal of the
board to bring their wages up to the median of teachers in
surrounding suburbs, which would mean raises of 2 percent to 10
percent, depending on seniority.
</P>
<P>
   Although many parents last week suddenly found themselves
searching for child care because of the strike, many parents in
this union town supported the teachers in their walkout.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers last went on strike here in 1992.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
