r s BC-BBA-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     09-06 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY TRIES AGAIN TO FACE DEMONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Cyclist Lance Armstrong rode out cancer's peaks and
valleys and received a conquering hero's ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Track and field star Ludmilla Engquist attacked cancer as though
it were just another hurdle to clear and was acclaimed far and
wide.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees outfielder and designated hitter Darryl Strawberry hung
in against cancer, fouling off its advances and eventually drawing
a free pass and all the pro-Yankee crowd at Edison Field could do
Friday was boo him.
</P>
<P>
   If Strawberry hasn't enjoyed a groundswell of sympathy these
past few months while battling back to the big leagues, it's on
account of the other progressive and often fatal disease he has
been battling in addition to colon cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, 37, was an alcoholic long before he felt the first
stabbing stomach pains that would lead to his cancer diagnosis this
past October 1.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, before he had finished his chemotherapy
sessions and shortly after he found out he hadn't made the Yankees'
opening-day roster, Strawberry was arrested in Tampa on drug and
solicitation charges.
</P>
<P>
   His body was cleansed of cancer, but it clearly continued to
crave the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry takes after his father that way. When the L.A. native
was 13, Henry Strawberry returned to the family's home in the
Crenshaw District in a drunken stupor, brandishing a gun. That
night Henry walked out of his family's life.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later, Strawberry would follow his father into
alcohol's death trap. He started drinking fresh out of high school,
after the Mets made him the No. 1 pick of the 1980 draft and
promptly anointed him the next Willie Mays.
</P>
<P>
   Despite repeated stints in rehab, sobriety has eluded Strawberry
_ and, not coincidentally, so has Mays' legacy.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of hours before his second game of the 1999 season,
Strawberry sat in the visitors' clubhouse at Edison Field and
addressed his rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   He was speaking in spiritual terms, not in the sports
vernacular, and his tone was so earnest you desperately wanted to
believe the old Darryl _ the one with nine lives and an apparent
death wish _ is gone for good.
</P>
<P>
   But the past is as insidious as cancer; it can never be
eradicated, it can only be kept at bay with due vigilance.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that even as Strawberry gave thanks for his faith and
the friends who have stuck by him, your mind was rewinding. It
stopped at this same spot five-and-a-half years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry, then a Dodger, failed to show up for the club's
final spring exhibition game against the Angels, sending club
officials and his family into a panic.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry would surface the next day and promptly enter a
rehabilitation clinic. You ask him about that time and this place
and Strawberry brushes it off, this dirt on his soul, as
unselfconsciously as he would the soil on his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've moved away, moved on,'' he says. ``At this point, I'm
doing what I'm supposed to do and not what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   You can't help but notice he looks you in the eye as he speaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a horrifying year Darryl's just gone through,'' says
Yankees manager Joe Torre, who knows firsthand of what he speaks.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Torre underwent surgery for prostate cancer and missed
the first 36 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``A doctor told me during my recovery, and it made sense to me,
that cancer is like diabetes. It's a condition you have to learn to
live with,'' Torre said. ``It's liable to show up any time. It
could come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the big ``C'' can hang above its survivors like a noose.
Every stomach ache, any little pain at all, transports you to the
dark place where fear resides. It creeps into your mind no matter
how hard you try to shut it out. You wonder, do you have the flu or
has the cancer come back to get you?
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people,'' Strawberry says solemnly, ``don't understand
the magnitude of having cancer. It's not something you just get
over.''
</P>
<P>
   However sorry he was feeling for himself, there's no explaining
away the pain Strawberry inflicted on wife Charisse and everybody
who believed in him with his arrest in April. He served a 120-day
suspension levied by Major League Baseball, then worked himself
back into shape by playing 20 games with the Yankees' Triple-A
affiliate in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got weak, what can I tell you?'' Torre says wearily. ``He's
a human being. I know he'd like to turn the page, close that
chapter of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Strawberry and his wife are rehashing the whole
horrible experience. They are co-authoring a book, ``Recovering
Life,'' that is scheduled for publication in mid-November. Baseball
fans probably will find the subject matter _ Strawberry's quest for
spiritual centeredness _ a tad too dry.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well. For Strawberry, the dry life is the only one worth
living. The high life is gone, replaced by endless AA meetings _
200 in a recent span of 90 days, Strawberry says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had taken care of myself better,'' he says. ``This
time around I looked at the enemy and it was me.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows he is lucky to be here talking at all, much less
playing baseball at its highest level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gift to be able to make it back and I accept that,''
Strawberry says.
</P>
<P>
   He hit a home run against the Angels on Sunday, his first since
August of 1998, and is batting a healthy .444 after five games.
</P>
<P>
   His swing has always been pure. Now if Strawberry can just
follow through on his intentions, there'll be no end to the
cheering. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
