<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-TERROR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO-JAKARTA GUNMEN INTENSIFY REIGN OF TERROR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Pro-Indonesia gunmen intensified a reign of terror
in East Timor Monday, herding thousands of refugees at gunpoint to
undisclosed locations, and raising fears of the slaughter of East
Timorese who voted for independence last week.
</P>
<P>
   Amid warning signs that vengeful elements of the military might
be creating a refugee crisis to sabotage the ballot results, or
even be plotting mass executions, pressure mounted on the United
Nations to send in peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses interviewed by telephone from East Timor's capital,
Dili, said hundreds of locals who had fled their homes were
captured and marched off at gunpoint Monday, while thousands more
were seized from shelters and loaded onto trucks bound for West
Timor, the Indonesian half of the island.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Kelly, a UN spokesman in Dili, said, ``We are being
informed that in the case of the evacuations it is a premeditated
scenario where authorities said that they expected to evacuate
200,000-300,000 refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   Indonesian President B.J. Habibie, apparently moved to action by
the groundswell of international criticism, signed an order early
Tuesday imposing martial law in the disputed island territory.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, meanwhile, Monday endorsed an offer by
Australia to send its own troops to help quell the violence, as
long as Indonesia approves. The Australian prime minister, John
Howard, put troops on alert Monday, cutting the time needed to send
peacekeepers to nearby East Timor to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Australia-based East Timorese International Support Center
said more than 170 people were slaughtered by pro-Indonesia forces
Monday, but the figures were impossible to confirm. Witnesses in
Dili described the noise of frequent automatic gunfire,
rocket-propelled grenades, and bazookas.
</P>
<P>
   US Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright said the Indonesian
government must either ``take care of the violence or let the
international community be of assistance.'' But she did not suggest
that troops be sent against Indonesia's will or without UN backing.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia has said it would consider peacekeepers only after its
national assembly, due to meet next month, revokes a 1976 law
annexing East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   As the unarmed UN mission in East Timor evacuated nonessential
staff Monday, diplomats and East Timor resistance leaders
complained that the UN Security Council's reaction to the
post-ballot violence has been slow and weak. The Security Council
voted Sunday to send only a small team of ambassadors to Jakarta to
discuss the crisis with Indonesia's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Secretary General Kofi Annan, who briefed the five
envoys _ from Namibia, Britain, Slovenia, Malaysia, and the
Netherlands _ before their departure for Jakarta, said the
``present chaos in East Timor cannot be allowed to fester any
longer.''
</P>
<P>
   If Indonesia's declaration of martial law did not produce
results within 48 hours, he said, the ``international community
will have to consider what other measures it can take to assist the
Indonesians.''
</P>
<P>
   Ana Gomes, envoy to Jakarta from Portugal, East Timor's former
colonial ruler, accused the Security Council of inertia in the face
of slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is East Timor different with many other places where the
Security Council did not forget to fulfill its mission?'' she
asked. ``How many more people killed do you want to start acting?''
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats acknowledged Monday that they had underestimated the
furious response of Indonesia loyalists to the landslide 79 percent
victory for independence in last week's UN-sponsored referendum on
East Timor's future.
</P>
<P>
   Jakarta must realize that it will pay ``a very high cost'' for
letting gunmen run rampant after a peaceful UN vote, said a senior
Western diplomat. ``They had to make a calculation _ how far are
they willing to go? Farther than we thought.''
</P>
<P>
   This morning, Indonesia released longtime resistance leader
Xanana Gusmao from house arrest in Jakarta, commuting the sentence
of the man widely seen as East Timor's most likely first president.
But supporters said going back to Dili now would be a death
sentence for Gusmao.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, a seven-month campaign by pro-Indonesia forces to
derail the vote had crossed all previous boundaries. Gunmen burst
into the Dili home of Bishop Carlos Ximenes Belo, a Nobel Peace
laureate, firing automatic weapons and removing a few thousand
people who had been sheltered there, before burning the bishop's
residence to the ground, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pray for us _ please just tell the world what's going on,''
one man who was in the house said by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's official Antara news agency said about 30 people
died in the attack, and quoted East Timor police chief Colonel
Timbul Silaen as saying militias were looking for pro-independence
politicians in Belo's compound.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Robinson, a UN political officer holed up in the
besieged UN compound in Dili, said he tried frantically to reach
Belo by telephone when he heard the bishop was under siege. ``By
the time we got through to him, he was basically screaming down the
line to us, `We're under attack!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Police then took Belo by helicopter to the home of another
bishop in the eastern town of Baucau, authorities said. Bishop
Basilio de Nascimento told Portuguese radio that Belo arrived ``in
a state of shock.''
</P>
<P>
   In a predominantly Roman Catholic territory, the gunmen have a
``sense of complete impunity,'' Robinson said. ``Our growing
suspicion is that these are not the same militias . . . they are
not local lads. They are well-trained members of Kopassus,'' the
military's special forces.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats described Dili as a war zone, empty of civilians and
controlled by armed men. Gunmen fired Monday at the Australian
ambassador and at a UN convoy on its way to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Military observers said they believe Indonesian military forces
are orchestrating chaos to overturn a peaceful ballot that went
against Jakarta's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen militias and, it looks like, the military, going
into safe havens _ certain towns, churches, the Red Cross _ and
grabbing people who were taking refuge,'' said a Western diplomat
who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``It's not chaos and anarchy.
It's directed, very organized, targeted violence and intimidation.
Anarchy might actually be an improvement in some ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers believe elements of the military may be sowing terror
for several reasons: to discredit the referendum, to undermine
Indonesia's civilian government, to scare other restive provinces
out of demanding independence, or to lay the ground for a partition
of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   But any of those scenarios, diplomats say, would translate into
international sanctions and condemnation for Indonesia. Already
Monday, worries over violence pushed Indonesia's currency and its
stock market down.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's national police chief, Roesmanhadi, who like many
Indonesians uses only one name, admitted Monday that things were
``out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunmen Monday attacked seven places in Dili that were sheltering
an estimated 25,000 refugees, witnesses said. The UN mission
estimates that 150,000 people have been displaced from their homes
throughout the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said gunmen also burst into the Dili office of the
International Committee of the Red Cross and searched the bags of
people taking shelter there for evidence of their political
leanings. When they found an independence flag, they rounded up the
owner and marched him out at gunpoint, one witness said.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen divided the people into two groups _ Indonesia
loyalists and independence-seekers _ before ``marching them onto
the beach and up towards the Jesus statue on the hill'' for unknown
reasons, said Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``A return to the 1975 scenario is almost taking place _ that
once the international eyes are gone, once the journalists are
threatened away, that Indonesia will do exactly as it did then,''
Robinson warned.
</P>
<P>
   The 1975 invasion set off a civil war and several years of
starvation and disease that claimed 200,000 lives _ one-fourth of
the population.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the months leading up to the vote, authorities said to
people, `After the vote, it'll be just like 1975,' '' Robinson
recounted. ``But in spite of that, people went out and voted their
conscience. When you consider that people probably knew what would
happen, it's all the more amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   All 22 remaining foreign observers from the International
Federation for East Timor's Observer Project were trying to flee
the territory Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-99 2347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
