<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-RULING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT OUTLAWS TORTURE IN QUESTIONING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Israel's Supreme Court Monday outlawed interrogation
methods that had been authorized for Israeli security services for
the last 12 years, ruling in favor of rights groups' petitions to
stop the systematic use of methods they decried as torture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court declares the Shin Bet'' security service ``does not
have the authority to shake a person, to force him into a''
contorted ``position or to kneel in a frog-like position or deprive
him of sleep,'' an expanded nine-judge panel of Israel's High Court
for Justice said in a unanimous ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups estimate that the interrogation tactics,
which an Israeli judicial commission authorized in 1987, were used
on more than 10,000 Palestinian prisoners in the last 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was at stake here is the very nature of Israel as a
democracy,'' said Eitan Felner, executive director of the Israeli
human rights group B'tselem, which participated in the petition to
the high court.
</P>
<P>
   ``A country cannot be called a democracy if it resorts to
torture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Balancing democracy and security is more than an academic
question for Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The justices issued the ruling just as Israel braces for what it
fears will be a new wave of attacks by militant Palestinian groups
aimed at derailing an interim peace deal signed on Saturday. On
Sunday, two apparently botched car bombs exploded in northern
Israel, killing three people in the vehicles and wounding two
passersby.
</P>
<P>
   Shin Bet has maintained that the use of what it calls ``moderate
physical pressure'' is necessary to extract information that can
save lives by thwarting attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Israel Radio quoted Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh as
saying the ruling would damage Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Limiting the Shin Bet's capabilities does not help protect
Israel's citizens in the reality in which we live,'' Sneh said.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Aharon Barak, the court president, wrote in the
decision that if Israel is to be a democracy, ``not all means are
acceptable to it. . . . Although a democracy must often fight with
one hand tied behind its back, it nonetheless has the upper hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruling was hailed as a landmark decision by
human rights activists who had brought repeated legal petitions
against the methods since they were codified in 1987 by the special
judicial commission, headed by Moshe Landau, former head of the
High Court for Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took 30 years of human rights abuse to get to this,'' said
an Israeli human rights lawyer, Leah Tsemel, outside the court.
``It will stop torture and make Israel abide by international
law.''
</P>
<P>
   The Landau Commission authorized the Shin Bet to use ``a
moderate amount of physical pressure'' against suspects believed to
have information that could prevent imminent attacks against the
Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   This became known as the ``ticking bomb'' justification, and the
Shin Bet used it systematically against Palestinian suspects while
investigating the militant Islamic underground. But human rights
lawyers said that with the questioning often being conducted over
months, the investigations could not be claimed to be urgent or
immediate.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups argued that the Landau commission's
guidelines had in effect created a bureaucratic infrastructure that
legitimized and gave a ``legal blessing,'' as Felner put it, to
torture methods that violate international human rights law.
</P>
<P>
   International human rights workers said the commission made
Israel, while not the only country to use torture, the only one to
openly authorize its use.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups estimated that more than 850 detainees a
year were subjected to such interrogation techniques. Thousands
have been hospitalized and 10 have died during such interrogations
since 1987, rights groups said.
</P>
<P>
   Nawwaf Qaysi described the ordeal he suffered at the hands of
the Shin Bet during detention in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested after he had been shot in clashes with Israel
police in 1996. Qaysi, 24, said he was held without any formal
charges against him.
</P>
<P>
   He was shackled with handcuffs to a chair in a contorted
position, and forced to wear a urine- and vomit-soiled mask over
his head. In this manner, he was grilled for up to six hours a day
for three months about his suspected membership in the Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   The officers tried to force him to sign a confession to bombing
attacks. He refused, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at the offices of B'tselem, Qaysi said he still
has intense back pain and only 70 percent mobility of his left leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an effort to break you as a person,'' he said, ``an
effort to destroy and take away who you are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
